text: from the smell , i 'm not getting a dipa , seems much milder . the taste is pretty pungent , but it seems like much of this is the alcohol . the hops are pretty tasty , but one dimensional ( as described 100 % centennial hops ) . i guess that explains the minimal hops in the nose . interesting technically as the 100-100-100 ... feat .  the best pour of any irish stout i have ever had , comes out of the draught can creamy and immediately begins to cascade down in my pub glass . a thick creamy head blankets the top of my glass and stays throughout the entire beer , even after the beer is gone the head remains in the bottom of the glass . intense lacing sticks to the glass . the color is a rich dark mahogony .  mouthfeel : i only had a couple mouthfuls ( did n't even make it through one bottle ) , but it felt more substantial and less watery than o'douls or warsteiner .

a hazy light brown with golden highlights when held up to the light . although the flavor was somewhat standard it was delivered rich and creamy and certainly felt in mouth like it was better crafted than the handful of other ales i 've tried recently .  at first pour it did have that great look , not as dark , but the perfect contrast between the creamy head and dark body .  m : was ok , but nothing to write home about .

very sweek candi-sugar smelling . no hop presence at all . then there 's a nice caramel malt and candi sugar flavor . very nice .  poured into a weizen glass , this brew is a very interesting color and one that i 've never seen before .  it had a light feel on the palate with very high carbonation .

a deep ruby blood-red with a milky white head , awesome contrast , one of the coolest looking beers i 've seen . has a well-balanced malt vs. spicy bitter flavor with a hint of butterscotch . kind of chewy but smooth going down , very drinkable . i ca n't believe i had n't had this one before .  bottle poured into a tall tulip glass a : hard pour produces a beautiful deep burnt orange & blood red sunset color , with 3-finger rocky , dirty white head . lots of lacing left behind .  mouthfeel - kind of effervescent .

s - malty , sweet , wood t - sweet , smokey , smooth ... mild hoppy bite shows itself as it gets warmer , tasty and not overwhelming as many porters have been to me m - not like some others of this style i have tried , it feels lighter but not watery .  an 8oz draft at the porter during the terrapin takeover on 5/21/11 a - wow , one of the biggest foamy heads i have ever seen .  perfect creaminess with a decent bite . mouthfeel - the only thing left is a slight bitterness on the sides of your tongue , average here . drinkability - above average , creamy and satisfying , could have a few of these without an issue .

smells metallic and slightly roasted with fig molasses . decent smells .  looks really nice ... .a dark hazy orange/brown with a creamy head .  the mouthfeel is a bit overcarbonated and burns the tongue a bit .

a fantastic beer from southern tier . ( poured into a brandy snifter . ) the aroma was heavy on chocolate and coffee , with hints of vanilla , caramel and oatmeal . southern tier does a great job with their seasonal bottles and this is one that i think goes above and beyond the expectations . great beer !  12oz bottle to tulip . wow , this is one awesome looking beer . a beautifully dense head capping a brew that is the deepest of amber , with a shine that would make any ruby gemstone jealous . stunning .  light mouth feel . hops win out . ; )

the smell was clean with a hint of sourness . there was a lot of room for the spices in the nose but they did not come through . accented with a sour bite and finishing dry . i wish the spices came out more in the nose instead of leaving a harsh note in my throat . an excellent beer , i wish my scoring in the drinkability category was higher .  pours a deep deep mahogany amber brown . moderate dense head of creamy tan foam .  a big surprise with this one smells great a west coast from the east coast t more big hop flavors but not quite as strong in the mouth but still quite good m a little flat and not as thick as i would like but it leaves some grit on your gums and the flavors hang out for a while d i really liked this beer i nearly took down the jug on my own in no time very unexpected winner with this one , after seeing it 's 7.1 % alc i give it even more props because the whole time i thought i was drinking a low booze ipa .

wheaty , yeasty , and a hint of flowery sugars . taste- starts out a bit peppery but quickly sweetens up some with hints of spring strawberries and blackberries .  poured from bottle to tulip glass a : brilliantly clear pale yellow color with huge 3+ finger head that fades very slowly n : nose of a light belgian type wit with some light malts , touch of spices , toasted quality , touch of yeast t : starts with more malts and toasted quality , pretty light otherwise , a touch of light fruits and banana , slight earthy marzen quality , no spices m : very light and somewhat watery f : finishes dry and very crisp with a fading earthy marzen taste , would make a good session beer final thoughts : its a very light tasting oktoberfest/marzen .  mouthfeel : a little on the thin side with high carbonation and a slightly dry finish .

the aroma is nice and clean , but nothing special really .  appearance : a dark , nearly black , reddish brown body with laser-beam red highlights . up top , two fingers of creamy -cream-colored head that endure almost to the end of the glass , leaving excellent sheets of lacing on the way down .  mouthfeel : it seems like a light body beer but the dry pokes and hop prods keep it active until the nearly numbing dry of the aftertaste begs for more .

aromas of spicy hops , orangy citrus . taste of spicy hops , a little floral hop hidden amongst the masses , grapefruit fo sho .  huge and lasting beige rocky head with lots of various forms in the lacing .  a little thin .

aroma is mild suggesting a chocolate malt driven train .  review from notes - bottle reads 3.5 % abv two fingers of frothy bubblegum pink head rests on top of a gorgeous ruby red body , displaying fantastic retention and leaving generous amounts of lace down the sides of the glass . heavily carbonated with a touch of haze .  tastes smooth and creamy sweet malt with light fruit flavor hints of spice and light alcohol finish good easy drinking beer little on light side but it does enhance drinkability .

faint chocolate and chili . mostly musky and solvent like ammonia . some decent complexity here , but not particularly appetizing . musky , almost fishy , stale coffee and even fainter chocolate .  a - pitch black with a nice fat two finger head of fluffy tan cream . lots of sticky lace . beautiful .  feels quite frothy and wild , perhaps a little over done . the carbonation also seems to mess with the flavor in a distracting sort of way . i get the impression that i 'm missing some of the flavor due to the wild carbonation . the big downfall for me was the carbonation .

it does n't have much of a smell ( perhaps if it were poured i could say differently ) . very tasty , kind of dry with floral/citrusy-types flavors , slightly carbonated . this beer is pretty darn drinkable , but has quite a high abv . so tasty i would have drank all six if i could have handled it .  once i got everything settled down i refilled the nonix and the head rose to four fingers and fell back to one . the color is of motor oil , dark as dark can be . a decently balanced stout nonetheless . light in mouthfeel , like an irish stout with an alcohol presence that overshadows any other aspects of an aftertaste . if this was just stout versus stout , heresy would have taken the prize though .  m : light to moderate body with very little carbonation ( like a cask ) .

this is a nice caramel color beer . this beer is very crisp and clean , with a smooth aftertaste and mouthfeel . overall , this is a very good offering from new glarus and is worthy of your time .  330 ml stubby poured into the requisite gold-rimmed maredsous goblet and held to the evening september sunshine yields a brilliantly-clear cherry red body with flaming amber trim and a succulent pile of soft tan foam atop . the cap retains at a thick creamy sheet that coats the glass in a persistent shellac of superfine lacing .  m : light body .

aroma is mild ... similar to your average wit-beer . yeasty , slight fruit ... overall sweet aroma . hmmmm ... wow .  a frothy off-white head crowns a radiant orange body . i believe this is what pumpkin beer would look like in a perfect world .  mouthfeel is a dissapopintment . with this much head , had little carbonation to feel and was also a bit watered down for my taste .

definitely different for a doppelbock . smell - average for the style . strong malt smell . taste - lighter on the malt flavors .  goeien saison 2008 pours a yellow hazy golden straw hue with tons of fluffy head that leaves lace all over my snifter . it looks like a beautiful saison .  mouthfeel is a little more thin than i would prefer .

i 'm getting some malt in the nose , but not much else . some fruit , but lacking . sugar candy , tropical fruit , alcohol , malt , and light bitterness . i laugh at this . loved this . loved this .  had this beer from bottle , very fresh . poured with a huge 1 '' head , thick and spongy ... cloudy golden in color , medium carbination .  medium carbonation and body . nose is the normal malty/hoppy-ness of a porter , starts malty and hoppy and finishes with a nice mostly malty bite . very fresh - brewed 12/13/03 . the abv is 4.5 % .

very enjoyable brew . aroma was a little disappointing in that a minor yeast scent was the only noticeable item . nice .  this looks fantastic in the glass .  holy crap , i think this is the first `` 1 '' i have ever given on taste for a brew . the only thing i can taste is friggin licorice and i hate licorice . this is a bad , bad brew , enough said .

sweet grainy smell tastes malty with a very light bit of citrus .  appearance & gt ; gorgeous ! big vanilla head over a robust readdish brown body . hazy with lots of liveliness .  if you like pecan you will like this . s- a little too light weight for me .

s. funky , straight up . i get earth , grass , wet barn , and some sour funk that i ca n't put my finger on . t. glorious . i use this saison as a bench mark for all others with this style . this is one of the more perfect beers for all occasions .  cloudy dark gold/yellow in color with a nice yellowish tinted creamy head . great head retention and lacing . this is how a wheat beer should look .  mouthfeel - average .

s-the aroma overall is faint but i got a bit of smoke , malt and a bit of toffee and vanilla .  insanely solid spongy tan head retains at a finger , leaves crazy lacing .  mouthfeel was rather thin for a porter .

smell is very subtle citrus , lemony orange and a bunch of wheat . nothing too overwhelming .  dark and smoky , light can not penetrate its depths ... one of the best mass produced brews out there , one of the most respected brews out there , just got ta have one every once in awhile . dark chocolate and dark coffee flavors .  however , you have few choices , this is most likely your cheapest option and most widely drank option . it wasnt terrible , but it just had no real good flavor . if i had a choice between coors light and this , i would have to choose the cheaper of the two , as they are about the same .

a - pours an amber colour , inch head with moderate lacing s - very malty , but loses a few points for being metallic t - a very balanced hoppiness and maltiness , i detect some toasted caramel in the malts m - medium to light bodied d - a very good lawnmower beer a really good beer for the value .  first of all : 2011 vintage = 11.4 % abv appearance : wow . black gold , totally effin ' nailed the name , i thought i was pouring oil into my glass that was thinned down with paint thinner !  m : light to medium body with fairly high , rough carbonation . lively enough , but a bit unrefined .

smells are muted , typical of the `` big three '' in irish stouts .  a beautiful black egg of darkness topped by creamy tan head .  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and an extremely dry finish .

by sight and smell , it 's a bit pedestrian .  the beer pours with a massive creamy head that lasts a long time and laces the glass nicely . the beer is a warm yellow orange color with bountiful pinpoint carbonation .  smell the smoke , not overpowering and nice . this is a mild tasting smoke beer . recommended for those who find other overwhelming . this is something i could drink alot without geting tired of the smoky taste . seems like the lager styles are milder .

the smell is faint smokey and malty . the smokiness continues , but it is well balanced with malt and molasses flavors .  from the classic duvel bottle into a tulip glass - as it should be . visual ( 5 ) : large , lasting , foaming white head made up of large bubbles producing a heavy thick lacing . overall ( 4 ) : a fantastic looking beer , lacing on the tulip looks top-notch the whole way through .  the mouthfeel is somewhat lacking , however . the lighter mouthfeel only makes this brew easier to drink .

smells mostly of hops . i smelled and smelled and smelled trying to sense something else , but could n't .  piss yellow with tons of carbonation and a bright and bubbly cloud white head ! ! gorgeous ! !  it was listed as an imperial stout , but had a relatively light body for such a labeling .

weird , some folks have reviewed this ale as though it 's a stout ! the ale aftertaste is much stronger when served cold . a far cry from the american cream ale which is more of a summer hard working easy drinking light finish beer .  pours a dark ruby red with a giant off-white head .  mouthfeel was a little lacking considering the initial sweetness .

extremely aromatic , some would say too much . extremely floral aroma mouthfeel- dry , crisp drinkablility - you 'll find yourself wondering what happened to that six pack you just bought  a very deep blood-red approaching dark purple with a khaki head that is big , creamy , and sticky .  i found it very highly carbonatedalmost too carbonated ( prickly , carbonic qualities are a bit distracting ) .

smell was quite disappointing and there was n't enough hops in the nose like a great apa .  deep reddish brown head which is absolutely decadent .  m : just a tiny bit heavier than what i would consider light bodied . wish it had a bit more carbonation , it just feels watery .

i freaking love this beer ! i have not had an abita beer that i did n't like . it 's a brown ale , similar of a newcastle or sam adams brown ale . very nice maltiness with a smooth chocolaty finish .  served in a reissdorf stange glass , this has a picture perfect appearance . the clear yellow color and one finger white head made an eager feeling , and the lace left on the glass was impressive .  first sip , light bodied brew with almost no carbonation , little watery texture but very crisp , and refreshing on this humid summer eve .

a - hearty black body with a tan grainy head s - smoke and oats t : burnt oatmeal , bitter chocolate .  poured a deep brown color with an obnoxiously foamy beige head that foamed all over , but patience was the key here . once the ale was finally in the glass , the head retention was magnificent and left some crazy lace on the glass - looks like a bomb went off .  mouthfeel is highly carbonated , i feel a little less carbonation may showcase this beer a little better but overall this beer rocks , i 'm glad i got to try it !

s - very sweet with hints of chocolate and caramel . t - malty sweet with caramel and chocolate .  large , proud head . like a beautifully dark orange ipa , lit from within . remarkable look .  m- fairly light and refeshing feel . pretty smooth , but a little over carbonated for the style though .

s - mild roasted barley noticeable , but not much more .  this beer pours absolutely gorgeous just like a big stout should , hosting a nearly four finger thick malted milk chocolate brown head . great retention as it slowly fades leaving a wall of fat lace and rocky bubbles .  feel is a little thin , flat and viscous .

smell- the head is far too weak for a stout . the roast that was noticed on the nose has virtually disappeared on the palate .  poured a deep garnet color with some persistent lacing .  m : a bit thin and watery ; smooth , but i prefer my hefes with a little more body .

smells of malts and alcohol . not overly impressive .  a : evenly hazy copper color . poured a 3 finger rocky off-white head with excellent retention to a 2 finger cap .  this beer is just flat out terrible . it smells like a loaf of bread soaking in a very bad pitcher of beer . flavor is sour with a hint of bitterness but just plain bad..the only thing i can say for davidson brothers at this point was this beer was not bottled by you it was bottled by shipyard brewing and hopefully they trashed it not you . i do not reccomend this beer to anyone , besides people who like budweiser because it might be slightly better than that .

aromas release some caramel malts , some sweet esters , and that 's about it . i was impressed with the light color on the pour and then was n't sure after taking a good sniff . flavors are solid - as in a single flavor , not something that falls apart as it rolls over the tongue . smooth , deliciousness and a really enjoyable brew for a high octane barleywine style of brew .  i extracted the cap and the brownish liquid poured forth into a splended goblet that reads duvel .  mouthfeel is a tad disappointing , not quite as slick , oily , or full as i would have preferred .

s : not much in the aromatic department , but i can pick up on a little of the hops .  pours out pitch black with a medium dark tan head that stays that way till the last drop .  let me start this by saying that i love all of gl 's beers and appreciatte their quality and price . taste was more of the same with a surprising cooked spinach taste also . aftertaste was also quite disturbingleaving a lingering vegetable taste . i bought a sixer of this beer but could only stomach four of them . i do n't know if the beer intended to taste like this , but even gl makes a mistake every once in a while .

for such a pretty beer , it shure does n't smell like much . faint caramel malts and and 'nilla wafers and a slight detectable hop aroma . the flavor is great , very elegant with a creamy yet bubbly mouthfeel . great balance , smooth malt , and crisp hoppy finish .  clear , brilliant ruby forming a poofy beige head atop fine bubbles with excellent retention and lacing . this is a gorgeous beer .  the same followed through to the taste , some malt , but again ruined by the corn . it is smooth , and with the light body it probably would n't be bad in the summer .

smell - smell of hops and slight coffee taste - slight bitterness , definetly hops , slight coffee , excellent balance . overall - enjoyable beer .  greedy bleached-brown soft-serve ice cream head that slowly recedes to reveal deep glacial crevasses . truly magnificent .  m : light body , slight effervescence ... not much here .

s : not much but some passionfruit and sweet malts . t : very interesting . biscuity malt throughout with a bit of passionfruit and lime through the middle .  poured into a pint glass a : aggressive pour yields 2 fingers of tan head with great retention . very good looking !  the mouthfeel is a bit thin , but the flavor makes up for it .

i 'm trying to pull out the aromas but it 's kind of tough . very mild nose of some fruity and malty sweetness . a really light nose for a big brew .  perfect pour , nice thick fluffy head , dark brown color with a reddish hue when held up to light .  claims to be be a no carb beer , better described as a no taste beer . almost clear in appearence . it was refreshing i give it that , and if it was really , really hot , it would be a plesant drinking experience , but if you actually want your beer to taste like beer , i 'd give it a miss . it seemed to have gone after the gimmick ( nop carbs ) rather than trying to produce a flavoursome beer . it 's a shame as i hear the rest of the burleigh range is okay .

leaves behind an artful legacy of lacing on glass . s : citrus and pine . t : opens with a big citrus hit of tart grapefruit that 's followed by an astringent scratch and burnt offerings of toast and brown sugar .  the pour was pitch black with a good one inch head .  mouthfeel - medium body mouthfeel . a tad bit watery .

picked up a bomber to try ... - really dark viscous stout ... rich solid black/brown , mild finger of head , rich mocha colored ... down to some minor spotting ... looks delicious . - nice sweet chocolate ... slight bitterness ... and a touch of rubbing alcohol booziness.. some grains , oatmeal.. etc , . thank god the taste does n't mimic the scent too much . - overall this is a fantastic stout , and and quite pleased with it.. one i would certainly purchase again .  its been a long time since i trid this brew ... it pours a very dark brown to black color with a finger of tan head that falls to a coating over the beer . the color is beautiful .  this beer was an amber color with a thick white head that dissipated quickly . a nice fruity/spicy taste , with some warmth in the aftertaste . it was a little too fizzy for me , but still a very smooth and drinkable beer

not much aroma . beer looks great , nice medium head .  this stuff is gorgeous , with its jet black opaque esspresso appearance . textured waves of dark brown nitrogen bubbles teem with an almost lifelike quality . the most beautiful , cappuccino-like head you 'll ever see in a glass . sadly it 's downhill from here .  m : medium bodied .

smell : light citrus and pinecone tones are tough to sense , but they are there .  a : very nice deep black with a prominent mocha colored head . sticky lacing left behind with good head retention . it settles to a nice film and perks back up with a quick swirl of the glass .  mouthfeel : medium body , light carbonation .

s : strong , roasted barley predominant , toasted nuts as well t : syrupy , quite a bit of alcohol in the flavour as well -- a bit too much for my liking m : thick and rich d : while enjoyable , this was slightly less appealing .  huge hiss when the cap is pryed off . great retention and lacing .  m : oily texture with average carbonation and a bitter finish . the mouthfeel is the weakest aspect of the beer .

s - grass and citrus dominate , with a noticeable resiny undertone and a hint of molasses . t - smooth .  so silky smooth and absolutely scrumptious ! appearance : ruby-mahogany-black , good clarity ( around the edges of the otherwise opaque brew ) , thick creamy layer of fine-beaded tan head , great head retention , lots of lace aroma : brown sugar , coffee , burnt grain , baker 's chocolate , lyle 's golden syrup flavor : gentle malt sweetness with hints of burnt caramel , chocolate , dark molasses sugar , and weak coffee ; unripe pear hop flavor ; finishes semisweet with a smoothly bitter aftertaste mouthfeel : medium-full body , silky-smooth soft texture , moreish as hell  mouthfeel is okay , but not great .

overall fairly light aroma . though the nose was a bit light , the beers taste was intense and enjoyed .  from the bottle poured black with a brown head and a lot of lacing .  a : clean , dark brown/amber , no sediment s : malty , dark fruit , and caramel , t : well balanced bitterness , malty , thick syrupy , dark fruit and caramel , m : thick , smooth , lack of carbonation is the big detracting factor , d : as noted , we had two to make sure - the alcohol is subdued and we quickly finished both bottles ; it 's really that good .

what 's really amazing is this guy was a home-brewer just five years ago and now has his own brewery . props brother . while the hops are n't particularly aromatic they add a nice bitterness to the overall flavor and the malt has a good toasted sweetness to it .  a : pours a dark brown body with a tan head .  quite honest and good mnchner beer . better than most of the german lagers , like warsteiner , lwenbru and bitburger . excellent taste , nice smell , very good appearance and drinkability . good balance among malt , yeast and hops . it worth a try , for sure .

pours a cloudy straw or unhealthy piss colour.nose is slightly sweet and a bit yeasty-musty . this is a fine tasting beer.strong starting carbonation , sweet , and slightly hoppy , very sharp in its initial bite.a background of pepper and i think orange . great mouth feel and very drinkable .  a - solid black , no light at all .  lots of bitter orange , banana , even cinnamon in the taste , with smooth but underwhelming mouthfeel .

smells very mild for such a rich brew . got hints of roast barley , vanilla , and charred oak . i do n't think this is a bad beer by any means but i think there are far better examples of this style .  amazing lacing .  body is medium full , but the carbonation is quite low .

chocolate aromas mostly , maybe a little smokiness .  pours a rusty ruby and amber color . very dark and very difficult to see any bubbling . the head is a dark khaki colorof two fingers after the pour and one finger of foam that stays with you through all twelve ounces . not to mention all the stickage of foam hanging on to the inside of my pint glass .  mouthfeel is average .

aromas of dark grains , light coffee , and hints of bittersweet cocoa .  this beer looks really great , effervescent like champaign .  m- medium body , goes down smooth . i was n't too impressed with the mouthfeel .

cork was impossibly difficult to remove ! smells strongly of either peaches or apricots , but unfortunately i 'm not a fan of either fruit . also apparent are wheat , honey , and malt .  cane & ebel is a very dark brown , almost black , cola colored brew , which glows an amber read when held to the light .  mouthfeel lacked continuity . good weight for a bpa though and a nice interpretation of the style .

3.5 s distant smell , maybe some medium malt . 3.0 t belgian yeast and malty sweetness that i did not expect . 5.0 d absolutely fabulous .  unbelievable . leaves some massive clinging rings around the glass .  mouthfeel was a bit of a letdown . it seems the cask had been open for a little while , as the natural carbonation was quite weaker than other cask beers i 've had .

the brewery added pasteurization this year . amber in color . not heavy on hops but some are evident at the finish . if you only tried this one last year it might be worth another try . i tried on tap at the brewery and out of a bottle from retail .  a : beautiful carmel brown color with a big , fluffy head that recedes to about two fingers . excellent and surprising clarity , given the style .  it 's light on the palate and slightly dry . i 'm not a huge fan of wheat beers but this one is really not to my liking .

a little more hop aroma might help this one out , but it is quite drinkable .  very good looking , perhaps the best looking beer i 've seen . deep amber and ruby , rich . luscious creamy , dense and enduring head ; off-gold/white color .  begins sweet , the top is skimpy in its mouth feel , with the finish delightful in its hop spicy bite and the carbonation perfectly matched , also the somewhat bitter and dry aftertaste makes it quite refreshing , quite the quaffable brew , and a new favorite .

pretty decent smell .  poured a dark dark brown with a super creamy light mocha head .  the only real knock on this beer is that the mouthfeel was a bit thin for an imperial stout , if it was more viscous it would be an a+ beer to me .

a slight caramel malt nose . i was surprised to see that its abv was over 6 % .  a - a beautiful pour into a tulip glass .  the mouthfeel , however , was watery for a porter , the body medium and the carbonation light . highly quaffable .

there are some faint floral aromas that are nice , but they would be better if they were stornger .  pours a deep copper body with a thick , frothy off-white head .  smelled of floral hops with a heavy alcohol presence . yeast and hops i guess ? hugely intense ( like a kick in the teeth ) flavor of hops and alcohol . sometimes the hop flavor won out , but mostly just alcohol . bummer . overall i was super dissapointed by the floaties and the overpowering alcohol presence .

s : weak burnt aromas with coffee and cocoa . t : sweet chocolate throughout and mild coffee in the finish .  orange amber in color , head retention was excellent and solid sheets of lace adorned the glass .  but i do n't like ipa . there is flavor , but those damn hops just interfere too much . average feel , but i could n't even finish the sample .
the smell disapoints . nothing more than a whisp of grain .  stone- double bastard appearance- hazy reddish brown with a big overflowing creamy head .  m - pretty straightforward . average .

smell : sweet , rounded grain with a hint of toast . a slight hint of hop oil .  this one is topped with a gorgeous tan head . great retention and very good lacing .  on tap at the brewpub . creamy rich aroma of sweet sugary hops , full of lime juice , fresh grated ruby red grapefruit and a waft of fresh mountain pine . fantastic aroma . flavor is a pandoras box of fresh oranges , mandarins and tangerines , reduced and drizzled over a grainy bite of malt . a bit of that hop buttery note on the finish , with a long creamy smack of grass and cilantro . a touch of chewiness . long aftertaste of apples and bitter resin . a top ipa !

s - leaves me kind of flat , i do n't smell much of ... anything , to be honest . it 's a relatively sweet-smelling brown , i do n't smell much trace of pumpkin or pumpkin pie spicing .  the smokin ' lager poured a cloudy copper-red with a lot of tiny floating particulates . it had a huge light tan head the had great retention .  herbal aromas with toasted grains , similar to a barleywine 's fermented sweetness . the taste is very sour , which builds in layers with each sip . outside of the sour , there is not much flavor except for a slight hint of malt . it is presented as a spring seasonal and it just does n't work , no matter what time of year .

s : very mild smell of sweet malt with a hint of hops . t : light flavor of caramel , i guess from the sorgum , maybe some honey with a mild hop flavor towards the end .  pours a three finger cream head that fades slowly to a thin layer leaving a good lace . nice deep , clear mahogany color .  m : very light and delicate mouthfeel . lighter body than i prefer , but it does not bother me whatsoever , all things considered . very slick , almost oily mouthfeel .

s - slightly sweet bready/grainy aroma with faint indications of hops almost exactly like scrimshaw pils .  a nice layer of foam remains throughout . excellent looking .  loaded with fresh hops flavor , spicey , that good bitter smack finish . i used to prefer darker beers to american pale ales , but this beer is the one that changed my mind . this beer goes great with crawfish and pizza .

initially came across as gimmicky because of vanilla taste . however , when savored in the mouth for a moment the bourbon flavor comes through and makes a really nice finish . best tasted when cool , not cold , preferable the cooler side of room temp .  a : a huge , tight head impressively crests the beer , gently churning , but never quite collapsing . a dark tan , it tops a much darker brown beer , completely opaque . good lacing .  mouthfeel is a little thin and watery .

has a malty aroma with a hint of licorice and coffee taste of roasted malts with small amount of coffee and hops make their way through . overall a pretty solid and complex beer .  boulder flashback is a crystal clear sparkling red ale with a dense , creamy , khaki head that has outstanding lacing and retention .  light carbonation , exactly what i expected from the appearance , not bad .
excellent beer .  pours a virtually opaque black with a great tan head that sticks around .  somewhat dry in the mouth , kind of the weak point of the beer .

the nose was smooth and pleasant but not hoppy in the least bit .  *i did not mind it and would not buy again* app : looks great big and sexy .  s-moderate , almost medium-light body , with a carbonation that at times seemed just a bit too much .

s - no alcohol smell like the regular yeti . clean . nice and average .  a : pulpy guava , huge voluminous soapy white head , copious clumps of lacing .  fruits and booze , non-sweet tastes very sweet at first , but it dies down considerably , which is good . it has a syrupy feel at first , but that fades away too ... more carbonation would have been better .

this beer pours almost a copper/red-brown color with a light tan almost white head . the smell is sweet with some hop in there as well as malts . its hard to seperate , but a plesant sensation regardless . it has a smooth medium body that is not heavy at all and makes this drink more robust but still very drinkable . very good al , highly suggest trying .  pours a deep burgundy color with a large sticky light tan head , a beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel is pretty average i guess , a bit on the thicker side , creamy carbonation .

smelled like alc and caramel .  it poured out a beautiful pale orange with a small head that left a nice lace . one of the nicest looking brews in my opinion .  m- this beer felt sightly heavier than it was .

smell is a bit one dimensional with lots of spices and some sweetness . nutmeg , cinnamon , ginger , and just a lot of spice .  very clear gold color brew . very nice sized , pillowy white head .  the body is nothing special however . feels overcarbonated and lacks a nice texture .

s - an initial grainy aroma with the malt subsided quickly to a much more pleasing caramel malt nose . sweet but crisp and clean aroma with a good hop presence to balance it out .  a - poured into a standard pint glass a clear copper with a creamy one finger off white head that leaves heavy thick side lacing .  mouthfeel strikes as kinda light bodied .

the smell is chocolate , and some roasted malts .  the beer pours a blackish brown color with a head that appears to have the consistency of whipped cream . head retention was exceptional and there was plenty of sticky lacing all around . visually , this beer is a thing of beauty ... on the nose , i do n't get a whole lot , just some light licorise , burnt toast and coffee ... maybe a hint of dark chocolate .  the only fault here is that the mouthfeel is a bit too full for a pilsner . it is thick to the point it seems a bit flat even though there are abundant bubbles . only fault is the weird thickness to this .

s : not much smell here . if anything , roasted malts . t : roasted nuts , strong roasted coffee , roasted malts .  poured a nice rich copper , with a thick foam cap that left great lacing .  mouthfeel : medium body with hardly any carbonation and a slightly slick finish .

a : pretty good nose . the bourbon does not overpower the aroma , just adds nice notes of vanilla and caramel . t : taste is similer to the nose .  nhhwha has a dark golden look with some bronze type tints . a significant amount of lace sticks to the glass all over the place , spraypaint like .  light , sweet malt aroma ... very little hops . mouthfeel is to style but with an explosion of tiny bubbles .

not bad ... it 's starts with a caramel like flavour but ends with the taste of rum raisin ? i think i 'd have to try it again befor i decide if i really like it .  appearance : black with a huge , fluffy belgian-style head that i have never seen in a strong stout before .  mouthfeel is thin , but not watery . nice carbonation .

smell is very faint and hard to find . just a bit of roasted barley and malty sweetness . overall very flavorful and easy drinking stout .  appearance : pours a semi-clear medium golden color with an enormous 4+ finger frothy snow white head . excellent head retention and perfect lacing .  pleasnt middle ale taste . smooth flavor and easy to drink.no unpleasant aftertaste which i dislike in an ale . generally speaking i prefer fairly strong ales and beers , but this one seems to be of decent quality without excessive hoppiness . recently discovered at a local beer discounter so further review may continue..

the smell is rather light for a big brew . some light roasted malt notes with a bit stronger nose of black liquorice .  puts on a nice show as the nitro makes the head form . awsome looking head as with most nitros .  feels light bodied with tons of carbonation .

this recent barrel aged release from avery left me wanting more , especially after the first in the series the brabant . the aromas were about the only thing i did n't like about this beer , you pick up on a lot spice from the rum cask and as you get closer all you get is a pungent alcohol smell . taste wise it was excellent , not a hit of high alcohol on it .  a- this has a massive creamy wet head that is creme-tan colored . quite beautiful . it produces awesome lace .  carbonated swallow is a tad sharp .

the body has a nice malty sweetness to it and there 's a hint of diacetyl as it goes down softly . there is a bit of bittering hop to clean up the finish .  i really have been really spoiled lately by russian imperial stouts , fingers crossed in hope that my lucky streak continues midnight black in color , and pours a creamy mocha brown head 1 finger in height that leaves behind a nice coat of lacing . truely beautiful .  this really could have been something with a little less carbonation .

lovely lace clings to my glass . on the nose , a hint of hops and some kind of sharpness .  pours a pitch black color with a thick brown head into my glass . very good presentation for the style .  the mouthfeel doesnt impress me . seems a bit thin and maybe chalky from time to time ... maybe from the hoppyness .

appearance : like a pale ale but darker , with a fat , long-lasting creamy off-white head smell : grassy hops balanced by a sweet malty presence taste : czech hops give it an understated bitterness balanced well with the sweet maltiness . there 's some lingering flavor i ca n't identify but it 's quite tasty . drinkability : very drinkable apa .  anchor porter creates about three inches of dark khaki colored head , which forms into a rocky crown . the body is jet black , with only slightly reddish hues to shine through at the bottom of the glass .  seemed thin in the mouthfeel with almost too much carbonation .
like the smell , the flavors are there and nicely balanced but subdued and weak at the same time .  i love beers that pour and look like motor oil .  m : light to moderate body and carbonation .

looks like a nice beer but smells really dusty . earthy .  this one started off great ... pours up a very rocky picture perfect schaumkrone !  feel : the fizz i feel could be less . sips feel light , masked by carbonation .

on tap at porter 's pub in easton , pa. nice 1 finger head with smells of wheat and grass .  a- pours black with good carbonation , impressive full creamy head and good retention . laces nicely as well .  mouthfeel was a bit thin for my liking .

~ca n't really smell much , a bit dissapointing , but a classic lager smell , the carmelized malts , and ca n't smell any of the hops , though i 'm sure they 're there .  a beauty on the look . s - has a big mocha and chocolate smell .  and now i know why people say it tastes like chocolate syrup , because it kinda does . but this is really good if you like chocolate . probably 1200 calories in this bottle . but who 's drinking beer and watching calories ?

the aroma is rather light , but the taste makes up for it .  very good retention , and overall , a great looking porter .  m - this part is a bit underperforming , but only relative to the rest of its strengths ; it just does n't have the substantive feel that i want , but it has proper carbonation and relative weight .

appearance was medium to dark brown and thick with a half-inch head that was a dark beige in color and very `` frothy . '' smelled of toffee or caramel rich with sweet malts .  appearance : down right black with about two fingers worth of head nice head retention very frothy and thick leaves lace from start to finish .  m : average carbonation and the hop bitterness sticks around .

the smell is common for a stout , with the presence of barley being more than detectable , but overall the scent is fainter than i expected to be .  poured into my aventinus weizen glass . plenty of frothy head that wo n't quit and leaves lots of lacing .  founds this a bit too fizzy for the style , possibly overcarbonated , possibly i do n't know wtf i 'm talking about .

s - smells roasted like any typical stout , but no hint of chocolate whatsoever . did n't really like the smell on this at all . did n't smell bad , but did n't make me want to dive right in . i know it 's a different style , but i session guinness often , and this kicks guinness 's ass .  pours perfectly with a three finger thick head of a bright white color .  m : it feels light to medium bodied with high carbonation . rather smooth though .

i move in to take a sniff and find a delicate aroma suggesting fresh cut hay .  a - pours a light hazy golden colour , with two thumbs of big bubbly head , nice amount of sticky big bubbled lacing litters the glass on the settle . outstanding presentation !  mouthfeel/drinkability : mouthfeel is pretty medium bodied , a bit thin and not overly impressive for an ris .

aroma - rather faint and not enticing aromas of medium and dark roasted malt . t markedly more flavorful than aroma suggests : a somewhat spicy rich malt flavor that leads to a fine and lasting finish featuring dark roasted malts .  a : black , with an amber/brown hue . the thick cream-colored head lingers the whole way down .  m - i would 've preferred a slightly more viscous feel .

a=beautiful cloudy golden orange . a nice 2 fingers of fluffy white foam s= spice of pumpkin pie , cinnamon , nutmeg and ginger with a little sour pumpkin and yeasty bread t= fruity , but dry with a good bit of bitterness to cut the warm spice . the pumpkin is in the aftertaste a nice surprise after the in your face spice and no perceptible alcohol despite the 6 % f= full and rich , coating my mouth and lingering on the palette d=first whole pumpkin beer i 've had ( had samples before ) .  by far the most appealing part of the appearance is the tall , pillowy , sexy off-white head .  i noticed to yeast in the bottom of the bottle after i read that it was bottle conditioned on the label . the malt comes through as i drink . there is the malt backbone with some hops . i guess i 'm just so used to ipa 's and dipa 's . this is a really drinkable beer .
the smell was very modest with just a bit of slightly sweet malt detected .  pours jet black with thick , foamy head .  mouthfeel is a but flat .

s : bit of bubble gum , caramel in the bouquet t : really prominent hop character , around which revolve the advertised spices : cinnamon , ginger , and orange m : silky and smooth very nice christmas ale .  pours a completely opaque deep brown ( read : black ) with a decent creamy , dark chocolate head . excellent head retention and good , well-defined lacing all the way down .  mouthfeel- a little thin and soapy feeling .

very smooth , nice malt smell , nice head with lacing , the most satisfying macro brew i 've ever drank ( blew pbr away after a tour of the pabst brewery - just a few blocks from school ... ) . macro brews get trucked all over the place , and even with multiple breweries , most of the big guys do n't want to admit having a hard time keeping their product fresh .  pours an opaque black with dark brown and red highlights , medium sized thick brown head forms , looks like tar , settles to a thin ring quickly , drops a ton of lace , this stuff is dark !  mouthfeel is decent but a little slick .

smell of mild roasted with some faint metallic notes . not a very strong smell overall .  the head is dark tan with good lace and kind of glitters . good lace .  poured from bottle to sniffer , looks like weak drip brewed coffee , ok head that diminished to a lace that stayed till the beer was gone . smelled of chocolate malts and coffee . the taste was that of black coffee with chocolate syrup added . i like this beer alot this is number five of six so drinkability is up there .

aroma is typical for the style , roasty malt smell , not particularly strong .  the typical stubborn head that comes with the style is here- one that forces you to wait ; and admire the rocky billows of foam that slowly sink to reveal magnificent spiderweb lacing and active carbonation .  peach / apricot on the nose with a bit of yeast , very interesting bouquet . a little taste of toffee/candy , again apricots , but not overwhelming . mild bitterness . very drinkable , very refreshing , i could see myself drinking this on a hot summer day ( unlike today ) , but nothing complex about it .

bready malt in the nose with some juicy hops , touches of caramel and bread crust . a bit sticky and resiny , touches of citrus too . nice backbone with caramel and bread crust .  presentation - poured into my chimay goblet appearance - a golden body with a very thick white head reminiscent of snow covered mountains smell - very hoppy , but a little bit of skunk , due to the ( green bottle ) being exposed to light .  m : i wish this beer had a bigger presence on the palate as the feel is too light and overcarbonated for the style .

aroma is faint at best , just a light grainy malt . except for an unexceptional smell , this is a very good german pils , on the bitter end of the spectrum .  pours a orangey red color with a whipped egg white head .  it was medium in body with moderate carbonation .

appearance : dark copperish coloring smell : light earthy aroma , didn ; t pick up on much taste : earht tones and the typical belgian yeast flavor .  pours a very dark amber burgundy . this bottle gave a good two finger head that diminished after about 5 minutes to very fine layer that remained for the rest of the glass .  light mouthfeel , good session brew for this time of year .

a - poured a very nice deep orange/brown with visible sediments of the good stuff a.k.a . yeast . s - obviously hops are the predominant scent upon first smell with the same aroma of sn 's pale ale but a little bit sweeter due to the different hop variety .  a- dark as night . half a finger of dark cocoa head . lacing is somewhere between big pocadots and total sheets . delicious looking foam .  one of the best winter warmers i 've had .

the smell is caramel and slightly metallic . fair .  poured into a tulip glass , the euphorique is a very nice looking brew . hazy golden straw colored with a very tall , dense and rocky eggshell head .  pours a thin , tan head , light brown/red coloring . aroma is a little hoppy but has a nice malt background . big hop flavor , small hints of toffee , but overall a nice maltiness . bitterness is on spot for an esb , as well as the floral marks . i 'd very much buy this again if i can find it .

not the best smelling beer around , but still good . t - amazing taste .  comes out a khaki-orangish color with a small head , lots of lacings , and tons of visible carbonation . i have to say this is one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen . it was gorgeous in the glass .  m : nothing to extremely special . a nice round fullness .

poured into pint glass beautiful `` reverse carbonation '' as the beer seems to flow downward and then corrects itself to display one of the most iconic heads in all of beerdom faint aroma of coffee , roasted malt and earth taste -- very clean and dry , flavors are very subtle-very easy to drink beautiful lacing , like melting vanilla ice cream overall , a fine version of a classic stout , very easy to drink , and at only 4.2abv , certainly session worthy .  ( served in a weizen glass ) described as a double extreme imperial wheat stout on the bottle a-this beer has an opaque black body with a strong carbonation of micro-bubbles that glide up the sides of the glass . the super thick head of tan sticks to the glass after each sip and last for the full beer .  i found this beer to be a touch watery compared to other oatmeal stouts ( specifically b.o.r.i.s . ) , but overall a nice stout that convinced me to try other beers from anderson valley brewery .

aroma is yeasty and phenolic with some earthiness and an herbal note . again , as in the nose , phenolic and earthy yeastiness .  black/dark brown , almost opaque with a huge tan head ! looks luscious .  a medium body and a little thin .

not much coffee smell but the taste is a bold somewhat sweet coffee with chocolate undertones .  this i2pa pours with an amber body topped by a thick , creamy , lasting head with lots of lacing left behind .  by far my favorite pumpkin beer . actually taste like pumpkin pie and not beer with a hint of pumpkin like some other pumpkin beer . o'fallon 's is a distant second . have tried southern tier pumking , shipyard 's , lakefront pumpkin lager , post road , blue moon , jack 's pumpkin spice and imo it 's the best !

i love it . i 've never smelled anything quite like this one . i especially like the aromas because it 's unique but it is exceptionally sweet as far as aromas are concerned . it looks spectacular and smells amazing yet it leaves you scratching your head with the flavor .  pours an awesome looking amber/red .  light bodied , this one is extremely drinkable .

( s ) - corn smell and yeasty . ( t ) - sweetish honey flavor .  great looking beer , deep ruby red when held up to light .  the mouthfeel is a bit on the light side , but maybe that contributes to its overwhelming drinkability .

s- does n't really have that strong of a scent , but you can slightly smell some malts . d- very drinkable . overall an extremely good beer .  a : beautiful cloudy yellowish brown ; enormous head s : wonderful bouquet of sweet banana t : well-rounded belgian-style wheat beer ; hints of cherry ; banana in the aftertaste ; bottle conditioning is n't cloying ; nicely sweet very nice version of a hefe .  at first the taste is disappointing , high carbonation seems to block out the taste of the beer , combined with a thin mouthfeel .

smell is mild . malt and oak . very refined . compares well to oaked yeti .  really dark body , garnet highlight when held to the light . light tan head on top . voluptuous head 1 '' thick that reduced slowly leaving thick lacing behind . good head retention . this has everything i 'd look for in appearance , even if it might be a little dark .  mouthfeel : not a lot of body , a little thin .

the medium unfortunately was a 6oz pilsner sampler . the aroma was mild but i sensed a slight flowery hop note .  a forced abv of 6.66 and a nice blood red awkward color make this one a really weird oktoberfest . a gorgeous ruby read with a semi pink foamy head . a pretty `` scary '' colored oktoberfest .  m : full-bodied , slick , oily , and a bit resinous . there is no carbonation , so this ale remains still in the mouth .

s : soft wheat on the nose , some floral hops , not much else . t : clean crisp beer , wheat up front , very faint hops on the finish .  poured into a duvel glass the golden straw color and extremely white fluffy head are beautiful . this is one of the most beautiful double ipa 's i 've ever had .  ha ha , funny guy ! for a macro that smells terrible , the taste is almost palatable . it still is n't good , but it 's not the road-kill skunk i recall . maybe it was the locales . or the company . not a good beer . at the risk of sounding snobbish , if my choice is old latrobe or apple juice , i 'll be happy to grab a cardboard container of juicy juice .

smell is light light , roasted malts .  poured from the bottle into an imperial pint glass a- beautiful copper brown with a huge off white head and tons of lacing on the glass . perfect clarity in the beer .  medium mouthfeel and light diacetyl .

dry , flat , and boring . maybe a bit of coffee bean . to be fair , as it warms up some rounder hints fruits open up . i needed an imperial stout right now .  this beer is extremely disappointing . it looks amazing the feel and body are great , very velvety the nose is great too ! , if you 're an 8 year old girl at a carnival this thing smells like cotton candy .  mouthfeel : becomes somewhat flat and watery as it moves across the palate .

i have had several other samuel smith 's and they have all been fantastic so i wanted to try this one out too . the tase was malty with just a hint of something extra ... .ginger perhaps ?  inky darkness and a sticky lacing create a picture perfect design on my glassware .  the middle is a little thin , a little plain , with pepper and a little butter at temperature . sweet apples abound in an otherwise dry finish . apples and grains in the aftertaste . good .

no freshness dating on the bottle . the faint aroma made it difficult to accurately describe , but from what i can tell it is malty and mildy doughy . the commercial description is right about the hops being a tad more pronounced than in other tradional scottish-style ales . taste is combnination of roastiness , nuttiness , and fruitiness -- ripe dark fruits such as plums .  a : comes in a clear dark amber hue , with incredibly thick frothy beer head sustaining forever , it seems .  mouthfeel is a tad thin for my liking , but not so much as it is a problem .

fahrenheit , and as such the projection of the aromas may be stunted a little bit . spices , breads , and even good amounts of off-sweet chocolate are there to spare though , with a complexity for sure .  an exceptional appearance . really could not appear better imo .  mouthfeel : a little thin on the palate , but otherwise felt good .
s : lime enough said it smells like lime and a light beer .  this one has a beautiful dark brown-reddish , ruby-like color .  i wish this would be a bit softer in the mouth , a bit less sharp .

the aroma was surprising bland and reminded me of a cheap light beer , like bud light .  it has got the most beautiful amber color , with a little reddish head and smells delicious .  mouthfeel is slightly thin .
aroma is interesting . bit of herbal/spice funkiness . intriguing .  beautiful amber color with a thick off-white head .  for the style it seemed light bodied and almost over-carbonated .

lemon , lime , and orange zest with husky grain and a tinge of alcohol .  a - dark chocolate brown with beautiful head . a beautiful beer .  m : very light with little to no viscosity . tap was much better , but most likely force carbonated .

the nose is somewhat disappointing . did n't get any cherry initially because the burnt malts kind of took over . as it settles a bit , the cherry starts to come out but still subtle .  probably the most perfect head i 've yet to see upon any brew i 've yet tried . white , thick and perfectly symetrical .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh and overcarbonated .

the aroma , on the other hand , is phenomenal . rich , dark fruit notes of plum and fig surround nibs of dark chocolate and toasted toffee malts . overall , this was a good beer , it 's just too bad that it was n't properly carbonated , or else it would have been truly great .  new holland dragon 's milk pours a beautiful black with just a bit of garnet showing when held to the light . a fluffy ivory head sits on top .  m : thinner than i was expecting ... .

smells sweet and definitely tastes sweet and malty up front , bitterness in the middle towards the end . very different compared to american `` winter warmers '' which are usually cloyingly sweet and over spiced .  appearance - cloudy golden yellow with a sparse white head . 3 floyds has some awesome labels .  m - a little like bodied for a stout , but still light and creamy .

the smell is nowhere to be found but like i mentioned the taste is the most important .  this beer has very good head retention and excellent lacing as well . in other words , this beer looks damn good .  lighter than expected on the palate . crisp . the low hop content ( 33 ibu ) is lost in the malt and alcohol . in fact its all malt and alcohol and a bit too cloying at that . i often wonder if some brewers actually taste their beers before they release them , because not only does this taste like one of my first homebrew bombs , but i agree holy jesus , what are these goddamn beers ?

a malty nose w/ a long lasting tan head .  lightly poured from big green glass bottle into my new belgium glass . ascending vortex of super-carbonation like champagne on steroids . beautiful deep gold and the foamiest head ever .  i felt that it was easy to drink and lives up the the quality of beer that sn makes mouthfeel : thin but not too think .

i did n't get much out of the aroma - certainly the hops were there , but nothing particularly noteworthy .  appearance : pretty much flawless . i love that pinkish orangey color .  delicious and refreshing , a bit too thick for my tastes .

a- coca-cola colored . with a thick brown-grey almost ash like mousse of a head . s- smokey sweet malt . a little metallic . d- very good .  drinking in a sierra nevada pint glass appearance : this is one of the best looking beers i can recall drinking . brilliant copper/orange color . 1 '' of dense marshmallow colored foam that dissipates down to a thin white layer of sea foam covering half of the surface area and laces nicely to the side of the glass .  it was watery with some carbonation and a slightly bitter aftertaste .

almost sweet smell maybe a little hint of pine . nice citrus taste butt the hops were almost overpowering at first butt after a few seemed to flow nicely .  a - gorgeous beer . pours a deep , dark brown , nearly black . the head is dark brown and is very aggressive and lasts quite a while , eventually subsiding to large bubbles .  mouthfeel is ok. a bit too lean on the finish , but still decent .

the smell was surprisingly not strong . a little sweet ( malts ) , some coffee , but nothing very distinctive .  9.4 oz bottle into a flute glass . pours a gorgeous , burnt copper hue with hints of orange and deep pink around the edges . amazing depth to the color of this brew . lots of carbonation seeping up from below makes for a well retained cap of foam .  nice clear beer . they filter well at this brewery . the taste is caramel notes finishing with hops on the tongue . is this a winter warmer asks the alstrom brothers ? i think not . a drinkable red ale that delivers the goods .

s - the nose is only there for a moment but it is enough to give you a preview of the flowers used during the brewing process . t - the front of your tongue gets the lavender , then as it moves to the back the sweet honey appears .  i got a beautiful pour from this beer , resulting in two fingers of thick , light-tan head . the color was a deep , cola-brown with lovely garnet highlights .  m : a little too thin , but passable for a nut brown ale d : good , complex flavor , nothing overwhelming , but it feels like something 's missing .

this is n't a good omen , but i was actually suprised as this is the first beer i have had from gray 's that actually smells like the style its supposed to be . a nice bit of oatmeal , chocolate , and smoked black malts . this beer is god awful tasting , super sour and vinergery , hopefully a bad bottle , but i know its a fresh sample so this does n't bode well for this beer . undrinkable , drain pour it !  i had this beer poured from a bottle into a snifter ... a : the beer pours a pitch black color , with a large fluffy mocha color head which is sticking all over the glass , may be one of the best looking beers i have seen ... s : the smell is of chocolate malt , maybe some sweet chocolate and a light earthy , not a brett earthly , but like a dirty fresh smell , hard to describe !  there is n't much to the feel of this beer , it 's light bodied , but smooth and pleasant so i have trouble scoring this higher than average .

bitterly hoppy aroma with some scent of fresh cut grass , along with a slight biscuit scent , and a bit of sugary malts that reminds me of wheat .  helluva head !  m - just a touch thin but the carbonation is fine .

has a mild malty smell to it .  guinness pours a black color with no light to be seen through it . what little light appears around the edges of the glass is an extremely dark reddish brown . the creamy off-white head is about one finger high and stays on top of the beer producing a good web of lacing on the glass .  average mouthful , good taste , maybe some caramel flavor to it , easy to drink several as a session beer .

nose is that of weak coffee and almond ; not very pungent .  appearance- light gold . very beautiful .  smell : coffee , roasted barley taste : coffee , roasted barley again , maybe some chocolate too mouthfeel : weird carbonation ; real small bubbles throughout drinkability : light bodied , you can have many in one night

a : black/brown dark opaque body with light lacing left by the creamy tan head s : almost scentless in my opinion ; light toffee malts and some milkiness ; maybe a hint of coffee t : burnt raw wheat w/ strong roasted coffee and hints of terra firma ; whole milk and dark chocolate are also present m : very creamy and smooth w/ a thick body that is n't too heavy d : a good solid respectable milk stout  poured a brown/amber color into my chimay glass , producing a nice fluffy 2 and a half inch white head that lingered for a bit and left a lot of lacing . very impressive !  the mouthfeel is maybe a tad thin for my liking , but drinkability is good .

pours completely pitch black this beer consumes all visible light spectrums emitted , large tan head viable forming a robust carbonation and honorable smell . aroma has hints of dark fruit/herbal/grassy/citric hops which would be a bit different than your average beer from this style . this is the worst version/beer/idea for a russian imperial stout i 've ever had .  a : dark chestnut body with a perfect mountainous tan head .  i find this to be a very clean tasting beer with good thin mouthfeel .

there seems to be very little nose on it , though - so i may have to revisit this later after living with the beer for a while . ( yes , you get the flavor of a good spiced beer , but a lot less of the guilt/abv - can you say winner ? ) i have to admit that i was skeptical at first , but i think yards has produced a real winner with this brew - well worth seeking out and tasting . as a side note , yards ' other ales of the revolution ( thomas jefferson ale , george washington porter ) are quite tasty too , so drink a bit of history today !  a : a beautiful brown color . three finger browning head that lasted most of the glass .  feels very light in the mouth , not creamy enough .

aromas of fruity malts and a bit of hops , nothing special here . has a sweet caramel flavor upfront , followed by some fruity spice , rounded out by a bit of hops .  a : black with a tan head . great retention & lacing .  mouth feel is exceptionally carbonated almost to the point of obstructing the flavor .

the smell was surprisingly weak . goes to show that i should never assume that based on the style or appearance it would have a strong scent . the nose picked up some vaguely piney hops and not much else . the taste was solid , standing up nicely to many of the better ipas i 've had .  a deep ruby blood-red with a milky white head , awesome contrast , one of the coolest looking beers i 've seen .  taste was good , mouthfeel a little thin , drinkability fine .
smell ; very faint ... slight notes of vanilla , caramel ? i 'm not picking up much .  really exceptional appearance .  mouthfeel is light and carbonated .

a - pours a translucent dark amber ... not what i was expecting for a stout , but beautiful regardless . s - not much of a smell at all . slight hints of coffee , but nothing stands out .  pours dark , chocolaty brown - completely opaque - with tons of creamy , mocha head . just gorgeous . it 's all downhill from there .  taste/mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is oddly thin and the carbonation , while crisp up front , is weak at best -- that 's not good .

smell : smells of sweet caramel malts and light baking spices like cinammon and nutmeg , slight hitns of orange as well ; smell is not especially strong though and i feel as if i 've got ta pull pretty hard from my nostrils to pick up on it .  a - ruby-red/brown color , very thick 3cm strong , stiff head . all around , it was beautiful .  been wanting to try this for quite a while ... went to boondoggles and they knew nothing ... lacing is extraordinary , low head but very stable and crazy good foam .. smug ? ... is a rich golden colour ... nice bitters ... a good beer , did n't quite meshing with the others.. another great brew from real ale..

s : underwhelming . a little weak . t : much hoppier than the aroma , with tons of bitingly resinous pine meshing with lightly sweet , biscuity malt . i just wish the aroma had delivered some more hoppiness .  nice retention and lacing . the lacing is thick hanging curtains -- absolutely gorgeous .  mouthfeel medium , if a bit light and strongly carbonated .

aroma : caramel , raisins , and some really strong booze . even as this warms , the booze is not at all well hidden in the nose and almost resembles a shot of vodka being added to the glass .  darkened orange in color , with a full lasting foam .  very little lacing , needs more carbonation and a bit too thin on mouthfeel , but very drinkable , and an excellent value as well .

smells really good .  a : pours a beautiful hazy dark amber/brown color . a two finger head forms and sticks around .  mouthfeel - medium and refreshing drinkability - i could definitely drink two or three , but that 's would probably be eenough

s- not a huge nose on this guy . some piney , slightly vegetal hops . the score is due to both the subtle smell and the vegetal hops . the vegetal smell does not come through on the tongue .  ah the beauty of a stout in your glass , all atramentous in color with the crown all frothy and light chocolate in color and after its decomposition , the velum like curtain of lace that clings so lovingly to the glass .  mouthfeel - very carbonated , light .

s- sweet , earthy notes dominate the nose . nothing offensive , but not much going on here .  pours a deep brown , nearly black color , opaque with the exception of the very base of the glass which rests a tawny brown hue . heavily carbonated , a slow gusher which makes head very quickly which makes it fun to pour . outstanding retention as well from the fine bubbled light brown sugar head .  mouthfeel is good but not good .
smells of restrained toasted chocolate and biscuit malts plus hops and alcohol vapors .  black squid ink liquid and a giant three finger head .  this brew is a bit thin otherwise .

s - almost nothing . wet dog , metallic grain with hint of sweetness . very faint though .  this is a beautiful looking stout , a non aggressive pour yields a huge 5 finger light brown head with serious lacing .  body is medium and carbonation is very active..a bit too active for me .

s : the beer has a bit of roastedness and some alcohol , but really not much else . smells like your basic stout .  excellent lace and retention . very good looking bber .  the mouthfeel is thus fairly thin , but finishes with a nice clean dryness .

i could smell the hops from a foot away during the pour . does n't seem overcomplex , just a strong quality hop aroma with citrus grapefruit undertones .  i love sour , and this beer had sour in spades , but it also had a kind of cloying sweetness that i found unpleasant and difficult to drink . it poured black with a fine sticky head .  on the palate the beer feels light and thing , and a subtle malt flavor yields to a building , albeit , not overpowering bitterness that is highly drinkable but nothing special .

the smell is incredible in that it would rival any trappist dark brown . malt , ginger bread , and dried fruits as well as deep floral smells abound .  a- pours a jet black with a one finger mocha colored head .  the flavor is malty and fruity with an emphasis on bananas and citrus . the palate is typical of the style . the aftertaste is bread like and a little sweet but fairly dry for a hefe .

s - kind of sweet and maybe malty but the smell was very weak and hard to distinguish . m - very smooth with medium carbonation d - i started off worried about this one after pouring it and giving it a good smell . nothing too impressive until it actually hit my tongue .  full sail imperial stout , brewer 's reserve served at cellar temperature in a stone irs glass ( tulip style ) . appeared true black , no light getting through , with a nice stratified head ; a frothy burnt crme layer overlays bubbly yellow-brown , below which is only darkness . excellent .  very light mouthfeel , but spritzy .

ca n't get much smell but i do detect some wheat malts , slight citrus and hops . a great lawnmower beer .  opaque black with a large , dark cocoa colored head . looks like what i picture an archetypal imperial stout to be .  mouthfeel was just ok though .

s - unable to pick out anything significant . t - wonderfully smooth . nice clean caramel taste .  it pours a somewhat hazy dark amber , almost coppery , with a thick , fine-bubbled , persistent off-white head ; haziness seems to increase a little as it sits in the mug i was using to sample this brewski .  aroma of chocolate malts , coffee , mild hops . starts with a creamy chocolate and coffee taste . finishing light to medium body with hop bitterness .

i only really got malt in the nose . sweet flavor that has a lot of roasted malt as is to be expected in the bock .  a very sexy orange hazy pour with a tiptop offwhite head and sexy lacing .  m : do n't exactly know how to judge mouthfeel yet either but i promise to work on it .

the smell is at turns complex and bewildering . it 's very sweet , with a perfumey , flowery scent and a strange spice that lies heavy over everything . pungent and rich , complex and puzzling .  pours a rich dark caramel with a great creamy half-inch head ... .exceptional for high abv smell is rich , mainly malty , almost molasses-like .  m - high carbonation and medium to full body .

aroma : somewhat vague blend of hops but with a slight off-odor . t - both citrus and pine notes suggest multiple hops { the brewer says `` four kinds of american hops '' } . o - dale 's pale ale is easy to recommend for `` no glass '' situations when one needs canned beer and wants one that is hoppy .  poured a deep golden cider color with a thick off white head .  mouthfeel is tingly , aftertaste is of chocolate and hops .

s : smells like pizza . oregano , pizza dough , mozzarella cheeze , tomato sauce , garlic , and herbs . t : light herbs , garlic , pizza dough , tomato sauce , and mozzarella cheeze .  best head on a beer i 've ever seen . looks like icing on the cake or the top of an icecream float .  mouthfeel : too smooth drinkability : great .

aroma is light and faint black coffee .  can poured into a pint glass . pours a bright , crisp orange-tinted amber . huge ( two to three finger ) rocky , foamy , off-white head that 's taking it 's time diminishing . a solid , drinkable beer , and the light body actually boosts the drinkability rating .  ) different malts , so that explains that ) mouthfeel - this beer is a bit on the watery side .

s- very faint citrus hops with a light buttery caramel malt . t- very sweet butter/ caramel malt balanced nicely with a slightly bitter grapefruit citrus hop finish .  pours a dark brown with ample carbonation and sea foam two finger head . the lacing is very nice as well .  but i ca n't ... the carbonation is out of control and really thins out the body . the mouthfeel is crisp and dry .

s : very subtle fruity sweetness , increases as you approach the bottom . t : sweet caramel , bready , finishes with just a hint of banana .  finally , a stout that claims to taste like chocolate that actually does . this one pours a beautiful viscous inky jet black . the chocolate mousse coloured head is a joy to behold .  it had a medium mouthfeel , which was nice , but the taste was a combination of perfume , bubble gum and cereal . the finish was dry , but it left a lingering taste of cereal in my mouth .

i 've never been a fan of the ipa because of the bitterness , but i 've been trying them more and more and the taste has rapidly grown on me . the smell is a little dull , but i pick up that typical citrus aroma with some hops .  pours black with creamy light brown head .  m - mouthfeel is where this beer is lacking for me .

i had this beer on tap at the elm city brew pub this past weekend while i was in nh for the weekend a - this beer looked just like an irish stout should , very very dark ruby red in color , and a nice creamy looking head s - again like most stouts there was n't much there in the scent . you could make out the roasted barely a bit and a little cream but that 's about it t - this is an excellent tribute to the irish stouts ( guinness , beamish & murphy 's ) it has the dry taste expected from this style while at the same time having a maltier character to it . nice and smooth all the way down , and the head managed to stay all the way down as well m - this was the only area i thought this beer could be improved , most stouts feel heavy in your mouth , this was much more the consistency of an english bitter d - a very drinkable beer , i had 3 over the course of an hour and a half or so and wanted more , excellent work elm city  one of the very best pilsner heads i 've ever seen lies atop a very hazy honey yellow pilsner .  m : light-medium with avg carbonation .

s - predominantly pine hops a slight malty note as well . it is about what i would expect from a solid apa .  stout like appearance , deep black , with a fluffy/foamy head , looks great .  this beer was extremely disappointing . neither toasty , nor full bodied . i expected the sense of fall in germany , but instead ... it tastes more like a pilsner . there is little depth and complexity to the beer , although it is very drinkable as it has a nice , crisp aftertaste . ... especially from a beer brewed in munich [ home of oktoberfest itself ] .

poured absolutly black with a decent tan head has a sweet aroma to it with roated barley character that you would typically find in a dry stout but does have a subtle hop aroma .  blonde body with just carbonation shooting to the top of the glass . head is a very frothy about 4 finger head , after a non-aggressive pour . retention is outstanding , which i expected and lacing is oustanding . just a picture perfect beer .  mouthfeel is spritzy in its carbonation and aggressive across the top of the palate , which seems to collide with the inherently thick body and expected smoothness of a big stout .

smell : aroma is an aromatic hop with spice presence . pine detected . overall aroma character is a little thin for and ipa .  from an aggressive pour into an oversize wine glass produced a massive +3 fingers worth of head and almost when over the top of the glass . good amount of lacing with head receding but never completely going away leaving a sort of foam island in the center of the glass .  this beer is pretty complex but overall the feel is a bit thin and the flavor a bit too roasty for my preference .
smell of grapefruit , blossoms and hops .  a - pours an amazing brilliant hazy golden color with a large lasting white head and great lacing .  the mouthfeel is weak similar to others in class .

s - sweet malt , vanilla , and a touch of spices . fairly diminutive nose , not much going on here , even after it 's warmed a bit .  poured to a hazy golden color , with huge , white pillowy head that lingered through entire beer , and left excellent lacing .  poured from a 12 oz bottle into a imperial pint glass . has notes of citrus and pine hops plus some apricot hints in there too . first taste it has upfront hop taste like a 90 minute ipa with a smooth fruity taste on the finish . this beer is a very refreshing ipa with a not to much fruit back but just enough to make it refreshing .

payed 15 $ for a 12pack at my local grocery store . thought it might be a quality dark beer from the makers of guiness , boy was i wrong ! you might catch a hint of hops in this if you meditate for several hours before drinking , but i doubt it .  all photoshop-labeling issues aside ( this is some of the worst artwork i 've ever seen from any brewery ) this is one gorgeous beer once evacuated : slowly enveloping 2 '' pillow head atop a dulled gold . lace forms as i swirl the glass , prodding with my sniffer .  m- carbonation is on the low side for an ipa , thin body .

very light on the nose . some sweet corn notes , a bit of another grain , and a bit of mustiness .  this is easily the most balanced beer i 've ever tasted , malts and hops are both nicely apparent , neither one dominating the other , flavor profile is nicely between a pilsner and a helles . beautiful dark gold color , nice aroma of malt and floral hops , absolutely delicious , this is probably my favorite everyday beer .  mouthfeel : very carbonated , the amount of sugar can be felt on the tounge .

nose : spicy hop aromas all over the place , some minty/eucalyptus notes and dried hop pellets . decent , probably better from the bottle ?  i wish every beer could look this good .  the mouthfeel is nice , it 's well-carbonated and prickly on the mouthfeel .

s : a clean aroma with a strong toasty/toffee presence . no hop aroma .  poured a dark red/amber color with a frothy beige head and sediment floating around .  the carbonation was much too high for the style ( seems to be a trend with australian versions of british beers ) but the remainder of the mouthfeel was okay . would make a great session beer at 3.8 % abv and packed with plenty of flavour .

nice chocolate scent , but that 's about it .  very good looking beer .  thin mouthfeel , just washes around in your mouth - i was hoping for big and beefy , but at least it makes for good drinkablity , this could be a session beer .

smell : buttery malt with grapefruit and other citrus/fruit , but there 's also a strong soapy aroma that takes a lot away .  pours a hugely pretty dark , candy red . just -- i 've never seen a beer that was this goddamn red .  m : thinner side of medium in body , carbonation is medium as well but falls off fast .

not really impressed with the aroma . cooked veggies a wet paper fight with and win out against toasted pumpernickel and brown sugar .  amazing look . s : interesting nose - smells of faint citrus but may have some element of melon present ?  m-a bit more carbonated than i expected . body is medium , nothing special here . the carbonation makes it a bit filling . very good beer overall .

i was disappointed in the aroma- i was n't getting much but a light , malty odor .  this beer was crystal clear and looked perfect ! s : big hop aroma of the earthy , woodsy , piney variety .  the mouthfeel is medium with sharp bubbly champagne-like carbonation .
