sam adams came up with one that won my heart over with the double bock . if you do n't like beers that use a sweet taste to cover their high alcohol content steer clear of this one . my only critisisms of it would come from the mouthfeel . it tends to be a bit thick for my taste , but you ca n't have it all i suppose .  one and a half finger head fluffy white head . lots of lacing .  mouthfeel is a tad thin , and contributions in body and mouthfeel from the oats are n't noticeable .

it seemed like the perfect day for a deep , smoky rich beer , instead of a porter , as i had some great lamb meatloaf awaiting me . instead , a bright coppery pour to dark honey lager looking 0.5l stein came my way with a fluffy white 1 finger head on board . i thought that the aroma would be smoky as well , but only in a subtle `` if you were looking for it , you 'd notice it '' kind of way . likewise with the flavor ; only a subtle smokiness that rounded off the malt flavors in this exceptional near dunkel lager . fresh , crisp and a bit bubbly to the mouth , this is one you could drink & drink & drink ... and watch your smile grow .  this is one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen . it pours a ridiculous translucent orange .  carbonation was appropriate , maybe just a tad too sticky in the feel .

the aroma is weak swampy wheat and citrus . the flavor brings a nice balance of bitter herbal citrus hop and bready caramel malt . crisp and very drinkable , a distinctive pilsner . quite hoppy , fair bodied for the style .  pours a deep chocolate black with an outstanding head and great lacing .  light carbonation .

the aroma is weak , but decent . kind of fruity , like melon and pear , with a pale malt profile and a faint trace of hops .  22 oz bomber from newbie bif : http : //lumen.phpwebhosting.com/newbiebif.html pours a cloudy gold beer with a puffy white head , basically perfect looks for the style .  great complexity of flavors m : average medium to light body . its a good feel .

smell is almost non-existant ... just typical grain smell .  a - great golden honey-comb color with nice clarity and a fluffy , very well-retained two-finger light almond head . good carbonation flows to the left-over pile below collar after collar of thick lace .  a - light and cloudy like a thick fruit juice , small head with little to no lacing s - sweet and pleasant t - refreshingly sour , a little thin at the end but a pleasant bitter flavor helps to hide it m - slightly over-carbonated and thin d - very refreshing , easy to drink , would be a great session beer on a hot day or while tailgating .

smell is a turn-on , big piney hop notes , makes me want to go roll around in a conifer forest . a disappointing mess .  appearance : wonderfully dark with a slight cream colored head .  creamy on the palate , perhaps a bit too heated for mass consumption , but overall quite well done .

enticing orange grapefruit followed by passion fruit aroma . ca n't get enough of sniffing this one ! rate this one very good , and did i mention that the aroma is heavenly !  it poured a hazy light golden color with an amazingly fluffy head that stayed and stayed .  m : mouthfeel is really where this beer takes a hit .

the smell is light straw smell with a bit citrus edge . very faint smelling , not too strong a stink . the hops in this show up much more in the flavor than the smell . the bitter herbal resinous hops rest underneath a crisp citrus edge on top .  a brilliant looking beer .  imitation maple . : ( there are good qualities in the taste and smell ; this would be a pretty good brown ale if it were not for the flavoring . the same goes for the overall feeling for this beer it would be an ok beer with some good qualities if it were not for the awful fake flavor .

the smell is passive , with hints of apple , bread and belgian yeast .  bottle : poured a deep brown/burgundy color ale with a super large foamy head with some exceptional retention and great lacing .  `` you will get some hop burps from this one '' mouthfeel a bit on the light side , with a tangy carbonation spike .

s - dark malt and nutty yeast . some other elements i cant quite put my finger on ... this beer 's weak point imho .  poured into a tulip glass . wesley snipes black . a beautiful bronze head that glimmers and cascades across the surface . a lot of lacing .  had 2 drafts of this beautious brew at `` point brugge cafe '' in the point breeze section of pittsburgh yesterday for brunch ... a surprisingly light yellow/straw color for what is usually an amber beer ... ( mind you , i 've just been to the penn brewery o-fest where their o-fest is a definite amber hue ... ) really impressive fine foam head ( a la nitrogen charged beers ... ) i love that .. really love it ... lends to better taste ... a quintessential marzen i feel ... malty germanic goodness with slight citrusy essence in the mid-palate and a nice clean finish ... the 6 % abv is apparent as i felt nice after 2 drafts ! @ girlfriend and i are going to get a case of this in the bottles for this weekend , we 're that impressed ... although i know i 'm in for a big disappointment with the bottled version ... bottled beer never as good as kegged versions ... . : ( session beer to the extreme ... . !
smells candy sweet with some jammy fruit notes .  this is dark with a big head that sticks to everything . this is one damned beautiful beer .  m : a bit light - almost watery .

s : slightly grainy/grassy . nothing special t : very good . a slight hoppiness comes on as it lingers . this one truly has `` drinkability . '' if you 're going for one of the two brews from metropolitan , i 'd recommend this over the dynamo , but try both if you get the chance .  poured into a guiness pint glass , absolutly the darkest of dark stouts . has an amazing lacing potential ... smell is a smooth roasted smell .  mouthfeel is nice . carbonation is just a bit above medium level and a bit too high . nice above average body .

aroma is malty sweet with plenty of fruitty esters and a hint of alcohol .  bottle , decanted into my trusty duvel glass ... marvelously clear . color is like bourbon-spiked iced tea . tiny carbonation bubbles floating up from the etched 'd . ' amazing .  i love kolsch , but this one does n't quite add up . clean on the palate with a pleasant herbal dryness . finish is rather short but crisp . still very refreshing and thirst quenching , but that is to be expected from probably any example of the style . good to see another addition to the domestic kolsch list but this one is miles behind pyramid curve ball and others .
s - sour apple juice . shockingly low smell .  after settling , a perfect golden-copper color with a two finger head forms .  m : a little watery , but i do prefer thicker drinks .

smells like a run of the mill american wheat with the slightest hint of fruits .  black body . thick , dense cap of dark brown froth .  ponderosa ipa . let me start this review with a nod to the brewewrs for keeping an ipa on tap at all times . average is the best blanket statement . but an average ipa is better than most mass-marketed beers . and by average i do n't want you to think it is n't good . i have seen many people try it and realize that an ipa ( and hops in general ) do n't have to be intimidating . but hopheads looking for the holy grail of ipa 's will have to keep searching ... consistant brewing is what pbc has always offered .

a beautiful beer , dark red mixed with a brown almost purple with scarlet swirls of sediment . mouthfeel and drinkability are very impressive and the carbonation is right on , have to hold back from chuging this guy . a dubbel light if their is a category , perfect for fall .  pours a brilliant and bright gold with an impressive rich and fluffy pure white head .  very light mouthfeel .

very light aroma of slightly roasted malt , bread , caramel .  pours a nice dark amber , the smell is heavily bready .  the mouthfeel is ok does n't really stick to your mouth , but the taste lastes awhile .

no noticable hop aroma . the beer has a very distinct yeast taste to the tongue but no after taste . overall a good beer but no wow factor !  a : a nice cloudy orange/yellow color with a two finger white head that sticks around . some great lace as well .  adequate carbonation ... decent drinkability , more a sipper than something you 'd want a few of , but a beer i 'll definitely seek out again ( especially considering its very reasonable price ) .

s - there 's some honey , roasted malts , slight chocolate . t - chocolate , bitterness/bittersweet , some honey sweetness , and theres some spice ( actually maybe spicy ) m - creamy , medium in body , low carbonation .  pours a wonderful copper color topped by a wonderful head . there is unparalleled head retention and gorgeous lacing .  lighter in body .

a light 1 finger head w/ plenty of lacing smell : pretty decent smell of caramel , spice and hops .  pours a pitch black with a thin brown head into my glass . black is always a good color for beer .  a little lighter in the mouth than i would like .

aroma is a little soapy and mineraly . as far as taste goes , this is one of my favorite oktoberfests made by any brewery . i 'd say the only things this beer lacks is some aroma and a more authentic german feel .  poured into a tulip glass from a 750ml bottle . a - this is one of the most attractive beers i 've ever seen . there is a nice thin 1/4 of an inch dark dark brown head that sticks around for a bit with some nice dense and frothy bubbles .  the mouthfeel was extremely creamy since it was a nitro tap but i think it could have used a little bit more carbonation .

( s ) - not much on the nose . some sweet caramel malt and dry , almost earthy biscuit bits . very subtle pine .  a- deep dark rich black and slight mohohgany with a full three fingers of head s- sweet chocolate and coffee , raisons molasses and red fruit .  i like a good lambic and a good sour , but this was way beyond anything i 've ever tried before . worst beer i 've ever tried .

`` superior hoppy belgian blond '' is printed along the side . the nose does not keep pace , as it is disappointingly mild , with just a hint of fruit and spice , but nothing identifiable as hops . the mouth is very prickly and slightly syrupy , leaving a bit of residue on the tongue . what a nice change of pace in belgium .  frothy baige head of about 1 inch with great retention and lace .  taste , the same except with raspberry syrup added . has an unpleasant twang . i dont believe i would even take one for free . well not if there was any other option available that is .

i was after christian to make a pils from the day lancaster malt brewing opened . it would probably look better in a pilsner glass and when i take the occaisional jug home , that 's what i use . gold star is one of the reasons east central penna is the pilsner capital of the new world .  the beer is black and pours with a beautiful dark brown head that clings to the glass as you tip it .  mouthfeel suffers as a result .

light spicy , malty nose .  pours a red/amber hue with a billowing white head of three or four fingers that has a pinkish hue . great retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with sharp carbonation .

s : sweet boozy molasses , chocolate , oak and a hint of play doh . t : sweet and hot .  this beer pours a huge head with amazing retention and a nice golden color .  the mouthfeel was light but with heavy heavy carbonation .

the smell was ok , but did n't have that light fruity appeal of a normal tripel .  2/14/2010 hair of the dog adam old world ale 10 % abv a=5 pours a huge ever lasting head with incredible lacing .  it may be a bit too carbonated , though .

roasted coffee/sour cherry nose . roasted/burnt coffee , sour cherry syrupy flavor , no aftertaste .  poured into a mj tasting glass ( tulip ) . pours a hazy yellow with orange highlights . big fluffy white head , that stands up and drops very slowly . leaves big chunky pieces of lacing .  the body is surprisingly and disappointingly thin for such an otherwise huge beer .

fresh yeast and a hint of orange hit the nose ; the flavor is well balanced , albeit understated , with repressed hops and creamy malts coating the mouth .  2011 vintage a- pours a bright orange with a massive fluffy head , very tight bubbles , thick and sticky lacing all over the glass .  the mouthfeel came off a little light and felt a bit watered down . the initial aroma was very pleasing and my only real complaint about this one was the mouthfeel being a little too light .

s-black cherries , malt and an almost buttery aroma . there is a pleasant hop smell that mixes with the subtle alcohol notes near the end . also smell granny smith apples and burnt sugar .  a : pretty awesome pour of a deep dark mahogony brown beer topped by a head of tiny bubbles forming a perfect head/beer boundary .  mouthfeel could be better , severely low carbonation .

smells pleasant , but subtle .  nice dark opaque amber with a massive head you have to control ... 2 fingers at least of slightly off white foam atop the glass which melts slowly to sticky lacing .  the texture was thick , and left a thin film in my mouth almost like when you eat too much syrup .

nose is cola based , must be the malt base shining through . slight smell of spices linger in the background , maybe mace which is a derivative of the nutmeg fruit , and nutmeg is used in the syrup found in coca cola .  with a dark reddish brown color and a very sweet aroma . the pour left a good head with very good lacing all the way down the glass .  mouthfeel light body with a bit of carbonation .

s - very , very light citrus notes as well as yest .  a : pours a clear bubbly golden , with a huge , long-lasting , frothy white head .  mouthfeel was somewhat effervescent but that was the only thing average about the beer .

little vanilla , mucho funk t : bad . infected all the way . big funky infection totally masked about 90 % of the flavor here .  appearance : pours a deep mahogany brown with hints of ruby and a fluffy tan 3 finger head . great head retention . very nice lacing throughout .  the mouthfeel was lacking , i was hoping for a heavier beer , but this medium light feel was ok .

it did n't have too much of an aroma to it but it was pleasant in appearance and the flavor had just a little bit of something different about it .  head is brown as well . impressively transparent . very visually appealing .  m. disappointing that there was n't much head and carbonation . tastes almost flat .

drinkability : the swampy aromas are a titch offputting , but the taste is nice .  a : deep opaque coffee brown with a beautiful frothy tan head of 2-fingers that settles into a 1/2-finger lace . glorious .  poured from a 750 to a sierra nevada hop etched glass . good to see that haze in a commercial beer , makes me feel better about my homebrew not being super clear . big citrus in the nose , grapefruit and orange predominant among those smells . the malt is more hidden in the background than in the regular 90min , and the is a bit of booze smell in there as well . despite the hop aroma , it is not at all overly bitter tasting . curacao in the citrus flavor , with a bit of almost orange rind bitter at the end .

aroma - started off with a decent citrusy burst , but quickly died down . now only emitting a faint citrus and biscuity-type smell .  pours a mahogany color with a big , frothy , ivory head .  the palate is thin but acceptable .

a beer haiku for you : '' unfortunate ale ; leave this bad boy in brooklyn ! looked and smelled good : taste ?  looks like a really nice refreshing beer .  nice clean alcohol as it warms or as i feel it ... not sure which is having that effect on the taste : -/ dry , mildly carbonated and very much the viscosity of water .

smell : bready hoppy nose . some horse stable aroma . not my favorite smell .  a- pours a pitch-black hue with brown highlights , head is brown , foamy and pillowy monster that is reminiscent of a wendy 's frostie , good retention , moderate lacing on the glass s- nose is big time malts- cocoa , coffee , molasses , brown sugar , some dark chocolate bitterness and a touch of citrus in the background ( reminds slightly of a karl straus chocolate-orange porter firkin ) t- initial taste is bitter dark chocolate and espresso , followed up by some tart and dark fruit flavors ( fig/plum/cherry ) that are a bit of a surprise , and finishes with slight hop dryness m- surprisingly light-to-medium bodied , texture is watery-to-creamy , and carbonation is subtle d- solid and tasty porter that is easy to drink , i think it captures the style well but is not ground-breaking on any front , a touch too bitter for my taste , but a good overall performer buy again ?  nose is malt and honey , some gentle spiciness , licorice . quite nice . taste is malty and pleasantly sweet . finishes up with a subtle , dty licorice flavour . good as a one off . too sweet to drink a ton of , but interesting enough to be worth a try .

not a whole lot happening , would have liked a bigger nose . t : very nice sweetness up front , ending in a very subtle roasted bitterness . where i was disappointed with the lack of `` bigness '' in the nose , i am actually happy that the taste is kept simple and accents the those residual sugars .  growler into allagash chalice : a : absolutely beautiful opaque golden-orange body with a nice looking off-white head with good retention and lacing .  m : the body is quite light for the strength . less carbonation would help .

this one poured and a slight head rose and disapered almost emeaditly i sweriled it from a stemed goblet to grasp the smell . the smell and taste worked well togother , this one is good but three pholofisers is better  the retention was outstanding and the lacing in curtains , an excellent looking beer falsely pumped up by nitro jets , like a woman with fake d cups .  it is very carbonated with lots of bubbles coming up throughout . my other major complaint is that the beer itself is a light in feel , i want it a little more robust . overall , this is very good and reminds me a lot of insanely bad elf . a highly drinkable winter ale that packs a great alcohol punch . needs a little tweaking on the feel and to give the aroma some oompf but so close .

smells mostly of coffee but slightly of chocolate .  the beer looks beautiful with a generous billowy head and a cloudy copper color . the chimay chalice really does justice to the way this beer is supposed to look .  mouthfeel- a little syrupy , with some sand.. drinkability- not coors light . gulp gulp , ph

the smell is of light bread , and the taste is slightly corny , but also slightly bready , almost as if they had soaked wonderbread in water and then bottled it .  ceremonially decanted in a snifter , the `` holy water '' takes shape with bubbling alacrity , it wears a deep pollen-crusted yellow orange hue , like the hot cadmium heart of a van gogh sunflower . the head is fair and delights when the drinker tips his glass , for it quickly scribbles in chalky lace some memorized stanza of medieval prose .  medium bodied very average to little carbonation .

bire de couleur rose-orang avec la plus grande quantit de levure et de grumeaux de peau de bleuets que j'ai vue de ma vie , on dirait un porto vintage de 20 ans qui aurait t brass . nez fruit aigre , en bouche on se bat avec des grumeaux c'est dsagrable .  single bottle of 2006 batch purchased from martignetti's appearance = exceptional looking deep , dark cherry reddish/brown . tiny bubbles rise up creating a very impressive appearance .  deep dark brown color with sweet chocolate aroma , the prominent caramel sweet roast flavors make up for a lighter body than most stouts .

smell : the smell is rather soft ... minimal amount of grass , some hops , and some fruit in the background , but it 's rather subdued .  appearance : i 'd say it 's the blackest beer i 've ever seen . it has the darkest brown head too . as a genius once said , `` none more black .  lots of different flavors coming through beer is way over carbonated which messes up the smoothness . flavors were great , smelled good , looked nice , but the carbonation was my only problem .

smell : interesting , mostly i 'm mostly getting a toasted malt smell , but there is something else , maybe from the belgian yeast . this is n't the best smelling beer . taste : very nice . toasted maltiness upfront followed by a spicy/peppery finish . lived up to the nice appearance and suprised after the let down on smell . mouthfeel : medium body drinkability : very drinkable .  tasted in mid-april 2009. almost black , very dark brown , with red/orange tint under the light . large , light tan head , fades to constant , thin foamy layer . amazing lacing .  mouthfeel is mild with little carbonation .

purchased the cork and caged bottle for $ 8.99 at 101 bottles in kent . lots of heavy bourbony fusel alcohol and maybe a hair of vanilla . overall this is a really satisfying beer , with a great value , though i could n't drink it very often .  has a great clear brown color with hints of ruby red .  smooth feel but i thought the body was a little too light .

fantastic lacing and head retention smell : slight malt tones and stale hops smell . slight peppery notes as it warms .  two finger rocky head that dies down to a nice layer of foam on top . retains slightly better than cascade . lots of lacing let behind .  it truly does hold that `` summer-time '' feel . the pour produced a nice rich white head which lasted for quite sometime . as it drank down , the lacing left just a soft amount on the glass , but it 's to be expected from this wheat beer . i would recommend this to anyone looking for a nice , clean , and refreshing evening beer to accompany good `` porch-sitting weather '' of the summer months .

for a really cheap beer , it is really good , and worth drinking . i am not a huge fan of dunkel 's , but this one was really good . i drank this beer very cold and i recommend drinking it cold .  a huge , two-finger plume of glossy mocha head forms and lasts very well while slowly settling to a tight , half-finger cap of foam .  loads of caramel and toffee with some bready malt detectable . there is also a slight alcohol note . overall this beer was decent but not one of my favorites . just a bit too sweet .
aroma is n't bad . some fruit and sours .  i think this is one of the most gorgeous looking beers .  thin malt backbone . carbonation is relatively high .

i did n't notice the smell -- neither good nor bad -- so i 'm going to dry-hop it just a little with willamette .  excellent retention and equally good lacing .  m - medium bodied with a medium carbonation level . lighter on the tongue than i expected .

smell : grass , hopps , and lemon . yeastie and sweet but very light .  appearance : volcanic opening of the bottle - it was still spuming even after half the liquid had been poured ; pours a cloudy toffee brown color with a mountainous head that leaves lacing all over the glass and remains intact throughout the tasting smell : pears and apples , leather and yeasty notes emerge from the brew taste : starts out with an orchard fruit flavor with a touch of caramel ; after the swallow , some earthy bitterness steps in along with some sour lemon flavors and mixes with some chocolate hints ; the finish is long-lasting mouthfeel : medium bodied but a bit too fizzy ( the offset of the great visuals ) drinkability : a very nice and distinctive effort that casts a vote for what 's good about english brews ; for those who are arguing that it is more an esb than an english pale , i disagree - according to the bjcp , english pale is often considered to be the bottled version of esb and this beer 's abv and carbonation levels are too low and high , respectively , to fall squarely within the esb category ( best by 7/18/06 so i have a relatively fresh bottle thanks to the dedicated efforts of knightly spirits in orlando .  malty , slightly bitter ... a good sort of bitter mouth feel.. medium carbonation . thin to medium body .

slightly sweet , malty aroma with a slight nuttiness .  poured from .5l into stout-style glass in the mid-40 degree range . 2f of tan head over a deep brown cola-colored body . really nice lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery for a brown ale .

the smell was kind of ansent , but there were malty hints .  a : poured a dark ruby color with an inch of fluffy caramel-colored head . it had long-lasting retention and left huge gobs of foam down the sides of the glass .  served from a 2 liter flip top bottle bought at the brewery , poured into a pint glass bought from the brewery . light amber color in glass , hazy finish . big head that dissipated quickly , little lacing on glass . light aroma of citrus on pour . went down quickly , i was surprised how fast i finished the first pint . a typical wheat , but a good pint none the less .

very light straw yellow with a semi-smeared clearness to its moderate bubbly body . crisp , clean nose . adequate but impartial strength of grains and a dantily tilting spicy/herbal/grassy saaz induced hopping . more of a corn-like sweetness emerges after a period of warming . overall , mild , clean , sweet , and perky with that certain zip of saaz hopping that 's traditionally found in a czech pils character .  this baby from stone is definitely a stout . it 's extremely dark brown in color , with a big caramel-colored head that bubbles nicely for three minutes before forming a lace that stays on the glass all the way through .  the mouth-feel was not great as the beer seemed a little thin .

cloudy , yet easy to see through . nutty , hints of tea with subtle sweet spices : nutmeg , cinnamon . easy to drink . well balanced . the beginning is more of an intro .  a terrific deep and burnt umbre with tremendous clarity topped by a dense head that receded over a minute .  awesome job with this one , not quite as risky as i would have liked , but very unique flavors m - very light , extremely easy to go down . could be improved , very carbonated and bubbly d - outstanding , once you get over it being over carbonated the true flavor comes bounding out of all corners leaving no rock unturned .

a- hazy golden orange with a good sized off white head s- floral and citrus hops , a little bit of sweetness . not as strong as i would have imagined or liked . the flavor is amazing . its so smooth , and downright refreshing . a great example of the style and one ive had time and time again .  great retention and great lacing .  surprisingly light body , dry but a bit fizzy mouthfeel - this makes the beer seem lighter than it really is ...

smell : nothing particularly special here , retry tommorow .  the beer pours a deep black color , with a beautiful sparkling , dark brown 3 finger thick head , that reduces to a very thin head during drinking .  the hop aroma lays , subtly there in the background t : cocoa , toasted nuts hints of earthy bitterness that make this a very well balanced brew m : medium bodied beer with average carbonation overall , this is a good sessionable beer , i think ill get this again

nice yeasty yellow with a banana scent and taste that is not too much .  330 ml bottle , 5 % alcohol this is a beautiful beer ( to taste and to look at ) .  the flavor is nicely malty in addition to the rest , but the body is significantly thinner than that of its bigger brother , the 10 .

hoegaarden is a classic and fairly reasonable . i find myself gaining new appreciation for this beer all the time . very smooth with a delicious head , it leaves a wonderful taste without challanging the palate too much . i would take it over a hackerpschorr any day .  it pours into the glass with a dark amber brown body topped by a medium thick head with a good amount of lacing left behind on the glass .  sufficient carbonation , low effervesence , medium-bodied , but a bit oily .

the nose consists of some hops and a hint of sweet malts . sort of an apple land caramel like smell . it does finish off very dry and makes you thirsty for more beer , but when a beer taste this good you do n't mind going back for seconds .  poured a glowing golden orange color with huge carbonation and a fluffy white head .  probably the only product bells makes that i dislike . it smelled like chocolate covered cherries , very delicious . but the taste , whoa step back . bitter and thick as hell with an overwhelming cherry taste ( and aftertaste ) . good lord this crap is bad .

s : aromas are quite muted , but what is detectible are malts and some sort of tinny , metallic aroma . not overly pleasant , so i 'm thankful the aromas are muted .  a : pours a deep black colour with only a little bit of light shining through the edges . 2 fingers of dense ivory head and lots of lacing .  mouthfeel was unexceptional .

the smell was a bit weak , with just a hint of malt & sweetness .  exceptional appearance because the head was roaring .  more sweet than sour ; it has a predominant taste of cherry m - does n't linger as much as other , imo , more complex sours/lambics .

s : cascade hops , not much else . t : good malt background that balances perfectly with the citrus hops sierra nevada is known for .  pours a super dark burgundy color with more of a lighter cranberry color at the thinner spots of the glass . a nice light tan , creamy head fades a bit and leaves layers of thick lace .  mouthfeel ... keeping in mind it was brief was ok but drinkability was awful , i could not finish the bottle and poured the rest down the drain , i think my taste buds are ruined for the day .

cheers to rmalinowski4 for sending this my way review adapted from notes taken 11/13/11 appearance : this is the most red beer i 've ever seen , ever - it 's a rich , dark red - off-white , kind of pink head , keeps a bubbly cap - minimal lacing , especially as it warms smell : borderline disturbing , but also good - so , so much cherry - like a bowl of cherries floating in cherry juice topped with cherry jam and flavored cough syrup - more or less no hint of malt , just cherries - a touch of sour , too - kind of scary , unpleasant until i actually tasted the beer taste : absolutely ridiculous - so much cherry - kind of reminds me of a cherry popsicle - tons of cherry , but the overall taste is better than just the cherry flavor - tastes like carbonated cherry juice , maybe a carbonated cherry pie , utterly no hint of alcohol - it 's kind of a stretch to call this beer - a little tart - sweet , but not excessively so for half a 750ml mouthfeel : medium body , crisp carbonation , juicy , sticky cherry juice overall : is this beer ? the smell is a little intimidating , but the flavor is excellent .  pours a crude-oil black with fantastic toxic chemical looking head . great retention and lacing . right on the edge of totally repulsive and totally loveable , this is a damn fine brew .  mf : light body , medium carbonation o : tasty , well balanced and easy drinking .

smell is mildly fruity , not that great .  a : cloudy and orange-amber in color with a beautiful 2-finger head of pillowy tan foam . head shows great retention and leaves sticky lacing trails all the way down the glass .  unfortunately the mouth was just a bit too thin and too carbonated for my liking .

predominantly citrus aroma , with occasional softer hops flavors on the edges . pale ale .  pours completely opaque black with a thick mocha head that creates some nice lacing . ca n't really ask for more in terms of appearance .  the aroma is very sweet from the malts and the hops is sweet as well . for flavor the malt is sweet just like you would think from the aroma . the hops is a solid bitternes as if you were drinking an esb . over all this beer is very tasty .

first off this is not an imperial pils , not even close , its a vienna and or marzen lager.poured into a 1/2 liter stein a rich deep amber with a fluffy slight off white head that settles into a creamy mass.aromas are clean except for a little caramel malt , much cleaner than expected.very much a marzen on the palate , caramel with a bit of sweetish dough , a nice herbal sharpness of noble hop comes in a cleaner finish.much lighter than expected in the mouth wich isnt such a bad thing , this should have been made in late september , i like it .  this is a seasonal beer , a cold-weather brew made in at least 2 or 3 different years . after letting it age appropriately , this beer becomes amazing in all respects . the maltiness becomes much more assertive , giving it a sweet , smooth , and nutty finish that actually presents very similarly to that of a bourbon-barrel stout . there 's such smoothness here that i could drink them all night , if only each one did n't pack such a punch .  m : crisp and light , on the watery side of things . smooth and refereshing .

i really like the color a lot but the lack of a real head on such a hoppy beer is a bit of a disappointment . smell is sweet and fruit forward . lots of tropical fruit scents coming through as pineapple , peach and mango . some alcohol comes through the nose but it is not strong at all , just kind of lingers in the background . wow , very sweet and very barleywine-esque . reminds me of fresh 120 minute or devil dancer . overall , this is not a great dipa but it is a great barleywine ( aside from the slimey mouthfeel that is .  bottle poured into a maudite tulip glass . beautiful classic barleywine color - translucent reddish-brown with a thick off-white head and really nice lacing . absolutely perfect appearance , but sort of a sub-par beer .  m- the mouth is light to medium bodied , which is a sin in my book for a stout . lively carbonation .

for a cask beer , i do not know if it was her expertise in pouring ( pulling , actually ) or paul 's brilliance as a brewer , but this was fantastic ! on this one , i noted some ruby highlights at the bottom of the glass , along the rim , but otherwise it was straight out of the creature from the black lagoon . even the white bits were black . the nose was much more muted . it was slightly malty , but beyond that , it was anyone 's guess .  a- pours a nice light amber/copper color with a 2 finger , ridiculously puffy offwhite head .  the mouthfeel for me is the only downside for this beer .

aroma - boozy and sweet . mediocre ; very abrasive . taste - strong toffee/caramel notes .  bottle : poured a medium brown color ale with a huge foamy head with good retention and lacing .  m - feels medium-light , crisp , but just way over carbonated .

the aroma is very slightly hopped with a hint of coffee .  dark oil can appearance , nice dark tan head , taste of coffee , coco , and sweet malty goodness .  lightly bodied and over attenuated , with a lanky mouthfeel that could use additional girth . a tasty doppel , although it falls a bit short on complexity and body . drier than most , for sure .

a & s : very aromic : rich molasses , chocolate , brown sugar , toasted sugar coated almonds , and buttery bread . deep red-ish black colored beer . toasty nuts and coffee . one odd thing , at the beginning of drinking this beer at this area of time between the mid taste and the finish there is this huge blast of iron . i would buy again ( probably in the winter ) , thanks for the recommendation .  from a painted , undated 12oz into a tulip . hazy orange with lots of carbonation that supports a tall white head that does n't die and clings tenaciously to the glas as it goes down .  mouthfeel was a bit of a letdown- on the thin side and made the beer seem less substantial .

s : bouquet is quite muted , with only hints of chocolate and coffee coming through . t : semi-sweet , with heavy doses of baker 's chocolate , coffee , and caramel .  pours dark orange with a beige foamy head that leaves a coating of sticky lacing down the pint .  rich aqueous body with virtually no carbonation ( i wonder if that 's intentional ? ) , but this beer pulls it off like few could . as drinkable as such a rich beer could be , though arguably a carbonation presence would improve things .
impressive ! t : intense .  pure white head . very pretty pour .  seems a bit thin , shame , because i really like this brew . the carbonation is good just seems that it is watery .

smelled a little funky , even after pouring it . the smell was one thing i did n't enjoy but it was n't by any means bad . there was a defined peach to it but not much else identifiable .  it pours pretty much the qiuntessinial way for a ris thick , inky black body with a huge fomay tan head that sticks forever before receding to some nice thick-walled style lacing .  m : medium body , lots of prickly carbonation . a little too prickly .

looks like a hefeweizen more than anything . head dissapates quick , good lacing though . taste is very subtle but sweet . good carbonation and easy drinking in this lager . overall this beer really reminds me of great white but with less orange flavor .  leaves an inch long frothy tan head after a moderately aggressive pour . good lacing .  the mouthfeel is on the thin side , very drinkable , & coats the mouth & throat . funny that the irish dry stout is distinct from milk stouts , because i feel the style is very lactic feeling .

big lace develops during the session . smell : little aroma as some soft malt sweetness and a hint of floral hops are tough to pull from the glass . very easy to quaff and despite the mild flavor profile , and it is somewhat refreshing .  served on nitrogen draught from a stout faucet by a competent bartender , guinness stout is at it 's best . creamy , easy sippin ' , tangy , roasted , pleasantly bitter , low alcohol brew .  a slightly sweet taste and smell , and a toasty aftertaste which i had completely forgotten about over the years . not a lot of carbonation after the pour . goes good with food , especially with a local delicacy - a zweigle 's white hot .

light scent of wheat and citrus . very refreshing and drinkable .  appearance : cloudy golden color with a thick rocky head that just does n't quit even after 10 minutes . a ton of sticky lace .  m - carbonation is lacking and the mouthfeel is a bit thin compared to porters , stouts , etc .

my favorite beer for anytime is allagash white and this beer falls just shy of that beer . to be fair , i will say they have different taste , but allagash being my 10 , i will say this is my # 9 wheat beer . i do n't give props for wheat beer easily , but this is an excellent beer .  in the glass it 's got a big three-finger head with great retention and classic delicate belgian lace . the color is a beautiful , partially cloudy , golden honey amber apricot .  quite a smooth feel , but i just felt it was too thin . if this had a little more viscosity it would be a real winner for me .

a good-looking beer - very appetizing . i could n't catch much in the nose - standard malt , maybe some baked bread with a touch of nutmeg .  glorious cloudy flame colored body suffused with gamboge highlights and capped by a humongous tower of old lace merengue which recedes to a lasting multi-tiered souffle of creamy bubbles . lacing scatters all over the sides of the glass like a pollock painting .  mouthfeel : lively carbonation is on the edge of fizzy , body is a bit light , and the finish is oily .

aroma is somewhat fruity with some toasted malt notes . not as strong as some other ipa 's but it does smell `` fresh . '' flavor is well balanced and interestingly spicy ( black pepper ) moment of grains and cracker up front .  inky pitch black body with a massive beige head that cascades down to three fingers worth . retention and lacing are both excellent .  mouthfeel : meduim carbonation is shown in a bit of thickness in the mouth that dissipates quickly and leaves the mouth watering .

nice perfume character although not real assertive ; somewhat elegant in nature . medium bodied ; creamy and rich mouthfeel .  black in colour with a good tan head and good glass lacing .  the finish is lightly smoky as is the aftertaste . normally i would hesitate to add i beer i liked this much to not skew the rankings , but my wife agreed that this beer was `` special . '' we both thought it to be exceptional .

hazy yellow with a small white cap . citrus aroma . id swear there was cascades in there . wheaty and citus/spice with a nice touch of bitterness .  flash flood arrives with a full finger of smart , well-sustained head thick as lambs wool and white as cotton .  body is thick , though the carbonation is quite prickly for something this rich .
a nice , bright pale ale but the aroma lets it down .  looks excellent .  hops are apparent but not overwhelming . m - no complaints . average with a bit of bitterness .
the smell is pleasant , but not very deep .  the pour was lovely . it was completely opaque and a dark brown with a rich tan head that left some lovely lacing .  m : syrupy and almost still .

aromas are nicely caramelized amber malts with just barely a hint of hops .  poured with a 2 finger tan head and a beautiful amber mahogany translucent body . as i understand it the monks centrifuge their beer before re-pitching and bottling , makes for a wonderful presentation !  somewhat thin on the palate for the style .

not a whole lot on the nose . some hops not much oak like i was expecting .  ( served in a tulip glass ) a- this beer has a dark opaque black body with a hint of light at the base of the glass showing a warm deep brown hue . there is a sea of micro bubbles racing back and forth to the surface where a thick light tan head stands .  mouthfeel is competent . worse than corona .

s - stewed sweet fruits and yeast . t - initially bitter before giving way to lots of vanilla that is creamy and smooth , a little bitter on the finisg with some nice burnt caramel flavours .  a- pours a dense white inch tall head that has ridiculous sustainability .  m not very much mouthfeel .

light hay and grain aroma with faint lemon peel . really nice sierra twist on an esb , although not my favorite in their lineup .  a : very dark brown , almost opaque . pours with half an inch of very foamy , thick head .  like all of the baltika brews ive had the chance to sample , this ones a little rough around the edges ; the alcohol , despite being a fairly modest 5.6 % and the mouthfeel is a bit thin .

appearance is good ; opaque and burnt-orange , although it looks a little light for a dipa.smell is very mild . overall , it 's delicious - and im willing to sacrifice looks and smell for that !  pouring into a tulip from a 22 oz chilled bottle . pours a slightly ruby/honey color with a creamy , tightly-packed eggshell colored 1/2 finger thick head .  body is very light and spritzy .

bottle from sams beer and wine in carrollton ... thanks matt pours a deep dark black with about 3 fingers of head that keeps growing out of the glasss ... not much on the nose here at all , smells sweet , thats about it ... maybe a bit of barley . definitely an interesting barleywine .  pitch black opaque beer . light brown head that 's holding nicely and clinging to the glass . looks good .  mouthfeel is on the thin side for me but decent .

aroma- smells pretty much like a belgian .  750 ml bottle poured into a tulip . big three fingers of brown head appears and leaves nice lace .  the mouthfeel is too syrupy for my tastes , with an unfulfilling bite of carbonation .

faint aromas of lemonheads and generic hops fill this uninteresting ( but not offensive ) nose . congratulations wachusett on brewing one of the most unique double ipas i have ever had .  it was a beautiful looking pour but it took me a while to finish this one .  mouthfeel : just like the taste , the hop head is a very wide-ranging beer in this category . it begins each sip as a light , crisp beer and then about halfway through , just before the malt bomb explodes it seems to fizz up almost to the level of a soda . it also has a bit of an odd mouthcoating property that dries the mouth out . i would prefer that the mouthcoating feel went away in this case , but it is nowhere near strong enough to ruin the beer for me . overall : this is a strong and complex beer that keeps things interesting .

smell - creamy and fruity aroma . very satisfying , makes your mouth water .  wow how great can it be . full head and great aroma . this is a stout however and is heavy .  m : not the chewiest , certainly not thin .

smell : light malt sweetness , grass , and a hint of lemon rise from the glass .  a- absolutely gorgeous tan head that drapes the glass over a dark brown sea .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too thin .

mild , sweet , slightly raisin smell . toasty malt taste and some caramel .  just barely opaque red black , somewhere in that cola range . there is a pretty , creamy head in light brown with good substance and stickage .  m : light bodied with moderately-high carbonation .

scents are strangely weak here . what one can smell is n't bad by any stretch but it does n't tell you much about the beer . some malt , some hops and a good hit of booze , maybe some raisin after lots of warming .  wow , i really mean wow ... im not a pro , but i`ve tried a few dopplebocks and i thought i will never taste a better dopplebock than the salvator ... a . it is a dark `` amber '' color . it shines for itself , and when watched behind a light it turns in a scale of browns , from the darkest in the bottom of the glass ... to the lighter one in the top of the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit sticky , and the carbonation is not too strong .

sampled on november 2 , 2004 , this brew came out a clear copper color under a half finger off-white head that faded slowly and left absolutely spectacular lace . there was n't much at all in the nose at first , but caramel emerged as it warmed . the taste features a nicely balanced malt and hop impression right from the start . the hops are flowery , not overpowering . good experience to be had here .  appearance - utterly black with a head so dark you 'd think this was an imperial stout . the first pour gives about an inch of frothy head and generous amounts of sticky lace . truly an impressive looking beer ; i 've seen stouts of twice the abv that looked more feeble than this .  the mouthfeel is heavy , but the carbonation was lacking for the style .

tastes crisp and fairly light for an ale . the finish is mildly bitter hops . could just be a normal hop thing .  the coloration was also perfect and conveyed what to expect in the flavor exactly .  this does mean that it is pretty thin on the mouth though .

i love the taste of the brooklyn pale ale . it is one of the pales that turned me on to brews that were not made by the major players and did not have the words lite in it . it is not for the faint of heart with its 7.0 abv .  a - beautiful beer ! not much floating on top of a gorgeous , warm and familiar toasty red , crystal clear brew .  lovely aftertaste that slowly fade for the first few minutes . most definitely a traditional brown ale in flavor and body .

s : almost non-existent but nothing really offensive is present . t : slight hops up front with some very mild citrus and a light malt finish . balanced but not complex or strong flavored . m : very creamy medium mouthfeel . delectable .  appearance is perfect as far as i 'm concerned with a bright , rich clear copper body that has a massive creamy off white head that is supported by a constant stream of bubbles and never fades to less than a finger thick .  m - thin and tingling . noticeable alcohol warming .

absent of any real aroma . this one 's taste makes up for its absence of aroma . no real hop bite , but still a bit drying in the finish -- very interesting .  almost looks like blood when held up to the light . it has and amazing foamy sticky tan head with amazing retention .  m : the same comment as i do with their other beers , tends to be slightly watery ; moderate carbonation ; medium body .

smell : mild malt sweetness is all that comes through .  great dark tan head ( tiny bubbles ) that stays around for a while . beer is a shade beneath pitch black .  medium bodied with moderate carbonation , this beer is both sippable and drinkable . the body is somewhat thick as it has a somewhat syrupy mouthfeel and slight stickiness . the carbonation is not overly apparent and could use a bit more strength to help cut through the thick body .
i never really received much from the aroma . it was always subtle and somewhat fruity .  displayed wonderful retention and great lacing too .  mouthfeel is decent , but a bit thin for my tastes .

( s ) - very dry and with a yeasty earthy quality . some light spice and lemon . ( t ) - similar to the smell in some ways .  pours a crystal clear coppery-amber color with a very nice dense frothy eggshell colored head . excellent retention and lacing .  medium bodied , carbonation is very noticeable , very tame malty sweetness that leads into a somewhat `` thin '' finish .

i was n't getting much in the smells department . flavor is where this beer shines .  appearance - beautiful orange/amber . nice level of floaties ( which i like ) .  full bodied , but even so there 's just too much carbonation . chewy , caky mouthfeel , no alcohol flavors .

smell is a bit odd . the smell makes me wonder .  a : burnt amber beer with a frothy two finger cappuccino colored head and excellent lacing .  tastes like hops to me . and nothing else . m- average d- what am i missing here ? i am not a fan of hoppy beers and that all this basically tastes like to me , nothing at all like a porter and no smoked flavor either .

very little aroma to be honest . taste caramel , spice , warming alcohol , citrusy hops .  hooray for being available now in maine ! toasted malt and dark chocolate flavor . unbelievably dark head . some hops that make it taste more like a very dark chocolate .  it is nicely carbonated ; the bubbles last till the end . the first sip is overwhelmed with carbonation and a tangy citrus under tone : almost like that first time or soda when the bubbles hit you , but this dose not last . the over all taste is a bit watery leaving a slight tangy-hopp after taste . it is a very easy beer to drink . the beer is a great beer to replace the useless monarchy of the current king of beers . for people who dont care what beer they drink and morally just go to bud , this is a great beer to get them hooked on .

smell was lacking , only slight yeast and spice .  though the smell does n't set my nostrils raging , the color is very inviting . this is a beer i always go back for when there is n't a micro that is catching my eye .  the mouthfeel is pretty full with a light carbonation .

cascade hops hit my nose for the most part . somewhat weak presentation on the nose . was hoping for more .  a - fantastic looking brew . hazed golden apricot-to-amber with a nice fiery glow to it .  really big carbonation , i 'd prefer it it was toned down a bit .

this beer has eluded me for years , partially owed to my laziness of not visiting this brewery ( sorry dudes ! ) . hints of caramel and raisin follow the warmth that makes its ' presence well known . its a little thin for the style , kind of a cousin to ridgerunner of sorts .  big vanilla head . larger bubbles provide decent lacing .  m - rolling carbonation makes the brew pleasantly refreshing and very quaffable , though perhaps a little too effervescent . body is lighter than i would like .

a : copper , clear , head with staying power s : pretty much all malt , not getting much hops , less than you would expect from an ipa anyway t : huge malt , lots of toast and caramel , almost to a fault , then plenty of hops to back it up , really great sipper .  beautiful crystal clear amber color .  creamy but light bodied - very light carbonation , not as effervescent as i would expect or prefer , but not terrible . simple but very tasty little ( small ) wild ale - curious to see what some age will do to it ... worth revisiting in a year or three maybe .

smell is underwhelming , need to check in with firestone chemists for more floral presence . smell of lavender/grape with some bread like toasted grape nuts . pleasent but not outstanding .  poured a 2 finger creamy off white head that lasted about 5 minutes . incredible lacing that lasts the whole glass . gorgeous .  mouthfeel : light to medium body , a little bit abrasive on the back of my throat as i drink .
there is no real distinct smell to the brew but the taste is just exceptional .  a- gorgeous burgundy hue with matter floating though out , with a bone while head .  kinda thin and tinny .

smells sweetly malty and-as promised- roasted . not much in the nose for me , but it is enticingly sweet .  inky black with a great dark roasted coffee flavour . i love this beer .  mouthfeel is decent , goes down like beer . leaves some flavor in your mouth after swallowing .

pours a cloudy amber color , thin head with slight metallic aroma mixed with notes of traditional german hops .  '' pours with a very substantial head , nearly out of control , enormous and sticky . dense yellow-white bubbles surge and froth , pillowing into a crowning mesa . rather auburn in color ; when held to light shimmers an electric bronze and metallic apricot , with streamers everywhere racing to the lip of the glass . stunning !  felt lite bodied on the tongue but bubbly and crisp .

pretty standard ipa fare .  750ml capped bottled poured into stemmed glass at brouwer 's on 4/12/11 a : beautiful slightly hazy golden peach color with fluffy white head that leaves some lacing around glass . got ta say i have never seen this color in any beer before .  the mouthfeel is n't bad , but stings a bit if you let it sit on your tongue .

all in all , a pretty beer with a great smell and decent taste that was not all that easy to get through .  huge , foamy head ; recedes with a rocky dome . leaves ample ring lace all the way down to the base of the glass .  i was home last night and decided that watching the office would be much better if i had some beer . taste of a malternative as it has been put , and incredibly sweet . felt like an ok beer with blueberry sauce . as a hop head myself , i should have gone for the inversion like i had the night before , but poor judgement dampened my sunday evening . steer far clear of this `` beer .

it seemed a bit thicker than most porters . they seemed to add spices to cover up the poor taste of the malt . not a fan , there are better porters out there .  375ml bottle with best by date of 05/08/11 poured into a chimay goblet a - deep , hazy golden color , two-inch white head with awesome retention and lacing , really great looking beer s - very yeasty and bready aroma , notes of lemon citrus and white pepper , light boozy heat t - mildly sweet and spicy lemon and white pepper up front , midpalate is pretty yeasty with a sourdough bread component , more lemon and pepper on the finish with a surprisingly strong bitterness that really dries out the finish , decent amount of alcohol heat m - medium-bodied , moderate to slightly higher carbonation , well-balanced finish that is on the dry side , good amount of alcohol warming d - decent in terms of drinkability , but the alcohol is definitely more noticeable than many examples of the style i 've had , and there is a bitterness that i 've not encountered in most other tripels , overall , however , it 's not too harsh on the palate and there is a decent amount of complexity in the flavors that keep it interesting this beer 's entry into the top 100 made me realize i 'd never actually tried it .  the feel is hot from the booze and a bit slick , moderate carbonation makes this brew drinkable ; very sweet .

i drank this one straight from the bottle , so i ca n't really comment on appearance or smell . in fact , the bottle i enjoyed was absent the sharp during and after taste that i 've come to associate with irish red ales . instead , there was a fine balance of maltyness with caramel sweeteness in the initial mouthful followed by a very mild hoppy finish . the hops were dry and barely noticable , but present . that i was surprised by the smoothness of the smithwick 's probably means that i 've been drinking a lot of poor red ales lately , but i found this ale highly enjoyable . i am a fan of german-style lagers and thought the smithwick 's exhibited many of the likable qualities found in my lagered oktoberfests and dunkels . very clean , but i did n't detect any of the butter or toffee flavors some find in irish red ales . i bet it goes really well with a porterhouse with carmalized onions and some buttery greens .  it did n't seem to have the body the stout enjoys . dark brown color and thick sea-foam head .  once it hits your mouth , the carbonation in it kind of picks at your cheeks . that 's why i marked it down a bit on mouthfeel .

earthy malt nose , some spicy alcohol .  a : it is black , pitch black . head is a creamy , milk chocolate , brown . intelligencia makes great coffee and this stuff smells like fresh pot of it .  ) mouthfeel : ok .

lets see ... more to talk than review ... first tried this at the brewery in juneau on vacation down from fairbanks ... .knew they had it but for some reason had never tried it ... was the only one on the `` tour '' of the brewery and the guy giving the tour said to try it and i immediately knew why he recommed it as soon as i sipped it ... had it a few more times and enjoyed it ... however the demand from you guys seemed to have raised the price ... oh well popularity has its costs ... as a side note , here in interior alaska we 've had a record fire season ( last summer ) and a again a smokey summer this past summer ... and by smokey i mean 1/8 mile visability and the measurement of particles was beyond `` hazardous '' , basically off the scale ( last summer that is , this summer it was just `` very unhealthy '' ) ... .so basically i 've breathed enough alder so as to not find it entirely pleasant but find at its easier to drink ... p.s . they sell it at the brewery in 12 oz six-packs  really amazing looking beer all around .  m - thin and crisp , but not watery .

slightly spicy yeasty aroma with hints of peper and a subtle light fruit notes , mostly apple and pear .  great head retention , thick , white and foamy that hangs around through the duration of the beer .  i saw that it was a kenyan lager and i almost did n't even want to try it . being the ticker that i am , i gave it a shot , and this is exactly why we do n't judge a beer by its location ... appearance nothing to note ... aroma is light and sweet , corn , but you 'd expect tons of skunk and none is present ... the aroma is light and sweet , not at all a typical lager . this is n't a great beer but it exceeds expectations for a lager and a kenyan beer .

pours pretty , beautiful frothy head and a hazy golden body ... i like bier that looks like it has 'stuff ' in it ... it smells like a pbr ... malty sweetness and evidence of hops ... taste ... exactly what i expected . sweet grain and an extremely mild fruity nose . a perfect beer for those inching away from bud light ... mouthfeel was a wonderful surprise ... it 's crisp and clean ... unlike a pbr , the mouthfeel is n't like drinking a sprite , it 's velvety ... drinkability is the best part about this bier ... it does n't feel like your eating thanksgiving and its not water ... it has plenty of yin and the right amount of yang ...  a : the beer pours black in color with a two finger cappuccino colored head . the beer has excellent head retention and stellar lacing .  moderate body , with a little bit of a gassy , bubbly feel . ultimately , although i quite like this beer , i think it would really shine on cask ; the carbonation is a little too prickly and gives the beer too much of a mineral water feel .

first i want to note that i am typically a dark , nut brown , or porter drinker and i tend to steer clear of pale ales such as this . just a nice clean refreshing ale .  this brew poured a medium head of fine to large sized light brown bubbles that left a fair lacing and an opaque black colored body .  very sweet on top of the tongue with lots of chocolate , but very bitter under the tongue . somewhat unpleasant down there , had the tendency to keep it on top of the tongue for the bottle . definitely a dessert beer . extremely flavorful but i could see how this could be a little too much at times . share a bottle , or have a full bottle if you 're feeling decadent .

eh , pretty soft smelling . better smelling than a budweiser , at least .  the beer itself is an amber-golden color ... lots of bubbles from the pour and some nice cloudiness . rich creamy white head ... looks like a fantastic beer ! this one has a maltier smell than the real ale pale ale ... maybe even a little towards the malt side of the malt/hops balance for this one .  despite this beer being from two kinds of beverages which bring expectations of intense carbonation , this beverage is not is as intense as you would expect .

s - not much of a smell as i expected malts and dark fruits and a bit of spice . t - really malty , caramel , with dark fruits , slight raisins , and a really awesome finish that leaves a sweet aftertaste .  pours very dark . the head on this beer is my favorite of all beers , towering and rocky , it is truly beautiful .  first of all , this beer predates the craft beer era . it 's makers brew a tastey brown lager that they call a porter , and they make this delicious pilsner that they call an ale . they were doing this when our fathers were toasting our european heritage with schlitz . it is light bodied , as it should be , and very drinkable . i suppose i can understand that if someone was expecting an ale they might misjudge this beer - but close your eyes , forget your encyclopedeaic knowledge of beer names - and imagine a time in 1975 when the best pilsner on the east coast was called an ale .

s- nutty and bready malts . nothing much else .  16-ounce can with a widget poured into a seidel yields a deep ruby-tinted ebony body awash in creamy goodness and capped with a finger of practically-solid cappuccino-colored foam that retains like foam rubber and sticks like thick whipped glue on the glass . extremely drinkable and a kick to enjoy out of the kitschy nitro-can , which really does make murphy 's look good !  already thinnish mouthfeel lost even more body as the glass emptied .

smells acceptable tastes pretty friggin good for a canned pale ale mouthfeel is very good for a pale ale drinkability i could have these or ol ' chub all night long .  this comes in a nice cardboard box . pours a beautiful dark brown orange color . the head is beautiful with large bubbles and this stays around . one of the best heads and lace package i have ever seen .  m- somer orange honey ale is thin with a light carbonation , slight snap of carbonation at the end .

nose is light , sweet and malty .  serving type : today it 's in a nitro-bottle ( first time trying one of these bad boys ) appearance : still the same lovely look , a bit nicer of a head that lingers more and provides more lacing . the difference is amazing ... looks perfect smell : same lovely smell of toffee , chocolate , caramel .  12 oz bottle into a dfh signature glass wow what a mess this beer was . while it looked fairly innocuous in the glass what was hiding in its depths was anything but ... butterscotch . lots and lots of butterscotch . this is where diacetyl men and diacetyl women meet up to have little bastard diacetyl babies . if saranac would change the label to saranac butterscotch porter they would probably have an award winner on their hands because this sure as hell meets that description . in a word ... terrible .

smell : slightly roasted malt smell with a tiny bit of an alcohol scent . note : i thought the taste was really good especially since i was n't impressed with the smell .  great pour ! cascade and all !  drank it straight from the bottle . smelled clean and fresh . as far as adjunct lagers go , i have nothing to complain about . this was this first time i 've had one without spitting it out , so i give it a thumbs up . it was actually very crisp and clean and possessed no off-flavours .

nose was full of corky aroma , but i had stored the beer upright , so i do n't think that it was from the cork in the bottle . maybe more of a earthy smell .  very clean and sharp looking bronze color with a huge , fluffy , pale caramel colored head on top .  i suppose an islay whiskey drinker might like the novelty of this beer . as a fan of wood aged beer and not of islay whiskey however , i would call this the worst thing i have ever tasted . i was the token beer geek in the group and as such i was the only one to finish the 3 or so ounces of beer in my glass . comments were : `` must be an aquired taste '' , `` aweful '' , `` that 's the worst thing i have ever tasted '' , and dumping the beer down the sink in descending of order preference . well , that being said , i am glad i tried it . it 's important to temper one 's taste for beer with the occasional dog brew .

the bummer here is i am trying to do this from memory rather than doing it on the spot as the original was . s : this was surprising , but to my nose , i really did n't take smell as one of the big features of this beer . it had all the hops you would expect from a wet hop beer ( being the main feature ) but also had a smokiness or savoriness that i ca n't pinpoint . i know most pale ales do n't store , but this provided quite the buzz so i am thinking the alcohol and hops may make this age ok ... i 'll see .  a- beautiful looking beer .  m - 3.0 - oddly pretty good . thin , bubbly , smooth .

s - smells of grains and malts , neither of which are very strong t - this tastes of malts and a little grain , as the nose suggested .  a 22 oz bottle into a nonic glass , pours a pretty clear copper amber with a very generous and everlasting off-white head and a whole ton of lacing .  fits the style of a dubbel . mouth feel is sharp and crisp with an average carbonation level .

s : its aroma is not very strong . smelled of alcohol and slightly of chocolate . t : very complex taste . d : this beer is delicious and an interesting style .  pours a hazy reddish amber brown with a huge rocky off white head that retains well and laces the glass .  it 's so much smoother and has much body to it , compared to all the other crap macro out there .

smells very good . tastes of caramel , honey , some hoppyness , and some floral essence .  a- deep gold , one and a half finger head , wonderful lacing all the way down . s- very clean , very light hop and malt aromas .  i like beer and i like banana bread . however i bought this with some trepidation because fruit beers can get too overpowered by the fruit . the aroma was just what it should be ... bananas . not much hops or malt aromas if any . surprisingly the taste was good . no lacing from the lackluster head but bananas was obvious . overall i enjoyed this beer , it was n't a home home run , maybe a stand up triple .

s- sweet grainy smell upfront with minimal hop presence for an ipa . what is there seems to be earthy , maybe slightly piney . definitely not very bold thought . magnificent .  a - fantastic cascading that never ceases to tantalize me . one finger , dense-as-cream , tan head with impeccable retention and thick lacing .  mouth feel is average , possibly a tad thin , but nothing to really detract .

pleasant but completely burried , it seems like they are cancelling each other out .  2007 vintage poured into a duvel tulip . beautiful port wine body topped by about 1/2 '' of creamy foam . the mouthfeel is a little thin - i was expecting something fuller .  aroma is orange and lemon wedges , sweet and sugary . taste is nicely balanced , lemon zest and pepper for a little kick of spice , but not quite a hefe in the traditional sense . slight bitterness at the end from the hops . nothing to write home about but a very sessionable ale . a solid american wheat ale , a good choice to have while watching some baseball in the summer or at a fourth of july party .

bouquet on this is quite small , almost non existent . i am just getting some clove sense , no kind of yeast or big malt ... seems kind of clean . taste is a big surprise . i think this one needs a food pairing for myself than just drinking casually , but it 's a tasty one i must admit and very different from most tripels i 've had .  deep amber liquid capped by a foamy head that holds together beautifully .  m-the body is surprisingly thin .

s- light smell of lemonade t- heavy on the lemonade flavor , with a touch of lager in the aftertaste . taste is far stronger than the smell . d- this is an extremely drinkable beer for a picnic , day at the beach , or a hard day of working outdoors . if you have ever brought an ipa to the beach , or tried sipping a stout on a 90 degree day you might know where i 'm coming from . i found this beer to be a tastier and less skunky version of leinenkugel 's summer shanty .  produces a vast amount of foam with awesome retention , which is off white in color .  the mouthfeel is thin and crisp on the palate , which causes a slender puckering , leading to an excellent drinkability .

not much aroma ... wish there was more but this style always is easy on the nose . taste- has a starting of a apple juice taste and then has a earthy hop feel that cuts off the rest of the apple taste .  poured from a 750 ml to a snifter appearance : great big pure white head lasts for a long time but does not condense into more liquid volume , giving the impression that it was quite light .  taste matches the smell , plus some licorice as it warms , though it does n't go down as thick as it looks like it would . the 8 % shows off a bit , but in a good way . overall , a by-the-book stout .
s - almost nothing !  the liquid was topped by a super tight and creamy , khaki colored crop of froth .  medium to full bodied that goes a little heavy on the carbonation .

s : roasted malt . perhaps a little coffee but not much .  the beer pours a sensational dark as night color , with an incredible rich , chocolate/coffee head . visually , this beer just looks incredible . on the nose one gets the expected coffee and chocolate , but with some dark fruits seeping in as well .  m medium bodied , but nothing special for the style .

smell was fairly unassuming and muted . there was some dark chocolate and coffee in the nose but nothing really spectacular . taste was good .  appearance : beautiful pure red body with huge off-white fluffy head .  m - medium bodied with extremely lively carbonation that is a bit too brisk and prickly .

s : light roasted malt and spice .  pours a perfectly clear reddish hue . a nice , fluffy , off white head stays and laces nicely .  mouthfeel is average and i really do n't have anything more to say about it , except that just as you would with starbucks coffee , you are going to be left with a slightly funky aftertaste on your tongue . its not unpleasant ... its just acidic and totally starbucks .

aroma - has a rather peculiar odor , cheesy or musty or something , then fades into total obscurity .  bottle : poured a cloudy light brown color ale with a super large foamy head with good retention and some good lacing .  m= a little thin on the mouth but nothing too bad .

smell is fruity spices and some belgian brewers yeast .  gorgeous looking beer . stunning appearance .  closer to light than medium bodied and fairly dry , moderate carbonation , a bit on the rough side . the difference in yeast added more complexity than i expected , but a slightly modified malt bill would probably improve the texture and create something truly impressive .

overall this was probably the best beer i had for the night . i did not drink this beer with any food , overall i would say it had a bit of a bite to it . good beer  very pretty beer , deep red/gold amber with a sticky , barely off white head . great cling and retention and slow , sparatic bubbles of rising carbonation .  on tap at the brewery 07-10-09 . pours a beautiful dark brown with nice tan head . great looking beer with a really unique aroma dominated with chocolate and orange . would have love to tasted this blind as the aromas were a bit confusing to the senses . pretty well balanced with a nice bitter chocolate finish . my notes are also saying that there was a nice woody aroma and touch of dry wood in the taste , though i 'm not sure how that came about .

smell- a very light aroma creamy malt and yeast slight hop presence taste- bold and complex malts .  a incredible look of a nice , generous white head that hung around for a minute and a half and generous yeast floating around in the honey yellow translucent body .  medium-low mouthfeel and low carbonation .

smell : sweet on the nose with hints of coriander and white pepper . while it has a stronger aroma than a lot of other brews , nothing special noted .  the appearance was ridiculously perfect , but it 's downhill from there .  light orange color ... awesome aroma ... just like fresh pumpkin pie out of the oven ... big cinnamon element ... the taste is more subtle than the nose ... nice pumkin flavor also strong cinnamon and some nutmeg ... mouthfeel is light and slightly watery.. decent pumpkin ... i 'd prefer to see it bigger in body with a little more assertive pumpkin taste..still pretty decent overall and a solid seasonal offering .

s : moderate notes of roasted grains and sweet malt . i also get a touch of fruit although i 'm not sure which one . berries maybe . t : a great balance between sweet malts and a touch of bittering hops . carbonation starts off a bit too spritzy and distracting but mellows out over time .  hook and ladder backdraft brown ale is a nice , deep red-brown ale that 's very clear and dense in appearance . it 's lightly sparkling with a thin , dense , splotchy beige head that leaves nice lacing . a beautiful beer !  mouthfeel is pleasantly crisp albiet a bit sugary .

still worth looking for and tasting .  this is a gorgeous beer . i 've got thick lacing and nice red body .  smells strongly of fresh floral and citrus hops -- it really smells like you 're sticking your nose into some highly-hopped fresh wort -- with the malt body weakly present -- a hint of caramel behind all of those hops . for taste and mouthfeel , it lags behind kona 's castaway ipa .

very light citrus in the aroma . well balanced malt and hop flavor .  the appearance of this beer was dark with a light head and it had a light burnt smell .  a : it pours a golden color , not quite copper or amber but far from light also slightly cloudy macro , head is thick creamy and firm s : its smells like beer , smells real fresh t : incredable it has a very heavy grain taste that screams fresh off the farm , very bold and yet refreshing at the same time m : this is average , low carbonation and tiny bubbles makes for a wet beer that lets you taste the flavor instead of the co2 d : very drinkable , my rule of thumb is if i can finish a 16oz glass its a good beer , if i cant it sucks ... i finished a full 16oz no prob and crave more , thank god i have 48 more oz that wont go to waste !

no aroma to this one . very light bodied , slight lacing on glass .  pours a bold and bright brownish red that i absolutely adore . the best color of beer i 've ever seen ! not an impressive head , but i 'll give it a 5 just because the color is so magnificent .  mouthfeel is on the thick side with a little more co2 than i like usually .
pretty mild all around in the aroma department .  pours opaque black color with a 1.5 finger dark tan head with incredible retention .  m - mouthfeel is a little thin .

i did not appreciate any powerful aromas , but certainly traces of chocolate smells were there .  this was my kind of stout ! i loved the super dark black tint and very dark brown head that leaves a very good lace .  carbonation is a tad harsh to start , but mellows half way through .

mmmmm , now this is what i 've been missing . mmmmm . mmmmm .  this is damn near a baltic porter , it 's so dark . everyone seems to have their own definition of doppelbock , and ayinger thinks it should be rich , roasty , chocolatey , slightly bitter and really smooth .  the carbonation is on the low side . very buttery , sorta nutty but on the watery side . i really like this beer . it 's unique and has some different flavors .

s - piney and citrus aromas are there but they are faint . t - hoppy hoppy joy joy !  pitch black appearance . not nearly as creamy and milky-textured as i would have liked .  m- high carbonation and light body .

intense and intoxicating aroma of hairspray , acetone and spice rack .  poured a hazy brown color with a huge frothy light brown head that was fully lasting and produced excellent lacing .  it has a foamy medium light body with a slightly gritty finish .

aroma is a bit disappointing , just a hint of malt and hops .  poured into tulips . ar : mmm , tart , cherries , green apple , light acidity/sour , light apple cider vinegar , nutty malt , earthy with brett , fruit down in intensity with time , light floral , *delicate , *caramel ap : light tan very large coarse chunky head , lace , clear light amber , rocky head , best head retention i 've seen t : brett earthiness , light vegetative , brett bitterness , tart hints , herbal spicy hop , nutty/crackery malt , fruity hints ( peach , light tropical fruit , cherry ) , long dry complex brett and hop bitter end , green apples ( light ) assertive but not aggressive , clean ( crisp ) medium caramel , woody spices m : dry lasting brett bitterness , lightly astringent , medium/high fine carbonation , *resin o : good , brett rather bitter , complex and clean , would like more sour in taste , would like it less vegetative , *darker than expected , *a strange beer , not really a full brett character , not sour , aroma and appearence are the best parts , *appearance is flawless *= ideas of fellow taster  feels a little thin and then the dryness is a letdown .

looks a lot like a stout . s : i get some roasty bitter chocolate upfront with some vanilla and cocoa in the middle and hints of cherries on the backend . ok. t : bitter , cigarette-like , roastiness upfront with some hints of cherry in the middle and some cocoa on the backend . more like a good standard stout .  pours a thick black with a duvel-esque dark tan head which lasts for ages and settles down to a permanent half-finger at the top of the glass .  mouthfeel - lighter than i was expecting from a stout , and somewhat heavily carbonated . drinkability - this would be even higher if slightly less carbonated , but the taste is fantastic .

really awesome lacing . smell : a little struggle on the nose . some hops but i 'm not getting much there . faint grapefruit . taste : very smooth . this is not a hop bomb . slightly hoppy balanced well with malts . no fruits here just wood hops and malt . drinkability : highly drinkable i2pa .  a : pours a deep black with no visible light .  m-is sort of thin , much more than i would expect . d-is very nice .
