the smell is really faint and obscure until it warms up significantly . full flavored , the mild roasted malt and oat notes are complemented by the feel and aroma . the 7 % abv is real , but easily well hidden by these stout , no pun intended , ingredients .  it looks like a classic marzen , with a deep auburn transparent color that almost glows in the late summer light . but , unlike many marzens , this one pours an outstanding soft white head that pumps up to three fingers deep , and has great retention over a leisurely quaff , leaving a lovely diffuse lacing on the glass as you go .  i was never a big ipa fan , but damn ... this one is good . my local bodega tends to get random 6-packs of whatever beer ... usually duds , but always affordable , giving me a chance to try lots of random beers . this one came up , and having never seen it before , i got a 6-pack to try out , despite not being a fan of ipas . let me tell you that this one changed my mind . this is a really , really tasty beer , and if you like this style , i encourage you to give it a try if you see it . i could drink like ten of these !

nose is mildly smoked , but really void of much else .  reviewed 8/17/2008 ( draft at flying saucer , houston , tx ) : pours a very cloudy fizzy light brown body . creamy white head , good lacing & lasting .  m - medium-bodied . carbonation lightens it up a bit , but it 's not distracting .

the nose is extremely subdued , kinda disappointing . taste- what it lacks in aroma it makes up in flavor .  pours a slightly-hazed , pale golden color with a prodigious billowy white head that builds to meringue . great retention and tight lacing on glass .  if this was the first baltic porter i 'd tried , it would have frightened me away from the style . i 've had several of the style , so i had a frame of reference , and i found this beer to be quite horrid . then the beer finished with a terrible , sickly sweetness , like some artificial sweetener mixed with a bittering agent . by my third drink , it had grown so intolerable that i could not go any further . from the other positive reviews , i 'd be tempted to think i had a bad bottle , but this really did not strike me as bottle gone bad , just a bad beer .

very drinkable , i can drink these 24/7 . a nice refreshing , easy to drink and pleasant enough beer to consume all night and get drunk off of . ) so , at least there are no cheap adjuncts made in this and tastes a lot better than others of the lager styles . outstanding ! !  this brew pours with a deep red-brown body topped by a thick off-white head with lots of lacing left hugging the glass .  smells like corn , tastes like corn . fairly bad , not recommended . you 're better off spending your time and money elsewhere . i did n't really expect much from a guatemalan beer , and it lived down to my expectations .

a pleasant blend , but pretty weak overall .  this beer pours an amber-orange with a bright white head which falls to half a finger and linger throught the drink . the lacing is remarkable .  mouth : most prominently smoky and bitter , the fruity entrance of this beer does not meet the expectations set by the complex aroma . also , i would prefer that the beer maintained a more strongly carbonated mouth-feel , but i think that the size of the head ( which remained consistent to the very last glass of the bottle ) uses up a fair amount of the bubbles . a little unbalanced , but over-all an enjoyable 3l celebration .

smell is citrusy and grainy malt .  a light golden ale that pours with lots of carbonation , generating a voluminous head . the bright white foam falls slowly and leaves some nice lacework enhancing the appearance .  i rarely find a beer that i feel has a good balance of smell , taste , `` mouth after feel '' , feel , drinkability , and overall balance . perhaps a bit over carbonated , the carbonation is the first to hit the mouth , followed quickly by sugary-wheat almost powered taste , as if a ground piece of wheat was poured directly into the batch , matched equally well later on by great coriander , orange , medium grain , and light spritzer flavors .
nice but on the weak side .  11/12/02 : dark , dark ruby , almost black .  average mouthfeel .

the scent is rather light .  the appearance is very similiar to duvel , immense white frothy head - comprised of millions of tiny bubbles .  this beer seems a bit too carbonated to me , but overall , it just seems too light .

s - the best part of this beer is definitely the smell . very heavy on the sweet maple , with just enough smoke and a dash of lavender . this is exactly what this beer would taste like if perfect . still a solid beer , but disappointing after the smell . o - i want so badly to love this beer , but there is simply way too much lavender in it for me .  a : bodacious carbonation produces a stunning whipped butter 2 inch head . the body is hazy , the color of rusy caramel .  medium bodied with a light oily feel .

smell is sweeter and typical for a porter with little complexity . all good i feel .  poured w/a huge , booming and sticky white head over a mostly opaque , rich golden color body . awesome to look at .  pours a opaque black colour with a medium frothy tan head . aroma is creamy with some hints of coffee and chocolate . initial taste is very creamy ( milk shake ) , coffee and some cocoa . minor bitter hops in the finish . great head retention and lacing was slapped around the sides of the glass nicely .
smells like bread , some malt and a little metal . this brew tastes great .  excellent deep amber color . nice off white head , with great head retention .  m - average , balanced carbonation .

strong malt smell , light hop flavor .  a- hazy golden yellow body lets light through and shows bubbles rising to the big , pillowy head that retains forever and leaves clumps of lacing .  the carbonation was a little high which was disappointing .

smell : mostly malt with a brief initial hint of hops .  good looking beer .  my only complaint about this beer is the mouthfeel . it 's overly carbonated and as such is quite abrasive on the tongue and washes away all the flavor before you can really enjoy .

aroma is low , but malty with some bready and oaty notes .  pours pitch black with a glorious fluffy brown head , fades very slowly and leaves lots of lacing in its wake .  the flavor is nice , roasted malt , bitterness adds to the chocolate feel and the finish is dry with a slight sour taste . while this brew for me is light in its feel , but all of the irish stouts seem to be , it is a nice and a step ahead of the beamish and murphy 's and seems to be way ahead of guinness . overall this is a great brew , one i would get during the st. patty 's timeframe .

smells like sweet alcohol with a touch of hops . pretty pleasing but also average . nothing truly distinguishes the aroma .  a- great looking . deep black with a rich cascading head . unfortunately the head doesnt stick around a long time .  very thin for a double stout .

very light hops and a little grain aroma .  it pours out a black beer with ruby edges in the light . the head is light tan with a good froth staying afloat throughout and beautiful lace clinging to the glass .  m : light carbonation with a light body .

the smell is a bit pungent , almost like ethanol or nail polish remover , but with a definite aroma of hoppy and fruity flavors . the taste far outweighs the smell .  the rocky and frothy head morphs into a huge tsunami wave and rushes to the shore . particles everywhere .  m - a bit too oily and overcarbonated for the style in my opinion .

straw like color . grassy nose with a weak citrus scent .  pitch black colour , big brown head .  this continues into a palate that i hoped carried a little more density . while a very nice beer i came out with the feeling that some barrel aging would smooth and fill out the midpalate .

very little aroma most likely due to age .  a deep brown-black with a lively head that stays and laces for the life of the beer . visually , it 's pretty much perfect for the style .  m- lighter in bodied than i would have guessed .

smell : a slightly funky smell with some grass tones .  dark brown to black with lots of mahogany to the light . nice creamy light brown head with nice active carbonation .  medium body with an easy , surprisingly fizzy mouthfeel .

the aroma is the weakest aspect and is a bit unpleasant . it smells of apples , flour and a hint of bread dough - definitely a wheat ale quality but different , hint of pine sap , and a hint of watermelon , mostly an old , turned unpleasant watermelon quality .  a- brilliantly clear and amber . outstanding retention .  poured a deep golden with some orange tint with a thin head but had a nice clear color , aroma was mainly of citrus fruit with some toasted grain , no alcohol aroma wich sometimes might be associated the style but that was to be expected i guess with this crazy law down here.nice flavors going on very malty and pretty sweet but not overly so i picked up some pineapple and some doughy qualities.a lighter version of a spring classic i could spend a day drinking this .

not much going on other than some light herbal hops , and maybe some sweet malt . o- honestly , if the malt bill were a little bit more balancing , this would be top notch . as is , it 's certainly well crafted , and tasty , just not world class such as troegs hopback .  looks great , dark with a wee bit of head .  mouth feel was average for the style drinkability was good .
s-very slight chocolate . no hops .  pours dark black with a large tan head that perfectly tops of the beer .  mouthfeel is average for the style .

not too much in the smell , just a bit of spice . taste is pretty good . a very enjoyable , easy drinking beer .  head retention and lacing are absolutely outstanding .  carbonation seems a little light and it fits the style well . like this but could use a bit more carbonation .

s - aroma is of citrus and hops , with a hint of tartness , none of which are overpowering by any means .  a- crystal clear gold , taunt fluffy three finger white head that holds it own very well , when it falls it falls to a 1/2 '' ring , full white lace on glass s- clean , crisp , floral , pine , citric lemon t- crisp biscuit malt up front , hops all the way through , grassy , lemon , tart yeast at finish , hop bitterness through finish m- dry , bubbly coarse , high carbonation , light bodied , hops leave impression on palette .  mouthfeel is medium-low and a little on the carbonated side .

upon investigation , i find the same aromas around . soapy and spicy .  golden orange in color and well-carbonated , with a billowy off-white head . quite attractive .  the carbonation is quite strong with medium sized bubbles ; maybe it is a little bit too strong ?

smell was very mild , slight fruit , sweet aroma , but nothing over powering . very flavorful , considering the slight aroma . malt , fruity citrus , and a hint of hops .  a- pours black and thick , tall head in begining , decent carbonation , looks like a wonderful brew , although i find the appearance to be sort of a trivial category , the bottle looks very impressive on the other hand .  the only real criticism is that for a summer beer , i expected a little more carbonation to leave my mouth cleaner .

smell : not a lot here , mostly hops and malts of course , although i do get a tint of skunk smell to it . a good holiday bock that scared me first from the aroma but didnt disappoint in taste and mouthfeel .  this brew poured a small light brown head of large bubbles . it has a opaque dark brown/black body as a stout should .  appears heavily carbonated with many bubbles rising to the top . mouthfeel / drinkability - light to medium bodied . second review notes : on-tap once more at 101 laundry .

english hop and munich malt nose , nothing offensive but nothing impressive either .  pours brown/black with no transparency . features a big bubbly tan head that is quite slow to fade . lacing seems moderate - the foam slides pretty easily on the sides of the glass at first , but becomes stickier as it dries . woah , maybe i was wrong - by the time i am done with the beer the lacing is incredible . crusted layers everywhere- tan ... and brown even ! looking great .  the term gold could be used to describe this lager , but 'gold ' makes it sound valuable so am going to go with 'yellow ' because yellow has more negative conotations associated with it . i suppose the carbonation level and overall body of the beer are it 's saving graces ; though even that is just average .

initially , there was a touch of vinegar acidity in the aroma , but that seems to have gone away as the beer completed its warming , and now all i 'm left with is a rich , wonderful chocolate milk aroma , appropriately enough . a decent sweet stout .  fluffy bubbles well up slowly up and then back down the sides of the glass like a guinness in slow motion . massive brown meringue head crowns a nearly-black ruby-tinted crystal clear beer .  essentially , this is imported bad malt liquor . cidery malt , with an overwhelming fusel alcohol presence . a strong lager can be done well , or , as this demonstrates , very , very badly .

smell - orange . overall drinkability - the bitter sourness ruins this beer .  amazing color from this brew - one of the best looking beers i have seen .  m = medium bodied , good mouthcoating , carbonation stings the tongue just a little too much .

smell : odd yeast flavour with belgian style malt and ester aromas . notes : this is a very exciting brew , varied complexities and very belgian .  on tap at the san bernardino location ... a - brown with reddish hues and a one finger tan head that follows you all the way to the finish . lots of sticky lacing to be had here .  m a little over carbonated but pretty smooth and an easy drink .

; ^ ) the nose is hoppy with some notes of pine and a bit of citrus . i really enjoy this ipa so i 'll put it in the very drinkable category .  a : black with some brown around the edges with a cream-colored two finger head and great lacing .  poured from a bottle into a pilsner a-very deep amber with about a 1 finger head s-malt , barley , bread and spices all come through very heavy in the nose with hints of a sweet fruit or maybe even cinnimon t & m-bready with a very plesant rosted pumpkin seed flavor as well , has a slight hop bitterness in the finish and goes down pretty smooth . d-this is one of my favorite oktoberfest brews and ill have more and more as the time nears .

pours dark amber with a light fluffy off-white creme head . first taste is of bready sweetness .  bottle looks awesome . poured into sniffer glass a-jet black with a lightly moca head that quickly disapates s-smells alot like bourbon upfront .  fizzy and light on the tongue .

the aroma is there . but the taste just was n't .  when guinness is served properly , it is a fantastic , and quite an amazing beer . very smooth , with a creamy head that just makes the beer perfect .  medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , the flavors throw back to the aroma , with a pronounced hoppiness that is balanced well by a base of biscuity grain .

smells of roasted barley and a hint of sweet.from the name , i thought it would be pretty hoppy .  a : dark brown with 1.5 inch brown head that stays the whole time you drink it .  m - pretty smooth , thin , a little refreshing , could easily be better ( especially considering i was in one of those `` i could really use a beer '' moods when i poured this ) .
aroma seems kinda subdued to me .  looks awesome for a red ; prototypical .  mouthfeel is a little thin but tolerable.finish is clean .
the smell is somewhat subdued , though a nice sweet aroma is present .  excellent color .  m-fuller body and grainy on the palate with an assertive carbonation and a semi dry crisp finish .

smell is a bit on the light side . sweet caramel malt is there , but you have to really hunt for it . caramel and sweet toasted grain , some candied elements , as well as a buttery note .  pours a big , thick and chunky dark orange color . looks beautiful ; perfect actually .  strong berry flavor with an artificial sweetener after-taste . drank like a b & j wine cooler . i drank half and barely finished the rest . if your looking for a good fruit beer id suggest bluepoints blueberry ale or longtrail 's blackbeary wheat .

i only wish it had more of an aroma , as there was very little scent .  pours almost a jet black with dark brown highlights beneath a massive three-finger dirty tan head .  m : good , not great . i drank one and thought it was on the thinner side .

smells like a handful of northwest hops , nothing crazy .  a- nice generous 2 finger head that has some serious retention . lots of carbonation bubbles rush to the head that is still very much there . lots of lacing is left around the glass and around the mouth from the sip i look . looks fantastic . s- crisp and tart with some sweeter fruits , maybe green apple .  m : oily , not very crisp .

smell had a little chocolate , smokey aroma but was pretty terrible in my opinion .  highly impressive is the outstanding pattern lacing all the way around the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin as far as stouts are concerned , but it 's not so watery as to ruin the experience .

with a name like thunderhop i was maybe expecting a much deeper aroma - mostly citrus with a tinge of sweet carmel . nicely balanced medium body that does want to wake the pallet a bit .  a a deep brown and caramel appearance . rather beautiful s toasted caramel was obvious , along with roasted hops .  the quantity of hops seemed very american but the style of hops seemed very european . as much as i enjoyed this beer , i was disappointed by the mouthfeel . it was thinner than i anticipated with a prickly , large bubbled effervescence .

very subtle malty bouquet .  a : pours with a think , dense head with great retention -- the color of the head reminds me of the froth of a cappuccino .  a little watery at moments in the sip ( light body ) .

it 's pale , no head , does n't smell good , watery , tastes like nothing with a touch of maltyness , blah blah blah .  poured into a lagunitas pint/mason jar and was totally impressed with the 2 finger tan fluffy head and nice lacing on this pepsi cola clear dark brown brew .  the mouthfeel let me down a little even though you can tell from the taste that hops arent a big figure in this , its not light and its not lively . there is no attack on your tongue from the carbonation .

the stuff looked like it was dying to be consumed , so i did the only right thing ... the smell is pretty bland , not a whole lot to report here , other than maybe a little bit of soggy grains . nondescript , but certainly nothing offensive either , so this will just get the old so-so 3-rating . cask-like , even , in its silkiness . a must-try if you ever get to this place and want to try an ultra-fresh example of an authentic german pils .  the deep brown color is wonderful , and the beer is not to heavy so it is easy to drink .  a- dark brown , almost black body with an off-white head that leaves lots of lacing s- maltiness and chocolate , not a whole lot else t- roasted malts , molasses , toffee , an interesting bitter chocolate finish giving a nice movement to the taste m- medium bodied and a bit too carbonated for my liking but not too bad d- i liked the complexity of this and will revisit it as it really does make me think of the holidays !

the smell is alright , i suppose . a little malty , not really much here . did n't smell like much of anything .  a-pours a muddled , ruddy orange with some slight flashes of rusty brown.the head on this beer was unbelievable.very belgian.three full fingers of super dense , barely off-white foam that left good sheets of lacing and stiff , half inch , meringue-like chunks on the inside of the glass for the duration .  m - a kind of average , standard ( within the class ) smoothness . maybe too much burn .

the smell is kind of not there - it smells slightly hop funky , but nothing really sticks out .  appearance of this one is extremely enticing - it s dark amber with a ruby tinge .  it has a good taste but i think the mouthfeel is too thin .

it took three sniffs to finally get some scent out of it , some nice chocolate odors .  pours a clear golden color , thick frothy white heading.crazy amounts of lacing through every sip a tremendous looking site .  mouthfeel was a little thin for a stout .

did not taste like beer , but wather like a `` tea '' product .  a - giant two finger , lumpy , fluffy , egg-shell colored head floats on top of a clear and well-carbonated amber color leaving lots of lacing .  m : sweet , citrus , malty .

1pint bottle serving size appearance : it pours a muddy amber colour smell : after not being able to discern much of the smell i decided to read through some of the reviews . upon testing again i did notice a distinct grape smell to the drink . there is also a toffee/coffee smell as well that lingers a little bit taste : hmmmm ... .what can i say ? it reminded me to much of wine and had the same sort of `` dryness '' to is that red wine often does . there is a taste of grapes and there is some slight saltiness to it .  appearance - pours a dark black with a brown head .  mouthfeel is lighter in the body than american ipa 's with nice carbonation levels .

s : unfamiliar hoppy , yeast smell . bananas and pears are very strong .  deep brown color with a light tan head . the lacing was also excellent ; it left a nice foamy trail down one side of the glass .  pretty smooth and estery.has some yeasty floaties in it too.mouthfeel is standard .

the smell was unimpressive , like a sweet roasted soy sauce .  pours amber with a a 4 fingers+ fluffy sand colored head . great lacing & head retention s : a hint of caramel & malt t : sweet malt & herbal/piney hops ; finsihed prickly & semi-malty mf : light/medium bodied with pricklyness , not balanced drinks average , this is a different beer than bottled version ; i 'm so confused ?  wife loves the weak bland weak beers and she didnt even like this . possibly the most bland version of this style ive ever had . m/d : offered you nothing and in terms of having a few , it was hard enought getting down the part of the sampler .

aroma is fairly mild but some chalky cocoa comes through mixed with a bit of roasted malt and some brown sugar . flavor is similar to nose , with some chocolate and a bit of roasted malt .  lacing is pretty sticky . this is a phenomenal looking beer , i could see it in commercials .  mouthfeel nicely carbonated , a bit lighter body than expected based on the pour but it is not watery by any means .

pours a very dark brown/black with a small tan head that casts faint aromas of burnt chocolate .  stellar tan head atop a dark body . lots of retention and lacing .  only quibble is that it seems a little thin , does n't have a lot of oomph or gravitas to it , just the flavor .

it smells faintly lambic ( duh ) and faintly otterpop . highly drinkable .  drank on-tap at deep ellum , allston , ma poured a gorgeous , dark , russet mahogany with a tight , frothy , two-finger head of sticky foam . excellent retention .  m - definitely leaves some sort of floral feeling in my mouth . a bit dry and juice-like . soft in my mouth as i drink it , but very dry afterwards .

boquet is pretty weak , there 's a bit of malt character to be seen but not much else . flavor starts off hoppy strong and finishes very mild . nice balance here between hop and malt . it is very smooth .  awesome folds , waves and loops of sediment stay suspended in the beer and slowly settle out . nice 2 inch white head too . betty has a solid white ale nose , definitely with some belgian influence . above average white ale body , very bright carbonation .  m : the medium body is syrupy and had soft carbonation .

aroma is faint , biscuity malts mainly , some minimal piney hops too . hoppiness is mild for an apa for a change , which is actually very nice imo .  wow this beer has the biggest head ever . pours a very pale lager yellow with a foamy monster that looks like marshmellows expanding .  m- the mouthfeel of this beer is somewhat thin but the carbonation is pretty much spot on .

smell is of rich roasted espresso , really nicely done .  first impression was the darkness . it really is dark ... almost black like coffee .  4.0 m thin like most porters but i like a bit more body , fullness than this offers .

decent lacing develops . smell : some fruit sweetness and yeast .  `` a liquid poem to the glory of the hops ! your palate will be left blank ; with an enduring finish you will be able to take the next swig with bitter grace . great rich golden ipa , if you like hops this is your buddy .  medium to light body , lighter as the beer warmed overall a good ipa with 10 % abv .

smell was good , but didnt get that big clean hoppy aroma i am accustomed to , still smelled some hops , but mainly it was sweet malt .  pours a beautiful opaque black with brown hues around the edges and creamy cappuccino-colored hear . stellar .  the flavour sees the banana upfront with a refreshing wheat body and crisp finish . my one complaint would be that the body is maybe a tad too light .

fresh , floral aroma . great initial texture , fine , if brief , finish . fits perfectly in the euro-lager bag , with nothing standing out , on the good or bad side .  incredible huge head that has great retention .  a little too much carbonation at times .

s - a nice belgian nose , that yeasty , sweaty .  poured an inky black with a big billowing creamy tan head that left lacing all the way down my glass . this is one good looking beer .  smelled of raspberries of course , but with a nice yeasty undertone . taste was very sweet , like raspberry pop . we had this as a before-dinner drink , and everyone was pretty happy with it . my mother ca n't believe it 's actually beer . i recommend as a dessert beer or a beer to give people who do n't think they like beer .

sharp aroma - not very strong - but sharp bite of coffee . the coffee flavor is very natural & finishes crisply . i find it light-medium bodied and not all that sweet .  a : poured with a great slight tan dense head with good lacing .  mouthfeel is somewhat grainy and perhaps a little more carbonated than i 'd like this style to be .

little aroma , slight spice , clove , but a huge spicey , banana , clovey , wheaty , wheaty , flavour .  geuze boon . appearance : poured to give a beautiful golden ( light amber ) beer with a rich , thick white foam head that had good longevity . the beer was slightly hazy ( chill haze ? ) .  this beer was very easy to drink , but really most of them are . it had plenty of bite from the hops , which i enjoyed , but it was very well balanced by the sweetness of the malt . i am definitely going to grab a few more . it is worth getting your hands on .

smell - light hop smell with some roastiness that faded as the head went down .  duvel poured into its proper glassware pours a golden straw yellow with a big , almost overwhelming white head that leaves huge spots of sticky lacing .  m.light bodied fizzy carbonation .

i had already tried ( and reviewed ) hilltop 's red ale , but i was thus far unprepared for their cask conditioned red ale . at hilltop , the waitress gave me a little shotglass of their regular red ale , along with my pint of cask conditoned .  a - a pleasing fluffy bubbled up tan head riding a midnight colored stout underneath s - strong toffee infused coffee and light anise spice with nutty vanilla aromas m - spicy bitter , smooth , creamy silky warming and ultra roasted t - creamy caramel and bitter sweet chocolate flavors grab my mouth by the tongue initially .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and kind of watery .

the aroma is not strong , but there is plenty of roasty , hoppy flavor . not a strong beer , but a very good , high quality beer .  from the bottle.poured mahogany big light tan head that left some lacing , aroma , toffee , malty , alcohol , citrus leanig towards .  m : medium in body , the carbonation could be a bit higher , and it leaves the mouth with an almost oily texture . definitely coats the mouth .

the bouquet while the head was there was pleasant enough .  a : this pours a transluscent and vibrant golden color with tons of fast-rising bubbles and two fingers of frothy , dome-shaped head that laces very well .  a bit more carbonated than i tend to like on a stout- and the consistency is a bit more watery than i really like .

pretty much nil aroma . there is a touch of grain but that 's it .  truly a spectacular looking brew .  taste is malty with a good bitter coffee aftertaste , seems a bit thin and watery though , if it was a bit `` thicker '' it would have been great .

some faint toasted aromas and a hallertau scent , but mostly clean . toasted pale and pilsener malt sweetness meets a noble hop bitterness for a magnificent balance .  into a tulip , pours a very large beige head atop a murky amber body .  thin for style , but perfectly low carb , quite creamy , with a finish that is tasty , but not in the way of the crazy clinging dank , molasses , and bitter of many fine offerings of this style . i like this , but i could see a lover of some of the major players in this category thinking it is n't thick nor full flavored enough .

s : sweet , malty with very slight metallic notes . sure it does n't have all of the pomp of an artisinal brew but it is delectable .  poured into a gouden carolus glass . cloudy fainted yellow colour , an abslolutely enormous head that lasts for all its life in the glass .  i was hoping for a belgian strong ale with some woody characteristics , but i got whiskey instead . whiskey aromas , vanilla , bubblegum and spicey alcohol mix together in the aroma and is off putting . pretty much the same going on in flavor with vanilla , whiskey , and coriander-like flavors dominating . odd , oily - almost like mescal - flavors made me want to puke . i tried hard to like this since it was a gift and wanted to tell the gifter that i enjoyed it , but i did n't . someone wake me up when this whiskey barrell aging fad runs its course .

the aroma is not unpleasant , just incongrruous with this otherwise majestic beer . the slight hint of sourness , faint but sharp esters , and touch of oak do not even begin to hint at the massive flavor explosion that awaist the drinker . simple incredible . the mouthfeel on this thing is creamy , magical , caressing . overall , the beer is insanely drinkable .  creamy head with excellent retention and lacing , steady carbonation .  it has too much fizz for the style . roasty roasty coffee notes , the sour/tart makes it different , but grows a bit too much as it progresses , and the carbonation is just too much for what it should be . still , it 's a very good imperial stout overall that i 'm glad i had the chance to have !
s= nice biscuit smell to it . not too much .  looks pretty exceptional .  light and a little thin o-great double , one of my favorites

rye grain and mostly citric hop on a rather faint nose .  dark , dark dark ! thick head that is also dark brown and sticks around for a while . i hesitate to use the word `` stouty '' with respect to a stout but that 's what it is , a dark rough mix of hop , char and wood .  there is also almost no after taste to be found ( weird ) mouth-feel : extremely dry with a light bodied feel .

aromas are subdued and largely of yeast with faint , nondescript malts . fortunately it is full of excellent taste .  the waiter slid me a pint of stout with a seal brown body and a thick , creamy , burnt chocolate head . retention was excellent , and lacing was everywhere ... probably left some down my sides , too .  almost juice ? mouth was bitter , to be expected , but not a strong bitter , washed about like any other average beer . watery . i 'm impressed with the balance with this brew . one time only but sure would be good in place of lagunitas 's other ipa 's .

smell was average because it did n't have any aromas standing out to the positive or to the negative , just smelled like a decent beer . now the taste was very good because i got exactly what i was expecting from a cream ale and then some ! the establishment was new , but had a potential you could already see that the brewers were taking to new heights .  pours a dark brown/black color , very little light being able to shine through ( only on the edges ) , perfect sized head with great retention and some lacing .  f - more than almost any other beer i 've tried , this one leaves a stickiness in my mouth , and makes me quite thirsty .

the smell however was a bit weak . but i really wanted something strong to smell and this drink lacked that kind of punch .  the head is strong as is the lacing and the color is jet black and the head at first is so massive , it however falls into this thin head that does n't break it 's surface .  one of the easiest to drink and one of the most refreshing beers out there . jimmy buffett knows his market ( summer pounder beer ) ! the only complaint i have is that this beer ( along with red stripe & corona ) are way overpriced for the style of beer . if i spend $ 9 a six pack , i 'm buying a craftbrew with high quality ingredients not this type of beer .

i really enjoyed drinking this beer . it appears to have a golden hue through the bottle . way better than beck 's , and even slightly better than spaten .  appearance : wow , this is a beaut . a thick , pocked berg of espresso foam with excellent retention tops it . great lacing .  i even like wild blue , even though that tastes like grape soda instead of beer . it does n't even taste like cider . it tastes a little like sparkling white grape juice and apple juice mixed together with even less of a cheap pilsner . i drank it , and ca n't believe that i did , so i gave it at least a 2 for drinkability .

smells malty , light saaz hop ? scent .  oily pitch black body beneath a towering cascade of deep brown foam . the head finally settles to a thick cap of tightly-packed bubbles , all the while draping intricate webs of lacing as the beer level drops . just gorgeous .  still very good though , even if mouthfeel is thinner than i 'd like .

with the foam gone , the beer yielded sweet , chocolate aromas with a very light roast . whatever was lacking in the aroma was trapped in the taste , in a good way . it 's not intimidating , like the czar . another success from a great brewery .  pours a black color with a frothy brown head , fair lacing .  mouthfeel was medium-thin , with relatively low carbonation .

slight soapiness upon agitation smell : a barrage of fruits citric fruits , apples & bananas .  it 's a dark golden colored beer with a fully lasting head , purely belgian , it laces well on the glass .  341ml bottle poured into pint glass nov1 2010 a dark brown with a light brown head that has decent retention and leaves a partial ring of lace followed by some patches s faint coffee with loads of milk chocolate and the cherry 's there but quite subtle t chocolates a little darker in the mouth and the cherry comes out a little more and just the faintest hint of woody smoke , not completely dry but a little more sugar may have worked well for it m could use some more bubbles and not as thick as the color would imply d overall this ones pretty decent , i 'd drink int again so that says something just enough cherries to have a positive affect any less and it would go unnoticed and anymore and it would take away form the nice chocolate flavors .

aroma is light , mostly dark malts . it does n't start as much , and even starts to fade .  poured into a pint glass and the look was pretty amazing . its truly a beauty to look at .  this is pretty oily , so i would like a bit more carbonation .

s : a promising nose is cut short by an unfortunate laundry smell -- mildew and detergent . inexplicably , the smell improved drastically . fruity with hop flourishes .  pours black with 2 fingers of mocha colored head .  the look was a little weak ( i felt it should have been a bit darker ) and i would have liked a bit more carbonation . the head was a little weak and thin as well . but again , it was the flavour : somewhat strong but not too bitter , and a very nice , somewhat nutty aftertaste which lingered for a little while .

s : bouquet is quite faint , and bread is all that makes it through . t : dry and crisp , with notes of caramel and citrus to make things interesting .  thick white , fluffy head holds together for a really long time . a very good looker .  the mouthfeel is on the lighter side of medium bodied , as it should be for the style . it is slightly over carbonated for the style though , and that seems to take away from the flavor a little .

the smell is somewhat metallic to me , although i do pick up some hops . t : just a plain out wonderful taste . i did n't want this beer to end .  it was pitch black and thick . it had a 2 finger dark brown head that slowly settled into a constant foam . no visible carb but great lacing that stuck around till it was finished .  m - not much of an aftertaste because the entire flavor dissipated before i was able to describe it and i have to take another sip . the spiciness lingers a little , but not as long as many belgians . is hidden pretty well ... however there are definitely better beers of this style out there .
nose was light with a hint of malt .  looks damn perfect .  a little watery in the mouth but not horrible .

the appearance was similar to an unfiltered ipa . the smell was of course hoppy , but there was a lot of sweetness lurking past the hops . it was initially hard to detect in the smell , but it was noticeable . the hops were obviously present , but my tongue got a workout with all the flavors .  pours perfectly with a massive amount of tan head , and pitch black opaque body with just a hint of reddish hues on the edge of the bottom of the glass .  mouthfeel was medium with a mild sweetness on the tongue .

very enjoyable arome if you like bloody mary 's .  a somewhat vigorous pour creates a massive and incredibly persistent head . body is a fairly dark but very clean and clear amber . this is a great looking beer .  it is a fairly crisp beer with high carbonation , so it has that going for it .

unique smell reminds me of a steel plant ( ie lots of sulfer ) .  pitch black in color in just about any light . poured slightly thinner than other beers of the style . significant deep brown coffee-like head that held most of the way through the beer .  mouthfeel - smooth , although noticeably watery .

i 've also had their regular original helles lager style beer that actually smells similar to this but this has a bit more maltier richer smell i guess because of its marzen style .  2011 vintage . looks hazy amber , great lacing and very inviting smells subdued , slight hop aroma which is surprising considering what this beast tastes like tastes like honey , flowers , citrus and has slight ethanol in the background due to the high abv .  the feel is a bit thin .
s- smell consists of roasted malt and coffee . a bit faint .  there is a lot of staying power to the head and some awesome lace . excellent looking beer !  m : like your average english ale .

aroma was even worse .  `` wow '' this is one hell of a stout ! pours a thick , robust , ink-black viscous fluid topped with a thick tan head that lasts a long time .  mouthfeel was unexceptional , and light to medium bodied .

cheap , so cheap , thanks joe ! overall , a very good beer , i will pick up a few more and let them sit for a few months or years , and for the price , why not .  this is simply one of the best looking beers you will ever see . nice head retention and super dark color . the color was so beautiful , i could n't see through it , so that 's a plus in my book .  chocolate and coffee lead off taste , with raspberry rising up among the hops just before the finish . the raspberry makes a nice accent for the stout , never dominating it . i had feared that this was the beer equivalent of dunking your toast in your morning coffee . no sense of alcohol , perhaps masked by the raspberry . while not watery , i like my imperials to have a bit more viscosity . surpisingly drinkable for an imperial . while i could n't see this as one of my staples , i can see me putting a bottle or three in my weyerbacher mix-it-yourself cases .

smell is really faint but mostly of roasted malts .  pours a perfect straw yellow , crystal clear with a careful pour , with a large foamy head of perhaps 3 fingers or more . fantastic head retention leaves lacing all the way down the glass .  the mouthfeel has little flesh and does n't really hold up to the caramel notes from the nose .

a thin , but uniformly solid tan head with minimal fragrances , mostly malt but with the faintest touch of cocoa also present . and as usual , the holywater used by rogue prevents any lingering aftertaste to ruin the experience . a great beer .  plenty of lacing -- very visually appealing !  because the hops and the malt do n't overwhelm you the mouthfeel is light to medium while drinkability is exceptional .

the nose is basically non-existent , but that is n't surprising for this style of ale .  a - pours a jet black color , impenetrable to light , with a dark tan half inch thick head .  first sip..boom lots of carbination almost too much almost burned my mouth , i didnt like that so i let it sit for a few minutes to warm up and still too much carbination which i did not enjoy at all kind of killed it for me . good beer just too much carb definitely a lot of other imperials out there that are better . check out moylans imperial its a lot more satisfying .

s : the aromas are mainly bakers chocolate and cocoa . not much barrel in the nose and a bit weak for an imperial stout . t : damn the nose did not prepare me for the taste .  pours almost black with a thick tan head an good lacing .  m/d : has a bitter mouth feel that dries it out quickly so it is not the best for drinking on a hot day or to quench a thirst but all in all a great session beer that has amazing taste and smells and i really want this one again .

also found `` cat-pee '' in the aroma . husband did n't like it as much and ended up adding a dash of raspberry syrup to his , which i tasted and must say was quite nice . instant raspberry wheat beer .  gorgeous hazy apricot with about 1 finger of head .  a little thin bodied , a little too much alcohol in the finish .

i 've never really quite known what people meant when they said their ipa smells like onion , until now ! this beer is full of raw onion aroma -- not quite enough to make me cry , but , it 's starting to feel like i should ! there 's a bit of earth and grass character as well , along with some garlic , strangely enough , but the onion aroma is certainly dominant .  a . beautiful looking lager . warm red amber with small head and almost no lacing .  the body is bit on the thin side , but that 's not necessarily out of the ordinary for an oatmeal stout .

aroma is malty and slightly sweet . nice `` lager '' . would make an excellent gateway beer .  looks great . nice hazy colorful yellow beer .  m : does n't feel to heavy on the pallet , a bit to much carbonation .

sweet and bready smelling . actually smells just like a warm bob evans biscuit slathered in honey ! sweetness still lingers on the tongue , but the fruity and floral hops are felt in the nose and throat . i prefer my american pale ales more dry and bitter , but this is a tasty little drink with no real conflict from the mountains of west by god virginia .  slight chill haze permeates the solid orange/rust colored body with a two finger head that fell slowly , leaving sticky lace all over the glass .  smells and tastes sorta like a coffee i once had , nutty ( ? ) i want to say . anchor porter is very unique to me ... of course this my first time having a porter . at first i thought i would n't want to drink a healthy amount of this , but then the beer just grew on me . it was soon goin ' down great . i would gladly drink again .

s : smells of grass , lemon , grains , bit o ' malt . t : quite nice .  big thanks to kraken6100 for this one : a : this beer is stunning . it pours a beautiful dark honey color with a massive tan bubbly head .  mouthfeel - slightly effervescent .

the aroma is that if light malt and a piney hop aroma . the hop aroma is not what you would expect at all from a ipa . it is very light compared to most other ipa 's .  light yellow/gold color , with a full , lasting , frothy foam .  mf & d- thin bodied and well carbonated .

the scent was a bit dissapointing though , kind of thin .  dark , rich amber body has a nice glow . the head starts off big-bubbled and a bit fizzy , but settles into a nice cream-colored melted icecream layer that does n't seem to get any thinner . plentiful streaming carbonation gives the beer a sense of being alive .  mouthfeel - 3.0 moderately carbonated , reasonably smooth , nothing to complain about here .

i guess that many cherries will do that ... the aroma was tart cherries , and fairly pleasant , with a definite edge to it .  beautiful in a glass .  i poured a 12 ounze bottle into a pint glass and immediatly noticed the beautiful color and head . the heaed left much lace which was nice and sticky . there was a stong hop aroma and a strong hop taste . neither was overpowering and both were artfully crafted and mixed . do n't drink and review .

overall , the nose is rather muted .  a : vigorous pour leads to a 4.5 finger quickly collapsing head that retains nicely at 3 fingers . also incredibly dense . frothy , thick , and ruler-like , measuring my every sip .  m : gently creamy carbonation , perhaps a little thin overall .

the nose was weak . i picked up some slight citrus and earthy hops and a bit of malts , not much .  pours a consistent head with a nice lay that looks like a great americano .  the mouthfeel was lackluster , probably because this bottle had plenty of time to sit .

i smelled right for an ipa with a hint of pine and trees and bushes and leaves .  very good looking beer .  smells of buttery pumpkin , spices , and hints of vanilla t- sweet and spicy , with a hint of vanilla in the finish m- very little carbonation . smooth and slightly heavier than i had expected .

s : the smell is a bit underwhelming for a big brew with a floral hop aroma t : a nicely balanced flavor that is hoppy , yet is not ridiculously vegetal like some dipa 's .  appearance - it has a beautiful pour from the growler to a pint glass . it 's a nice pale orange color and fades extremely slow . the body of the brew is a hazy orange and amber color . superb .  i took my first sip and was shocked , this tasted totally like an ipa . seemed overly carbonated and gassy . 21st amendment is a great little pub and they have a fine addition to their solid line up with this one .

this may have reduced the aroma when i did pour it , or else it just does n't have much of one . what i could detect was more malt than hops . it did have a nice clear dark golden color and a big foamy head . a smooth malty quality predominates the flavor with a backing of hops . i usually think of the opposite with czech beers . my brother referred to this as the miller of the czech beers , referring mostly to its lack of uniqueness compared to others . this is not a hard beer to drink .  appearance - this beer pours a 2 finger thick and frothy head into my tulip glass . the head 's hint of pink and sexy figure conjures images of cotton candy , barista creations , and clouds of the imagination . pretty straight forward at the nose and then the flower power hits you over the head in the end .  moderately carbonation a bit too strong for my taste - better on tap .

not much aroma except some faint roasted malt , wonderful roast malt , chocolate malt flavor balanced with hops . finish is smooth that begs for another draught .  this beer is great , beautiful glowing amber color with significant , lasting head , stained glass window lacing , and plenty of little bubble friends to hang out with .  toasted grains , coffee , somewhat sweet and not a bad nose for a porter , the start mostly malt , the top rather thin . finish has a mild acidity , the hops perky in their spiciness , very dry and long lasting aftertaste , overall a fair to middling porter .

smells of strong maltiness mixed with a strong infusion of hops .  i 'd say there was about 1.5 inches of very frothy , highly carbonated head on top which dissipated to about a quarter of an inch within minutes of pouring . the beer itself is a golden-ish , peachy , honey color .  only complaint is that it seems overcarbonated , and too foamy and tingly . other than that , a very nice beer .

coors light works for me in the following ways . out of a cooler packed with ice on a hot summer day doing any of the following activities : backyard bbq , mowing the lawn , a day at the track or any sporting event , or just hanging with friends and family . the golf cart girl has few choices , and is usually stocked full of these and miller lite . best served ice cold - as cold as you can get em . now - i would not compare these to any of the craft beers in any way shape of form .  pours from a pint bottle a deep , dark amber , almost mahogany color , with a 2 1/2 finger head that protrudes from the top of my hobgoblin glass . extremely creamy head has phenomenal retention , and very slowly falls into a creamy blanket on top of the glass leaving behind a veritable wall of dense lace . looks perfect .  m - a little more thin than i would like with a little lack of carbonation .

it 's an example of a very drinkable apa . i bought a bottle from halftime , in a mixed 6 , and tried this one first . it even looked a crystal clear dark golden brown . i might grab a 6 pack of this sometimes .  a jet black beer with lovely head that resembled the crema from espresso and a nose of a rich dark chocolate .  the was a little too thin for my liking , but this is typical of most terrapin stouts .

maybe it 's too chilled , but getting almost nothing in the nose . another swirl and i might be getting distant malt . the taste makes up in a nice way for the near-null nose ... very bready/biscuity/malty .  a : first of all ... huge head ! this is a truly gorgeous beer .  when my friends and i sampled the whole assortment of cheap beers , this was the one we settled in with as our most purchased variety . it was the most tolerable , easiest to drink cheap without `` bad beer face '' , and produced the least amount of hangover effects . i have on occassions tried this beer over the 20 years since college and still find this beer in particular to be one of the easiest cheap beer to drink without any bad taste . i 've tried pabst a few times and struggle to finish them because it actually tastes `` bad '' flavor . sure natural light lacks any strong flavors compared to a high-end ipa , porter , imperial stout etc ... but compared to its equivalent price-marked competitors its one of the best choices you can make .

smells a little mediciny - perhaps evidence of some oxidation , or a hint of the alcohol . hops and malt balance very nicely . rich and flavorful .  pours rusty with slight cloudiness . gorgeous , puffy head that does n't quit , and phenomenal lacing .  mouthfeel was medium , not terribly oily and almost chewy . it 's maybe a bit to cloying and sticky for my liking but all-in-all a decent , well-balanced brew .

smell is sweet , some toffee , butter , fruits , yeast and bread .  enjoyed in my chimay goblet : rich , ruby red coloration with a thin , white head and a touch more carbonation than its brother beers ( blue & white ) . no other red brew looks this majestic , while still being mysterious and imposing .  m : medium with a little creaminess and some oil .

that aftertaste had to be washed out with a bell 's two hearted ale .  appearance : poured into a pint glass ( made two pours ) black ( how black can black be ? ) , with a nice 1/2 inch brown head . leaves some good lacing .  taste : higher carbonation than most stouts and some extra bitter roast coffee notes .

a - very dark ( little to no light passes through it ) , almost no head at all ( what is there is tan and dissipates quickly ) s - smells promising with notes of dark chocolate and malt t - initial notes of coffee and dark chocolate resolving into a bit of smoke ... and then nothing ! disappointing because initially it shows a lot of promise with a good nose and some enticing darker notes .  a-this is the absolute blackest beer i 've ever seen . decent head , but it 's hardly noticeable because of the body .  mouthfeel a little heavy , with medium carbonation .

i expected a nice rye bread scent , which it had although very faint .  bottle poured into a tulip glass a - the color of wild honey . heavy lacing on the glass . simply gorgeous .  mouthfeel : lots of carbonation , feels light and airy .

beautiful light straw color.white foam disappears quickly , thin lace remains around edge of glass , expected longer lasting foam for this style.faint hop aroma . mild malt aroma with spicy notes .  pours out a beautiful picture ; a huge creamy beige head sits atop a pure black colored body .  well carbonated , a bit prickly at times . drinkability : a reasonably complex , enjoyable brew , though , for my tastes , the carbonation was just a bit too high .

this was the last keg left of this brew , and it lacked any discernible aromas . otherwise , the mouthfeel was too good making drinkability all too easy .  i 'm a sucker for the guinness cascade , though the appearance of this beer is great even just based on its midnight darkness and bronze head .  the carbonation becomes a liability to the weight and texture , which go up in bubbles before i can get a bead on them . some of my fellow bas have been unnecessarily critical of the unique carbonation level rather than seeing it for what it is .

aroma is of wheat and spices ( cloves or nutmeg- i have difficulty distinguishing between the two sometimes ) . maybe some hops poke through , but it lacks a little in this department .  a - black with an enormous head that takes an eternity t fade and leaves thick webs of lacing everywhere on the glass . a mountain of head rests in the middle over still half an inch of head . very pretty .  m - i did feel violated , but i wo n't press charges , officer .

i expected more vanilla scent out of the bottle , but there was n't much .  this brew pours a picture perfect presentation . the head is very tight with lots of ultra white foam and a golden clear body .  m - carbonation is a little too zesty for my liking .

softly bread-y and only mildly roasty . instead , i 'm met with a huge diacetyl rush . definitely not an english porter but firmly an original american entry into the style .  a - copper color with thick three finger foamy head after very non-agressive pour . a decent ipa but a little bit of a let down after all the hype and the great smells .  m- very clean with a good amount of carbonation . it does build on the palate a little bit , which i found odd considering how thin this beer was .

smell was average to the style . really good flavor , though i 've had better tasting german brewed oktoberfests .  pours a rich , slightly murky amber and really is a work of art . produces a generous , yet loose head which slowly retreats to a thin cap that lasts the duration . lace is moderate but sticky .  a little rough going down , but over all very nice .

the smell , well i had to only give this a 3 because my nose is plugged and i ca n't smell so i dont necessarily want to just throw a number out there . the taste is a little stronger then what i like but it is still a tasty beverage . overall great buy and would recommend !  lovely hazy orangy gold color .  bottle poured into st. bernardus chalice three finger head murky gold in color , off white head s : spices , belgian yeast , and phenols t : lemongrass , spices , coriander , and much more m : okay , i 've had better tripels , this seemed too thin .

s : good porter aroma .  750 ml into a snifter/ `` best before '' of 07-2009 p : golden brown from the bottle , sits a deep brown with red grape/purplish tint to it in the glass . it 's huge & healthy , dense , frothy & rocky with unrelenting retention . it finally sinks to leave sticky lace caked all over my snifter .  m - this one coasts all the way down .

s- heaven.. grapefruit , citrus , and piney . seriously i wish someone would market an air freshener that smells like this . great beer . too bad that for $ 2 more than i got this single bottle , i could get a 6pack of two-hearted .  lace is solid froth from top to bottom . awesome .  the mouthfeel was not as great as i had hoped it would be , i really would like to taste this beer on draft . reminds me of guinness , but with a richer taste and more carbonated .

lots of great smells coming from this brew , i can not wait to try it . smells a lot better then it taste .  this beer poured a reddish gold color and formed an amazing sudsy white head . the lace was an incredible airy cloudlike style .  mouth feel is fairly light with light carbonation .

s : i could n't smell much , sort of a maple smell , kinda sweet , but nothing really stands out .  awesome appearance when poured ... big , pillowy , creamy , yet rocky head on this 80 watt bulb-opaque , brown-black beauty .  i had this year 's version at the brewpub and while it is not as good as great lakes ' christmas beer or sn celebration , it is still a very good beer . you can really smell the cinnamon and taste the blend of malts and spices . if you are in the toledo area it is worth the stop at maumee bay brewing co. for a pint or three or maybe a stop at the andersons or other store for a bomber .

smell : earthy and hoppy in the nose . not much there in terms of smell .  a : stellar ... beautiful red . thick foamy head that makes you wait ... damnit .  malt in the nose ... malt in the taste . caramel shitty malt . yes i sound angry . it borders on barleywine , which is the worst beer style ever .

rye bread and soap , maybe a hint of citrus and pine on the nose , a touch of lemon . not too much till it warms up , then it emphasizes more of the same . amazingly smoothe on the tongue , creamy and luscious . mildly malty at first , a hint of caramel , followed by a fine blend of bitter hops .  it pours like motor oil , coming out a warm chocolaty sable with a very thick and fine-bubbled tan head . there is also an odd rubbery tone that i usually find with wheat beers .  smell : corny , grainy a little bit of lemon and grass , very little hoppiness taste : taste follows nose , bland and unexciting mouthfeel : goes down really smooth , i wish there was a little more thickness but it 's ok all in all this is an ok beer for the price but imo labatt is the best cheap beer around .

excellent retention and lacing ( the nitro pour probably helps ) very faint malty aroma . super creamy and smooth ale .  pours pitch black into the corsendonk tulip , and an aggressive pour produce a thick and sexy tan capper , sheets of lace on the way down .  m : smooth , not as robust as i would like in a ris , a little thin , pretty average . d : the lessened mouthfeel adds to the drinkability , making this probably the most drinkable ris that i 've ever had .

s : smells ... well ... really hoppy . mostly grapefruit . t : well balanced . m : medium , slick , pretty much good for an ipa o : bit of step-down overall from the unearthly .  a -- pours a near black that glows with a reddish/brown hue when held to the light . huge two finger tan head that recedes slowly and leaves a thick layer of lacing on the pint glass s -- very unique imperial stout smell , the vanilla is so thick here i wonder why they did n't just call it a `` vanilla imperial stout .  the taste comes on mildly hoppy at first , but sweetens in the middle , possessing an almost carmel-like overtone . the finish is clean and refreshing . i would consider this a fine session beer for a hot , sunny day .

s : not its strong suit ; reminded me of day-old beer smell . t : a pleasing , tangy flavor ; not bitter but just enough kick .  poured into a weizen glass appearance- clear golden color with a large , stubborn fluffy white head . this beer just looks phenomenal . smell- lemon , fresh cut grass , semi musty dank cellar , the sage as stated on the bottle is very present , a hint of wheat .  as others have said , this is very reminiscent of an ipa , the aroma of fresh hops and pine are similar to that style . this brew has an amber color and when poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glass creates a nice white head . the taste is very refreshing and seems like a fabulous brew to have on a hot summer day . i could , and would like to , drink this again . too bad i can never find it .

light hop aroma is not overpowering and not much to write home about .  a - deep amber-brown pour with a very rich and generous head , grate frothy retention with a remarkable surface memory and rich lacing .  the body is medium-light with medium carbonation , and could benefit from being a touch heavier so that it boosts the flavour even more , but its okay as it is .

nose was rather light but consisted mostly with sweet malts with a faint aroma of spicy hops .  pours a fantastic , rich tan head that looks like puffy clouds that you could jump in .  mouthfeel seems dominated but a fast carbonation , over a thin to medium liquid .

a more subdued aroma than i had expected ; mainly grapefruit , with a bit of caramel malt . a very complex flavor . a very nicely balanced beer , for sure ... really an excellent and quaffable ale .  the pour is jet black with a luxurious , thick , creamy khaki head that sticks around forever .  the body was cloudy and a deep yellow color . the off white head and lace was very creamy . this might have been the sweetest flavored weizen i had ever tasted . it was very banana like and a bit of bubble gum to it . as with all of their beer though i did find it to be thin .

aromatic malt characteristics are of the chocolate and burnt caramel variety . not roasty , per say , but certainly a `` burnt '' quality to it , maybe even coffee-like , an acrid presence which is a touch of-putting . i love the coffee character as it does n't get too roasty and the dark chocolate flavors suit the beer well .  appearance : pours very black with a thick , billowy , light chocolate brown head that sticks around for a little bit .  this is well-done and a clear american classic , but the mouthfeel seemed a little thin and i think the beer could have been a tad more aggressive wrt maltiness and/or malt complexity without hurting the smoke profile at all .

i had this on tap at smokey bones . i 'll have to say , this beer did'nt really have much of a scent to it . it was caramely and i also smelled a slight sweetness in it . plus there was a trace of hops in the nose but again not very pronounced scent . i 'm never really got into oktoberfest 's as much as i could have , but this year i am starting to appreciate this most festivus style a bit more .  a : hazy gold with massive white bright foamy head . retention superb . carbonation brisk and beautiful . gorgeous beer .  a : golden straw/amber hue , passes lots of light , nice white head , mild lacing s : strong bourbon , vanilla , malty t : vanilla , bourbon , mild caramel m : decent carbonation , light to medium bodied , watery overall , this beer has a great nose and taste .

nose is unremarkable , though i do n't recall ever hankerin ' for a big whiff of a bock before , so i figure this one is typical - and therefore average - for the style .  pours a deep brown that lets no light through . the best part is the head on this . tan , chunky , and thick , this 2 inch creamy show-stopper stays all the way down the pint , leaving gobs - literally the size of marbles - stuck to the sides with every sip . absolutely fabulous .  the body is moderately light and mouthfeel is clean . the beer is not brewed with corn and it 's good for another 10 months so i do n't know what the problem is . i expected a helles with less body and malt flavor , but what i got was a corny mess . i ca n't imagine why they would even sell this beer .

smells of sweet , sweet malt liquor goodness . corn , funk , and alcohol .  a - pours copper gold with good clarity and a 2 fingered white head . it dissipates slow and leaves beautiful lacing .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied .

autumn gold in color , nice malty aroma , sheet lacing . not too much head , but left beautifully striped lacing all through my glass .  appearance is perfect with a thick foamy white head on a nice murky golden pour .  hints of raisins & toast with a dry , fruitty ( dates ) finish mf : a bit sharp with a little too much carbonation drinks fine , just a little too young ( i think )

very malty aroma , which was okay , poured to a brown with hints of red .  bell 's kalamazoo stout poured black , with a brown head , that was of decent size .  m : light to medium body . medium level of carbonation .

smells like a brooklyn black chocolate stout but without the rotting fruit . yes , it 's smoky , but that flavor gets muddled by what can only be called the prune juice factor . tastes much better than it smells -- a very nice combination of ( surprisingly ) subtle fruit and strong , well-developed malts . regardless , it 's astonishing that the same brewer that puts out a beer as mediocre as harpoon ipa could also put out this very well made baltic porter .  the graphic design on the bottle is seasonal and gorgeous : the beer 's color is remarkably similar to the outlay of the `` themed '' elements : foothills covered in snow , hollyberry replacing the hop trellises , the bear-ish creature done up for the season . the giant , rocky head and unbelievably sticky lace are noteworthy but seem on par with this great brewery 's offerings .  mouthfeel is average , medium body and on the crisper side with the finish .

chocalate , toffee , a sweetness that i just place , and a remarkable aroma that faintly reminds me of soy sauce of all things .  pours dark brown with a super thick and foamy tan head like a milkshake .  a bit thin , imo .
smell : not much aroma here , just a hint of bitterness .  what a great foamy head and lacing some coppery amber hues .  the mouthfeel was a bit weak for the style .

leaves a pleasant thin ring along the top edge of beer . smell - very slight citrus odors , a reasonable wheat presence , and an alchohol scent just barely gets past the coriander . taste - impressive . very smooth wheat start and a little bit of bite on the end . excellent coriander taste.. has a moderate amount of warmth which compliments the flavor .  pitch black pour with a massive tan head .  the mouthfeel is smooth , but a bit lacking in the carbonation .

aroma is deeply of dark grains , i note coffee and oatmeal , but i 'm sure the chocolate 's in there somewhere .  intense 4 fingers of dark tan head . great retention and sticky lacing .  mouthfeel : nice mouth-coating , but a much weaker carbonation than i was expecting ( the tap ? ) .

s : nothing too complex , just sweet toasted caramel malts . t : nice munich malts play a big player in this flavor .  midnight black ... as black as black can be with a milkshake like bubbly brown head ... smells a bit like a milkshake too with a sweet nose of milk chocolate .  extremely mild , even for an english style , however it had an interesting coffee finish , which i do n't think i 've ever found in a nut brown before . particularly curious , since the malts were not all that roasted . hmm .

very grainy , malty nose . solid scent , but not neccesarily 'on . ' chewy malt and graininess dominate he moderate hop taste and bitterness .  this one gets high marks for appearance . very bright gold with clarity , but pepper like particles float around . it looks like it is boiling while it sits there . lots of carbonation coming from the bottom .  taste : a true witch 's brew of vegetables , raspberry punch , and a thin maltiness . finishes tart and watery . mild carbonation .

the color is a nice amber color not too amber , but decent , lil too much of a carbonation feel when i drink it , overall this one was a good hefe , i could really see drinking this one again , or even becoming a staple in the choc line up .  two and a half fingers of frothy/creamy tan head with great retention and a thick ring of lacing . good looking brew !  medium bodied with an oily texture .

earthy , malt ball , carob-tinged aroma - but very subdued overall . even when it warmed up , everything was very neutral in the nose .  appearance : awesome multi finger head that lasts .  my main complaint is the mouthfeel , which is a little lacking given the style . a porter should be a little bit thicker , with more substantial body .

smell : light in the aromas . there is some caramel malt , with a slight nuttinessto it , nothing much else stands out . a very approachable oktoberfest beer , one to introduce a person to the style .  had this beer last night in fact , and ive always been a fan of the darker beers . appearance is great the good olde coffee like look , with an good smell as well . mouthfeel great though thats one thing the did better then mack 's stout , but yeah its a sam adams for a reason to get the good feel of beer .  pours really great , decent aroma for a porter , nice head and lacing , but the taste seems to be a little off ... but in retrospect the flavor is ok. enigma ... what the hell . seems like i got kicked in the head by a pack of wild hyenas , and then my throat got ripped out by a flock of roaming vampires and then my essence was drained by a murder of migrant tigers . weird stuff .

poured into a pint glass from cask at varga bar . initially cloudy from the pour , the slow cascade as it clears up is beautiful to watch . the smell is , in a word , english . maybe it was the pint glass , maybe the bar , but i was n't able to discern much beyond the english hops and malts . the taste backs up the english heritage , with appropriate malt , hops , and yeast flavors to an english beer . on top of that you get lovely roasted grain , some sweetness , and some nuttiness . it is amazing how much flavor this beer has , particularly given the very low abv . i have drank many english style beers recently , bitters and esbs and the like , and found i did n't like them nearly as much as i used to .  excellent construction , long lasting head .  nice ... mouthfeel : somewhat dry and crisp , but the body is 'way ' too thin for an oatmeal stout . they should thicken it up for a more chewy mouthfeel .

light coffee and chocolate smell , rather pleasant . the taste has a bit of a bite on the front end , followed by a stronge toasted malt flavor that dances over the tongue , with just enough hops for a nice bitter finish .  cloudy yellow amber with huge silky head with great retention and lacing .  mouthfeel : this beer kind of dries out my mouth .

no lasting lace . the aroma has hints of toasted malt , hay , and caramel . it has a medium mouthfeel which along with the smoothness and balance makes it easy to drink a few .  from the beginning , it has the perfect color for an imperial stout , with a deep , dark opaque black/brown color and a fluffy mocha-colored cap .  mouthfeel is decent , but the carbonation is way too pronounced , very fizzy and bubbly .

i was n't sure what to expect from this beer and i got a surprise both for good and bad . for one thing , this beer is much closer to a lager in taste and character than i expected . at the same time , i 'm really impressed by how spicy and bold in flavor the peppercorns came through . i love the back-of-the-throat spicy hit fromt he peppercorns .  almost pitch-black , impenetrable colour - big brown head with generous lacing . very low carbonation , thick and oily mouth feel , medium body .  medium dark lager yellow color with a smallish head that disappears rather quickly . aroma is a little soapy with pumpkin pie spices ... like from a can . flavor is pure pumpkin pie spice powder without the pumpkin meat . just spice sprinkled over a malt beverage . there are much more complex and genuine tasting pumpkin beers out there .

the smell is subtle roasted malts with a subtle , sweet hop aroma .  a- an orange to ruby red color , amazingly bright just like a fresh ipa .  medium to full bodied with carbonation on the high side .

smell : very light and subtle , with hints of toasted grain and a somewhat biscuity malt coming through .  this beer is very visually striking to me . it pours a brown color , with beautiful red hues around the edges , especially when held into the light . it has a moderate off white head that fades and laces the edges of the glass .  complex hops all the way and some fruity esters but not too strong just the way i like it mouthfeel is ok for the tyle but not as refreshing as i like i will probably revisit this next summer

nice hop aroma up front on the smell , dominated by citrusy hops and a bit of a piney aroma in there as well . very light and simple , but very crisp . aroma is maybe a little subdued for a dipa .  this beer is just looks great and enticing .  medium body , light effervescence .
the smell seems weak compared to the taste .  a : a very bright and saturated yellow with just a hint of orange .  the mouthfeel was light with a decent aftertaste of malted wheat .

not a terribly complex aroma , but nice . flavor picks up a bit more than the aroma , initial taste is a forward malt sweetness with faint flavors of oranges and bananas . very tasty , disappointing aroma is saved by an otherwise excellent drinking experience .  this beer came a candy apple amber with a big creamy oatmeal head that left some awesome lace .  i had this at the kickbacks cigar city/st somewhere dinner . i 'm reviewing this by memory on this i had this at the kickbacks cigar city/st somewhere dinner . i have had most of cc 's regular beers but i have not tried this yet . it 's not a sour saison , pretty malty and more bosy than usual style and the hops were more nocticble as well , a little citrus on nose and taste .

however , there is also a bit of a sour smell that i 'm not really digging .  rheingnheimer weizenbier hefetrb is an outstanding looking hefe weizen . it 's a little darker than normal , but has a beautiful light tan head .  mouthfeel : light-bodied . medium carbonation .

flavor is quite nice . never one of my favorite styles because i usually find the hops under-reaching or the malts a bit over the top .  appearance : pours dark brown , almost black in color with a pretty mocha head that lasts throughout aroma : mocha coffee , alcohol and chocolate .  carbonation was a bit heavy but no head developed as i poured . plenty of mouthfeel for the style .

missing any pronounced smell or aroma . sharp fresh hop taste , buffered by a bit of sweetness and bread taste .  pours a brilliant reddish-orange that radiates from the glass and has a bubbly off-white head that dissolves into a swirly fine layer around the glass .  m : fairly light body with matching carbonation . a little less substantial than would be ideal .

s : smells a bit musty with a grassy hop smell .  12oz bottle into a stone ipa flute . pours a clear gold with 2 fingers of off-white poofy head . even when it shrinks down some , there is still at least a 1/2 finger of retention left that leaves just massive hop lacing all over the glass .  mouthfeel : far more carbonated than most stouts and my only fault with this beer .

had this out of a bottle poured into a pint glass ... a : cloudy golden yellow color with a large white head ... s : some bitter hops and some faint malt ... t : wow , not as bitter as `` brutal '' implies . but starts with a nice maltiness the leads to a flowery bouquet of hops which are quite subdued , and actually taste very good , and not very bitter ... m : smooth and low carbonation ... d : a very good beer , i suppose the `` brutal '' part of the name may scare some people away , but it is actually quite drinkable ...  pours red/orange with 1 finger of sand colored head . great head retention & super lacing s : an almost dirt like smell , maybe mushroom ?  m -- perhaps a little too thin , but the carbonation is about right d -- nice sessionable porter here .

straight out of the fridge smell was almost non existant , but once warmed up for 5-10 minutes there is a pleasent sweetness of oh ... maybe light karo syrup and berry skins ?  appearance : the beer comes to me in an imperial pint with a big , fluffy khaki head . as the glass is drained , a nice layer of lacing is left behind . the beer itself is a ruby brown in color .  m : combination , lime tang drinkability : yes yes yes ... football beer

s - very delicate with light scents of pine , fruit , and sweet malt . t - malty sweetness , big breadiness , and a strong hop presence conspire to create an interesting ale of unique character .  a - black with a one-finger with a billowing chocolate head s - smells of booze , roasted malts and some baking chocolates t - starts off with some sweet , chocolaty malts that fades into some marshmallow and toffee . this is very solid , nothing ground shaking , but nothing mediocre .  the only redeeming fact was the mouthfeel was decent ; aside from that , it 's pretty bad all round .

s : malt with some belgian sugar and yeast . very subdued .  pours a nice chestnut brown color with a big foamy head that sticks to the glass as it recedes . just a little bit of haze to the body of they with some red hues coming through .  fresh hops and grapefruit wedges sprinkled with sugar all wrapped up in a big big big aroma . bitterness is overwhelming on the tongue . very welcome for a local beer . has balls . tastes great and ct needs more intensity . here it is . a+

it pours dark an bubbly with a perfect white head.very nice lacing all the way through , it looks very much like root beer . the taste starts smooth an mild but its very hoppy an nutty ( if i had to guess it would be almonds ) after it goes down . if you like brown ales but are searching for one thats easy to drink and still has the flavor this is the one , its a perfect compromise .  head almost rose past the rim ; exciting . appearance : hazy amber orange with three thick fingers of creamy ivory foam with a little bit of an orange cast . head retention is great ( still there even as the glass is almost done ) and big , chunky lace is left .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with some prickly carbonation .

loved the rich dark color , but the smell was nothing more than average - it almost steered me away since the lavender was lingering .  pours a three finger cream head that fades slowly leaving a good lace . nice crystal clear amber color .  mouth feel was a little thin , but there was little , if any , astringency .
