a-light golden color..nice pillowy white head s-not real assertive ... was hoping for more of a noble hop aroma ... more grainy than anything , ..not much for hops at all on the aroma . t-much better than the aroma ... nice crisp malt flavors..breads and crackers ... grainy ... hops lend a floral characteristic to the taste and a zesty peppery dry kick to the finish . m-clean , crisp , perfect carbonation ... d-wow..just drank two bottles of this way too quick ... .great session beer ... i like the taste a lot but wish the aroma had a little more to it .  great looking medium-copper colored brew , with an excellent , full , frothy , creamy head , which just would not go away .  the mouthfeel is kinda sticky and medium bodied , but once you drink about half of one , you feel very refereshed , even for the relative bitterness .

the smell is of a bit of hops , but mostly a thick , malty aroma .  pitch black with a few glimmers of brown around the edges . the persistent head is a tan one finger affair made of solid cream cheese consistency foam , and it never sank below a finger the entire time ! massive sheets of brown lace coat the glass from top to bottom .  m/d : very drinkable since it is light in the mouth because of smell and after flavor i would buy again .

the nose is quite minimal . definitely richer than any real german alt , but kind of like an uber-alt thats bigger in all dimensions but retains the relative balance among the flavor components .  the deep black opaque body and the creamy light tan head made up of so many tiny bubbles .  feel : prickly at the begninning but eventually going down smoother . by far one of the best bulgarian beers .

after one sip i threw it away , and placed the other five back in the fridge for company . it 's more like a wine cooler with a hint of beer . we debated what they could have won their gold medal in ... best blueberry beers ? it leaves the same dissapointment ab beers usually do with an irritating flat fizz afterwards .  served in a tulip glass . a - black pour with dark brown edges , rich towering creamy ecru head , nice retention , rich surface memory and lacing . overflowing as the growlers were served but this justifies all the overflow . quite the perfect looker ... s - roasted nose , chocolate , dash of coffee , bitter hint ... t - very nice roasted range , rather flavorful sense , plenty of chocolate malt , roasted notes , nice touches of coffee , small vanilla lingering in the finish .  appearance was only the can , which looked simple - nothing really wrong with it very little smell like bud light initially tasteless , except for the aftertaste bitter in a natural light kind of way mouth feel was alright - one of the better aspects the taste has made me hope to never be so desperate for a beer that i drink this again .

the smell is a disappointment with only a slight aroma of candy sugar .  looks very impressive , a murky brown color with a pillowing , sticky head .  m & d : light to medium body , but overly carbonated imo . the carbonation makes for a brew that stings a bit on the way down .

bomber chilled into 10oz glass a-deep amber color topped off with a tight white cap no head really..zero bubbles present..the graduation of color from bottom to top of glass is quite nice ... s-fairly neutral to be honest..a slight nose of sweet malts and a rustic smell ... no hops present ... t-nice subtle dry fruits and sweet malts ... a vinous character is there ... a very slight bit grassy and finishes a bit dry on the palate.. m-oily and coats the mouth well..the hops really stand out to me in the mouthfeel with their resiny character ... taste lingers for a while..carbonation is low but is what i expected with a beer of this style .  the density and staying power of the foam was amazing . tons of sticky lace was left on the glass . flawless appearance .  the mouthfeel is okay , but not the highlight of this beer .

cream ale is right ! not much to smell , a bit like cream soda . i could drink this stuff all day every day .  pours from the bottle a cloudy , opaque reddish orange hue under a huge , thick and frothy beige head . superb head retention throughout with a trail of thick lacing .  m - a little bit over-carbonated .

my nose sucks , really . i dont get much from sniffing beers . wonderful , wonderful .  pour yielded a tall brown and extremely thick head.the color was an opaque black.head took forever to reduce so i could take a sip.left tons of sticky and thick lace.appearance was exceptional.aroma 's of molasses and sweet chocolate with a hint of hops.a very easy and creamy mouthfeel.leaves a long lasting bitterness in the back of the throat.full bodied with a sweet finish.hints of coffee and smoke flavors.i taste the hops i didnt taste at first now.overall not bad.a little less bitterness and maybe a higer abv.needs a distinct flavor .  this beer 's body was a little light for style . the hops and sweetness do play on the roof of my mouth and the carbonation tingles my tongue .

smells like rich caramel and toffee , earthy and mildly citrusy ... the aroma is n't bad but could use some work .  reviewed this beer on www.beerutopia.com first impression great color , an bright orange ! good head on the pour .  bland and offensive . m- creamy with a boozy burn . if you have the patience to wait for the foam to die down to a point you can actually drink it you wo n't be rewarded .

aroma fails to impress . herbal and floral hops are up front , but end up a bit astringent . nice drinkability if it were n't so expensive .  pours a deep garnet with a big , airy , cratered tan head . wonderful lace . gorgeous in an imperial pint glass .  m - a bit thin , in my opinion , for a complex beer like this .

high on the fluff facotr ! some roasted malts but not much else . i assume the potato adds the sweetness . overall a very solid irish dry stout .  enormous white frothy head .  mouthfeel : oddly thin but with a smooth silky texture . the carbonation is really low which is n't too far off but still could be higher .

discovered this ale last year and i 'm glad i did ... a - pours a coppery red color with 1/2 inch head and a bit of lacing s - nothing too overt here , just some bready malts and hints of flora t - taste is wonderfully floral with hints of sweetness and nice chewy malt m - smooth malts balanced by a nice carbonated bite , sticky in the finish d - this is very drinkable , not too alcoholic and although the flavors are robust they are n't overbearing . 2 or 3 would be a piece of cake this is a great ale for sessions , sitting around a campfire comes to mind .  beautiful shining dark shade of gold .  a very carbonated mouthfeel , lots of fizz .

the aroma is light . some beers slap you in the face when you inhale at glass level , this beer is very gentleman-like .  beautiful .  mouthfeel is a bit watery , not nearly as thick as a stout ( but as-expected for a porter ) .

smell : not a whole lot going on here , except a slight fruity aroma . taste and mouthfeel : it 's malty - the bitterness is mild and definitely in the background - but not too sweet , more bread-like . very easy drinking . notes : simply a nice english bitter - and real tasty on cask .  probably the best head ive ever seen in an i.p.a . thick and heavy , it cascades out of the bottle , giving even a belgian beer a run for its money .  i think i stand by my previous opinion of mouthfeel and drinkability .

not a huge fan of the smell . aromas of hops , pine , and alchol .  a : hazy orange , very cloudy and active . tons of foamy white head everywhere . its great retention leaves a sticky trace of white lace behind .  it takes away from every aspect of the beer . the taste was week in the malt department and nonexistant in the hop department . rice was detected . a-b should be ashamed .

attractive lacing s- colorful , textured bouquet t- roasted grains , barley and caramel m- nice texture , crisp and clean d- 9/10 .  it pours a deep brown to light black in color .  very dry pils . and by the way , pils taste completely different in bottles than they do on tap . looks absolutely stunning in a bischoff glass . fish especially .

the aroma is most akin to orange blossoms , there are some other hop esters along with brown sugar and clove , but the orange blossom smells of a wonderful floral bouquet . the taste however let me down so very much .  color is a dark red/black with ruby highlights when held to the glass . very active carbonation streamers can be seen racing up the inside wall of the glass . a very beautiful beer to look at .  thick mouthfeel but not as dense as some in its class , which i suppose makes it more drinkable than most in its class .

smells of some dried overripe fruit , with some breads , maybe just a hint of vanilla . not an exceptional beer , but a good amount of flavor - even if it 's not the most elegant or cohesive beer in the world .  hazy , orange-amber beer with a thin white head that retains forever and leaves some of the craziest lacing i 've ever seen . i have to give it an exceptional mark for the look on this .  taste : : malts , roasted malts , bitter cocoa meets with a mildly bitter hops mf : i think that this pour was pretty thin .

nose is sweet and belgian , big perfumey notes , extremely floral , with a sweet honeyed character , and a dose of belgian yeast . such a delicate nose for a beer called demolition , but it 's an extremely good one . taste is a little lighter than expected , quite thin on the front , with a slight light honey on the back , mixed with a subtle phenolic astringency . it 's a shame , given the nose was so floral and complex . feel is very light , which matches with the light palate , but again , it 's a little disappointing .  looks really nice .  m : this beer feels a touch too thin .

poured more of a deep brown than black , when held up to the light light it did show thru the whole glass , a thinner light mocha colored head atop.aromas were very light wich suprised me a little , a bit of iron and chocolate mainly.the moufeel was execellent though , full and creamy almost like a marshmellow in my mind.full on chocolate on the palate with a tinge of earth , the alcohol is well hidden , the creamy feel and well hidden alcohol makes for a very easy drinker.a very nice `` bigger '' stout , it lacks a little but is nice to drink .  pours with a black as night body topped by a thick foamy lasting brown head with a good amount of lacing .  with the amount of carbonation this has , i have a really hard time picking out anything other than the wheat and banana . it also leaves a pretty dry aftertaste .

pleasantly sparkling in the mouth giving way to a strong currant aftertaste . simple , yet fantastically unique ( at least for most of us who ca n't find another cassis ) . while i do n't like many fruited beers ( including most lindeman 's ) , this is the exception .  the head is craggy in shape and doughy in texture . great retention and good bubbling and sticky foam .  m - very low carbonation , a little creamy but a little thin for an oatmeal stout .

smells like a mild sugar bomb . lots of big pine scent . almost smells sour .  this poured a hazy copper , big frothy head , that left puffs of lacing all the way down , smell was of raisins and fruit , taste was light fruity and tangy , mouthfeel is light and slightly tart , and highly carbonated , drinkability is fantastic , just another fine product from ommegang .  out of bottle . not my type of beer at all . did not match the typical belgian flavor beer of which i am not a big fan of anyway . for me this had a charcoal , ashtray type taste that is just not a match for my palatte . seems some folks enjoy this , so give it a try if you 'd like . i have turned the page on this one .

) comes in the bud brown long neck..12 oz this `` beer '' actually looks not too bad at all poured into a glassnice orangy brown colour with a large frothy white head..it looks like a beer at least . smell is bothersome though ..malty but in a sickly way . cold this `` beer '' tastes not too bad at all for a na..its all malt with some faint hops in the after taste pretty watery in mouth as expected .  22 ounce bomber into a pint glass ( 2 pours ) pours out a deep red with 3 fingers of thick and dense off-white foam that leaves paneling of lace everywhere . this is really the epitome of what beer can look like . i stared at my half empty glass for about 5 minutes .  mouthfeel : good medium body but just a tad under carbed overall impression : its surprisingly good for a gimmicky beer ; very nice taste and very drinkable .

the aroma was pretty mild : caramel , and some bitterness , but really not much there .  a 22oz bomber poured into a regular pint beer glass a : a great amber copper color , 2 finger head , good carbonation .  m - i wish actually for more bite and nip to clean up the palate a bit better .

my bottle of samuel smith 's taddy porter is 550ml with gold foil on the top . by letting it sit for a while , i can get some roasted caramel flavors and some hops but i ca n't totally get the skunkiness out of my nose . would be very drinkable if ever bottle that i ever purchased was n't skunked .  this is one great looking porter .  m : light to medium-light body with mild carbonation that coats the mouth and leaves a tingling sensation on the finish .

smell : it smells like cologne ... haha , what kind i could n't tell ya . some mellow espresso bean flavor is the focus here , with a touch of dark chocolate hidden within a mostly milk-chocolate zone . crisp alcohol and gentle prune hide underneath all of the above .  poured a bright , golden-copper body with a fluffy white head that fell slightly and remained all the way to the last sip .  mouthfeel was a bit on the thin side , in my opinion .
smells slightly spoiled .  this beer poured a deep amber with a lively tan head .  highly carbonated with a long lasting white head . a bit thin , but well balanced .

smell : soft chocolate and malt sweetness are very mild . taste : chocolate , malty , caramel , vanilla , prunes , raisins and a mild bitterness .  a : beautiful deep amber color , almost on the verge of being purple . a nice 1.5 fingers of head that left some nice lacing .  winter warmers are one of my favorite types of beer . however , i 'm a rheinheitsgebot type of guy . i taste nutmeg and maybe ginger in this beer . that 's outside the boundaries for me , even if the flavors were managed through some odd hop/malt/yeast combination . i had to dump it down the drain after a couple of tastes .

not much smell besides a light malt .  serving type : 12 oz bottle poured into 16 oz nonic pint glass a - creamy beige head , opaque black , only a slight hint of red hues when held under bright light s - very chocolately smell , though not entirely strong , with a bit of alcohol scent shining through t - bitter taste all over , roasted malts are , as expected , the dominant force , and as a note , the bitterness tends to linger around throughout m - good tingle from carbonation , with a thick creamy body in other words , pretty much everything i was expecting it would be .  a - murky red with orange yellow depending on the light with a nice head when poured vigorously enough , but it dissipates quickly s - sweet caramel and bubble gum t - sweet , floral , light at first and yet heavy with a regular beer aftertaste m - only slightly better than bud light ( my fav mass beer ) d - all the time brew .

smell is roasted malt and that is about it for that .  gorgeous looking beer .  some harsh roast flavours show up in the finish and it is also sorta sorta chalky . mouthfeel is ok i guess , but who cares when it tastes this bad ? i 'm guessing this flavour comes from some sort of cheap grain/adjunct .

s : light nutty malt , sugar . t : the flavour gives a strong caramel malt sweetness that dominates the brew .  appearance - dark dark dark with one of the best dark heads i have ever seen .  this beer poured a pale yellow colour , simmilar to a pint of stella . it had a thin yet bubbly and large head , which dissipated quickly . it had a very delicious taste , with a metallic note and a slight taste of honey . it smelled sweet , also with that metallic note . this was my first bosnian beer , and it will not be my last .

aroma is of lots of fruit ( reminds me of strawberry jelly & gummy fruit snacks ) . slight yeast aroma sneaks in there as well along with a tiny bit of alcohol-big but not complex . the fruit overpowers much of the aromas .  i like the voluptuous bottle , very ergonomical . a huge 3 finger pillowy white froth tops my rapscallion snifter , a cloudy dark golden beer supports it .  mouthfeel is a little thin but carbonation levels are average and work well .
the smell was very modest with some faint maltiness .  beautiful crystal walnut color with fine pencil line cream head .  mouthfeel : well carbonated , strangely thin but not in a bad way .

poured from a 40 oz bottle ... .gee , maybe i could get a 6 pack of this stuff sometime ... the pour foamed up pretty well , smell was allright thought it might be good afterall .  pours a hazy oragelinke color with a huge rocky head that leaves laces all the way down .  m- thin to medium body with a little unattenuated sugar . there 's a little bit of soft carbonation here as well ... but for such a sweet and malty brew , i would have liked to have more unattenuated sugar ... a chewier and more textured mouthfeel ... d- very very drinkable ... a perfect fall or winter nightcap ... and the alcohol is very well hidden !

s : sweet apple aroma with a hint of phenolic spice in the background . not bad , but pretty weak . pretty standard stuff for the style .  pours beautiful clear garnet-brown , thick off-white head with good retention leaving pillowy , chunky islands of foam .  m : good amount of carbonation , could be cut back a little bit .

smell : smells grassy and floral , also a bit `` bitter smelling .  a : color is beautiful . rich , deep , dark red .  smell : roasty wood smell , with some chocolate and coconut , and something resembling coffee ... taste : strong coconut flavor , sweet malty chocolate , some brown sugar almost maple flaovrs then ends with a roasted coconut flavor mouthfeel : medium body , sweet feel , medium carbonation , nothing special drinkability : really sweety , pretty drinkable though , good flavors .

with this beer you need to let it sit for a moment as it will get rid of the skunk smell and become the traditional smelling beer . the golden unfiltered beer was poured into a pint glass and let sit till the foam started to settle .  the brew is a gorgeous deep brown ... almost black . it has a monster 1.5 '' head which leave huge chunks of lacing as the beer is drank .  if not for the thin mouthfeel this would be one for the ages .

the aroma is vinous and sweet , like a port , with an intense smell of prune juice , raisins , maple syrup , rotting black cherries , vanilla extract , and a hint of dark molasses ... wow..this reminds me of sam adams triple bock .  dark as dark can be .  ) mouthfeel - not bad , perhaps a trifle thin .

s- leaves a little to be desired . some bready malts , and a little sweet caramel , but it seems like the `` volume '' got turned down on the smell . t- remarkably well-balanced . a delicious , sweet caramel / brown sugar type of malt flavor going on here . m- smooth and balanced , this is a very drinkable beer , especially at 5.9 % overall , i think this is an awesome beer . love it .  pours pure black with a dab of brown head .  just hoping future versions can improve that mouthfeel .

* red wine vinegar aroma dominates but aroma is overall somewhat sweet . oaky notes are present .  appearance : clear orange in color with a big fluffy 2 '' head .  first sip reveals a very fine carbonation that gently tingles my palate . the body is fairly thin , but not watery .

the troegs beers are really good , however i was not impressed with this beer . everyone i have talked to said that it was really good . maybe i got a bad bottle or something . however the appearance was really good and the color looked really good too . the small was not so great and neither was the mouthfeel . i guess the take home message for this beer to watch where you get it and check the born on date .  drank at the monk , fremantle a - pors a deep mahogany colour withe two fingered off white head that left rings all the way down the glass .  m : the mouthfeel is slightly slick .

a - pours jet black with a small mocha head s - i could n't detect much , a little smokey with some chocolate t - smokiness throughout , ends with a strong coffee bite and some molasses m - very smooth d - medium i really enjoyed this beer . smoked beers are usually hit or miss for me , but i thought this one was really well balanced and tasty .  first thing is the absolute massive duvel-esque head that forms with even the softest pour . it 's really quite beautiful floating atop the cloudy peach body of this brew and though it does dissipate in time , it still leaves a huge dimple filled marshmallow island and sporadic lacing everywhere and for the duration of the session .  taste & mouth feel : decent crispness over a light body that holds some unnatural dextrin in the mouth feel . vague beer flavor , nasty herbal flavors flail around chaotically .

the sent of hops rushes out at you at the crack of the cap . this is one of the best smelling ipa 's ever .  this bier pours up a masterpiece , if only in looks .  mouthfeel leaves a little to be desired in my opinion , comes across a tad bit too syrupy , but at the same time a proper amount of bubbles for the mouthfeel .

smells like a blend of sweetness and sour cherries .  cloudy golden body , bottle-conditioned with plenty of yeast particules . superbly laced huge foamy head , rocky and leaving a trace on the glass at each sip .  mouth : slightly tingly , a sweet bitter hop presence stays around , fairly thick bodied .

the crisp , yet smooth taste leaves mouths wanting more , yet the potency lets you enjoy `` beer '' . c'mon guys , this beer is one of the best . down to the bottle , its smooth , yet tasteful . enjoyable , yet manly . this beer has weekend written all over it , and if you do n't agree , well then , have a miller high life !  a : poured a huge three finger light-tan head with great retention .  m - too light for my liking , and sometimes even border-line watery . at least there 's a strong carbonation , and it 's nice to kind of toss around on the tongue to search for the other flavors . still , fairly average .

s - muted dry hops and rich malt . grapefruit and a bit of pine on the nose . t - spicy and sweet . d - great esb .  hazy copper with a few long strands of carbonation bubbles running throughout . a huge off white head that is chunky enough that i could probably draw designs in it if i wanted to . good retention , excellent lacing . looks like an apa should look .  in th mouth , though , it 's a little too watery for a weizen .

s - yeast and phenols . a little flat smelling . t - definitely wheat .  a : the nicest looking wheatwine that i have ever seen . looks brown until it is held up to the light .  watery rather than full bodied for a stout . fantastic . ' i just wish it was a bit thicker in terms of oral sensations .

appearance - a nice clear beer smell - smells clean organic and fresh like spring rain .  a : wow , this is one of the best looking beers i have seen . pours an excellent creamy head that lasts the whole beer .  some nice foam when poured . dark brown/copper appearance not too much in the nose , but smells vaguely of belgian yeast spice up front , sweeter flavor and then ending with a cinnamon and alcohol taste . notes of vanilla and banana . overall a good beer but could use some subtlety .

light hoppy smell and a nice amber orange , with a fizzy white head that left superb lacing , i 've seen rabid squirrels with less foam than this beer going down the glass .  pours a dark clear brown to settle a solid varnished blackness . beautifully capped with a finger high light shaded cocoa firm frothy , creamy dense foam . the cap stays firm and holds steady for great length finally dissipating to a heavy skim and lots of broken stringy lacing .  it leaves a pleasant fruity citrus taste in the back of your mouth . the carbonation is moderate . worth trying if you feel like something light .

s : smell is somewhat subdued ; very light , flowers , wheat , belgian . t : very spicy , some cloves and bananas , light fruit , roses , floral - both hop and flower - sweet , tortilla kind of breadiness .  poured in the struisse beerglass the beer looks very very very dark with an enormous chocolate head .  medium body , lingering flavors .

earthy aroma with yeat/bread , caramel malt , rye and caraway seed notes . smells slightly tart with subtle spice presence . very smooth and extremely drinkable .  when held up to light , theres an ever-so-slightly lighter , russet-looking color at the extreme edges . big , rocky , light tan colored head that took its sweet time dropping and left lots and lots of lace on the sides of my glass .  a bit chalky . hints of grapefruit and bold coffee flavor .

aromatically unimpressive , as pine and grapefruit notes struggle to make any headway up the ole ' nostrils . a bit of caramel malt makes a sturdy backbone , as the hops eventually show a bit of flare .  super dark , almost completely opaque with frothy dark caramel head . ridiculous retention every sip of the way . d : looks amazing .  the mouthfeel is a little uneventful .

faint amber malt smell but really not much on the nose .  appearance : possibly one of the best looking ipas i have ever seen . ( i tend to pour gently ) smell : the smell is nice and sweet , though it does not blow me away like many other ipas .  i have been known to sit and smell the beer for five minutes before i drink it . the taste is carmel with a almost pine after taste . after four beers the tart pine after taste is really noticable . i really like this beer . though sometimes they do n't taste right . i do n't know if i just have an old one or maybe it is too new and needs time to mellow .

nose is full of chocolate and dark roasted malts . so far , i 'm not picking up on any coconut smell , which is a bit of a disappointment given the name ! there is a bit of a metallic scent in there also .  pours a gorgeous hazy orange with yellow streaks , the head is monsterous . a 3 inch thick frothy delicious milkshake of a head , by far the best beer i have ever seen poured .  oy gevalt ! pours an interesting reddish brown slightly hazy body with a finger of beige-white head . head lingers and it laces the glass well . aroma is nice and sweet . tastes very hoppy with dates dark fruit notes . a bit of a bite in the aftertaste , that is not pleasant !

i waited to review this until i had the ba version from the bottle ... looks like the ba version , dark brown with a light tan head , a little better lacing ... the aroma is nice with vanilla , creamy chocolate and a touch of raspberries ... the taste has a lot more chocolate than i expected , i was expecting and hoping for more of the vanilla and raspberries .  beer pours out a nice hazy golden color with tons of little bubbles rising to the top . huge clusters of thick lace all the way down the glass .  body is light to medium , carbonation is perhaps a bit high for my tastes .

s : strong coffee notes and a kind of roasted grain aroma that was pleasant , but was n't terribly distinct . the smell , while attractive does n't do the taste justice .  poured a nice amber orange hue with an impressive bold white head .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel is okay .

the smell is ( by far ) the least appetizing part of this beer 's appeal-it 's earthy and a bit sour . the taste is quite different ( thankfully ) from the smell . there is a strong hop presence . my hop-head brother thinks it 's the second best beer he 's ever had from here ( first was the giant star ) .  a- a deep , black liquid with just the slightest bit of light getting through the top when held to a light . the creamy brown head has some decent retention .  the mouthfeel is a bit thinner than i expected , with medium carbonation .

s : cocoa pops out at you then i got quite a bit of roasted malt . t : this is supposed to be a chocolate beer .  guinness 250 anniversary stout is a brownish black beer with a thick , foamy , dimpled beige head that has great retention and leaves nice lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel was a tad thin , surprisingly , but did n't affect my overall impression of the beer much .

good and nutty nose too , but it was a bit overly boozy to my nose .  this beer poured great , with a crystal clear , golden color , and a big fluffy , snow-white head .  the feels is about average for a lager with moderate carbonation .

nose is nice and hoppy , but also has a nice belgian yeast nose with some coriander .  [ best served in a trappist glass ] poured a nice rich murky brown with a large frothy light brown head that lasted throughout and had some really excellent lacing that remained on the glass until the end .  tropical hops , brown sugar , molasses , earth , sweet yeast and a bit of oak m - light , a bit of carbonation , light to medium acidity and short finish and some what balanced d - nice for an ipa , easy to drink .

s : smells mildly skunked . t : tastes very similar to smell . d : beyond the skunk , i could probably put quite a few of these away . very nice .  *note : this is a 2007 vintage* a - poured into a goblet this has a nice mahogany , cloudy pour with one of the most impressive heads i 've ever seen . this 1 finger of big bubble head hung around for the duration of the ale leaving massive , clumpy side lacing . i'ver never seen bubbles of this size before in my brew , its insane !  mouthfeel slacks off a little .

s - soft roasted malt character with muted caramel and nutty notes . very soft nose here with a bit of brown sugar .  a - one word - black . dark as night with a big espresso like dark brown head . head is a solid three fingers after a somewhat agressive pour and slowly fades to about a one finger cap . big rings of lace left behind .  however , it almost lacks a bit in body and gets watery towards the end instead of carrying the expected viscosity of an oyster stout .

the nose brought it all the way back : gorgeous cherry and plum notes mingled with dried fruit and a touch of roast malt . i can only imagine how terrific the aroma would be with more carbonation driving it up . the flavor was quite good , too , though a bit sweet . very nice spice influence , as well .  really nice looking beer .  m : hefty , frothy , and over-carbonated . it 's quite a mouthful , but not always in the most pleasant way .

very mild sweet malt in the nose reminiscent of caramel and light bread . nose was a little lacking , but still some nice , fruity aroma was present .  poured ( of course ) in my struise glass the beer looks perfect . what a deepdarkbrown colour !  the head is only a half inch and it does back fast , leaving a thin foam coat and the carbonation seems to keep it replenished . the taste is rich and fizzy : like the carbon dioxide gets release when it hits my tongue . this is good stuff , although i agree it is darker than most saison .

smells mostly of malt and bread . that is about it not a really aromatic ale .  well , first off , the appearance of this beer is likely its best feature . beautifully black with an oh-so-creamy looking tan head .  carbonation is very low , could be higher really . very unorthodox but amazing anyway .

smell : the aroma is rather simple , with biscuity malts and wheat dominating . ) and hop aroma , but these aromas were difficult to pinpoint . taste : the taste was excellent .  poured into a tulip a - absolutely perfect looking beer .  light body , sandy mouth feel , faint malt spine .

very nice . some yeasty scents , some light malt , but that 's it . wow . this is good , although the ipa factor is far far in the background .  pours black with a nice two-finger tan head but subsides quickly to a one-finger head and stays throughout . had very nice lacing throughout .  m- the body is a little on the light side .

smell : strong malt , no hint of hops , and warm alcohol .  vernon sampled to keep me warm during sunday 's st. patrick 's day parade pours a deep dark brown/black that was fairly opaque with a bit of reddish highlights . had a thick off-white head that lasted forever and left beautiful lacing down my plastic imperial pint .  moderate to thinner in the mouth with mild carbonation .

s-coffee , subtle chocolate , and earthiness and fruitiness from the hops . not a whole lot going on here . very restrained . absolutely fantastic drinking porter .  red rust color with sparks flying through ( yes , sparks ! ) which was probably the carbonation rising to the top . a thick head disippated very slowly , leaving behind a pelasant amount of lacing .  m : a little on the light side of medium bodied , and i 'm afraid my somewhat rough pour put almost all of the carbonation into the fantastic head - it feels a bit flat .

muted , not very strong aroma , but it was difficult to detect in the bar . really terrific taste , as good a mai-bock as ive ever had .  served in 12 oz snifter/tulip glass a- big 2 inch mocha or light brown looking head , very frothy , looks like the head of choc milk shake , completely opaque s- wonderful cocoa smell with a lil spice in there that i can tell is not hops f- wow can u say chocolate , very cocoa tasting , very hot spicy finish ... after looking at the bottle i see it is cayene..as the beer warms some notes of oak and vanilla are noticed .  m : a little carbonated , slightly burns .

a nice zippy spiciness here that 's enjoyable . first sip brings an upfront pale , wheaty maltiness that is a bit astringent . no real detectable hops here .  a black as night body , with a hint of dark brown highlights , topped by a billowing three fingers of frothy coffee au lait foam . head slowly subsides like it 's breathing , leaving excellent stretches of lace .  definite hints of caramel and roasted malts in the flavor and the hint of roasted malt lingers a bit on the palate along with a candied sugar taste . goes down ok , a good session beer .

it had a pleasant malt smell with little complexity .  found at spike 's pub in san luis obipso ; 2005 vintage poured into a tulip glass . a : reddish amber color , with golden fringing in the light . a very small head , as is to be expected from such a strong beer . swirling the glass leaves a nice thick coating , i 'm expecting this beer to be thick and creamy .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but not exceedingly so .

tasted : just about everyday appearance - reddish brown body and a tan head smell - caramel/malty , not too strong taste - malty , smooth , sweet , drinkability - full flavor and easily the best flavor/ease of drinking i have had . but , all are good . overall , a great beer .  a - pours with an ample off-white foam that slowly settles to a chunky cap , leaving splotchy intricate lace patterns .  can really feel the carbonation , it almost foams up a bit in your mouth .

i ca n't pick up very much smell on this beer . i detect a faint carmel apple scent . a little bit of a sweet scent . maybe something 's wrong with my nose . i can definitely taste way more than i can smell . it creamy like a milk stout .  picked up a bottle of this at cork & barrel recently , have been waiting for this one to hit minnesota eagerly . beautiful beer . by some bent of magic , the beer is a dirty , earthly red around the edges , while maintaining a dark brown , light-repulsing core .  just beer . this beer is good , let me say that first . that said , there is absolutely nothing salient about the brew . taste is almost like a brown ale , but without the caramel flavor or biscuit-y quality . tastes like beer , drinks like beer , great for packing 'em in .

very clean and refreshing . t : starts off with a nice citrus taste up front , lots of orange and grapefruit .  a : a great looking beer .  meekly carbonated finish , bitter , hops understated , alum dry aftertaste , different from what i would normally drink , so it takes a lot of contemplation to be accurate in my judgment , drinkable , but something i 'd not want to sample on a regular basis , but after some serious decanting i found it to be a bit more pleasing to my palate , so if your not into the sediment at the bottom of the bottle , even if it means pouring a bit of the beer back into the bottle you may make a serious misjudgment of taste .

smell-sweet honey , light caramel . very subtle . taste-wasted expecting it to taste this good .  the appearance of the beer is truly amazing : a towering , everlasting , rocky , white head tops a coppery-caramel colored liquid .  m-medium bodied , though lacking a bit of the rich mouthfeel i like to see in an oatmeal stout .

all the flavors seem to jump out especially as the brew warms . i had this one at just over celler temp . nice roasted malts and chocolate a small touch of coffee not overly done in anything and all the flavors blend to form and intense drinkable experience you and expect going into a beer like this.awesome  a- pours a slightly hop hazy ipa golden / golden brown liquid with a beautiful thick billowy white head .  it was a little fizzy , but that was a minor problem .

appearance - sweet smoky nose , pleasant , persistent , but not overly complex .  appearance : poured a coppery orange body , with a beautiful fluffy white head . nice suddy lacing .  the only thing i mark this beer down for was it mouthfeel . i tought it had a very light mouthfeel and certainly no creaminess .

the smell of the beer has a little bit of roasted aromas and a light sweetness too . the taste of the beer actually impressed me .  the appearance is a beautiful honey brown that calls my name and says `` drink me .  had on tap at the brewery in moab , ut . i believe this is just the cream ale served with jalapeno peppers served in it . this also tastes like a wet cat in a pool of vomit ... absolutely disgusting , with a `` beer-like '' flavor trying to emerge ... pale malts , and butterscotch combine gloriously with the jalapeno . no heat is evident , either . this is a horrible mistake .

s - citrus - orange and grapefruits . o - the scents and taste do not match .  i was rewarded with a lovely looking , clear , old gold coloured beer with a large , snow white head . plenty of bubbles rising upwards to the head indicated a lot of carbonisation .  this is a great porter . i have been a fan of anchor brewing and this porter is tops . beautiful black color when poured into glass . and the aroma is very mild . enjoyed this on a really cold night and i could n't have picked a better porter . i could be wrong , but this porter was almost sweet . good meal in a glass .

reminiscent of vomit and cat food . we would expect the hops to be stronger , but all we really got was alcohol and cat food . but very round with long finish .  shakespeare poured a shimmering obsidian black , with an cola-foam colored creamy head .  poured into s snifter , with a very nice quick vanish head and a even nicer lacing around the walls smells quite boozy almost brandy like with a faint fruity winey aroma taste oaky with obvious caramel and molasses characters . finishes with a biscuit like citrisy aftertase very complimenting this is a decent old ale and being this years ( 2011 ) batch my guess is it will get a little better with age . 9.8 50 ibus

appearance - dark brown/eggplant color with some brown head smell - this one is faint , picking up hints of coffee , cocoa taste - wow , this is good , these flavors really burst , i 'm picking up dark chocolate , a bit of expresso and hazelnut mouthfeel - this is smooth and creamy , high amount of carbonation , medium to full bodied , flavors really linger on the palate in the aftertaste , no hint of booze at all drinkability - this is going down nice on a chilly night , for $ 1.89 a 500ml bottle , this is really good value .  pours a brilliant , bright copper color ... almost orange with the assistance of some natural light . a full finger and a half of white head ... fades fast , but leaves behind some thin lacing that covers the glass nicely .  i liked this beer , but the mouthfeel had a little high carbonation for a new belgium beer .

the aroma of this beer is rather sweet , that of caramel type malt and maybe a sherry aroma , judging by this and the bottle date , the beer may be a bit over the hill , well see . i can not detect much of any hop aroma . overall i truly enjoyed this one , not as much as the uerige sticke , but this was very good . i would like to try a fresher sample sometime and see if the aroma is any different .  a - pours a pretty monster dense white head with incredible retention and lacing . it looks like snow on my glass and there is still about 3/4 inch of head ~10 minutes later .  mouthfeel : highly carbonated as youd expect , but dare i say a little watery ?

the body of this brew is totally black , with barely a hint of red wine like hues . i did n't really detect too much in the way of aromas . there is just a little bit of a coffee/burnt toast fragrance . this tastes like a dream come true , in a land dominated by light pilsners and weizens . this is very drinkable but complex . every sip must be enjoyed with this brew .  appearance : black as you can get of of the darkest ive seen . wonderfull head and retention . perfect lacing in a symetrical pattern . perfect .  feel is a little on the weak and thin side despite a decent amount of carbonation .
the aroma was n't particularly intense to me , but the taste stood out .  this brew pours an opaque black colored body with a large creamy head .  mouthfeel : a bit watery .

a : a bit lighter than most pumpkin ales and what i had expected . s : i did not catch that much pumpkin or pumpkin pie spices in the aroma , but oddly enough found it more in the taste .  this one pours big and black , with a 1-inch tan head .  medium bodied with a slightly watery , though smooth , finish .

a : poured from bomber a dark black color with good lacing and one finger tan head s : smell is not too prominent . slight metallic smell t : very sweet like mollases .  it pours exceptionally well ... beautifully dark ... rich , brown head ... perfect .  its now called winter warmer , not strong ale , but i figure they 're the same thing . mouthfeel is just a touch on the light side , but the flavor of this beer makes up for it !

it seems like every other batch of this stuff is skunked , and i live and shop in a pretty populated city . i do n't know how or why it 's like that , but any beer that offers you a crap shoot of being spoiled or not , is n't worth anyone 's time .  appearance : big cascading tan head on top of a hazy red/amber body . despite a high alcohol content the head has terrific lasting power .  m - medium to full mouthfeel . tongue feels chalky .

overall , this is one of my favorite styles from one of my favorite brewers . i did n't quite love it as much as their white or other similar styles , but it was still quite enjoyable .  it 's got a perfect appearance with a very light golden color , excellent clarity and a large white head .  is a bit watery , though .

s - not a lot of essence in the aromas , other than that of the roasted barley that was slightly muted due to , i 'm guessing , the temperature . t - real nice and straight forward . caramel hints amongst the roasted barley .  very assertive and no-nonsense , with lots of caramel and alcohol notes .  i actually like a few of the canadian brands better ( as some have the actual raisins and what not in the bottle still , and better carbonation levels and lower abv ) . taste is great malty , sweet , and very filling ( it 's nutritous to boot ) . i only generally drink water , tea , coffee , beer , wine , spirits , juice , and dairy ( kefir , etc ) . this is the noly soda type beverage i drink and it is absolutely stellar hangover relief ...

really sour .  huge billowy beige head atop a clear and golden amber beer . slathers of lather 's thickly on the glass , and the head relaxes some , but stays the whole ride down .  light bodied , heavily carbonated , became foamy in the mouth at times .

nose was weaker than i was expecting and bit grassier than i prefer . their new process could benefit from a bit of tweaking in the nose department . taste is good but nothing different , exceptional or noteworthy , but a good tasting ipa . overall this is a good ipa that i could probably drink most of the night .  the beer poured magnificently . it raised a beautiful head , probably a half-inch thick . it was poured into a lead-crystal goblet , and it was the perfect choice for this beauty .  light in body though it does n't live up to the initial crispness of the nose . carbonation seems appropriate .

oddly after the gorgeous appearance the aroma was pretty pedestrian , maybe my nose is blocked..i dunno its distinctlly average..some malts and a little fruits , thats about it .  poured this into a guinness extra stout pint glass , and perfectly it does so . mounds of dark tan colored head , and an opaque black colored body that allows some ruby red highlights on the edge of the glass .  m - light body . slightly watery finish .

smell : best feature . coffee , tobacco leaves , roastiness , chocolate sweetness . mouth : good but not overly exciting or viscous . smell was the standout of this beer for me .  out of a 750ml foiled and capped bottle . pours a light honey golden color , fairly clear , with tons of carbonation bubble racing to the top . big and rocky , just wo n't dissipate , pure white , super chunky lacing ... beauty .  the first and dominating aroma was apples , and then other fruits . flavor was that of apples , bananas , malts , and carmel . the finish was a bit sharp .

4/5 s : mild/medium aroma . sweeter/fruity malts and a lighter fruity hop aroma as well . 3/5 t : smoky/maltier taste than a typical american lager , and more flavor as well .  a : in a snifter , this has impenetrable blackness . it looks like a candle in the glass , with a gelatinous chocolate mousse head .  m : hardly carbonated , but the subtleties between the aforementioned sweetness and hoppiness make for an interesting drink .

this is probably the third time i 've bought a 12 pack of these but the first time i 've really tried to figure out what i thought about this beer ( besides the fact that i liked it ) ... # 9 has a very nice appearance , the beer is gold in color , i would n't call it dark so much as deep , and very clear . the smell is the weakest part of this beer , it does n't lend to the taste like you would expect . it has an almost sanitizer quality that i do n't find pleasant but it does n't keep me away . it has a great balance between light fruitiness with the apricot essence and the hops which take over the tail end of a sip . i never even knew i liked apricots .  black albert o happy pour into my hotd tulip glass . after only pouring half this motor oil like substance from the bottle i had to stop to let the amazing mocha colored head settle . after the fine bubbles settled down , a nice lacing remained . this is what a good head of beer should look like .  mouthfeel is rather thin , as expected .

very earthy hop aroma , and oddly enough , i could sort of smell alcohol even though it 's not a very high abv . hint of grapefruit hop flavor , but mostly earthy/bitter/herbal hops - reasonably assertive , but not extremely assertive . very balanced .  a-rich dark brown with a thick dark brown head that thins . i 've personally never seen a head the dark before !  s - overwhelming peach . that is all this beer has , and i found it to be utterly unbalanced . d - my partner and i drank many different beers over two weeks in belgium . also , i do n't think this has any lambic as in it , as that it not claimed by dubuisson on their website .

appearance : golden raisin body with a nice 2 finger white head smell : pineapples hit my nose first than some apples , oranges , lemons and toffee taste : very good dipa !  superior head retention & lacing s : pineapples , lemons , & breadyness t : grapefruit , caramel & breadyness up front , along with leafy hops & pineapple .  as noted , the mouthfeel is both on the thin and flat side .
heavily tart and yeasty smell . some spice barely creeps in kinda tart at first .  great retention and lacing .  not a run-of-the-mill pale ale by any means but i 'm finding it a little thin .

smells of carmel malts . tastes really good .  a : pours with a two finger thick , off-white and chunky head . the beer is clear , bright , deep amber with small bubble streams raising to the top - an attractive beer to look at . suds rings form through the duration of the drink , leaving a hard crusty film on my imperial pint glass . m : medium-bodied with a semi-crisp finish - highly vicious overall .  the body is pretty thin but the feel still comes across as creamy to some extent .

really did n't like this beer at all . it boasts being a strong beer but it 's not strong in alcohol content it 's strong in taste ... but not a taste or flavour i enjoy in a good ipa .  a : pours a very dark black color with a beautiful tan head and slight lacing .  t : wheat flavor , lemon , and slight banana/clove taste m : a tad on the overcarbonated side but not too bad d : good easy drinking hefe , would like to try again sometime .

i had this beer for the first time out of the can yesterday ... .the greatest part was it was course one of a 5 course beer pairing dinner at the front door in boise . jamie from nb gave us the coolest presentation on how they can their beers and why it is so damn fresh still . this beer is simply a great beer but i tend to carry a headache the next day from this beer even if i only drink one .  it poured out beautifully , looking dark and rich like a barleywine with a very nice thick head .  lack of head on the initial pour but this beer is definitely carbonated .

the carbonation was on par with what i 'd expect from a cask . ( s ) spiced like many christmas ales . it had a ginger/cinnamon aroma that was inviting and reminicent of holiday brews .  i love this beer so much that i sometimes drive to south carolina to pick up a case to bring back with me to georgia . i love yuengling and hope one day it gets to be served in my state .  a very unique apperance . the taste is very hoppy and refreshing . has a bit of a bite to it . i am not a big fan of ipa 's but i would drink this again .

smell : readily apparent but not overpowering hops . pine notes in the background .  a : crystal clear amber colored and topped with a very good eggshell white head . excellent retention and great spiderweb lacing are left behind .  mouthfeel is crisp and very highly carbonated ( only complaint and wish it was toned down a bit ) .

the smell really was not there for me . i could tell that it was very hoppy though and that some fruit was present . drinkability was also fantastic .  dogfish head au courant is a beautiful golden ale with bubbles streaming up the center of the tasting glass like vintage champagne .  m- light bodied , maybe a little on the watery side . the carbonation is a bit too high .

i note that it had little to no smell to it besides the normal beer smell . this was kind of a dissapointment i was hoping for a nice roaste malt scent . tasting it took care of that .  deep red amber color offwhite head , very stubborn lacing .  mouthfeel is light , not much carbonation or bite on the finish .

s : roasted malts and light hops make up the nose . the aroma is crisp and clean but somewhat muted . notes : if the nose had more of the characteristics of the taste then i would have rated the smell rating a lot higher .  in great similarity to the ara bier , stille nacht has a ton of head that seemingly never reduces into a rich , thick , white head . lace is very nice all the way down to the bottom .  body is a bit flat and thin .

s - aroma is a bit lacking . nose was a little weak , but this brew made up points in the taste and mouthfeel departments .  pours with a very nice head of off white foam , leaves lots of lacing all the way down the glass .  body is about average and carbonation is quite lively .

the smell is faint and that is the best thing about it , i do like the raspberry arome , so not too bad here .  talon pours a crystal clear deep red amber with a thick off white head that lingers on the glass .  very lightly carbonated .

s : light floral hops aroma . t : piney , resiny , floral and spicy hops . toasted bread and a mildy sweetness from the malts .  after pouring from the nitro can and settling into my pint glass , this beer is jet black with a tan colored creamy head . a wonderful site to behold , exactly as you would expect for this style .  found the texture to be overly thick and needing more carbonation to compliment the sharp flavors .

s corn grit and sweet cereal adjuncts and some musty notes t a tiny bit of alcohol and sweet malt upfront .  aroma : light hop aromas appearance : good foamy , white colored , long lasting head clarity is excellent : crystal clear .  m : this beer is thiner then i was hoping for , but still good d : great beer nice flavor

a : pours a hazy copper color with a foamy head that quickly fades to leave a thin white lace s : really hard to place this one ; no single smell sticks out above the rest . estery and earthy tones balanced out by moderate hop scents . t : a solid interpretation of a nice english ale .  pours with a healty tan head over a clear , ruby-to-garnet colored body with some carbonation flowing up . really nice lacing .  mouthfeel is carbonated , which kind of deadens everything .

smell was decent . strong notes of grapefruity hop goodness .  12 oz bottle poured into a tulip tumbler . a cloudy dark brownish orange with a massive head .  mouthfull is medium , not as thick as you 'd expect from such a good russian stout , but you get past that very quickly .

s - lots of pine and other woody aromas . t - piney hops dominate , with the oak adding a good deal of spiciness to the brew . malts are well-hidden , but just assertive enough to balance this enormous beer . d - to be honest , i ca n't see myself drinking more than one of these in a single sitting . it 's a damn good beer , but the spiciness of it is a bit much for me .  an aggressive pour sometimes produces 4 or 5 fingers of white head , so i poured it nice and easy this time so it was only about 1 fingers worth . nice bright yet subtle grapefruit aroma with a sweet malty backbone .  mouthfeel was average ; nothing great , or bad .

should only get criticized for brewing a run-of-the-mill lager . shiny gold in color with a grassy average malt body . high in euro hops . nice white head lasts an average amount of time . green bottles prone to light infiltration and skunkiness .  a = great amber rich color , had to comment to wife right away that this was a beautiful color of beer . poured a slight head from bottle to glass .  unfortunately thinnish in overall body , with an overly lean , passably viscous mouthfeel .

smells heavily of citrusy hops , lemon and some pine all well remaining somewhat sweet . syrupy herbal hops , pineapple and toffee on the forefront with some serious alcohol warmth in the aftertase .  poured into a wide snifter , pitch black and completely opaque with not even the slightest hint of lighter edges when held to a light source and a massive three finger pillowy coffee and cream colored head that has amazing retention , barely fading at all and coating the glass with lare chunks of soapy lacing on the way down . one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel is off due to the alcohol burn feel to it .

it smells of spice and citrus , plus an earth tone that i like but do n't really know how to describe .  appearance : poured a dark blood-red , but was crystal clear with ample light brown foam . the color was brilliant !  taste first of sweet pine , then fading into a rich , malty , yeasty sweet oblivion . this beer tastes surprisingly belgian to me . aftertaste is thick , sweet , yeasty , mildly floral with a bit of bitter hops in the back of the mouth . i actually really liked this beer for the price ( i believe it was around $ 3.50 for a 22 oz ) , surprisingly flavored for a northwest brew .

very malty , smooth , and creamy which is typical of scottish ale . another solid cask ale .  i ca n't see how this one will be ... a : standard pour yields a 1 finger foamy pink head with great retention . beer is a striking clear red .  mouthfeel is slightly thin , but not watery .

typical pils smell , not much else . then the corn takes over turning it into a corn beer . a very drinkable beer , could and would have another , although , the thick body is filling .  a : pours an absolutely massive cream colored orange-tinged head beneath a hazy orange-copper body . when it finally receded it left tons of thick , sticky lacing on the glass and a solid 1/2 to 3/4 inch of foam retained atop the beer . looks great , i must say .  the liquid is smooth and a little sticky .

s - sweet smell , probably from all the malt . ca n't really pick up much . not a bad thing : ) d - overall this is a very enjoyable beer .  dark brown with violette hues and two fingers of creamy beige head that fill the glass perfectly .  about 15 minutes or so later , the aroma became or of a solvent one ( like expo markers ) and tropical fruit . t- soy sauce , alcohol , belgian yeast , and a touch of hops . m- high to medium . o- very complex .

smells of sweet malt , a little oxidation , nothing outstanding , but ok. tastes sweet , malty , barely noticeable bitterness .  poured into a pilsner glass , revealing thick head and a champagne-bubbling light golden body . head has excellent staying power ( is it the glass ? ) and leaves beautiful lacing . fairly sweet and estery , with little yeast funk as you get down past the head that reminds me of agar plates in a bacteria lab .  it was smooth , but a bit too thin ( ie . watery ) .

the smell is roasty and coffee-like .  appearance : very deep and dark reddish amber color with a massive , offwhite and foamy head with good retention , that left lots of lace .  pretty average mouthfeel .

o no ... very strong raisin aroma , in fact so strong it 's worrying me . i 've had some very gross beers that were just overwhelming with the raisins . aroma is also slightly sweet and boozy to balance it out a bit . ok ... not as bad as i thought with the raisin flavor ... in fact , very good .  had that bright burnt orange look , clear as can be . head was absolutely amazing ... 3+ fingers thick that left a plateau of whipped foan in the middle 5 minutes after i poured it . massive amount of sticky lacing down the entire length of the glass .  the body feels a bit thin and flat .

smells of sweet medium roasted malts , hints of peppery alochol spice , dark fruits , stale smells , and urine .  pitch black colour , big brown head .  from 12 ounce bottle . i will not finish a brew that i do not like , so this was tossed after 2 mouthfuls ! it tasted to me of rancid coffee and it left a nasty aftertaste that unfortunately lingered quite a while !

the smell is interesting , but not exactly what i 'd expect .  here it goes : even without the nitro , the head rises nicely and the retention is excellent .  only fault is perhaps excessive carbonation , but i 'm getting more sensitive to that so maybe it 's my problem .

s - light and malty with a fruit punch hint .  great color full bodied.lemony undertones , can hold up to almost any food.glad i finally tried it.all the glb beers i have had have bben great , still need to try the eliot ness , being its my fav type , the vienna style .  flavors are again hopcentric , with a fresh-hopped feel to it . the beer is mid-bodied , yet cloying and slightly sticky in mouth , with a bitter and spiced hops aftertaste . very green , with an overall fresh-hopped feel .

i smell coffee , roasted malt with a touch of milk chocolate . an appetizing aroma .  very dark body , with a small beige head , which leaves really impressive lacing all the way to the bottom of the glass .  mouthfeel was slightly slick and long after the finish this brew becomes dry and oaky - grainy wood seems to slide across the tongue .

i like this beer a lot ; it is one of my favorites . it is smooth , not overpowering , easy to drink , and has a good body . its not too sweet like other new belgium brands nor is it too bitter or too strong . a dark beer with light beer drinkability .  a - poured ( pumped really ) with an insanely rocky , craggy head of white foam that rests on top of a perfectly clear , golden body . this is possibly a visually perfect beer .  mouthfeel is medium/thin but with a bit of a creamy mouthfilling quality . light balance and a bit watery with little character . flavors are just simple and watery . flavors taste like a decent lager to which one has added about 50 % water .

this is a soft ale . hazy , radiant amber color with modest carbonation and a restrained aroma . this is an easy drinking session beer with a splash of citrus and a lot of charm . theres plenty of hops here , but also a judicious restraint .  black/brown body with a chocolate-ice-cream-brown creamy head with tons of retention and lace . as good as it gets .  mouthfeel is slightly diluted and flat but the overall feel and enjoyable nature leads to a quite drinkable brew .

very nice ipa . it was very light smelling for the strong taste .  this beer is one of the nicest looking beers i 've ever seen .  medium carbonation , very light and crisp with a slight malt taste mixed with a nice strawberry flavor . it 's sweet , but not a bad overpowering sweetness and i think the brew is just the right mix of fruit to give it flavor and still be a good beer . this was very tasty and refreshing , went down easy ( almost too easy as i drank 2 in 15 minutes ) , and is the type of beer i could drink all night when it 's hot outside . overall a good summer beer !

the color was an intriguing pale amber but it had a citrus/floral aroma to it . tasted very light and flowery like the aroma .  big brown head that quickly left only a ring around the edges . super black .  medium bodied and tingly from the carbonation .

smells a little funky but the taste is very good .  a - pours a dark honey golden color with amber highlights . superb ! s - piney hops with mild citrus undertones .  m - very light and smooth . grain water .

s- dark fruits- prunes and raisins . reminds me quite a bit of the raison d'extra of a couple days ago . there is also some off tones , perhaps dms ?  pours out into my tulip with a chunkified suspended pieces floating around and carbonation rising up in a dark dim honey amber hues topped with a frothy 1 '' pillowy sandy colored head cap that paints the sides of my glass with frothy lace .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel of ruby is nothing out of the ordinary . mild carbonation and a lighter body .
smell : some funk and mild kiwi .  pours black as night with thick , dense foam .  mouthfeel is rather thin , the only real drawback to this beer .

s : hoppy , very faint here .  dark brown color , full creamy light brown head that lasts .  overall a very good beer for the warmer weather around the bar-b-que . if you are looking for a complex brew that you can stare at in amazement , this is not it . this is the type of beer that you grab when you are thirsty , standing around a garage looking a car , or just something to drink while you are doing something active , like softball or ping pong . this is a perfect beer for those who want a macrobrew but have a couple extra bucks or a `` macro '' chip on thier shoulder .

not much in the nose , slight aroma of fruits and some alcohol is detectable .  what really makes the appearance amazing is how the head stays even while i 'm eating greasy buffaloo wings .  m : it has an average mouthfeel .

s : i 'm hoping the massive , foam-toffee head is inhibiting aroma b/c they are very muted here . still , i can pull some smokiness along with some roasted chocolate . t : very , very nice balance between roasted coffe-like malt , dark chocolate , slight smoke , and hop bitterness .  poured a vibrant raspberry red with a half finger of pink head and left lots of bubbly lacing sticking to the glass .  sweet and sour start , the top middling in feel and the finish mildly acidic , hops are forceful in their bite , quite dry aftertaste .

s : not much . some very faint chocolate malt and something else ... almost , but not quite , black licorice . t & m : a long pull wraps the tongue in an envelope of complex creamy malts with plenty of hints of chocolate and some sort of spice that i just ca n't place and secondary waifs of molasses . there is just a touch of alcohol at the very end or else this would be just perfect for me . d : i think i could drink this until i was dreaming . the flavors are beautifully matched and the alcohol is kept at bay with the velvety goodness that grabs your attention .  looks quite beautiful -- very deep , nearly brownish amber with a voluptuous , caramel head .  very bland and acidic . can taste the 9 % all the way through .

smell is yeasty and boozy with light notes of orange ; a little on the subdued side . to this point , appearance and aroma have n't blown me away . it 's not la fin du monde , but it 's damn good .  color is almost black , some sharp ruby color shoots out of the glass as it is held to light . really great looking beer .  m : prickly carbonation with a relatively full mouthfeel . to be honest , i would n't mind the carbonation being dialed down a touch .

s. malt , floral components t. balance ! nice malt and coffe hints , no heat either .  ah , the hard life ... amberish colored beer -- certainly unintimidating in it 's color -- with a simply gorgeous , rocky , big head .  mouthfeel is ok. on the heavier side of medium bodied . it starts smooth and ends sharp .

appearance : a strongly yellowish yet golden color that is slightly darker than a czech-style pilsner , at least . smell : not much , to be honest : some hops , a grainy , malty smell reminiscent of cereal grains and tinge of lager yeast thrown in . taste : who cares about the smell here , it 's all about the taste on this one . it contains a thick , malty taste , significant carbonation , and a bitter yet fruity bit to it that makes it very enjoyable to drink . even though i 'm a bigger fan of ales , this beer contains the nice , light funkiness of lagers and the thick malty body of ales . as a session brew , it 's crowd pleaser for sure , yet a slightly complex beer that beer geeks can enjoy as well .  a- using a tulip . awesome looking , super white fluff of a head . looks very tasty and i ca n't wait to try it .  light body- almost too light bordering on watery with only moderate carbonation . overall i liked this and it 's drinkable , but i wish it had a little more body and i 'm not crazy about the bitter alcoholic aftertaste .

s : pilsner malts , a bit of an lemony hoppy profile , but it has faded a little bit , still smells nice . a faint alcohol burn in the nose , but its pretty small .  a popular and very classy beer , especially when served in the tulip shaped duvel glasses . a cloudy golden color with a big white foamy head .  a : cloudy urine yellow s : acidic and unpleasant ; not like lemon ; more like lemon rind t : like a cheap mass-produced lager , yuengling for example , with an unwelcome metallic finish m : somewhat velvety , then dry and acerbic . watered down ?

it has mild dark malty aroma .  appearance : a bright orange amber color with a pillowy white 1-1/2 finger head . nice clarity with plenty of lacing .  medium bodied , highly carbonated and prickly from the hops . i 'm a little put off by the amount of carbonation and i prefer the sweeter stouts .

s - not all that pungent for a dipa , some citrusy hops but not much else . bitter and hoppy up front , the taste is far different than the scent would reveal . d - very drinkable and tasty beer .  fiery burnt orange , a little hazy , topped with a good inch of ivory foam . looks terrific . smells hoppy , as i expected .  palate is slight corn and slight malt with a slight bitter hops and the carbonation . odouls is a slight of everything brew , no yummy malt , no well bittered hops bite , just a lot of gas ( carbonation ) and if you ask me , its a slightly boring brew .

i found some nuttiness/malt in the aroma , which actually seemed really muted , though perhaps i was a little congested . first sip was deliciously roasty , and i tasted coffee notes .  appearance : yellow and clear with incredible , foamy , white head that sticks throughout .  mouth -the beer leaves quickly and body does n't add much to overall characteristics , but nice tingling on front and clean but not dry finish .

excellent stout . very drinkable , went down nice . nothing bad to say at all .  hazy amber/orange hue with a gigantic head that just does n't want to go away . very , very tasty looking .  the carbonation here really attacks my mouth in a way that makes it a bit unpleasant .

definitely not what i expected with a pale ale . not much aroma . a little coffee and great big hops .  this beer pours with a beautiful white head . love the cascading colors of golden and dark wheat .  m : somewhat thin for the style .

) detecting the smells of these beers was difficult . also , the heads had receded by the time the waitress brought the glasses to the table , decreasing my enjoyment of the appearance . a - cloudy golden s - weak presence of spicy hops t - weak malt flavor overpowered by spicy hops ; cloves m - light-medium body ; medium carbonation o - not much to it ; would not purchase again  pours a pitch black color with a two-finger head .  mouthfeel is where this beer falls a bit for me . very carbonated , too much so for me .

it is like a creamy bass ale , only better . not too hoppy but right . almost as wonderul as guinness but nothing comes close to the original  big , pillowy white head on top of an amber , semi-cloudy liquid . leaves gobs of lacing .  m : medium in body , the carbonation is a touch high for me , paired with a fairly dry finish , the mouthfeel seems a little too active for the style .

ugh , i think i finally found something more offensive to my palate than st 's cherry saison . this was devastatingly sweet , with vanilla and coconut along with some odd , misplaced bitterness .  it looks very inviting .  the mouthfeel was a bit sharp at first .

s : roasty . ca n't get much else on the nose here ... t : roasted black-coffee bitterness . d : easily drinkable .  a : pours a very dark brown with a giant , foamy , everlasting head . perpetual sustain and heavy lacing .  m : the beer was almost still . just the slightest hints of carbonation after an extremely aggressive pour .

the nose is limited , but displays some roastiness and some dark caramelized sugar .  splendid appearance ! massive thick off-white head about two fingers thick .  m : needs more body i thought , but after i ate i noticed it had more body ?
aroma - a light roasted grain sniff , not much more than that .  terrific looking .  the mouthfeel is very spritzy ... too much so .

the aroma was not strong at all and did not inspire any fall-out-of-my-chair moments . sweet smell with toffee and nut .  i was left with a rocky island of head in the middle of my glass . super sticky . the lacing was so impressive that i actually felt bad rinsing out the intricate design left behind . it was remarkably consistent . the body was clear and sparkling , half way in between yellow & copper . d : becomes more drinkable as the temperature rises but definitely not an all day beer . a good night cap .  mouthfeel/drinkability- lightly carbonated going in , it never gets interesting enough to best highlight the hop and malt features to its potential .

this was my first taste of a heavier bodied beer , and it grew on me as i drank it.i found this beer to be well balanced.the taste was bordering on assalting me , but somehow it made me appreciative of the complex taste.i think i 've met women like that.very drinkable.i am yearning to taste the other versions of beer from this brewery .  a - gorgeous blackness with a profound dark tan head .  mouthfeel : this is a little thin somehow .

aroma is dark caramel , light golden fruit , dry cocoa , and an earthy noble hop notion . flavor is on the mild side foir this style , but still very authentic and tastey .  black with a quarter-inch , creamy brown head that remains . very nice .  this is a medium bodied brew that is excessively carbonated . it is quite bubbly and fizzy on the tongue .

terrific aroma , nice hoppy palate .  pours a hazy copper color with extra large white fluufy head and good lacing .  this is a full-bodied beer , but mouthfeel is a bit weak compared to the rest of this beer 's qualities .

lacing is pretty skimpy s : does n't actually smell like much ... a bit of hops , kind of a dulled down version of ab or db ... no oaked smell t : completely different from the smell . the taste is absolutely amazing ! meaning perfect !  big off-white head on a luxuriously dark red body .  carbonation is very high on this one leading to a prickly mouthfeel that is just a little bit too much .

you 'd be like , hey , here 's a normal looking beer , something weird to the aroma , like vanilla and ginger . mouthfeel of that , and drinkability , must suffer , like a cubs fan .  this beer pours black , with a very efervecent thick tan head .  m : medium carbonation , very light body , definitely too watery for my taste .

in aroma , bitter backer 's cocoa with metallic undertones dominate .  appearance : orange amber in color with a thick 2 '' head .  m : a bit to much carbonation initially , but it gets calmer after a while and all in all the beer is very smooth and creamy .

a- orange-amber color , very little head s- mild and sweet , very fragrant t- bittersweet with a very strong aftertaste m-smooth , kept nice carbonation throughout the beer d-not one of my favorites , could n't have more than 2 due to the strong aftertaste .  pouring it slowly was not enough to tame this wild head . the head literally grows before your eyes , forming a peak of meringue so thick , you can float a half dollar on it . the beer itself is highly carbonated . the color is crystal clear straw golden . aside from the wonderful head , i do n't know why this beer earns such stellar reviews .  mouthfeel leaves something to be desired in that it 's a bit too light , but this still a nice wit overall .

the aroma of the oranges creeps out in the nose , but it is n't bitter or too bold . no real essence of the hoppiness . nice and tasty brew .  urthel hop-it served in new belgium globe glass a : pours clear pale gold with big , meringue-like head that shows great retention and leaves wonderful brussels lacing .  alot of the reviews i read said this was michelob 's best offering in their craft beer line . not even gon na try and be a beer geek here and sound intelligent . i just do not think this my type of beer . tasted like rotten bananas mixed with bad oatmeal . i wish i could say something nice but i can not think of a thing .

mmmmm . s - floral and citrus hop , hint of malt , nothing special t - sharp citrus hop that hits first , then balanced by moderate sweet malt which arises more slowly .  brilliant , deep amber body wit a copious , sticky tan head that smears lacing up and down the glass ' sides .  m - nothing typically outstanding in the mouthfeel , but it is more than made up for in taste .

smelled more like acetone than fruit .  beautiful beer - black with 1 finger cream head that does not diminish one iota and how can you not like the reverse cascading effect . decent lacing all the way down .  medium-light bodied , a bit thin , with gentle carbonation and a light hop bite .

i could find nothing malty about the aroma , but there was a fair hops presence .  phenomenal retention leaves behind mountainous gobs of lace on the sides of the glass , after falling for 20 minutes or so . the beer is a very hazy cloudy straw gold color .  personaly , i 'd like the mouthfeel a bit fuller , but perhaps i 'm spoiled by the big pilsner which initiated the hoffmann series .

smell is pleasant , but somewhat muted with citrus and hops coming through .  deep redish amber in color , not quite see through . giant , sticky , oily , toffee colored head that left great , chunky lacing the whole way down .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied , which seems a bit on the lighter side for a barleywine .

nose is crisp , with definite british hops and somewhat soapy . i could drink a ton o this stuff ... fantastic beer .  the beer is a dark umber brown , topped with a creamy almond colored head . that 's some great head retention in my book . lots of lace on the glass , leaving rings all the way down .  too carbonated .

n : bananas , some heat , and sweet fruits . nothing abundant but pretty mild hint of bubblegum yeast .  pours a hazy dark amber with a large long lasting tan head , with very good lacing and head retention throughout to the end .  flatness of mouthfeel is a negative factor but i still thought it was a tight attempt at the style for a relative newcomer to the trade .

there is little immediate aroma , though when the beer warms up a bit a thin malty sweetness can be noted . this is a very subtle , slightly malty , slightly chocolate brown ale . one of the nicer brown ales out there . i was pleased to note the lack of a sour aftertaste , which i sometimes notice with other brown ales .  drank from a 12 fl oz./355ml can purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma served in a pint glass the beer poured a a slightly hazed , medium amber color with a frothy , off-white , three-finger , sea foam head that slowly faded to a resilient cap .  good balance m- light and watery . lots of hops that stick to the tongue .

this beer smells musty ! but it 's the sort of friendly musty smell of clothes you wore to the beach and let dry out on a sunny day .  super dark brown but not quite black . excellent head retention . there is almost a brown outline near the edge of the glass with a very dark center .  the feel was light bodied with light carbonation .

hoppy dipa aroma is evident as soon as you start pouring the brew into the glass . piney and generally grass-like notes . i find it very drinkable as i 've drank half the pint quite aggresively .  duvel is a slightly opaque but very sparkly straw-colored ale with a huge , fluffy , rocky white head .  slighty carbonated , with a nice albeit thin mouthfeel .
