the floral hop aroma is noticeable without even lifting the glass to my nose . upon closer smell , there is a lush bouquet of floral , lemon and grapefruit hops . hop bitterness right off the bat over a sweet malt backbone leading to a very bitter , slightly oily finish that is quite lingering . body is medium and drinkability is ok , hurt by a bitterness that boarders on harsh . i know that 's stone 's thang , but i think this would be an exceptional ipa if they toned down the bitterness just a touch .  the head is about two fingers and frothy and foamy . the head resides to a half finger and it leaves nice gobes of lacing all the way down with a ton of visible carbonation the aroma is of breadiness and earthy and citrus hops it also has a slight tea aroma to it .  exceptionally smooth mouthfeel , a buttery diacetyl eases it along .

the bourbon aging is evident in the aroma and smells like coffee with oatmeal laced with bourbon .  weihenstephaner korbinian is a solid , crystal clear , brown-red beer with an oily , bubbly , beige head .  the feel is amazing here , silky creamy smooth with just the right body on it .

the nose was mostly floral hops and biscuity grain . some dms in the background , but not so much that it detracted from the aroma . not real complex , but still enjoyable . i have a few more aged bottles that i am looking forward to drinking .  perfect big black , creamy head .  m = medium heavy body , great carbonation level , great mouthcoating , almost no real burn from the high abv and what there is goes so well with the flavors and warming winter mood that it fits perfectly .

sweet , roasty chocolate goodness . is this stuff available as an air freshener ? `` alcoholic chocolate milk for adults '' . really good !  bottle : poured a deep hazy amber color ale with a very large foamy head with nice off-white foamy head with good retention and some very good lacing .  big and chewy with a very smooth , creamy finish .

s - in a word - awesome . one of the best noses ever ; let 's see we 've got mango , apricot , orange rind , pineapple and candy . usually am not good at getting aroma off beer , but this one is an exception .  looks exactly how a good pils should look . poured with an impressive white , foamy , frothy , thick head that lasts a while and good lacing .  with the ginormous head , i expected the carbonation to be knocked out of this brew somewhat , and it has been . no complaints here : the medium body has a gloriously soft , silky feel as a result .

smells insanely strong ! it smells strong but wonderful . i ca n't wait for the first sip !  a - the beer is so thick that the pour is virtually silent ... massive head forms in a brown colour complementing the black/dark brown colour of the body .  great dry mouthfeel , perfect on style points .

dry though its taste and afterwards , with roasted grainy taste on the subtle side . great *irish* stout ( not to purposely compare with some very great domestic varieties ) .  poured a murky dark copper hue with a two and a half finger pillowy white head . there was excellent retention and sticky lacing .  perfect balance in this mouthfeel , perhaps the best quality of this beer .

rum soaked oranges , fig , aged caramel malt make for a great fragrance . t : sweet toffee malt , oranges , butterrum and brandy .  lacing is very nice too .  feels wonderfully silky and smooth on the palate .

aroma was amazing , perfect . lots of amarillo and maybe nelson ? taste , pretty easy going , very full of floral hop mouthfeel .  looks like a golden spritzer . a beautiful large , sticky cream-like head , that looked liked stiffly whipped egg whites . i loved watching the creamy head explode after the pour .  m-very smooth and creamy , full bodied , good carbonation and a crisp grainy finish .

s : lot going on , i can smell the hops and dark malts right away . the hops have a nice aroma and blend well with the spicy notes of toasted almonds . t : lot going on with the first sim , hops up front followed by the sweet malt , the an bitter finish , the bitter is more of a burnt toffee or coffee not citrus .  it poured very nicely into the thick semi opaque cranberry/burgandycolor .  the mouthfeel is very thick and pleasant , almost creamy .

beautiful floral candied orange rind and subtle pine resin aromas rise from the glass . floral , but bitey , hops attack the tongue before being met with a firm malt body . the mouth is coated with pleasing hop oils .  big frothy head made out of creamy , delicate bubbles . head color is a light sienna and the body color is pitch black , though hints of ruby when held up to the light . even through the murkiness i can still make out long , thick ropes of carbonation from many nucleation sites .  the mouthfeel has an almost perfect extra virgin olive oil and buttery finish to it .

very nice copper colored with 2 fingers of sticky white fome.piney/grassy hop attack on the nose is excellent . bursting with tangy citrus hop flavor , with some sweet malt flavor to back it up .  a fizzy , bright lemon yellow pour topped with a pillow of foamy white marshmallows , creating sheet lacing . superb . highly charged with carbonation , you have to gently pour - even then the head blossoms heartily no hint of the 11 % , just an excellent sipper .  m : full body , not the least bit cloying . awesome . d : great for it 's weight .

this smells absolutely fantastic ! i was expecting an explosion of pine resin and grapefruit rind , but to the contrary , this smells very much like a j.w . this is very nice , indeed , but certainly one to sip on . this is an absolutely terrific american attempt at an english barleywine . it looks nice in the glass , it smells wonderful , and is just a well crafted , big beer .  bottle : poured a pitch-black color ale with a dark brown color head with great retention and some very good lacing .  mouthfeel is very full and creamy , easily the strongest point of this beer . strong hoppy ale with a great mouthfeel .

018 a - pours a bright golden color , quite cloudy , one inch fluffy white head , not much retention or lacing s - great aroma , lots of barnyard funk and sour lemon , very earthy , light acetic character , aroma is closer to the character of a traditional belgian lambic than most of the american wild ales i 've tried t - strong tongue ripping lemon sourness and barnyard funk up front , lighter acetic/vinegar notes on the midpalate with the funk and sourness leaving rather quickly , as great as this is initially , the finish is really truncated and disappointing , really my only knock on the beer , finish does extend a bit when the beer warms up , but it 's still rather short , alcohol is well-hidden , pretty dry overall m - medium-bodied , with moderate to lower carbonation , not much alcohol warming , dry finish d - pretty drinkable for the style , the sourness and funk are intense ( up front , at least ) , but they are n't overly harsh on the palate , the smell and taste are interesting and sufficiently complex , alcohol not an issue really good sour overall that would be exceptional if not for the short finish .  a : pours a beautiful yellow-orange with slight cloud and hint of yeast sediment . like admiring a wondrous sunrise .  mouthfeel : pure silk from beginning to end .

s - wow , smells just like a pumpkin pie , lots of pumpkin and spices , cinnamon , clove , allspice and some malt sweetness . as the beer warmed up the sweetness turned overbearing . o - just too sweet for my liking , but may be worth a buy for the smell alone .  it pours black with a brown head . depending on how you pour it , it will keep the head on it until the glass is empty . thus it leaves a very nice lacing on the glass .  the taste is mellow chocolate on the front as it glides down with its thick silky mouth feel . almost a fudge aftertaste .

this is definately a unique esb in the grand scheme of things . i get even added bitter qualities from a slightly roasted malt goodness . notes : this is arguably the best in the style for my money . hell take style completely out of the equation , this is a kick ass offering .  a - nice deep yellow color with a moderate white head , foamy . a perfect 5 for the style .  viscous , creamy and full . medium low carbonation .

smells outstanding ! highly sweet smelling . overall , a great dipa . best smelling beer i 've ever experienced . definitely recommend this one !  thanks to r moe nay for this one . golden amber body with a nice thick head and lacing . a real beauty here , competes with christina ricci and taryn manning .  sooo nice .

a beautiful and warm aroma . t : immediate spiciness and brown sugar , dark caramel , banana , heavy baked good like scones or biscuits , with a bitter punch that sneaks up on you in the end . superb . o : what can be said ?  a-pours as black as a dark night with a cream coloured creamy top .  with arthur , shaun consistently demonstrates his mastery as a brewer - and the mouthfeel department might be his greatest strength . this is exactly what i want my saison to feel like .

s - massive aroma of weed , weeds , dandelions , herbs ( catnip ? ) , skunk , sharp lemon peel , and as it warms up a bit sweet malt emerges . t - taste is a lot milder than the aroma , with only faint weed and herbs and a bit more sweetness . d - this was kind of awesome in that peculiar fantme sort of way .  the beer filled 3/4 of the glass and was crowned with a thick and frothy , nearly pure white head that lasted the entire length of the sample . the beer was a mohogany brown color with ruby highlights and appeared very still ; no carbonation streaming but a big sheet of sticky lace . one of the best looking beers i 've seen .  its alcohol is hidden well underneath my favorite part of the ride , the thick , creamy mouthfeel bcs provided .

smells of corn and some alcohol , it has a sweet and malty taste .  a - a thick monsterous head that will not dissipate rests over this opaque brew . argueably , the nicest rings of lacing i have ever seen form down the side .  medium-thick with a nice velvety feel in the mouth . high carbonation ; letting it sit in the mouth , one feels light bubbles on the tongue . pretty exceptional . yes .

lots of citrusy hop aroma with some pine and maybe even a hint of peach . overall it 's good but not as great as i 'd hoped .  a- this one pours out a somewhat hazy glowing golden colored body with a really large bright white head on top .  would be better if it were more balanced with the malt . really velvety . nice appearence , really dark , good tan head tops it off .

the smell is easily the best thing about this beer -- it 's absolutely wonderful . i absolutely expected more hops from this beer .  look : orange/copper in color with a great 1 inch off white head and great retention and some sticky lacing smell : the amarillo hops give it a bit of a skunky note with traces of pine in the background taste : the flavor honestly is not very good .  has a perfect 10 body with an exhilarating highly carbonated mouthfeel .

aroma : sweet and dark chocolate , very inviting . taste : not quite as good as the smell . chocolate and coffee flavors dominate throughout .  apperance is great with a large fluffy head that reminded me of a nice snowy christmas day .  juicy taste.. great medium thickness and silky texture . abv is most noticeable as a warming sensation in the stomach , and the fire definitely builds up down there . i can put away hercules like nobody 's business , this thing is a digestif at best .

a - the pour produced a vibrant golden-yellow body with some orange hues ... a small , white head formed and fell to a wispy cap ... decent lacing was left behind s - what a nose ... super fresh hops as if they were sitting on top of the beer ... they had a leafiness to them again saying they are right in your glass ... lots of citrus with an underlying piney aroma t - again the super fresh hops are jumping out ... they provide a butt-load of citrus flavors along with the slight bitterness of the rind ... there is some brief caramel which balances things slightly ... the part that balances more , and the part that makes this beer what it is ... the wheat malt comes in towards the finish and mellows out the bitter rind and marries with the citrus to create that bittersweet finish m - light bodied ... refreshing , bitter , dry , balanced o - another please !  a : black texas oil tar . darkest head ever .  a feel : i actually loved the medium-bodied mouthfeel as it just seemed to have a perfect flow across the palate with the hops and malts doing wonderful things to tickle me.. this is what a doppelbock should feel like.. drinkability : is ok - its a very strong beer and sierra nevada certainly did not try to mask the alcohol too well , nor the hops nor.. well , anything .

the applewood bacon , oak , and beechwood smoke smell incredible . beneath the smoke i find toasted malt . the nose is very clean . overall : a good smoked doppelbock with an incredible aroma .  22 oz bottle , no freshness date discernible , poured into a nonic pint a-pour yields an impressive 2 inch white head that recedes at a snail 's pace leaving behind a magnificent lacing along the sides of the glass . deep yellowish orange in color , perhaps a shade lighter than copper . head finally settles to about a half finger and remains for the duration . excellent head retention and cling .  extremely smooth with very fine bubbles of co2 , medium bodied , superb texture .

great bursts of citrus aroma coming off of this one . the fresh citrus aroma does n't translate into the flavor profile much .  poured into my duvel tulip produced a huge fluffy meringue head that stayed until about halfway through the beer .  wonderfully dry mouthfeel .

very nice ! t - this is where the beer starts to turn downhill .  a : it pours a great cloudy orange , with big tan head . in some parts it changes color to yellow .  m : extremely full-bodied , thick and viscous . a big stout , but the alcohol is well hidden , a very smooth drinker .

right out of the bottle i can smell the delicious hops in this beer . very oily and fruity . with a minute i smell the roasted malts in the background . the flavor is not nearly as good . it is a lot maltier than i expect . very full bodied/syrupy .  fantastic clinging lace tapestries on the chalice . the nicely designed , minimalistic graphic artwork is also quite nice .  feel : low carbonation , rich full body , ridiculously smooth and creamy , somewhat dry finish . drinkability : fantastic english-style stout .

aroma is a brilliant bursting bouquet of vanilla , cherry , bourbon , and roasty-toasty malt . i ca n't pull my nose out of the snifter , we 're getting some chocolate notes now as it warms up , sweet molasses too !  dark amber in color with a 2 '' head and nice retention . excellent lacing . a sexy beer .  matching taste and awesome creamy mouthfeel .

smells fabulous -- i detected honey , cloves , and other spices that almost gave it a floral smell . it 's a very curious , aromatic beer .  dark brown with a creamy head and an earthy coffee aroma .  extremely smooth and creamy mouthfeel .

amazing aroma and then a little lackluster on the follow through .  the beer pours super black with a tan dense head fomaing up and fading to a sturdy surface layer .  mouthfeel is medium to full bodied . incredibly creamy with extra smooth carbonation .

smell : i 'm not a huge fan of oktoberfest brews , but this smells heavenly . light spices of cinnamon or nutmeg and a gentle hop addition accentuate a deliciously sweet malt nose . a touch of bitterness near the end , cloves as well . taste/mouthfeel : ooh , very sour !  pours a most excellent dark bronze color , with an appealing ruby tint and a nice almost beige head .  taste : excellent body , the cherries and acidity make a wonderful balancing act , the murky , yeasty funk is there and the alcohol is solid and warming at the end .

damn shame for him . smelling it reminds me of a merlot or another rich red wine , very vinous and showing signs of maturity . very thin body , but overall a unique brew . it 's a very unique beer .  a - dark copper with a large , well defined foamy white head that slowly fades to a thiner layer that stays throughout .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is amazing . just about medium bodied with quite a bit of fine carbonation .

the aroma was a malty and a brown sugary smell . definitely malty and sugary tasting as well but not very well balanced with an aftertaste that was n't very pleasant . drinkable , but not much more than that .  appearance- golden-orange hued color with a huge four fingered large bubbled head .  could be because of the spices , but it tastes more like a full bodied saison , with less yeast , and a well done version at that . it has a great texture to it , and the taste is amazing .

this is a truly unique aroma , one everyone should enjoy .  a - hazy amber-orange color with a thick two to three finger light brown head .  `` imperial '' means alot here . good light malty base to keep this full & thick . very welcome bitter finish after the malt & citrous front end , nice & dry . like most rogue products , quite drinkable , but the taste of alcohol tends to put one off a bit .

aroma is a+ , nice and minty ... but not over the top .  pours pitch black like molasses . even on the way out of the bottle it seems to come slow and thicker . dark tan head slowly forms well after the pouring is done . the bubbles take time to form and then take even more time getting to the top of the liquid to form head .  incredibly thick and creamy , and perfectly carbonated .

aroma is a very , very faint corn .  a : it pours a hazy orange color with a huge , three finger head of ocean foam that holds and laces exceptionally well .  mouthfeel is oily , heavy and smooth with a low amount of carbonation , magnificent .
this is one of the best smelling ipas this mans nose has come across . the taste of this aipa was awesome !  great retention and lacing . good looking brew indeed .  the mouthfeel is really nice .

definitely an excellent quaffer . quite pleasent . this beer has surpassed my expectations .  picture-perfect beer -- dull cloudy gold with an immense pillow of sticky , long-lasting lace .  the lack of carbonation and warm temperature really allow these flavors to develop , creating a wonderfully complex palate . mouthfeel is full , rich , thick , and the finish is creamy . delightful . overall this is the best blue point has to offer , and on cask it 's even better .

delicious . t : bready , rye bready .  appearance : pours a beautiful ruby red liquid with a soft pink head . nice constant carbonation in the middle of the glass keeps the head going till the end . the really nice part is that if you swirl the liquid around in the glass the head takes on different shades of red . a beautiful color overall .  the mouthfeel is what really stands out about this beer , it is very coating and penetrating , a very different sensation from most other beers .

there is a nice hoppy and herbal aroma , which coupled with the high carbonation , feels good in the mouth ... the beer is very satisfying and strong on the pallet without being too strong in the stomach , but it does leave the throat a bit dry .  pours a lovely caramel color with a fine long lasting head . it 's a beautiful thing .  perfect mouthfeel .

s : huge nose . lots of fig , dried fruit , honey , toffee and caramel . no hops present . after about half the glass , some alcoholic warmth becomes perceivable , but it is quite subtle given the strength of the beer . overall : this is a very intensely flavored barley wine , but still nicely refined and well-balanced . excellent , world class winter beer .  2004 bottle pours a beautiful reddish brown .  mouthfeel - perfect . so smooth .

it smelled like milk chocolate and creamy coffee with a bit of pine hops . reminiscent of old rasputin .  `` bottled in 2011 1c '' a - my antonia poured a beautiful gold color that bubbled steadily and continually with a thick and vivid white head full of bubble of all sizes that left great lacing down the length of the glass s - the beer had slightly sweet ( caramel ?  mouthwatering feel that 's very creamy and silky smooth with a grainyness that 's pleasing .

pours a clear pale golden yellow color with almost clear light straw colored edges and a 1.5 finger frothy white head . slightly spicy , earthy hop aroma with lots of grass , straw and pilsner malt . faint light fruit notes , mostly apple .  i think this beer has the best possible appearance , that 's why i gave it a 5.0 score on appearance . again , the appearance , and the way it pours into a long fluted glass , makes you want to sit down and just stare at its beauty before taking that first taste .  in the middle there is a dry briney sort of flavor with just the slightest hint of salt , which just tingles on the tongue because of the delightful carbonation . this beer is delitefully light bodied with a zesty sort of carbonation that just feels great on the pallate .

the smell makes me think of my grandmother pulling a fine pumpkin pie out of the oven in her old lakehouse . damn the silly bjcp judge who informed me they are tasteless gourds .  but , this one pours a rich orange color with a 3/4 '' off white head . tons of lacing .  the mouth feel is big and round with almost a sticky lip smacking finish that is pleasant and has you eager for the next sip .

aroma : dry hopped with centennial and crystal hops ca n't beat this , great floral earthy hop aroma nice mellow caramel malt tone good stuff . drinkability : the aroma alone leaves me wanting more and more beer , awesome stuff not expecting anything here but boy i 'm i glad i found this gem of a balanced hoppy ale .  procured from grand cru in baltimore and poured into a large hefe glass humongous white fluffy heat atop a cloudy dark yellow hazy brew . excellent retention , lacing , and carbonation phenolic as all getout , with sweet malts and yeasts vying for space in your nostrils medium bodied malt monster .  highly interesting mouthfeel does the trick .

s - wow , fresh hops explode as soon as the can is cracked . finish is semi-dry with a touch of malt . o - great fresh hop ipa .  it has the same characteristics as standard guinness draught , except it is chilled to a few degrees below the normal serving temperature . the few extra degrees really made a difference for me , as it made the stout even more drinkable than it already is without affecting the flavor .  high carbonation and a light body leave a mildy dry finish and a marvelous mouthfeel .

a very fresh and exceptional smell . tangy and tart taste !  the presentation was great ; the rolling foam that starts at the bottom and works its way up the glass was awesome . there was no aroma i could detect .  delicious m - this is probably one of the smoothest beers i have ever had .

huge scent . spend a long time enjoying it before your first sip . mouthfeel - perfect . so smooth .  fish serves their leavenworth pilsner in tall , slender pint glasses that elegantly showcase the robust carbonation and refined copper body . and the smart cap of head and frayed sheet lace are regal .  perfection . o= one tasty treat .

smells fantastic , aged pungent .  pours pitch black with a fine , rich , hazelnut head . looks delicious .  m- creamy and oily at the same time . smooth with a lasting syrupy finish . d- absolutely delicious . unique with well-hidden alcohol .

the volatiles wafting from the surface quite simply overwhelm the sinuses , but in such a good way . perfect balance of aromas . d - overall , this is a very good beer .  the look of this beer was very promising . i 've never had a double pilsner , so i did n't know what to expect , but this has a thin head that is frothy and beautifully stable ( although thin ) . it is perfectly golden and foggy .  very smooth body and almost creamy carbonation .

s : wow - best chocolate smell by far of any ris claiming to have chocolate in the beer . it 's fabulous . also some smoke , malt , and a bit of booze t : wow - this baby is hot - chocolate comes through well , malt , some smoke in the back . the hotness is a bit distracting though so it ca n't get higher than a 4 here . needs to be a bit thicker but it 's good .  pours with a full 2.5 inches of rich , creamy darkish tan head that is very slow to recede , with great retention . fantastic appearance .  mouthfeel/drinkability : mouthfeel is full , thick and creamy . totally awesome in my opinion .

hard to find a better smelling beer . the dry hopping really took it to another level t-very nice hop taste .  the slow nitro pour produces a deep dark and just plain black as night hued brew .  mouthfeel is great , super thick and creamy .

lacing is nose is super pungent , i could smell it as i was pouring the glass . very sweet smell , with a touch of fruit and black licorice - damn , almost like a jagermeister . then turns amazingly sweet , almost too sweet .  appearance : pours a pleasant clear amber color , with 2 fingers of foamy head in my darkness tulip . as the head begins to recede , sticky lacing clings to the edge of the glass .  m - so beautifully thick and creamy on top and then thinner once you penetrate through the top layer . a softly sweet mouthful . perfection .

the aroma is stereotypical drie fonteinen . it has that gnarly , musty brett character on top of the lactic sourness .  appearance : the body has a dark appearance with good clarity and very deep brownish amber color . on top there is a huge light tan head that has great retention . also it makes for some cool splotchy lacing on the glass .  mf- the feel is the best part for me .
ar- very hoppy with some citrus notes . o- one awesome ipa .  excellent lacing and incredible head retention .  a very drinkable dubbel with a smoothness that gives a fantastic mouthfeel .

i thought i knew what roast smelled like until i smelled this beer . this is roasty ! i home-roast my own green coffee beans , and this smells exactly like roasting coffee beans .  very impressive to say the least . a truly beautiful looking stout .  unbelievably smooth and creamy mouthfeel .

the bourbon was clearly superior to me , and i believe that was the consensus among the group as well ... the aroma on the bourbon is awesome , dominates the brandy , vanilla , wood , dark brown sugar ... the taste is alcoholic bourbon vanilla , but it still works . tons of prune graham crackers which are awesome on the aroma and taste . a little sweet right but in time will be unreal .  beautiful black pour with fine tan head .  this brew shines in the taste and mouthfeel department ! extreme bitter hops up front and an alcoholic bite lingers .

wonderfully sour pineapple-like aroma with some , but not overwhelming acetic character and lemons shining through .  nice head , spongey and a semi-glossy white . three fingers after the pour , and a thick film and good lacing after each sip troughout . hazey and translucent golden amber .  the feel is outstanding . full bodied and creamy .

s - wonderful sharp piney aroma with a grand hop bill for an english brew , really great fresh bouquet . t- extra yum .  appearance- i love lots of head ( lol ) on my beer . the best retention i 've seen so far on any ipa period .  4/5 m : velvet in the mouth here with a medium fuller body and small carbonation . beautiful . 5/5 d : very easy going down and plenty of balance .

smell : tons of hop and malt aroma . smells delicious . taste : great balance of hops and malt , though the flavors are a bit less distinctive than in the aroma .  motor oil.. midnight black body , the head looks like chocolate milk .  mouthfeel is full bodied , creamy , and quite smooth on the palate .

smell - smoky , campfire , charcoal , wood-oven , ... you get the point . so good .  pours out a beautiful mix of dark ruby and nutty brown with a thick , mocha head with a raised island in the middle . as it recedes after some time , it leaves huge , chunky lace on the glass .  mouthfeel is perfect , bright , but still substantial enough to stand up to the chicken .

grassy and earthy in a strange way , and unbelievably intriguing . taste is sweet , strong clove and cinnamon , with a nicely subtle citrus hops to cap it off .  as with most mikkeller beers the appearance is exceptional ( opaque with a very small head of coffee with cream ) bottomline , your ten bucks is better spent on the beer geek by mikkeller , if one has the option , and share this one with a friend because your taste buds will diminish as you get more drunk .  soft , so soft . like drinking velvet . it felt amazing and looked and smelled good . well worth trying for the texture alone .

poured into a large tulip glass a clear deep golden with a large blooming white head that took forever to subside.multiple layers of lace left behind.wow what awesome aromas , there is an american twist to this beer no doubt , floral and citric hops all over the place , its perfect as far as iam concerned.dry on the palate with grassy herbal hop notes , light spiced phenols but they dont play a big role.this is quenching and bone dry , i really like it.if all beers of this style were like this i would be a convert , the american craftmanship to the belgian strong pale style in this beer shows thru with great left coast hop flavors.the alcohol lends a little sweetness but its held in check pretty well .  pours a gold hazy color with a thick cloud like fluffy 3 finger head that dissipates to a constant one finger head .  beautifully carbonated and smooth .

a dark tan head , not much retention , a little streaky lace ... the nose on this is pretty outstanding . the laird apply brandy shows off strongly , very sweet , dark fruits , a little wood .  pours a unpenetrating dark oily black but seems light ... tan head with exceptional lacing ... thick head present throughout ... smells very simply of chocolate , caramel , and alcohol ... very nice ... whoa , explosion of flavor ... the dry hopping gives this a nice finish ... robust dark chocolate and coffee flavors dominate with a strong and full flavored finish ... damn , this one 's good ... i thought the high alcohol would give this one a slight burn , but it does n't ... very rich and refreshing ... very bold , lightly thick , and refreshing ... again , the hop finish gives this imperial stout an amazing touch ... no stale aftertaste which i sometimes get with stouts ... overall , you 'll love this one ...  f - the ultra-sticky , resiny feel we know and love . this is basically unchanged from the bottle .

shared by drewba at a recent sour tasting . it is such an odd color -- like burnt orange with 1986 chevy truck rust chunks added in liquid form . lightly sweet malt followed by really intense cherry notes . some oak and some vinegar . the nose is dominated by the sour cherries .  on pouring : this is the perfect colour for this beer , almost efflorescence , golden copper , liquid autumn in a glass .  the lactose makes it presence known as well adding the smooth and velvety creamy texture which is spectacular . overall this is one of the top 3 milk stouts i have ever had ; perfect example of the style .

fff just has a knack to developing the most beautifully aromatic ipa 's and this one is not lacking . d : this is an interesting dipa variant .  extremely foggy light copper . excellent head retention .  mouthfeel smooth and creamy , with a full body and low carbonation .

the aroma is decadent , with loads of fresh bananas , lemon zest , a clove spiciness , tart wheat , yeast , grassy and floral hops , vanilla and perhaps pears . overall a very complex , yet traditional hefeweizen that is packed with flavor and aroma .  it at first appears dark walnut but gives to me what is an extreme red . the head is surprisingly a very faint light tan , about three fingers , with some good retention and some decent initial lacing . really impressed by the color of the body on this beer . the beer looks great though .  m : full bodied and velvety smooth . there is enough carb there to liven this thick brew up a bit .

4.5 smell : the aromas are oaky , raspberry , and tartness . 3.5 drinkability : this beer is very tasty .  it looks so wonderful being drawn , cloudy and creamy , with insanely thick bubbles settling in to a milky , rich thick head .  nice warming sensation from the alcohol . rich , velvety and creamy .

the aroma is killer , blueberries and ripe fruit . unfortunately the taste could n't live up to the nose , few do ... nice rounded tartness with a hint of funk . it was great , but not nearly as epic as it 's made out to be .  pours a beautiful , light , slightly hazy amber . has an amazing full white head that really stays around for the entire glass !  the nose was somewhat sweet and the mouthfeel was really full , almost creamy , nearly belying the idea that it was cask-conditioned .

the aromas are , as another reviewer noted , precisely that of boiling ears of corn .  a - profoundly black , with a respectable chocolate milk-colored head that actually sticks around for awhile . looks incredible in a snifter .  this was a surprise , very drinkable and excellent mouthfeel .

a : very dark ruby red ; good head but it dissipates quickly ; good lacing s : beautiful , very strong aroma of brown sugar , currant figs ; lingers long t : really intense flavor , dominated by non-citrus fruits : currants , figs esp .  a= this ale poured an extremely clear copper color with a 2 '' heavy , off-white head ( aggressive pour at fridge temp ) . beautiful .  mouthfeel is silky , creamy , like a milkshake .

smell is a beautifully blended hoppyness and roasted coffee , some chocolate and earthy tones . wow , usually i do n't go much for black ipas , but this is really nice . taste is a bit of a let down , heavy on the dark chocolate/cocoa , slightly burnt/smokey , pretty heavy on the astringent/bitter without much of the delicious hoppiness .  this is a good looking beer . nice deep red color , sparkling body , and good sturdy/sticky head formation in good quantity .  this is a big beer , with a full body and a thick , syrupy mouthfeel . chewy .

what a fantastic nose . taste : refreshing - a brief flash of bready sweet malts followed by amazing dry pine bitterness . this is a beer that demonstrates that well-crafted brews can emphasize just a few flavors well and nonetheless be truly impressive . wonderful .  poured chilled in flared glass a : dark caramel , clear ; very thick head ; good carb beads ; great lacing s : a bit univiting ; thin , malty ( sweet ) aroma ; but i do n't smell a bock here t : one-dimensional bock ; little double about it m : watery , thin , dead it looks fantastic , but 'tai n't .  the thick mouthfeel is a st trademark style and it really works for this beer .

smell is really , really good . when i put my nose to the glass , i get punched in the face by citrus hops with hints of citrus . it feels really slick while going down , very oily , very smooth .  appearance : pours out of the can into my sa perfect pint with fantastic , rocky , 2 finger mocha colored head , which never really dissipates . excellent .  m- thick full body with some carbonation .

this is a very good ipa and very easy to drink .  grand looking ... deep burgundy red color ... .cream tan head on top ... .aroma is earthy ... pretty big cocoa impression ... .tastes like an english style beer ... earthy hops ... .almost a bit like an esb ... .i like the flavors of this ... .very enjoyable and easy to drink with some character .  probably the best balance of chocolate and stout roastiness i know of , with a smooth , somewhat creamy mouthfeel .

sculpin smells incredible , a mega blast of peaches and juicy grapefruits . sculpin was a bit of a mini roller coaster ride for me , thrilled with the appearance and nose and initially underwhelmed with the taste , only to have the beer recover beautifully .  excellent thick head with great retention , leaves behind tons of lace . almost `` ring like '' as each sip it takes there is a ring left to mark the previous level .  m- perfect for this style . the natural carbonation from the cask worked wonders and made the body feel extremely smooth .

smell is quite faint . sweet fruit smell , a little hops come through .  appearance - a very dark beer with just the barest shade of brown or red at the edges . moderate to light pour still yielded a 2 finger tan head that receded slowly and held at a solid covering . impressive lacing .  mouthfeel was beyond exceptional with this beer .

a new white ale from the two brothers crew . appearance : nice cloudy/hazy pour with a minimal white head . smell : very dull and lackluster . weak weak weak chalky lemon nose taste : the taste makes up for the the weak nose .  it is ultra carbonated and produces massive amounts of bright white head . the body a beautifully clear and gold in color .  very , very nice .
nice thick head settles into a nice aroma capturing thin cap . smell is exceptional ! carmal malt and fig jump out !  this beer poured a deep rich brown color .  perfect feel .

a wonderfully complex aroma t -- upon first sip i am immediately hit with a very unpleasant metallic taste .  vigorous pour yields 2 '' of off white head , bright copper body with orange tinge .  m : extremely creamy and oily as it goes down . this is probably the smoothest beer i 've ever had . d : goes down so damn smooth . i found myself wanting to drink more just so that i could maintain the slick feel in my mouth .

caged and corked , popped the cork with a loud pop ! brett tartness hit my nose immediately and got me excited about this beer . it pours a bright yellow color- pretty cloudy . smell- tart cherries , a nice funky waft of brett , maybe some white wine notes , perhaps champagne . this beer is pretty unique . i do n't feel like it sits well in the wit category , and it is n't 100 % about the brett either .  appearance : extremely dark brown , some may say black .  goes down smooth with no bite at all and finishes crisp with just the right amount of dryness on the palate . just as good as their vollbier . great stuff .

s : amazing . wow . totally unique and enjoyable . t : buttery malts , light fresh grain , elements of corn , fruity hops .  terrific , rocky retention and plenty of lace . gorgeous beer .  mouthfeel is smooth and creamy ... excellent ... one of the best .

bananas , sweet sugars , hops , excellent . this is a very good tasting beer , but there is a touch too much water in the mouthfeel and a touch too much soapy residue left on the tongue afterwards .  this porter pours with an opaque black body topped by a thick , brown head wtih good lacing .  like velvet as it goes down , with a nice bit of prickly carbonation . very nice body for a regular ipa . not watery or lacking at all in this department .

overall , very delightful and balanced scent ! t -- & gt ; i tasted mostly yeasty malts like the smell , but the dark ( very ripened ) fruits came out less upon swallowing ... unlike abt8 , which has a far fruitier dominance .  16oz nitro can obtained from steve 's - university appearance : ahh the nitro can ... pours into an imperial pint glass , massive chocolate milkshake pour settles into a solid black body and a huge creamy chocolate fluffy head . wonderful , it is absolutely beyond my comprehension how anybody could possibly rate the appearance below a 4 ... what irish stout are you comparing this to that i cant access ?  big abv but not hot , well carbonated , the amazing mouthfeel , fantastic complexity and drinkability .

has the trademark belgian spiciness ( particularly coriander ) that all of my favorite beers have . t - the same spiciness as in the aroma ( coriander and pepper ) with hop bitterness .  pours a cloudy , dark brown on top that fades to a dark copper . great retention and great lacing .  mouthfeel is perfect : medium carbonation and medium body .

very attractive bomber . i can not believe how amazing this beer smells . it 's like straight chocolate bar . with southern tier 's , it 's absolutely about that chocolate . it 's like a hershey 's bar melted down .  it looks great pouring into the glass . it looks fantastic . but it looks and smells awesome .  m : medium body , just about perfect carbonation .

its not very good , but far from the worst beer i have ever had . i can not stress enough that this is more of a cinnamon ale as opposed to to a pumpkine ale . not too much too look at , a bit pale . could n't say that it was very drinkable at all ... too strong of pumpkin to enjoy .  nice bubbles race continuously to the top , excellent retention and lacing .  t- super balanced across the board . m- very balanced . d- delicious .

the smell is outstanding , and i thought i was going to be experiencing a genuine flemish red ale .  pours an effervescent amber/orange with 3 fingers of fluffy tan head . insane lacing & head retention s : citric & floral hops show up early , but muted t : floral & piney hops , plus biscuitty malt up front .  m - the feel is amazing . it begs to be savored over and over again .

a : golden , almost orange beer , with a touch of red ; almost the color of apple juice ; very clear and clean , as if looking at the world through orange-tinted glasses ; light carbonation , with bubbles floating to the top periodically ; head pours a white , frothy , .5 finger thickness that quickly dissipates ; soapy lacing minimal , but there s : pleasant , gentle bouquet of fresh , light , citrusy hops ; when i say fresh , i mean same nose feel as when catching a whiff of a dryer sheet for laundry ; really good t : a bit more flavor strength than the smell indicated , but not in a bad way ; the hops are definitely there , bringing crisp , fresh , citrus notes that make me think of summer ; yeast/bread notes ( biscuit ?  a : looks like oil in a glass . opaque black with a sepia head . great retention and lacing as the beer goes down my gullet .  carbonation is spot on . very gentle carbonation , just how i like it .

the aroma is a citrus almost so complex , my nose ca n't comprhend it . wow ! ! very interesting dipa . highly recommended ! !  dark brown , almost opaque colour , big , soapy and lumpy beige head with generous lacing . looks are about as gorgeous as they could possibly be , ill admit .  '' i in truth have never experienced a mouth feel that was so smooth that packed that amount of flavor , but the downfall with most dark beers is while they taste great , and may have a great mouth feel , you never really want to just drink them non stop .

this brew pours very pretty , featuring a rich , deep , orangy/reddish brew , topped with a tight , tan head . the aroma is hoppy ... and , you can definitely pick out the malty side of the aroma of this beer , too . it has a lot more of a malty smell than i have found in other ipas .  split a 750ml bottle of this nice one from france ... i did n't like the way this one looked too much . it was kind of a dirty dark orange colour , and the yeast chunks were just all over . there was a huge , long lasting head though , which distracted me a little from what was going on below .  mouthfeel= nice creamy mouthfeel .

lots going on in the aroma department : gingerbread , cinnamon , sugar , dough , chocolate , toffee , and a dash of spice & fruit . taste is n't as flavorful as the aroma 'd suggest : some bready malt notes with chocolate and mocha coffee . basically , the aroma on this beer hooked me . everything else is good , like most rogues .  not much lacing . looks to be the norm , but nothing beyond it there .  nice full mouthfeel that 's not sickening like some can be . carbonation is perfect .

s- the smell is a wonderful blend of tart apple , sugary sweetness , soft floral hops , and a subtle background of bready yeast . what is left to linger is minimal floral hop bitterness , a moderate alcohol heat , and an impression of sweet bready yeast , m- medium to high tingly carbonation and lightweight body that is more on the smooth yeasty side than the astringent side . d- this is a really good offering that may be a little bit better with age .  a : this beer looks okay but i found a little lacking with head retention .  felt outstanding in the mouth .

a- pours black with a thin white head s- cold cold coffee or cafe mocha t- dark chocolate , coffee , and roasted malts m- satin with vanilla bean finish d- not for the faint of hearts , excellent example of a porter .  held up to the light there is ruby tint . small tan head that dissipated almost immediately .  mouthfeel : this is one of the best feels i have gotten from an ipa . unbelievably creamy , with a light level of carbonation .

other than the color and mouthfeel , nothing else about this beer reminded me of a hefeweizen . had an extremely strong alcoholic finish that lingered way too long .  a : clear cider brown with a fast fading finger or so of off white head . no lace or cap .  more malty sweetness under it all ( caramel and toffee ) m- full-bodied , creamy , smooth , ca n't really imagine it any better d- very solid beer , easy to drink and very happy to receive this gift

smell : they could do something about this if the american public did n't have such bland tastes ( read ambitious brew , great book explaining american 's pallet preferences and why ) .  22 oz bottle a : deep golden , copper with pretty much no head .  medium-bodied and silky smooth cask mouthfeel . long finish .

very smooth initial mouthfeel with a strong flavor , maybe it 's me but i 'm finding it hard to distinguish what type of flavor exactly above the bitterness that has taken over my whole pallet , it kinda reminds me of lefe , only more bitter ! quite strong though making this review even more difficult , ouch ! quite frankly i wouldnt drink this again , a chore to drink .  375ml bottle poured into my large st. feuillien goblet oude kriek is murky dull red with very thin white head skim that quickly dissipates , basically still .  mouthfeel is superb , full bodied and zesty .

s - strong odors of honey dew melon , banana , cloves , honey , and some more conventional wheat grain aroma . a slight mustiness , but that is barely noticable .  a : this was a lightly hazy , extremely pale golden corn color .  m - incredibly creamy mouthfeel .

a very sexy barleywinish caramel and oxidized malt characteristic . complimentary booze aroma is exhausting in my brain . why does this smell so amazing ? heard some peoples talkin some shit bout this beer , but it smells amazing . hard phenolics , strong booze .  a - pours a deep , rich minerally garnet color , that has to be clear but i ca n't really see through it . atop it was a nice creamy light brownish ruby head that faded quickly to leave no side lacing and very light haloing .  mouthfeel is thick and lush . wonderful overall , a great scotch ale .

good 2 finger white head , transparent golden color smell is grainy and sweet bready dough . some mild alcahol fumieness .  looks nice , poured into a goblet , black as night and virtually no head .  pours a murky gold with an insane pillowy head that i had to eat with a spoon before i could finish my pour smell - all i pick up is apples taste is sweet spiced apples and light grain this beer has perfect mouthfeel - light crisp and creamy with very active carbonation drinkability is almost perfect - had to take off .5 because all the carbonation made me burb too much overall this is a great summer/fall brew .

smell - sweet with orange zest , coriander , clove , and banana , smells amazing . taste - very sweet with hints of banana , some other fruits i ca n't really pinpoint , coriander , and clove .  minute brown head that fades almost immediately and leaves no lacing .  mouthfeel is excellent the lacing is about medium . had it in a six pack from local store .

wonderfully complex . t - big bold hop flavor .  the cream coloured head did n't stay , which was a pity , appearance score drops because of that .  mouthfeel is very viscous and rich , probably my favorite part of the beer .

perfect . really quite nice . the malts are here , but not in the spotlight , which is just fine . d : i was much happier with this beer when compared to the warrior version . overall , it is a really nice ipa .  a bit too much sediment suspended in the pour ... but smell made up for it ... floral .  digging the mouthfeel on this one . it 's damn near perfect for the style .

very sweet smelling blended with a dark roastiness that balances it out . it has an amazing nose which unfortunately outshines the flavor profile of this brew .  it pours a caramel-y orange-brown hue , somewhat drab , capped with soapy bubbles .  mouthfeel is full and round .

thick and black as it pours , thin chocolate-brown head aroma : this smells awesome ! i get heavy chocolate smells with some fruity hints to it , maybe black cherry . a little underwhelming for how it smelled overall : a great beer . great aroma to this one tho . definitely leine 's best brew !  11.2oz black wax dipped capped bottle . the pour yields an opaque black body with a small head of coffee colored bubbles . the head quickly becomes no more than a crown , leaving behind very little as far as lacing goes .  m : exceptionally not that big while being silky smooth . too sweet imo , but still the individual flavors of the beer were pretty good and the mouthfeel were simply phenomenal .

very inviting . t - resiny , piney hop bitterness up front that lingers till the crisp , biscuity malt finish .  a - a murky copper , not much head . reduces to ring fast , big bubble lace , not much of it .  the mouthfeel are carbonation is excellent so this makes the drinkability high .

aroma is rich and exuberantly heavy -- from five feet away , i can smell bubble gum , banana , clove , cracker malt , more banana , pepper ; and -- oddly enough ! fascinating and delectable aroma . the flavor profile is not quite as complex as the aroma , as the obvious alcohol presence tends to dominate some of the more subtle esters . still quite tasty . mouthfeel was surprisingly crisp for an 11 % beer : served a bit colder , one might call this `` refreshing .  the beer poured a nice reddish amber color into the glass with a huge frothy head . i could also see a large amount of sediment floating around . i do n't mind some sediment , in fact it 's good for you healthwise , but it detracts from the appearance .  i really enjoyed the balance of flavors and the wonderful mouthfeel .

smells great ! pumpkin hits you first along with bread and spices . very good but a little disappointed from all the talk about it .  southern tier cherry saison is a pretty clear , sparkling and golden with a bubbly white head that fades to a bubbly white film .  mouthfeel and drinkability are both top-notch . smooth , silken texture that sticks around just long enough to show off a pleasantly sweet aftertaste .

aroma : strong floral hop aroma , which tends to have a citrusness to it as well . wonderful to the nose . pleasing taste , due to its balanced use of hops and grains .  a- pours a light yellow , straw color . not much of a head even after an aggresive pour . m- what a great feel for a pilsner , extremly smooth , light body , med-high carbonation .  the feel in the mouth was outstanding and was that of milk or cream .

aromas are excellent . yeasty , spicy , lemon citrus like , and with a bit of sour funk .  pours black as coal , no light penetration at all . small head dissipates quickly and with a bit of fizzing sound .  very slight carbonation .

smell of faint citrus and hops is noticed , but i struggled to detect them .  i was n't in the mood for a belgian , but i am glad i had it .. a : nice golden color , but a bit hazy .  first sip smooth silky texture and average body with fine fizzy carbonation . easy drinker that has a very nice feel to it .

smell is a little weak . there is a bit of a wheat base and a european hop tinge .  served in a flute , the beer pours a hazy dark gold color with about an inch carbonated white head that fizzled away quickly .  huge thick luscious body .

amazing . t - malty profile that is very sweet , but not overbearingly so .  13 degrees pours a typical hefeweizen appearance with a cloudy yellow-gold body and bright white head .  the body is just right , medium and silky , silky smooth .

excellent . o - very nice and not very sour if that sort of thing deters you .  appearance : pours a delicately hazed , light golden-orange body with a smallish , brief , white head .  the mouth-feel was great , champagne liveliness that excited my tongue . i wont have this too often unless i am teaching a friend about trappist beer or have a specific craving upon seeing the bottle .

to quote from the label : `` doggie claws has a light copper color and an intense herbal hop character . this is a truly hoppy beer ; the aroma literally fills the room and my fingers feel sticky from handling the bottle and glass . it 's incredibly hoppy , though , and delightful for that .  l - somewhat hazy deep amber color with a beige head that thinned out completely after a few minutes .  big powerful mouthfeel with a puckering of the tongue due to the hops .
very complex scent to this one .  no residual head . corn ? drinkability- overall was a really nice refreshing beer for something light .  o : very good eye appeal and remarkable mouthfeel .

outstanding . taste is just like the smell , only more intense .  the beer poured a fairly clear light brown/amber color with a -finger of off-white head that dissipates fairly quick and leaves only minimal lacing .  mouthfeel is , on the contrary , excellent . extremely creamy and smooth , with good carbonation .

a- the beer was served with a foamy white head about 2 fingers and had a cloudy but welcoming color s- i thought the beer smelled awesome with noticable citrus notes and a slight yeasty smell present in most witbiers t- the citrus and corriander did come through in the taste but i was distracted by the tartness of the yeast m- it almost had a chalky feel but paired well with food .  appearance : pours a dark orange color with very little head . whatever head is there , does n't last long .  ultra creamy mouth feel , smooth .

the nose is a magnificent mix of banana , yeast , wheat and light malt . simply an amazing in your face brilliance . this is what all weis beers should smell like . the taste was light bodied and smooth yet full of flavor . simply a perfect blend of wheat and malt with the banana esthery wheat . overall , a great , classic beer .  pours a deep , reddish brown . as with other of their beers , not much head to speak of . lacing nill as well .  m : fantastic amount of carbonation .
s - perhaps one of the most amazing smelling beers i 've had .  standard cloudy color , but not standard on the nose .  m : incredibly smooth .

strong aroma of fresh fruits , most notably mandarin oranges with a hint of candy . this is followed by a slightly boozy , earthy bitterness with hints of burnt sugar . also , not as much hop flavor as i was expecting , especially after the smell , just bitterness .  looks the color of tea with a short quickly fading beige head and almost no lace to speak of .  huge full body with medium carbonation ; very creamy and slick mouthfeel that goes down fairly smooth . a bit of alcohol noticed in the back of the tongue , with a decent sized warming on the finish .

not overpowering and very very pleasant . if an air freshener had this scent i 'd buy it forever . t/m - like any good ipa , it 's a wonderful kick to the mouth .  a- pours a dark brown with a garnet tinge . no head because the carbonation is rather low but it completely works .  m-medium carbonation , nice creamy finish , just perfect !

oh boy . ukrainian beer . rather strong , too . as soon as i poured it , my poor nostrils were flooded by this metallic , rangy , adjunct-laden odour . this beer is drinkable if you can get past the odour . the bottle , however , is rather handsome , and is welcome in my collection .  pours a oily peach tea with a pinky of white head . drinks fine , a very confused belgian golden imo . & probably as cheap or cheaper here as it would be in that heavily taxed country .  ( m ) - smooth as silk . spot on carbonation level .

the nose is a wonderful balance of strong clove and wheat aromas . spicy with some banana and honey in the back . wow ! the taste starts off malty but then quickly changes to some clove , some bite from the carbonation , then a biscuity finish with some suggestion of bitter hop .  poured a nice brown body but with very little head .  it is thick with a slight creamy feel to it . interestingly , the 7.2 % abv is hardly noticeable alongside the bold flavors this beer embodies .

the smell is fantastic with a mix of coffee and chocolate flavors that are very strong ... reminds me of a chocolate covered espresso bean .  pours a cloudy , muddy , brown , with plenty of particulate .  it has a fabulous creamy mouthfeel .

on draft at brewery , consumed 01/21/08 . no aroma from the taster glass .  appearance is nice , very dark amber color , almost black . head retention is poor , almost non-existent , a little dissapointing smell is not what i was expecting , surpisingly subtle , with a nice malty sweetness taste comes as a wave , roastiness , coffee like , followed by mellow sweet malt , bitterness like dark chocolate lingers in the mouth , pleasant after taste wonderfully full mouthfeel , thick , fits the beer 's complex flavor the alcohol is apparent , but not overpowering , easy to sip , not exactly quaffable , but pleasant  mouthfeel is just about perfect for an ipa .

it basically smells like your garden variety shit beer , vegetal and with hints of grain adjuncts .  the colour is dark , dark brown-red . the head disappears quickly with a fizzing sound , leaving just a thing beige ring .  it has a really creamy mouthfeel as well .

smell is wonderful . reminds me of alesmith ipa and deschutes hop trip . taste , as i 've found it to often be with wet hop ipas , is a bit of a letdown after the perfect aroma . still pretty good , with a tart grapefruit quality and notes of orange and pineapple .  appearance : murky medium-brown . thin beige head that dissipated quickly .  m = heavy body , exceptionally good mouthcoating , luxurious creamy feel , slight heat from the alcohol , but no medicinal alcohol tastes .

probably the best ipa i 've ever smelled . intense floral hops , citrus and pine needles . well balanced . hops are prevelant but not bitter . probably my new favorite ipa .  poured from bottle to snifter : a : poured a thich pitch black with a minimal head with turned into a thing collar in no time most likely from the high abv eating it up .  it feels really silky on the tongue , almost like chocolate milk , but the taste was surprisingly bitter .

good stuff in the smell - fudge , chocolate syrup , and roasted coffee .  the beer poured into the chalice a very slightly hazy medium amber brown with an off-white head that fell very quickly and retreated to the edges of the surface and dissappeared without a trace on the glass .  the mouthfeel , i am guessing due to the aging , is nearly perfect . just a hint of spiciness on the palate leaves this fairly dry and wonderfully smooth .
the smell was just awesome , sugary caramel sweetness .  poured a golden copper with seemingly little head .  the fruity flavors go nicely with the crisp mouthfeel , perfect for the style .

s - big coffee smell like just opening up a bag of coffee beans , just awesome . t - a ton of coffee hits me right away , slight sweetness and bitterness that you would expect , good carbonation , pretty much tastes like carbonated iced coffee .  a - deep , dark molasses in color with a struggling light tan head that gave way to a thin film and a small ring around the glass . not much lacing at all .  this brew is full bodied and creamy smooth .

the aroma was pretty boring , but there 's a nice malt flavor in there with a hoppy spicy bite .  appearance : a deep golden body , with a very active inch of head that has poor retention and does n't last .  mouthfeel is thick and rich with a low/moderate carbonation that allows everything here to sit , settle , and linger .

poures a deep deep dark brown with some ruby hue thruout when help up to the light a large fluffy light brown head sits atop leaving a nice ring of lace as it setteled slowly.fruity as all get out in the nose wow juicy fruit dominates with some caramel thrown in everything takes a backseat to the fruitiness here and i love it.man i really wanted that same fruitiness if not at least some of it to carry over into the flavor but sadly it really didnt its dryer porter with some notes of molasses and unsweetened chocolate but the main show is dry earthy finish like a unroasted nut almost.what a start to this porter but an unremarkable finish but it is still got nice flavors dont get me wrong i really enjoyed but man those aromas were killer .  alpine pure hoppiness pours somewhere between tangerine and orange , with just a little bit of haze to it . there 's about a finger of white foam serving as a head . head retention is not bad , but lacing is fairly spotty .  creamy and thick , one could even say there 's a slight syrupy quality to it , but that is to be expected to an extent from this style . still , an outstanding beer and a great intro to duck rabbit for me .

s-huge blast of a complex swirl of aromas . dominated by a large dose of caramel malts , toffee and turbinado . deep lingering flavours and a nice astringent finish . d-as good as advertised . this is a bba malt lovers dream . nicely done , but i think the sweetness and abv would slow me down in the end .  it has a dark reddish/brown color covered with a thin cap of tiny bubbles .  m - this one feels zingy and electric on the tongue , and the hoppy aftertaste is really nice . wow ! d - this could become a summer staple in my beer fridge .

my first time that i can remember with expedition stout , but wow . this is an incredibly complex and drinkable imperial stout . i drank this outside in the 45 cold paired with a tatuaje black petite lancero , so the nose was somewhat frail . this is a beautifully thick beer , with a ton of carbonation , which really brings the flavors out . so very complex , with that inimitable bell 's malt flavor .  appearance -- poured light gold with a creamy two and a half finger head .  mouthfeel : terrific . full bodied , smooth , and creamy .

aroma was pretty bad , like an old musty bathroom .  pours a rich , deep mahogany with barely half a finger of head , no lacing and only moderate retention .  perfect as far as i 'm concerned for an imperial stout .

very complex odor . t= just as complex as the odor . deliciously rugged . d= pretty good .  12oz capped bottle wooo wee the samuel adams weizenbock looks like some thin maple syrup with a big , tight , monster of a tan head . some spotty lacing .  thick mouthfeel ... which i really like in a stout .

s : a beautiful , rich oaty aroma from the malts at the forefront , partnered with some bitter chocolate and roastiness . o : a really good oatmeal stout and arguably better , though i handicap it on a personal level due to the fact that i love a rich , oaty flavor in my oatmeal stouts and i found that to be less emphasized in this beer than i would have liked .  literally large , floating , totally unappatizing chunks of yeast ( hopefully ) swirl around in this beer . other than that , it 's a hazy reddish brown color with a small , bubbly white head with nice retention .  m - full bodied and well balanced . just wow .

s : wonderful citrus and farmhouse funk . definite brett too . perfect for style . i wish it more closely followed the aroma , but still very good . m : smooth and creamy feel .  pours a transparent orange-red-brown ... color of a pumpkin i guess you might say . tiny head which settles to a ring . no lacing .  mouthfeel this one is a hair above medium-bodied , its actually on the lighter side for the style , with fluffy cheek-puffing carbonation and a light alcohol warming . but man oh man this beer defines a velvety mouthfeel .

the aroma is so splendid and heavy .  poured into a tulip glass a murky cider color , extremely hazy , with a light tan head that collars around the glass .  m : one of the more viscous porters , has a feel more in line with a stout . extremely smooth and creamy , finish is perfect bitter sweet ( and the hop presence does n't wear out it 's welcome ) .

intense nose . vinegar notes , but not as overpowering as some others of the style . nice .  this beer pours a dark brown color .  very smooth mouthfeel , almost perfect . went down smooth , but not really a sessionable beer , can drink more though .

the aroma was very interesting . i picked up a significant sour scent that was similar to apple cider . very unique , but very good . the taste mimicked the aroma , including the sour , apple cider combo .  appearance the sample glasses did n't allow for a whole lot of cascading , frothy head . this one is a very cloudy burnt orange color .  the mouthfeel here is awesome . medium-full body , very chewy , even tannic almost .

smells wonderful . t : bitter , malty and chocolaty with toffee and caramel flavors as well .  the beer poured a pale yellow with a minimal white head .  a silky smoothness and a sugary thickness finished up a fantastic drinking experience .

aroma is of sweet caramel malt and some raisins and plums .  a - nice brown soapy head . looks like ginger bread . brew is jet black .  this is among the thickest , chewiest , densest body i have experienced .

appearance : pours black as dolls eyes with a 2 finger off light brown crown that shows moderate retention and little lace . attractive ! smell : wow this is one fruity porter ! seemless . taste : nice roast notes and dry dark chocolate notes from the malt . very bitter ( coffee like bitter ) finish mixed with a whisper of alcohol . highly enjoyable !  the good news is that this oktoberfest is a very fine lager . all other properties were appropriate such as the abundant carbonation and the copper-amber color - though the body could have shown greater clarity .  coated everywhere , and felt so smooth .

aroma is amazing , rich sweet dark fruits , caramel , toffee . it smells like a barleywine .  hazy orange hued fiery appearance . slim coating of off white head leaves spotty lace .  m : huge body for the abv with very light and fine carbonation giving it a very soft , silky texture . quite dry with a lingering bitterness .

tulip tasted nov. 12th 2011 ( from notes ) a - very nice semi-translucent copper/brown , barely any white as snow head and minimal lacing s - wow , the smell is incredible , resin , fresh citrus fruits , fresh flowers , crisp water , fresh malt , the grapefruit is beautiful and a slightly sweet smelling yeast t - very fresh ! nice refreshing crisp water , very nice hops , citrus , grapefruit , nice malts , weed , pineapple , slightly toasty , flowers , earth and wood m - medium minus body , well balanced , even complexity , low acidity and medium finish d - best part about this beer is its simplicity . this is a beer for any craft lover . just well put together , refreshing and just plain well done final thought - if you like hops , fresh tasting beers , deschutes and only paying $ 5 a pop , get this ale !  a - poured a practically black liquid with a slim tan head that retained as a thin patch , then finally disappeared leaving no lacing at all .  the mouthfeel is fantastic , a smooth , airy , coating ; just perfect .

s : wow , what i consider to be a perfect witbier smell . beautiful refreshing lemony yeast . almost like lemon meringue pie . strange yeast , sour . d : sadly the taste does n't live up to the look and smell , but it 's ok .  i poured into my glass to a small light tan head . it is a ruddy amber color .  m : very creamy and smooth . fairly thick in the mouth . quite strong .

smell - hello bourbon , i was told this spent 2 years in the barrel , and it certainly smells that way . wonderful notes of bourbon , vanilla , and dark ripe fruits . taste - fantastic brew , the bourbon is very present upfront along with dark sweet rasins , dates and figs and great caramely malts . very sweet . mouthfeel - smooth and velvety with little or almost no carbonation .  pours a bright orange color with golden edges , small white head that fell quickly , no lacing .  mouthfeel is right where a saison of high quality should be . high carbonation , incredible dryness , and a nice drinkable viscosity .

caramel and brown sugar baked goods nose . sensory pleasure . bitter and somewhat medeival in its aged hoppiness .  the beer set in front of me was a transparent rust brown color with absolutely no sign of head . ruby and orange elements are emitted when held to the light ; this beer is certainly not unattractive .  mouthfeel : full creamy body .

caramel and sweet malts balance the nose quite nicely . t : taste is pretty average for the style .  but about the highland : poured into a samuel adams boston lager glass . pale peach appearance , hazy at the top and middle of the glass , clear and yellow toward the bottom .  m-just perfect carbonation .

very strong too . awesome . t -- lots of bready maltiness to compliment the huge hop bomb that is in front of me .  can acquired in a trade with mnfinnkidd poured a deep , translucent rust with orangey-amber highlights and a small , thin , bubbly , tan head .  m : the flavor is great but the mouthfeel is the best aspect .

there is a wonderfully elixer-like nature to this great aroma . i asked others to smell it and they were universally impressed . the flavor is great but a bit over the top on richness and fullness . but this is a very rich beer , rather like the too-rich nature of a great piece of pecan pie .  a : pours a hazy brownish-gold with a finger of white head that recedes into a thin layer with little lacing .  amazingly chewy .

aroma is nice and hoppy , with hints of citrus and grass . smell finishes with a little yeasty nose and has a solid feel to it , hinting to a malty body .  this beer pours a clear amber color with a trace of head that does n't lace or retain well .  the carbonation is perfect ... d : a really good beer .

pulled this one out of the cellar , brewed in september of 2008 , poured into delirium snifter a : pours like used motor oil , one of the thickest imperial stouts out there ( behind hunahpus/mashal zhukov ) , with a nice dark head , decent retention and lacing s : huge notes of dark chocolate and oats up front , compared to the fresh version , this is much more mellow and chocolatey ... personally i think this smells better now than before t : deep rich roasted notes up front with tons of chocolate , a little licorice and molasses , some coffee , everything is big and bold but nicely in balance . mf : thick , velvety viscous , low carbonation d : i have always loved expo , but have never tried it at this age .  head is white , light and fluffy , 2 fingers deep off a rigerous pour . hazy amber in color .  m- thick , chewy , syrupy , pillowy , warming .

alluring and sophisticated aromatics tempt you to drink ... t- ... . but then the flavor falls short , embarrassed by the lovely aromas . thin yeasty dough , some tropical fruit .  minimal head ( at least on this pour ) with little or no lacing activity .  the mouthfeel is marvelous , again especially for a bottle . full body , silky texture , very low carbonation .
very nice ; i forgive it for being in such a hurry to get out of the bottle .  the beer is black . a cream colored foamy head , no lacing .  f - beautifully silky-smooth . perfect carbonation level .

nice retention and spotty lacing left behind . the aroma is absolutely intoxicating , with an acetic tartness of apple flesh that just started to brown before being dipped in caramel . supporting notes include leather , a hint of pepper , and some barnyard funk . delicious , delicate notes of toffee and caramel malt join with a drying tartness on the finish that leans toward apple cider and various other dark fruits ( e.g. , raisin , fig , and plum ) . i wish the sour flavor matched that of the aroma , as it 's a bit subdued in comparison .  reserved , pored a clear copper color with light beige head that dissipated rapidly . the lack of head and lacing is not due to thin viscosity .  mouthfeel : light-bodied but excellently carbonated ; frothy and velvety smooth . drinkability : flavorful and robust but still extremely refreshing .

s- deep dark roasted coffee/toffee . t- this was awesome . almost tasted like a mocha porter .  cap has a brown reside/rust under it . appearance : bright clear yellow that goes hazy as my glass widens at the hop . a careful pour leaves behind dark sediment . surprisingly smooth texture given all the wheat . this is just a nice weizen , id say krystal weizen more than hefe , but that might be due to a longish cellar in my fridge to let the yeast settle out .  thick , chewy and velvety smooth .

this is possibly the best smelling beer i have ever laid nostrils on . rum soaked chocolates with burnt caramel and toffee and a really sweet candy spice that just tips it off the scales !  the head is bright white and about an eighth of an inch tall but fades fast .  malty , hoppy , sweet are all combined in the taste . immense taste and great balance . i keep commenting on the balance but that 's the most remarkable characteristic of this beer . it 's not at all well mannered like a pliny the elder but it succeeds as a full on palate assault .

smells somewhat like smoked ham , delicious ! i get the impression of smoke when i exhale , i can only imagine what my breath smells like ! very little in the way of mouthfeel , leaves a residual smokiness , but very ethereal . probably a good thing - you get a nice dose of smoke and then it fades away .  this beer pours a cloudy orange color with a thin head but it 's retention was great .  the mouthfeel is a little shy of medium-bodied , and has the perfect amount of carbonation and feels just right .

not the most subtle or complex beer , but smells delicious nonetheless .  poured a very dark brown , like a good coffee . but no head at all .  feels great . milky , sweet , toffee malt , light coffee , light chocolate milk . carried very nicely by the density . its all there . a meal and dessert at the same time . fantastic .

the smell is the best part and outstanding in its own right . the aroma is intense brown sugars , caramel , liqueur , thick syrupy malts , and heavy fruits of the fig and raisin variety . this is a thick and full bodied beer with quite a throaty aftertaste that will requires some neutralization before trying anything else . good luck with this one . i do n't think i can finish it .  transparent amber color , only the faintest head . the doppelback flavor is lost in the smoke and the appearance was average .  awesome texture , just a very slight tingle from carbonation , great body , great feel .

quite lovely . you can tell that this beer spent quite some time sitting in those bourbon barrels picking up as much flavor as possible as well as some of that lovely lactobacillus-like character that comes from extensive and careful barrel-aging .  pours with a very small tan head , with no retention or lacing . nice dark red in color .  as expected for a cream ale the mouthfeel is like silk . packs a punch but not at all rough on the edges , smooth as silk .

the aroma is citrus hops , floral hops , spicy hops , sweet hops , grassy hops , hop hops , and just a hint of caramel malt . this is a very nice dry hopped ale . overall an excellent ipa . hoppy , smooth , an alcohol punch , and pleasant in the mouth . but hey , that 's being very picky .  a : pours a hazy straw yellow into an american shaker pint with a little white head that dissipates rather quickly and leaves some lacing .  excellent for the style .

smells good . smells like wheat , i like wheat , i want to drink it .  a- very little carbonation , light brown color with a touch of gold , cloudy appearance s- insane hop smell , really could n't get any other smell from my glass , slight malt after finish .  mouthfeel was thick and creamy like it should be .
smells like bacon on a campfire .  large bubbled head ; little lace .  mouthfeel- super velvety smooth ! drinkability- the mouthfeel alone make this brew worth trying .

wow , aroma is just like creme brulee .  presentation : it was poured from a brown 12oz bottle into a pint glass . on top of the body is a small white creamy head . the head fades fast and makes only a very little slick lacing .  mouthfeel is wonderful ... velvety smooth , perfectly rounded , syrup-like without overbearing stickiness or thickness ... just perfect .

leaves a weak lacing . aroma : holy wow . light , spritzy hops . tangerines . pineapples . wondrous in its fruity expansiveness ... most of which im sure comes from hops , but lacks any astringent botanical character . expertly balanced.. like the 5-course bubblegum in the willy wonka movie . overall : really , one of my favorite new discoveries of summer 2005. shame i didnt have the chance to get more of this ( hard to find locally ) .  a- a bit lacking appearance wise . not much head to speak of , and what there is dissolves into a film . no real lacing either . nice dark amber color though .  founders black biscuit does n't have the intense flavors to blow you away but it 's incredible balance and perfect mouthfeel make it an extremely impressive offering .

smell a whole lot is going on this the nose : some very fresh , mildly roasted malt smells , which i enjoy so much , abound as well as super citrusy , orangy smells .  g : pint glass a : clear dark orange body with one inch white head which had pour retention . leaves very little lacing s : the pumpkin is very strong with spices of nutmeg and cloves faintly in the background .  m : fantastic blend of carbonation , sweet malt , and bitterness . goes down very easy .

wow , thats a shit load of cinnamon and nutmeg in the nose along with pumpkin spice , brown sugar , and booze . i currently have a homebrew pumpkin that smells nearly exact to this ! this , along with good gourd from ccb are probably the best pumpkin beers i have had to date .  appearance : unfortunately not too much head on it , and the lacing does n't seem to be sticking very well .  mouthfeel is perfect for a dipa -- not too syrupy/thick , not too thin .

wow , does it smell good . like nutty caramel that has been chewed up by an elephant and spit in yo face .  appearance : bright , semi-transparent blood orange color with minimal head receding to a ring .  mouthfeel : well carbonated , creamy and very , very smooth . this brew is extremely smooth and drinkable .
