deep , rich , milk chocolate hits my nose , with backup from dark roasted malt and hops . a slightly sour note is also present but strangely a perfect mesh with all the chocolate . overall , this beer is delicious , smells amazing , and is very well made but seems to fall just short of true stout greatness for me . still , definitely worth a $ 3.99 flier every once in a while in the winter .  33cl bottle from florian 's in auburn . murky yellow body with a half an inch of off-white head .  incredible balance , not quite the devil its name makes it out to be . light to medium in body with lots of carbonation and incredible drinkability .

s - phenomenal yeasty aroma of banana and other fruits . a little spice as well .  very similar to hacker-pschorr , which is a classic . not much lacing , great smell , of pears ( maybe ?  mouthfeel is rich and creamy . the aftertaste is extremely clean ; not sticky , dry or anything bad .

s : perfect . pine needles , citrus zest , green grass , maybe even some tame malt . t : initial hop bitterness , calmed by a smooth and mild malty goodness .  [ best served in a snifter ] poured a thick dark rich black with a very small ( less than 1 finger ) dark medium brown creamy head that was fully diminishing and had fair lacing .  wonderful smooth texture .

great aroma of orange , spicy coriander , malt , caramel , and a nice addition of star anise . very intense sweet orange aroma . some earthy and yeast aromas as well . then more tropical fruits like mango , and pineapple ; also some apple , tangerine , and hints of dried coconut ( crazy , i know ) . well carbonated and fairly clean finish , a few lingering notes of tropical fruits . fairly easy to drink but the orange peel and star anise do become a bit too much after half a bottle , thats pretty much my only complaint .  pours a thick black oily body with a tan head . not much in carbonation , not much in lacing and little retention .  top-notch mouthfeel , creamy frothy and just a hint of rawness .

very enjoyable aroma . t : not as subtle as the nose .  poured into a weizen glass . 3.0 a : cloudy darkish yellow color . two fingers of frothy white head .  m- the mouthfeel on this beer is exceptional . it is smooth and heavy and clean from beginning to end .

very robust and uncommonly hoppy . it has that signature sn cascades hop aroma . it tastes sharp and bitter , yet balanced enough to drink easily .  a - head dissipates quickly into nothing , not even a ring . ( one other person on the front page of these reviews reported this w/ this particular vintage - you 're not the only one ! ) no lacing . s - smells just like cherry pie filling upfront , but more sour . great summer beer ! i 'd definitely try other years of this beer as well as other beers from this brewery - definitely got me curious .  m- full , smooth , creamy , oily , thick ... .pretty much exactly what i want in a stout .

s : very fruity aromas . the orange essence dominates this beer and really sets the tone the entire time you drink it t : the citrus is by far the leading character with this one .  growler date is 04/30/2010 appearance : pours into pint glass a copper/amber color , not translucent somewhat hazy , with a thin white head , thinck creamy lacing .  the mouthfeel is very thick .

s - sweet milk chocolate , bourbon , gingerbread , vanilla , cinnamon , expresso , and caramel . i 'm mostly picking up the sweetness of this one , and really not much of the bourbon or oak . m - medium bodied , perhaps a bit too thin for me , but still a rich beer nonetheless . carbonation is slightly tingles and the finish is dry , and leaves you wanting to refresh your palate with more blackout goodness . d - the 2008 vintage is drinking nicely at the moment .  a : reddish- copper with a red glow through the brilliant clarity . poured a thin off-white head that dissipated quickly .  quite a full and velvety body . it had excellent body too , and the alcohol was fairly well hidden .

chocolate malt , too , as the initial notes fade off . the bourbon twang is somewhat overpowering . mouthfeel : body is lightened , i think , by the etoh level , but this is still a thick-bodied stout . very flavorful , but so rich that it demands thoughtful sipping . not particularly easy .  the grnbacher weissbier is a well brewed german wheat . this beer shows a thick , foamy head with a medium carbonation . the murky , yellow orange hue indicates enough yeast in the bottle .  mouthfeel is spot on : wonderful carbonation combined with a luscious consistency .

the smell of this beer is nothing short of amazing . taste is fantastic , color is a rusty , bubbly and quite dazzling array of sheer beer goodness ( or perhaps godliness ) .  a - pitch black color with almost no head . very little creamy tan head , that disappears almost instantly with almost no lacing .  m - outstanding , big chewy dipa .

i love the smell . there is an enticing aroma i ca n't place . just overall rather edgy . it has some sweet caramel character but is way over-played by by the alcohol .  12oz bottle to a kronenbourg tulip bottled on 9-3-08 a : a steady pour produced a 2-finger eggshell white head . color was yellow to straw colored with haze as expected of a witbier .  the mouthfeel is particularly noteworthy , and every swig leaves a viscous coating of robust barley goodness on the tongue .

maybe some of the best retention i 've seen s : surprisingly more fruity then i expected . very inviting t : starts with a sweetness , which i 'll guess is more candied malts .  a - very dark brown , almost black . not much head or lacing going on s - strong malt smell with a oak smell t - caramelized malt are most dominant $ definate wood taste also that was very pleasant m - medium bodied .  average belgian pa that is saved by the incredible body that seems to be characteristic of italian craft beer .

i smell citrus , bread , pine , and a nice showing of hops for a pale - very nice . the taste is phenominal and follows the nose nicely - sweet and citrusy up front with a bitter and malty bite at the end - delicious .  fairly clear body tinted by an almost artificial red color . no head to speak of .  a solid milk stout , with good aroma and flavor , and impeccable mouthfeel .

aroma is sweetish toasted malt , bread , wheat , some yeast .  p : deep mahogany pour with a 1 inch loose tan head that quickly levels to a scant cover . d : not a session beer but one to have when available and to offer to friends who think that a big beer is 16 % and black and sludgy .  m - the best part about this beer is the mouth feel . it 's got the perfect mouth feel with a nice look and delicious taste to back it up .

very nice and aromatic . t : slightly sweet at first with lots of orange and grapefruit flavors following . the flavor does n't quite live up to the aroma , but is overall one of the better ipas out there .  it reminds me of the warrant video `` cherry pie '' for some odd reason .  into the mouth it goes , the smoothness and creaminess of the beer is heavenly and excites me for the whatever flavor could be coming my way . pine , sticky sap , and caramel are among the flavors that rule it all .

smell did n't hit my nose right , i got an antihistamine spray impression .  bottle into a pint glass : appearance and smell- poured a nice bright orange with a nice thick head which dissipated completely after a bit and left just a hint of lacing .  very creamy and smooth . the carbonation is quite low which gives this even more appeal . perfect . d- not the most complex beer , but still something i look forward to drinking ( and collecting ) each year .

big time hop aroma , as was expected , grapefruit is the main player here followed up by subtle pineyness . overall a great imperial ipa , the great balance between the malts and the hops make it enjoyable for all , even if your not a `` hop-head '' .  the head is ta in color but has no retention or stickage .  mouthfeel - quite thick and chewy , you will know that much from the pour . perfectly smooth on the palate . slightly below average carbonation .
it has that classic cantillon aroma which pleases me so .  '' deep , dark brown ( but not really black ) .  the flawless velvety , silky medium body melts the flavours together perfectly .

aroma is fantastic , showcasing tropical rays of amarillo sunshine . think mango juice or even tropical bubble yum . bitterness is n't really that harsh at all , and pretty approachable . for an 8 % dipa , it drinks incredibly smooth , and is refreshing .  pours a ruddy black amber with a smallish tan head that melts to very fine lacing .  the mouthfeel is indeed creamy and the beer is quite drinkable . edit , re-review : had a bottle at the milwaukee airport 10/09 , and i was struck by just how creamy and perfect the mouthfeel on this brew is .

s- sweet bourbon and chocolate , love the smell cant get much coffee but very enticing . t- i can certainly taste the coffee , the beer is more bitter than i expected from the smell , i get the bitter coffee up front , maple bourbon chocolate in the middle back to a coffee finish .  '' the cherry saison is a fine brew with nice depth of flavors but really light in the cherry fruit essence . unlike a sam adams cherry wheat ( ex . ) , the fruit infusion is almost undetectable . a = medium amber with a very light redish tinge .  the mouthfeel , however , is fantastic . this is an exceptionally smooth and creamy feeling beer , and it really improves the drinkability considerably .

maybe a bit too much but still very good . d : the carbonation may get to you after a while . abv is good .  poured into tulip . batch 243 bottled 7/5/09 a : rusty reddish body , minimal head barely covers the surface then dissipates .  rich , thick and full bodied , with flavors of brown sugar , belgian yeast , chocolate , booze and raisins .

the smell is intensely bourbon , with plenty of malt , fruit , and a hint of vanilla . the bourbon is a great , warming smell . awesome . when i put it to my lips , call me nuts , but i think i picked up on some bourbon ! at the end of the day , this is surely a damn good beer , but it 's too one note with the bourbon for me to give it a great mark . but i do think that with some vanilla or coffee to cut the bourbon , this would be truly spectacular . i guess i need to obsess on the vanilla or coffee versions of bcbs .  a : a cloudy brass body with a small cream colored head which falls quickly . a few pillars of carbonation .  taste & mouthfeel : insane smoothness rolls of the tongue like a million dollar beer if i ever saw one .

im enticed by the wholesome sweetness of the smell . there are definitely gingersnaps and molasses cookies here , heavy on the ginger , with a peach , honey pastries ( baklava ? ) and caramel sweetness beneath . green grapes too ? it goes on and on . truly a pleasure . the flavor starts similar to the smell but is oriented more around the green grape and caramel along with a big sticky barley . again , im impressed by how clean this feels . nice .  a : poured a syrupy dark black color . not really much head at all . no lacing down the glass .  mouthfeel is fantastic , thick and smooth , soooo smooth .

aroma is full of rich , complex malt . very complex and just big ! good toasty malt flavor with high alcohol providing most of the balance . a wonderfull beer , with excellent malt character .  absolutely no cap , ring , or lacing of any kind- appears purely still . gorgeous color , but i 'd like at least a bit more visible carbonation .  mouthfeel is amazing , thick , viscous , almost like a milkshake . best mouthfeel i have had in a beer .

this might sound crazy , but the beer smells like an armpit . but collectively the beer smells like an armpit and it 's just not appealing at all . the drinkability is alright because the taste is good , but the aroma just ruined this for me .  a : pours a light golden-straw color ; small head that dissipates quickly , not much lacing s : sweet sticky tropical fruits and belgian yeast .  t/f : feel was wonderfully rich and creamy smooth , without being heavy , thick , or filling .

s- thin smelling malts and i can detect some hops in the distance .  ruby , amber in color with a 1/2 '' light tan head that gives up the ghost way to quick . spotty lacing .  excellent body ; truly perfect for the style .

semi-sweet , light chocolate aroma . tart fruity esters : grape , sour cherry , green apple . notes of meaty raisin and plum . tangy molasses adding a touch of spice . the sour fruit quality that was foreshadowed in the nose is almost absent in the taste .  dark opaque brown color . no head to speak of .  the body to this brew is full and creamy which really gives it a nice mouthfeel for a barleywine .

s -- this is exactly what i would like from a winter beer . i immediately thought of christmas upon smelling this . a sort of piney smell , mixed with a sweetness and a bit of spice .  light orange color .  between medium and full bodied , the elements are peppery and memorable , and an underlying creaminess impresses like satin on the tongue .

big coffee aromas .  dark brown and opaque with minimal carbonation .  a - a wonderful pale apricot topped with a pure white lace that fades quickly into the glass s - light and grassy , with a hint of the alcohol to come t - potent bitterness at the front mellows to sweet dried fruit flavors , with a spicy bitterness at the finish m - perfect ? in mouth feel is exactly balanced against the bitterness , and then coats the mouth to balance the lingering bitter bite d - dangerously so .

m/d this drinks and feels like a lighter ipa with some really interesting smells to it .  poured from a bottle to a pint glass appearance : deep red-mahogany with particulates floating ( the reason for the low score ) . loud , crackling , thick tan head .  m - perfect . absolutely spot on with both body and carbonation .

s : beautiful smell of pumpkin pie ! brilliant beer .  a : this one pours black from the bottle into my pint glass with not much light breaking through . tan head is quick to settle and never developed much . d : this was a very drinkable beer and it got better as it warmed .  dangerously tasty with an amazing mouthfeel .

smelled just great t : slight sour in front , apple cidery in the middle , and bitterness/peppery at the finish . i felt was a little too bitter , but liked the tart dryness d : awesome . very drinkable .  pours a hazy light golden orange color with dark golden yellow edges and a one finger frothy white head that slowly settles into very thin ring .  m-on the low side of medium carb the beer is very full and creamy with no detectable oiliness . the texture is possibly the best i have had in an ipa , and although not bitter enough to satisfy true hop heads , the flavor is very interesting and pleasant , and the aroma complex .

s- hot , mild bourbon , oak , vanilla , and chocolate , overall very interesting with a lot to take in an assualt of complexity . t- not as impressive as the smell , still very fresh and fairly detectable abv , little hot for me at this point .  on-tap at sour fest a : the beer pours a hazy pinkish-orange color with almost no head .  very easy to drink with a soft silken mouthfeel .

yes it is a macro-brew , and yes it is distributed by coors , but honestly this beer is a very drinkable amber lager . malty smell , but nothing too strong or distinct . flavor is sweet , malty with a bit of hops .  pours a bright white , but short lived head .  absolutely perfect . d : thanks to jdv for this one .

the aroma , however , is fantastic . call me crazy , but i 'm getting hints of blueberry and citrus up the wahzoo .  poured a clear faded tangerine color . it was about 19 degrees out when i had this and it was still pleasant , would make a great heat beater in the summer . highly drinkable .  the texture rocks - silky and almost chewy .

a big basket of exotic fruits it is . dominant passion fruit aroma , background of grapefruit and hibiscus notes . its also a sweet treat , that the malt brings forth . a certain sourish note reminiscent of green apples . taste bittering hops and grape fruit , lots of it . still some of that floral and passion fruit but very toned down . in conclusion for a being the first beer ( 2nd batch ) to come out of this brewery i must say im impressed .  2007 vintage pours a thick deep black with a very thin tan head on top .  i truly enjoyed every sip and the palate cleansing carbonation made every bite like the first . the carbonation and strong complex flavors force you to slow down a little to appreciate this truly unique concoction .

aroma is incredible , i think . the taste i do not think compares to the aroma .  even with a pour straight down the middle , black tot is a beer completely lacking in head . the beer is basically black but nothing much to look at .  soft and creamy texture , medium body and almost no carbonation . really nailed this .

aroma right out of the bottle is just excellent . powerful fruity sweetness with background spices .  raftman pours with a generous tight eggshell-colored head , dissipating pretty quickly leaving little or no lacing behind .  - feels bloody velvet sick lovely .

smell this has a nice orange and pine hop aroma with a solid malt base . the malt base that i thought i smelled at the nose was completely awol . drinkability i sure liked smelling it , but i wont ever buy another bottle to drink .  a - poured out a clear , copper color with almost no head to speak of .  mouthfeel is smooth creamy heavy on the tongue a bit chewy nice , overall this is wonderful and ill never turn this down .
smells like tart , lemony funk .  a- an extremely murky dark amber with no head whatsoever . really not much to look at though .  mouthfeel is very pleasing , smooth and medium bodied .

s : strong tart/sour aroma with a hint of funk , dark raisins , figs , brown sugar . wonderful aroma . t : overwhelming tartness that seems to be closer to a gueuze than a flanders/flemish ale . it 's really too much for my palate , and seems a little one dimensional .  this pours a slightly hazer amber colour , with a thin white head , that diminishes into a resilient filmy coat .  m - full , rich , viscous , light carbonation , chocolate creamy finish .
very nice hoppy nose for a porter .  pours a clear orangey amber , nothing out of the ordinary on the head .  full , super creamy body .

aroma - bready grains , just a bare trace of citrus . too light , but gets a little better with warming . taste - much caramel character up front , roasted malts , yummy . turns citrusy as it gives way to the hops . drinkability - a fine all around ale , i could use another !  very light spots of lace on the glass . very full and smooth .  velvety smooth mouthfeel , actually .

the aroma was really pleasant . deep , roasted mocha coffee beans with chocolate notes , lightly bittersweet . the aroma is worth the experience . try this and enjoy the delicate aroma , but in my opinion this one needs some work before it can be considered a definitive and quality `` stout '' .  a - deep dark ruby color , minimal head , and some sediment floaties .  silky in the mouth .

22oz bottle poured into my half acre pint glass ... pours an incredibly thick and hazy pale orange with just a one finger light tan head that leaves a bit of lacing behind ... smells wonderfully of sweet and juicy tropical fruit , pineapple and mango come to mind . juicy , i know juicy is not a smell , but it just smells , well , juicy ... tastes as the smell led on , juicy and fruity , tropical and sweet up front . sticky and resinous finish , very good ... would love if this one was canned along side the regular daisy cutter ...  no head to show of and a light tan lacing .  mouthfeel was smooth and silky . very nice ale .

smell : rice , an off sweetness , artificial fruitiness , water , hops hard to find mouthfeel : carbonation medium , body light taste : rice , grain , water , very slight hop bitterness lingers with a watery flavor drinkability : easy to drink , but lacking in every other department born on date nov. 23 , 2005  hazy and kind of opaque golden brown with a small tan head .  mouthfeel - very nice feel , smooth and creamy with the perfect amount of carbonation . the bottle conditioning really left a nice feel .

aroma explodes from the glass : creme brulee ( duh ) , vanilla , semisweet chocolate , cocoa , and brown sugar . otherwise a very good beer .  this beer poors a dark brown with hints of red . virtually no head or residual ring or laceing to speak of .  fantastic mouthfeel helping to make this a truly drinkable brew .

very subdued aroma . nice yeasty , spicy aroma , i just need to bury my nose in the glass to find it .  appearance was nothing special . huge , rocky head , but quickly dissipated and was soon nowhere to be seen .  m : creamy with a very smooth carbonation , tiny bubbles . and what a beautiful body .

smell - anise mixed with alcohol . a good hint that this is n't an ordinary irs .  pour is a light orange/brown color with a nice medium sized head atop . there is some cloudiness towards the top of the pour .  palate : perfect , really .

a - dark copper with a thick white head and excessive lacing s - pine , grapefruit , apple , malt - smells tasty t - huge amounts of pine and grapefruit fighting for tastebud domination .  p : bright golden with a thin , dirty white head that settles to pools of bubbles and a patchy covering .  really good mouthfeel .

its really hard to pay attention to the color and look of the pour as the attention is wrenched to the aroma that greets you once the cap is pried off ... pine , oranges , grapefruit , an absolute cavalcade of hops ! how wonderful ! alas , i ride no horses so no wishes for me . a real pleaser .  the color on this one makes you think that its a hefeweissen but its not . its color is a straw yellow color with a slight haze to it . wonderful lacing .  mouthfeel is very smooth , with low to medium carbonation , and a full body .

quite pleasing . overall : the appearance and nose are fantastic .  2007 vintage appearance : pours into my new weyerbacher tulip a deep brown with the tiniest tan head on top . it falls to nothing but a thin collar immediately .  for all the previously mentioned bitter qualities , the mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth . perfectly carbonated .

above average head retention & lacing s : plummy & figgy notes merge with oakyness & a whisper of vanilla , the strength of this beer is the aroma , plus much peattyness t : follows the nose along with brown sugar & molasses , plus iron & leafy hops . finishes dry , smokey & fruitty with nice charred grain notes mf : fairly smooth , medium bodied , starts to become almost prickly as this warms , but also becomes a bit sticky nice drinkability , easily one of the best bottled beers i 've had out of britain in the last 12-18 months & a top flight example of this style on the upper edge of abv , yum  a-pours very dark brown , nearly black . there was no head to speak of .  definitely a sipper d/t high abv , bourbon taste and thickness . one of the best imperial stouts ever .

rich , smoky , chocolaty , coffee-ish aroma has just a touch of sweetness and is very appetizing .  but , as you nurse a glass of anchor steam , you 'll soon find it 's hidden complexities and it 's undeniable uniqueness . it pours a light color with little head with the accompanying smell is kind of underwhelming as well .  t & m- big lush mouth feel with a long drawn-out smoothness .

bomber picked up at the lcbo ; no date . fantastic aroma , plenty of pumpkin , spices and gingerbread . yep , it smells like pie . very smooth , and very drinkable despite the abv .  growler from hawthorne 's in pa. a yellow , slightly orange body , kind of hazy , a few bubbles on top . i am guessing the long journey is what caused the light carbonation so i ca n't really take away too much from it . overall a fantastic beer .  a thick , chewy body rounds out the mouthfeel , and the full malt profile hides the alcohol while accentuating the flavors making this beer strong , but very drinkable .

s - smokey and toasted aroma which made me want to eat it , easily one of the most impressive smells i 've ever encountered .  i still needed to try this beer since i heard it uses the most hops that stone has ever used per barrel . not 5 seconds after i pour the beer into a glass does my wife from across the kitchen ( who hates hops ) said she could smell the beer from there and not to bring the glass any closer .  a fantastically smooth and creamy mouthfeel that leaves you begging for another pint .

the nose is a bit disutbing at first as there is an odd scent going on . the taste erases the weird nose and slays it with a nice balance of some bitter , floral hops and nutty , sweet malt .  bell 's oberon ale is a clear , bright golden ale with a thin white head that fades to a film and leaves nice lacing .  mouthfeel is heavy as hell and thick , very chewy with minimal amount of carbonation , heavenly .

the aroma is absolutely incredible . the beer is surprisingly light on the tongue ( perhaps it is a bit cold ) , but begins to coat the mouth as it passes on through . the finish is quite complex and interesting , it is almost smoky , slightly astringent , but definitely long and satisfying . this is quite the sipping contemplative brew , though the flavor did not quite live up to the awesome aroma .  hazy , pale yellow-peachy hue . smallish white head that doesnt hold long , produces soapy residue . very drinkable !  m : superb in my opinion .

smell was very nondescript , with hints of sourness and water .  clarity is obscured somewhat by chill haze and perhaps a little sediment ( though i left the bulk of it in the bottom of the bottle in large pieces ) .  floral taste flows into a yeast-centric raisin and fig body with a clove punch and an incredibly round , estery mouthfeel that warms in the mouth as the malt matures . fruity , but in a fig sort of fruity way , with a round , peppery , malty , incredibly complex and balanced body that also possesses a certain nuttiness to it . very smooth .

third , the malt , which in combination smells absolutely fantastic . t : very rich and vinous , cherries and alcohol are at the forefront .  leaves a thick bubbled head of 3mm which disappears in no time . good continual carbonation . a very small amount of lace remains on the sides of the glass .  feels nice and chewy in the mouth and is quite drinkable despite the ever present tinge of alcohol .

i would say that enjoyed the citrus and corriander aromas and flavor nothing else really came through in this one . for once upon a time i drank this a celis grand cru ( when it was brewed in texas ) only for a few months way back when .  obviously black hole black . even very aggressively poured , there is no head whatsoever .  awesome mouthfeel !

caramel malts . not unpleasant but not much going on . taste had biscuity tones with a slight alcohol taste as common in scotch ales .  a - alright , looks like a cider . afterwards i get a burst of apricot .  mf- is creamy and lush , big and forward . very inviting dr- needs time to age , a year or 2 will open this big bold beer imensely.lots of potential .

the aroma is incredible , and it the strong point of this beer . very very good !  a-fairly clear light golden , one finger head with almost no lacing .  m - super creamy and full bodied almost like pudding , this is the highlight of this for me , one of the best mouthfeels of any beer i have had .

amazing fruit nose . taste : surprisingly simple after such a complex nose . initially , some ever-so-slightly bready malts and some black pepper and pine resin . eminently quaffable .  pours black with a small head that dissipates quickly .  it has a very nice creamy mouthfeel to it that i really like in my stouts .

the smell is absolutely amazing - chocolate , fresh coffee , almonds , more chocolate , plums , and dark roasts . the taste is also great , but the smell is better . sort of like mesenteric ischemia , the greatness of the smell is out of proportion to the taste - but again , the taste is wonderful .  '' appearance : peach in colour with some slight chill haze and free floating solids .  this beer has a very thick mouthfeel , with a creamy sweet taste to it . very nice thick and full mouthfeel . top notch balance between an easy initial crisp feeling , and then a thick and full finish .

qiute complex and very good . taste : roasty , caramelly , ... notes of honey bring a lightly sweet touch to the brew .  i also got the pilsener . just barely over the top and exceedingly drinkable . very appropriate for the style . like the pils , this has a bit of a creamy mouth feel , which seems like wabash water to me ( that 's neither good nor bad ) .  mouthfeel was superb . thick bodied , smooth and creamy .

this would make one amazing candle . it has a burnt quality to it - smells mature and serious . taste- initial sip is surprisingly biting - carbonation is more present than you might expect .  this beer pours a copper ton with not much of a head .  texture is smooth , creamy , very thick .

aroma was very fruity and excellent . it was a good bit hoppier than i expected from an english ipa , but i liked it .  pours a cloudy copper-brown color with a airy off-white head . head falls to about nothing . not much lace , very thin .  very nice full bodied mouthfeel .

slightly sweet smelling too , very nice . it tastes pretty hot , not really burning but there 's no doubt where this beer has been living .  a poured out a very clear light orange with a half finger of stark white head that receded quickly .  the mouthfeel is exceptional i believe .

on the nose this beer was just wild , and initially i got an aroma of sweet golden raisans and hazelnuts , with honey and sour funk . talk about an intriguing aroma . the beer is not quite so complex on the palate , though i thought the brewer did an excellent job balancing the sour brett with the sweet belgian ale flavors .  appearance : orange color with medium head and lace combined with very little carbonation .  m : like the taste , excellent creaminess to this one . utterly brilliant .

smells of fresh floral and citrus hop cones . also a hint of peach adds a nice touch .  my previous experience of tasting this beer at this pub was extremely satisfying , hence the decision yesterday to write down how i feel about this beer while enjoying a nice afternoon out at this remarkable pub on the `` st. george 's day '' ... a : served in a half-pint straight glass , it pours a light-golden colour , with a foamy head at first but fast retreating ( quite unlike my previous experiences , when it had this very very thin but incredibly lasting beerhead ... ) ; the carbonation is very low .  m - exceptionally smooth , a sight tingle of carbonation . a beer with a great body .

unbelievably intense hop aroma . sticky , dense and pungent citrus , pineapple and evergreen scents that blast you in the face . certainly the most enjoyable black ipa i 've had to date .  a 1 '' head fades to a thin film . lacing is extremely light , only a thin strand is formed and fades quickly .  great feel in the mouth , absolutely . fluffy and great body .

a great spicy citrus nose with a sweet boozy kick . if you dig the hoppy explosion , buy a case !  the beer pours clear amber with a modest bright white creamy head and after its decomposition the lace forms a thin veil upon the glass .  the mouthfeel is extremely thick and really coats the entire mouth .

smells amazing . smells just like a heavy stout with a chunk of burning hickory in it like a cinnamon stick in apple cider.. awesome taste is great , a little boozy but for 10 % it 's nice . very complex but also very enjoyable and not too much .  came with a neat glass . i was sceptical when a almost colorless beer was put in front of me , with a minimal head , but the smell of lemon was inviting .  the mouthfeel is a strong point for this beer . nice a full mouthfeel with lots of fine carbonation and a dry finish .

cask wet-hopped with chinook served at the brewery . smells like something i never want to stop smelling - citrus , pine , floral , herbal , if it 's associated with a hop it 's here . backing up the hop aromas are grainy and lightly toasted malts that gain steam as the beer warms . tastes good , just not as good as it smells . hop flavors dominate but caramel malt flavors that are more earthy and mineral-like than sweet serve as a sturdy backbone .  large head with impressive retention . not really any lacing there .  m : extremely smooth and creamy . great carbonation carries this beer . surprisingly my favorite part .

s - heavy pine and hops . ammonia ? sorry if that 's harsh . not impressed here .  a : pours a beautiful golden hue . some fizz leads to a light head . okay retention and no lace .  richly smooth and medium-full body .

nose is hugely phenolic ; musty , dusty , with a background of grandma 's spice drawer . long slow deep breaths leave the senses reeling with delight . entry lacks the expected fireworks and imparts a fuzzy mouthfeel . a very different take on the saison style from one of the best .  12oz brown bottle with that fancy red foil to denote that this beer is part of their unplugged series . no pssst when the cap what pulled off though showed enough carbonation to produce a healthy looking lace on top of the dark tawny brew .  mouthfeel is velvety smooth , thick & creamy .

smell is of intense piney hops , the aroma fills the whole room .  this kriek pours with an amber body topped by a thin head with little lacing .  flavors are big , and the mouthfeel is incredibly full and well rounded .

this beer presents an awesome floral smell . it actually reminds of the way dandelions smell . without even tasting the beer you can get a good idea for the amount of hops present here .  decent , nothing incredible to look at .  body is thick , smooth , rich , creamy , and as close to perfect as you can get . an enjoyable , if strange , experience .

a : pours a slightly hazy orange , thin white head with some retention s : waves of aromatic hops on the front , lots of tropical fruit with features of mangos , tangerine , and grapefruit . mf : light body , medium to high carbonation o : this is an awesome and drinkable apa . it features a nice presentation of tropical smelling hops .  some slight bubbles rose upon pouring , with no residual head whatsoever .  for the style , this beer has incredible feel and almost unreal sensation of bitterness .

s- great smell . citrus mostly with some really nice sweet tropical fruit notes .  12oz bottle says 10.8 % nice looking bottle . darkness . looks like an eight-ball in my tulip but upon closer inspection you can notice tiny brown yeast particles floating everywhere .  m - really shines here , with a nice , round mouthfeel . very nice .
smells great . t - strong hoppy taste to it .  a : could pass as a coca-cola , dark brown but not quite black . can taste the oak and maybe bourbon ?  mouthfeel is appropriately thick and chewy .

s : i loved the noise on this one . this is one of the best smelling ipas i have ever had . maybe amarillo , do n't quote me on that , t : obviously very hoppy and a bit sweet .  wow ! this is my first ba review and for good reason . i am just glad that i purchased only 1 bottle of this junk . the only thing i want back is the $ 1.59 i spent on the bottle and the peanuts that i spent cooling it down . question for the brewery ... .what kind of coffee did you use in the brewing process ?  mouthfeel is amazingly thick and rich .

smell is incredible . you can open this beer , set it down and enjoy the aroma at arms length .  poured int a pint glass on 7/1/10 cloudy & dense pineapple color . one finger of white foam fizzles away over a few minutes . bubbles on the inside of the glass slowly release to the top . small ring of retention , not much lace .  again the hop flavors are earthy and grassy m : good amount of carbonation and a good medium mouthfeel perfect for the style .

s : this smells fantastic ! there are notes of brandy , vanilla , oak , caramel and dark fruits . i 'm hoping that this tastes as good as it smells !  appearance : hazy dark orange . lighter in color than i expected .  m - big , full , and smooth , with just a prickle of heat .

awesome nose to this beer , notes of quality wheat , toasty grain and some definite detection of bright citrus-like hops .  appearance : pours a clear golden colors with a tiny head that turns to lacing and a medium amount of carbonation .  the carbonation is near perfect for me , not overwhelming like most pale ales .

just an awesome aroma , and one i kept returning to before my glass emptied . pretty good , but a step back from the smell . closer to a 4.25 in my book , but i was generous elsewhere . d - i liked this almost as much as the berliner weiss and may just have to seek out another bottle .  rogue makes some great brews with wicked distribution a- pours a light brown appearance . not completely opaque and not much for a head .  m : perfection . my words simply ca n't do justice to the body of this beer .

s : very , very nice . milk chocolate , bourbon , malted milk balls , sweet cream . perfectly complex for the style . the bourbon scent was amazing . the distinct chocolate flavor was real nice . overall , real nice .  amber with a golden hue . thin white head that fades quickly , leaving some patches .  mouthfeel from the cask conditioning is amazing . smooth and almost creamy , very light on the tongue .

smells : sweetly sour . perfectly balanced and amazing in every sense . the oak is subtle and perfect . the flavor bill ranges from sweet tangerine to lavender , lemon peel , lime juice , grapefruit and a certain very subtle smokiness .  into a tulip , pours a white head atop a virtually impenetrable , yellowish/slightly golden body . the head reforms quickly due to the carbonation , but weak legs and no lacing .  excellent mouthfeel ... nice and viscose with just the right amount of carbonation and foam .

smell : a rather subdued aroma of some spices and some floral hops . perhaps a touch of pumpkin , but overall their is not much of a nose on this one . taste : despite the aroma , it is not hard to find the pumpkin and the spiciness in this one .  flat . amber with a bit of haze . settles nicely into an oversized wine glass very ( and i mean very ) minimally carbonated .  tastes strongly of the caramel and finishes with the hops and alcohol.. the full-bodied creamy mouthfeel and warming alcohol make this sipper a solid holiday barleywine .

there is also a smokey characteristic that brings everything together very nicely . taste : there is a lot of smoke and roast throughout each sip .  got this bottle from mike , thank you poured into a tulip glass at 51 degrees . appearance : there was a two finger head that quickly dissipated . the clarity of the beer is hazy .  mouthfeel is extraordinary . everything about it is just perfect .

aromatics offer up tart acidity almost vinegar like notes i think the green bottle created a mild off note but it does n't overwhelm and it definitely does n't smell like a skunked euro pils . oak barrel effects weigh in with some earthy wood notes . some pineapple and tropical notes are aroused as it warms .  pours a deep copper orange color , very hazy , moderate head with pretty quick dissipation . looks okay .  really tart-fruity and tasty with an amazing feel to it .

the nose is wonderful ! lots of butterscotch and vanilla up front followed up by toffee and caramel .  pours a very hazy ruby , with a white head that fades quickly . some visible carbonation , but the depths are too murky to make out well .  mouthfeel - very silky . just the right amount of carbonation drinkability - goes down really easily , but the sour might wear on me after a while .

even though this was a new hop , a descendant of perle , it reminded me of standing in the gigantic hopunion refrigerated warehouse , swaying , intoxicated by the brilliant and bold aromas of citrus assaulting me . in an instant with my nose in the glass , i was transported back to yakima , a kid in the nose candy store . ultimately , another awesome dipa , but quite a different brew .  thanks to drewba for this 375 ml cork and cage bottle , which i poured into a tulip . askew pours a hazy orange with yellow highlights and a two-finger white head . it 's a little cloudy , though i can see through the glass .  excellent , ok heck , perfect mouthfeel for this beer .

s : huge aroma of roasted coffee beans right off the bat . i do n't particularly like coffee ( except the sugary starbucks versions ) , but i 've always loved the smell of raw coffee beans . and this aroma rivals that of the best coffee stouts.. t : mostly just coffee and sweet malts . just damn good beer .  a - pours a very dark brown and almost borders on black . retention and lacing are hard to review because of this fact . very solid .  mouthfeel is sublime . creamy , oily and full - this really just makes the difference between a good and great ipa for me .

good head retention & lacing s : fruitty , bready with dry candied fruits & honey t : fruitty , bready & boozey up front . finishes with loads of honey taste & touch of lemony hops mf : syruppy , chewy with low carbonation & a bit too much dryness drinks a bit slow because of the intense dryness , but a solid winter warmer  pours an amber color , not the red hue i would expect from a red ale .  m : the mouthfeel is really excellent on this beer .

the smell of cascade hops hits hard and leaves a slight fruity sweetness behind . fruitiness reminds me of banana . the hops are a bit piney , but not off putting . the smell after a while turned to heavy grapefruit . they blend together well . the mouthfeel is smooth and carbonated well .  bcbvs pours the kind of all encompassing black that i 'd expect from a hefty imperial stout . it sticks around alright , but does n't leave any trace of its existence as it slowly fades away . for what 's supposed to be a stout aged on vanilla beans , there 's not much vanilla at all in the nose . that transitions int a very pleasant warming sensation from some bourbon .  burnt brown head poured incredibly thick and foamy with very small bubbles and a meringue like topping ... a good one finger of foam remained throughout.. some thick lacing lines ... aroma - lots of roasted sweet chocolate malts backed with caramel and strong coffee , toasted nuts - hazlenuts mainly , quite earthy , some faint citrus notes , liquorice , brown sugar , honey notes , some light smokiness ... taste - tons of dark chocolate up front followed by strong black coffee notes , roasted malts , cocoa powder , some light smoke just coming through , dark fruits ( black cherries and currents ) , nut brittle , treacle / molasses , warming alcohol is just noticeable.. feel - smooth and velvety with just a little sharpness underneath ... full bodied ... pretty drinkable for an 11 % brew although becomes quite sweet towards the end ... overall - another superb example of an imperial stout from southern tier although again a 650ml bottle is way too much ... definitely recommended though ...

smell : complex and interesting . this really smells unlike any other doppelbock i 've ever had . strong fruity , almost belgian yeast and candi sugar notes , but still wonderful malt sweetness ( molasses , caramel ) balancing it out . wonderful ! taste and mouthfeel : not as earth-shattering as the smell , but it still taste great . complex malty sweetness greets your mouth at first , with a ncie touch of fruits , and then finishes with a ncie hop bitterness . the flavors and smells of this are really unique for the style , but are entrancing as well .  a : thick , cloudy center , syrupy , brown . with thin ruby highlights . kinda the opposite of sir mix a lot 's famous quote `` little in the middle but it 's got much back . like a chocolate twizzler made by a drunk willie wonka .  m- this is my 51st ba review and i have to say that of all the beers i have reviewed i think the sa octoberfest has the best mouthfeel .

smell : smells great . wonderful combination of spices , sweet fruits , and citrusy hops .  this beer pours a dark amber color with a two finger head that recedes fast .  mouthfeel is perfect , thick to go with the maltiness , and great carbonation to help the sourness .

excellent smell . m - a medium bodied beer . has a syrupy feel to it , with a good amount of carbonation .  poured golden with a 1 '' white head . some lacing & minmal head retention s : floral hops t : floral hops combines with fruittyness up front .  velvety , smooth mouthfeel , goes down like a thai ladyboy hooker . it 's a wonderful texture , impeccable even .

the smell of this brew is great . citrus and pine all the way , a very noticable northwestern hop profile . overall a fantastic beer .  a : deep copper ( much lighter than the uff da ) , very light-tan head , very little retention , initial leg/lace . ( does n't look like a doppelbock .  mouthfeel is exceptional , as a cream stout needs to be , and this brew from st. peter 's goes above and beyond .

smell is outstanding with a heavy whiff of maltiness , akin to a certain wheat doppelbock of some notariety . no floral armoa here - this one is all malt .  this was poured into a tulip and reviewed blind . cloudy tangerine in color , with a one-inch head of cream the consistency of soap bubbles . the head fizzles away quickly to a thin , transparent top layer with an accompanying tiny ring of bubbles .  mouthfeel is perfection . silky , perfect body , great carbonation .

had a dark red hue that i could just barely see through s : smell was ridiculously awesome ! exactly what i think of as a peanut butter and jelly . she absolutely loved it and is begging for more already .  the color of this beer is a nice ruby-copper . there is a thin head which does disappear except around the edges , i though hops aid in head retention .  mouthfeel is fantastic . carbonation is spot on .

pours a dark amber , tiny bit of head , nothing really special but o the smell , it 's delicious , my stomach told me i needed some sweets as soon as i smelled it . i liked the first sip a lot , carmelized maple glazed bacon ? if the mouthfeel had had something more to it , this would have been perfect .  pours hazed orange with an off-white head that immediately disappears to a thin wisp of a patch , leaving very little lacing .  m - thick and creamy without becoming chalky or cloying .

s : instant pop of the top is burst of sweet mango and tangerine aromas . best fruity and floral nose in an ipa i have come across in a while . better than flower power maybe . malts hardly detectable at first but the hops do settle down fairly quickly and give way to this sweet caramelly malt goodness . soft caramel and sweet cracker . nice bittery dry finish . m : sticky resinous hops do coat the tongue but overall pretty creamy in texture and peppers out the palate on the finish . d : pretty damn nice ipa out of a can i must say .  although it looks like any run of the mill pale , this is certainly above average .  mouthfeel is very creamy and dessert-like . this one is truly a treat .

amazing maple and honey aroma . i foresee this to be an amazingly sweet brew .  smallish growler , courtesy of one of the brewpub 's employees , who was in line with me at dld , poured into a wine glass . a : clear russet body with a hint of ecru head that disappears quickly , leaving just a touch of floating foam .  as smooth as they come , with a thick , luscious mouthfeel that does n't dissappoint .

wonderful caramel sweetness with an expected hop aroma . the taste was a little sweet for my taste for a lager .  a - poured a slightly transparent brown with a thin white head with slippery lacing .  mouthfeel is great , thick and syrupy .

awesome nose with caramel malt , oak and fruit . taste echoes the nose , but here the alcohol is very noticable in the finish .  pours a bright golden-straw yellow color with about two fingers of bubbly white head .  m - fucking awesome . i ca n't describe it better .

appearance : one finger head that dimishes quickly with a nice deep dark reddish brown body smell : loads of sour cherries and funky oak taste : very tart/sour cherries which makes your mouth pucker . also you get a nice malty and funky backbone on this brew which compeletly hides the alcohol .  hoppus maximus pours a cloudy orange with small chunky particulate suspended . overall it 's pretty light for an amber ale , but a solid beer none the less .  m - it was very soft and velvety .

smell is nothing short of phenomenal . tastes like fresh wheat bread with a little bit of burnt espresso bean and caramel molasses .  a - transparent copper color with a short head that does n't hang around long .  the texture is excellent for the style : creamy but not too heavy .

the nose is terrific ! pungent floral and citrus hops explode out of the pint glass .  poured a deep dark reddish brown , served with little head , low carbonation .  medium to full bodied and extremely smooth and creamy , definitely a sipper but it sure is a delightful one !

wonderful smelling beer . huge dark fruit aromas .  poured from 330ml bottle into a tulip . appearance : rich golden hue with a somewhat hazy body . not bad , but could be prettier . mouthfeel : medium body with great carbonation in spite of its mediocre foam cap .  the taste of faint coffee , caramel and roasted malt slid on my tongue like silk , not too cold and felt just right . nicely balanced .

the smell is wonderful . huge blast of citrus assaults the nose - lots of grapefruit and tangerine , really smells wonderful . it took me a while to take the first taste just because it smells so good . otherwise , this is a very good ipa .  decent head . pours dull brown with reddish notes .  mouthfeel - wonderfully smooth , medium-bodied with a memorable resilience post-swallow .

strong scents of black cherry , blueberry , and sweet red wine . t : sour cherries up front meld with the flavors from the sherry barrels to give the beer a woody aftertaste . overall , i 'm glad i got to try this again ( not sure what vintage the first one i had was ) . it 's nice to see what this beer is like as it warms to room temp .  poured from a bomber , no head to speak of than the first bit from the aggressive pour . black in color as to be expected .  m - great . it had an almost creamy mouthfeel that it reminiscent of a stout on tap ( not quite to the level of nitro-tap , but it 's close . ) d - the alcohol really puts a damper on drinking this beer , it 's overall lack of flavor strength does as well .

smell is an obscene amount of decadent chocolate fudge . amazing . taste is lots more earthy chocolate , more complex earthy/rye notes .  a - poured with a dark orange colour with good carbonation . hazy with no head retention or lace from a head that started at slightly off white with one finger .  it has a perfect amount of carbonation and crispness .

smell : subtle , i smell the grains and malt a bit . taste : tastes much better then it smells , surprising , easily one of the better lagers .  enjoyed at trinity bp pours orange/amber with sand colored head , average head retention & lacing s : apricot , peach , bubblegum t : much dryness , bubblegum , & a touch of toffee up front .  however , the richness of those hops combined with the oppulent mouthfeel still make his a truly great ipa .

s : wow this smells out-of-this-world delicious . wonderful rye character with a delicious citrus/pine hop presence . tropical fruits give a great background .  this beer pours a surprisingly pale , golden color ( i expect a much darker hue from a double ipa ) .  nice carbonation o - it looks great and has fantastic mouthfeel , i just wish more of the barrel character came out or even more of the citrus ... just a bit one sided .

aroma is fantastic ... sweet figs , raisins , cherries and vanilla ... .no alcohol detected in the nose .  pours dark brown . looks fairly thin off the pour but very nice head .  m - creamy and luxurious . the bite is done through alcohol rather than carbonation .

smells awesome . there is n't a lot of malt up there but there is a lot of nice hops , a mixture between the pine and citrus variety . amazing wonderful smell . medium body ( approaching full ) , sweetness and nice hop flavors in the midpalate and bitterness up back .  1988 vintage : this elixir pours into the glass with a dark brown body with little head or lace .  m - nice thick mouthfeel with minimal carbonation . very oily and damn smooth .

s : stunning aroma ! this beer smells simply fantastic . funky and wild , similar to a belgian lambic , i could take in this scent all day . very enticing indeed . d : a pleasant surprise .  this double ipa poured a clear copper color with no head .  mouthfeel is amazing , an incredible smoothness and creaminess . very full and round in the mouth .

s - delicious aroma ! the aroma is absolutely delicious with nice malty aromas and finishes with some nice mild hop aroma . t - the flavor starts off with nice roasted malt flavor that is perfect .  a : pours a clear , deep copper with a tight head . so far , this is n't looking too kolsch-like .  it is milkshake creamy and is truly amazing . i have not read catherine the greats review but i hope she appreciated it in 1795 as much as i did in 2011 .

like most belgian strong dark ales , it 's very malty and pours a muddy burgundy-brown with a thick creamy head . it smells great - like candy sugar , raisin , plums and spice . up to this point it 's about perfect , but on the first sip things start to go downhill a bit . it 's definitely sweet , spicy and delicious , but in my opinion there are better beers given the prohibitive cost .  in a mug it 's opaque as any stout would be but through an angle it 's an amber plum color.the head was minimal , due in part to an overly careful pour .  feel : low carbonation , smooth body , exceedingly thick and creamy ( almost as much as the egg nog i had earlier ) , dry finish .

smells amazingly smooth and tasty . t : very surprising . i love the taste on this .  a : pours a mostly opaque brownish-black with russet highlights . 1-finger head settles quickly and leaves no lacing .  m : this is where this beer really shined for me .

smells clean . heck , all i can smell is like rice lager ... ok , oof , at least it does n't taste like that ! sadly , i could n't call this one drinkable - every time i bring the glass near my face i can smell it and the smell just throws me off entirely ... i guess i 'd do better drinking it straight from the bottle .  pours a small head that sticks around for half of the glass . clear and yellow color . smell is of wheat and lemony grass with some passion fruit . the citrusy flavor and the passion fruit combines with the wheat to provide a very light and flavorful beer that is perfect for the spring and summer times . it is a great beer for the summer time .  m : very full bodied and it is like i am eating a fresh piece of grapefruit when i take a sip .

s- very pine forward , not much citrus here . o- i drank this about an hour after a pliny , and it stood up well .  1 finger head , honey like in color . s : bread like , in a good way . t/m : smooth overall good beer , nice blend of hops , just the right amount of carbination . d : very drinkable , pale ale , will be picking this up again in the near future .  mouthfeel was superb . very smooth and thick , and with just enough carbonation .

s - wow . great nose . chocolate , cherry , raisin , assorted fruit , floral , alcohol is in there ( but not offensive ) , plumb , and prune . very pleasant nose on this guy . quite inviting !  straw to yellow appearance , very clear , very still . large fluffy head that drops to less than a quarter inch after a couple minutes .  this has a nice , smooth mouthfeel , and the foam leaves a good lacing around the glass .

drinkability : a great beer with a wonderfully soporific effect from the smell alone . who needs a bong when you have this ?  pours a two finger light tan head that fades slowly leaving no lace . cloudy amber/brown color .  mouthfeel is full , rich and lush . i almost wonder if they added some maltodextrine to beef up the mouthfeel .

smell is just amazing , tons of grapefruit and citrus . i mean , this is a citrus blast , like nothing i 've ever smelled before . i can smell the bitterness - i swear they must put grapefruit juice in this . wow , this is some good stuff . nice and bitter , but not mouth-raping . and most importantly for me , a good balance is struck between hop bitterness and hop flavor . hopped with amarillo and cascade . amarillo and centennial are my favorite 2 hops , and to my palate the 2 c 's are almost indistinguishable .  a- very hazy yellow with good size white head .  there feel is pure perfection . it coats the mouth and leaves a satin residue in the finish .

thin tan head that dissipates quickly smell : sweet caramel and roasted malt , smell of alcohol , some dried fruit notes , taste : sweet roasted malt is prominent but the roasted flavor really stands out , some coffee and nut flavors , minimal bitterness , kind of an acrid aftertaste mouth feel : dry mouth feel , significant bite from the carbonation , light bodied overall : the color is appealing , the smell makes you want to drink it but the flavor lets you down .  a- poured from the bottle with virtually no head- just a diffuse haze layer and a collar . not much lacing to speak of .  wonderfully thick and viscous in mouthfeel , slick with a subtly prickly carbonation teasing the tongue .
the aroma is faint but what i pick up is good .  head : very small , barely any foam aroma : yeasty + hops equals a fermented , citrusy , piney aroma .  the feel is full , velvety , and soothing .

the aroma is deep , dark roasted malt , nearing almost burnt toasted . this had the deep , darkest roasted malt aroma i have come across in a stout .  a- cherry brown .  m : the mouthfeel is exceptional . a very nice silky smooth body with light fluffy carbonation .

s : incredibly complex and balanced . the first thing i could smell was coffee , followed closely by chocolate and caramel . t : the taste is less balanced than the smell ; a smoky mocha is the dominant flavor . o : this beer has more hops and carbonation than your average ris , making it somewhat unique , but the smell is better than the taste  has plenty of carbonation , but weak on retention .  m : fantasticaly smooth - medium bodied , fine bubbles . velvety ! d : gettin ' up there in abv % , but this one 's just really well crafted - better so than the unearthly , in my opinion - and is one of the better dipas i 've had the pleasure of trying .

s - strong chocolate , wood , nut , light coffee and vanilla t - slightly astringent dark chocolate and up front , settling well into a nutty/woody flavor . the smell is the highlight here .  appearance : this beer , when poured from a bottle into a pint glass , produced a 1/2 '' slightly off-white head with fair head lacing that dissipated quickly . body was a cloudy gold with soft carbonation aroma : picked up a light aroma of grapefruit and pine .  this is a little heftier than the supposed style stalwart , hoegaarden , but the soft , almost creamy mouthfeel makes this a surprisingly satisfying beer without being heavy .

roasted malt aroma with touches of dark fruit , earthy hops , subtle peppery spice and a nice bit of oaky vanilla bourbon/whiskey . this beer smells amazing ! surprisingly earthy and musty flavored medium body which is very complex , balancing a lot of different flavors and providing something very unique . it 's a nice change of pace to drink a barrel aged beer that is n't dominated by hot booze .  a : hazy golden ocher . head is fast to form , but is not very rich and recedes quite quickly . kind of lackluster , in the end .  full bodied , silky smooth and creamy .

seriously great smelling beer ! body is fairly thin overall impression : great nose , but the body doesnt back it up .  a : little to no head .  m - super creamy , coating the whole mouth . very nice .

from arrowine big arty green bottle that emitted a musty aroma of port and masala wine . the beer poured a beautiful clear burgundy , though it did n't hold much of a head ( not nothing , but minimal lacing and only a collar ) . the nose from the glass was equally complex and winey as from the freshly uncorked bottle : reminded me of my mother 's chicken masala . so incredibly sweet , with little of the sour belgian character i was hoping for ( my only experience with with style previously was a rodenbach , so my standards are perhaps artificially high ) .  this is a light vienna style lager . served extremely fresh , this beer is excellent and appropriate for warm tropical weather . i found 12-packs for sale at a large store in boston ( allston ? ) , across from the sunset bar & grill . upon trying a bottle it was evident that this beer must be served very young and fresh , and does not travel well .  m : super smooth with a thick body .

s : the best part of the stout it smells of chocolate with a bit of a woody smell as if you could smell the bourbon barrel . the smell it a bit more complex than their to be named later stout which is now know as sodbuster stout . t : more neutral than their normal stout but there are hints of coffee chocolate and due to the aging process the bourbon barrel . the stout really takes on the taste of the bourbon barrel and really intermingles with the chocolate taste of the stout . this cost me about $ 4.25 which is $ 0.25 more than a refill of the their sodbuster stout in a growler , i personally would prefer the growler over a pint of the bourbon stout , but it is definitely worth a try .  appearance is a dirty gold color and clear .  m : low carbonation yields a smooth and silk laden mouthfeel .

s=this is probably one of the better smelling ipa beers that i have had . also a nice pine smell came along with the citrus .  strange appearance to a dipa , it 's a very hazy golden color with a tiny head that does n't retain for long . looks more like apple juice than beer .  very impressed d- good imperial stout , great mouthfeel !

the aroma is what first jumps out at me . flavorful .  some nice head on the pour ... .  m - full bodied , sticky sweet but not cloying . coats the mouth perfectly , with a touch of dryness in the back end . good carbonation , too .

s - fantastic aroma of a classic hefe . big wheat and pale malt nose with a fruity and floral aromatic yeast nose . banana and clove with a bubblegum scent . absolutely classic ! t - big wheat on the flavor , the taste is immediately thinner than the nose would lead you to believe .  a : black , and slightly brown on the edges . the head is made of big bubbles . it disappear rapidly . very drinkable and a good beer .  the mouthfeel is right on the money !

smell : wow . this is a whole new realm for me . it literally smells like a sweet cup of fresh coffee . wow . taste : roasted malt , dark chocolate , and plenty of coffee flavor .  light golden , with a very thin white head that fades quickly .  feels like liquid velvet , as all of the best tripels should , imo .

the aroma is fascinating . it is flowery and herbal , yet there is a pungent note of lime . marvelous . flavor is wheaty and herbal , with spicy notes such as oregano . astonishingly clean for a fantome beer , and not sour , but lightly tart . light and refreshing yet satisfying , this beer is incredibly drinkable . excellent saison with an awesome aroma . here 's to fantome !  this pours dark and viscous with barely any head .  the mouthfeel is a pleasurable experience .

i did n't have to put the glass to my nose to catch a whiff of lovely hops .  pours golden yellow with a white head that fizzles down to a lingering patch .  flavor is exceptional , very subtle and complex on the palate full body excellent complement to the flavor .

very sweet . god this smells like tiramisu . t/m- taste is much more roasty and porter like than the nose leads you . nice subtle coconut flavor and sweetness that adds incredible smoothness and balance .  bottle poured into a tulip . *the bottles on the store 's shelf were rather dusty* ( a ) - pours a cloudy reddish copper amber color that produced a decent off-white head that dissipated quickly .  mouthfeel is full and round .

sweet malty scent , with a touch of fruit in the nose .  pours very clear , copper/brown in color , with a rocky off-white head which is a bit thin and dissipates fairly quickly .  m - huge milkshake like feel on this brew makes it feel great in the mouth . this is an excellent full body for a porter with this much chocolatey flavor .

s - smell is fantastic - very strong citrus smell , with some flowers .  a : it pours a straw yellow with a one finger white head s : it smells like hops and a little bit of spiciness .  m : nice full body with a creamy mouthfeel .

a- translucent purple-pink grape color with alot of carbonation bubbles and a bubbly ring of a head s- smells like fresh strawberry jam .  appearance -- pours a bight cupric orange with a slender sludsy head . head retention is pretty woeful .  m - creamy , velvety , perfect .

pours a really nice straw yellow with a hint of orange . aroma is awesome . mango , pineapple and floral hops create an awesome tropical scent .  pours a hazy golden orange color with a thick tan head .  m : thick but clean in the mouth , almost oily , with a warming alcohol effect down the throat . light carbonation balances the thickness of this brew quite perfectly . d : hmm , i do n't think this beer gets all the credit it deserves .

s- wow , some really dank hops ! ! ! i 'm hit with exceptional floral hops , lavender and jasmine , followed by citrusy hops and mangoes , you can get a very light sweet yeast smell in the backround but almost unnoticed . t- taste is nothing as promising as the smell , definate floral hop , lavender and jasmine , citurs and mango flavors are somewhat lacking almost a little watered down on the taste , of course it follows with a nice light belgian yeast to subdue the hops . nice light/medium body , would have liked more body , seemed watery .  a : a slow , steady , high pour results in a thick black body underneath a mere half inch of frothy light-brown head . mediocre retention , spotty lace . not terrible , but pretty darn average .  t/m-extremely full bodied and quite syrupy . very smooth on the palate and a low level of carbonation that i actually very much enjoy .

the smell is of toffee and chocolate . excellent !  12 oz bottle appearance - rather clear for a rouge , yet not `` filtered clear '' hazy amber/copper color with a respectable head .  m : perfect body and balance !

wonderfully spicy aroma with a blast of cinnamon , clove , ginger , brown sugar and nutmeg . the abv is extremely well masked without even a slight touch of alcohol heat making it extremely quaffable .  wall to wall customers , mostly ordering mojito 's ! nice beer menu . i ordered a rochefort 10 but they were out and the bartender brought this as an alternative . ) i was content to drink from the bottle .  mf= medium body with a slightly crisp to crisp mouthfeel . carbonation was near perfect for the style in my opinion .

garden fresh - citric , grassy , piney , knock your ass over dank aroma . incredibly crisp , and insanely aromatic . this beer should win an award for just it 's smell alone . i 've seen ipa 's with way less impressive aroma profiles .  the head was short-lived , and no lacing .  mouthfeel is very full and chewy .

picture prefect hefeweizen smell imo t/m- taste is a little more subtle than the nose would make you think with the bouquet of esters it provides ! still , very good . sweet and silky and a slight yeasty bite on the end .  a cloudy light yellow , with minimal white head , not much in the way of lacing .  mouthfeel is amazingly soft over the tongue , and drinkability is superb as well .

s : sweaty socks and lemon juice . the hallmark of good gueuze . some bretty old leather notes in there add to the classic bouquet . a complex true to style flavour .  dark golden hue with not much head or carbonation .  perfect . 5 an easy drinker .

s- lots of sweet roasted malts upfront . coffee and milk chocolate as well . lots more chocolate than i could smell , and the coffee/hops at the end is pretty strong . very cheap , and quite good .  head started off a big fluffy white pillow , but is now a scant layer of suds . zero lacing .  mouthfeel is silky smooth .

absolutely unbalanced an awesome . t - after i was punched in the face by the aroma , i was kicked in the gut by the taste . extremely flavorful , alcohol content was undetectable , easy to drink .  appearance : honey brown in color with a small white head .  the mouthfeel is very full , rich , bold , and creamy .

smell is tons of toffee , lots of vanilla , and even some chocolate , if you look for it . none of the complexity of the smell . mouthfeel is good , thick and creamy .  the sah'tea has a very cloudy appearance with a very urine-like color .  sits in the mouth well extremely creamy porter that was very enjoyable .

the aroma was super boozy , oaky and smooth . rich , rum-like alcohol came through strong along with dark chocolate , brown sugar and molasses . unlike the nose , the taste was quite harsh .  a : dark brown , almost black body , with a thin , creamy tan head ; mostly lasting , but no lacing .  m - creamy and velvety , not syrupy by any means . low carbonation .

before you say `` that 's not what i want from my beer '' , let me note that there are limes , taffy and butterscotch , bananas , and something like sweet kansas city barbecue sauce . underneath all this is a funky and old wood/grass aroma . it 's really amazing and wonderful , but strange nonetheless .  pours a deep , dark , opaque brown with very little head .  the mouthfeel was super bubbly , light and creamy on the palate .

this may be good over fried rice , but it should certainly not be consumed by anyone unless of course , they happen to enjoy chugging soy sauce in their leisure time .  pours gold in color with a 1 finger white head that faded quickly ; very good lacing that left rings .  m : a silky smooth mouthfeel that was also very crisp . an awesome feeling beer that was very easy to drink and very , very smooth . d : excellent mouthfeel and taste combination .

s : the best ipa i have ever smelt . t : it is n't the best ipa that i have ever tasted but it is very good .  a-pours a pale , golden copper with a white , one-finger head s-toasty , and really pronounced caramel malt with an understated spicy hop characteristic .  m : medium bodied , slightly carbonated , and incredibly smooth .

s : juicy citrus hops that make me weak in the knees !  appearance- pours a really hazy light peachish yellow with a half finger foamy white head that recedes very quickly . the cap is non-existent the collar is fairly thin and leaves almost no lacing .  this feels more like a stout to me ... the mouthfeel is amazing . it 's almost like licking a wet board , freshly hewn from the live tree . there 's a graininess reminiscent of chewing on raw sugar cane , and i can feel all of the wonderful fibrous matter in the mouthfeel of this beer .

s - delicious ! really inviting , the aroma does its job making you crave that first sip . that 's pretty incredible . i have to say , i was a little biased going into this , being unimpressed with every fullers offering i 've tried . still , outstanding . a very good representation of a non-extreme porter .  no head . lots of sediment .  i would say that mouthfeel is perfect for the style , chewy and full , and the carbonation is there but very light with a natural feel .

amazing nose , properly dominated by minty , refreshing , floral coriander , which entwines itself together with the malts and hops to call to mind all sorts of things : licorice , cardamom , pine , cola , lime , and of course other coriander beers like hoegaarden and stone pa with coriander . herbal and verdant , though it tastes less interesting than it smells . fruity with berry qualities and a pleasant herbal echo of coriander and oregano . this is excellent , it 's remarkable how much more complex a beer can become with the addition of just one ingredient .  poured into my glass and for some reason , it appeared to be somewhat flat ?  m : smooth , medium to light body ; small particles of yeast give an interesting texture d : extremely drinkable , smoothest hefeweizen i 've had .

it 's just beautiful . lots of apricot , definitely some mango , and the peach . really one of the fruitiest beers i 've ever smelled . just great . taste - comes pretty bitter up front . the smell is amazing , but the taste does n't quite live up .  a : very murky and cloudy . the head is high , little teeny bubbles that last for 5+ minutes .  the mouthfeel is the best part of this beer .

the aromatics are impressively vibrant - and begin their assault on your senses the moment you remove the cap . excellent , and while hugely hoppy , somehow is n't overdone .  wimpy pour lead to a one finger head and some nice cloudy burnt amber body.grapefruit and some piney smells in the nose.piney taste then leads to malty then to amarillo hops , the dank , resiny hop taste that sticks to the roof of your mouth.nice mouthfeel.i also smell some pancake and syryp in the nose as well.there really isnt a bad part about this apa.its tasty and i think it weighs in on the west coast side of the style.tasty and the alcohol isnt that bad , but two may be your limit.i would have again for sure .  m : nitro + stout = perfection . huge , silky body with a 100 % chance of creaminess .

aroma is excellent . behind some lemon and sourness i almost get a west-coast ipa - apricot , grapefruit , orange , tangerine , maybe a bit of pine .  ) , this 22oz bomber ( # 1769/4884 ) was poured into my duvel tulip . the beer pours a murky color that 's caught halfway between plum and brown . the initial pour yielded about a finger 's worth of light caramel foam , but a more aggressive follow up pour got the head up to two finger 's worth . the nose is of dark fruits primarily , with some alcohol in play as well ( in a good way ) , but it the lack of any remaining head makes the smell a little weak . carbonation is nice and low , picture perfect for the style , body is just a tad on the thin side though .  this mix is just exceptional ! mouth feel is creamy , thick , carbonated , and just wonderful . you can sip on this for hours .

the aroma was delicious ! citrus , caramel , toffee , alcohol , sweet dough and spices ; an excellent blend of hops , malt and yeast elements . well balanced and quite drinkable for the massive 12 % alcohol .  pours into a pint glass a slightly hazy orange/gold with a thin white head that quickly dissipates into nothing more than lacing on the surface of the liquid .  m- thick , chewy , sticky . great adjectives for a strong beer . a nice mellow carbonation is present enough to give an even fuller feel . d- very good , if pours of this were n't $ 7 a pop i would have drank this all night .

good head retention , and lacing on this one ... s - dark chocolate assaults the nose with a full on attack . this one smells of dessert .  so i got a free pitcher of this stuff after a hard fought game between the lines ... let me just preface this by saying stone is probably one of the greatest brewery 's in the united states . ok so im drinking it ... . i can drink this stuff like water ... they said that they put a lot of hops in this beer ? must of lost them somewhere between manufacturing and distributing ... i think i drank 3 of these ipa 's without even buzzing ... i mean cmon if your going to pride yourself on a 'hoppy ' beer gim me a buzz dewd . it tasted great but id like to recieve a buzz next time .  luscious , velvety and silky smooth ... what any exceptional dipa should feel like . all in all , i prefer `` plain '' un-earthly .

the nose is great ( and `` tickly '' ) ... apple sweetness to apple tartness with faint coriander on top of other spices . there is a ton going on in this aroma , and it 's all stellar -- i just do n't happen to have the exotic fruit knowledge to help describe what all is there . a very unique and complex beer , but not all of it works well together .  it poured a golden/straw/pale yellow hue , more golden towards the core . it had a nice clingy three finger head .  mouthfeel is very full and round .

really outstanding nose . the taste is completely different than the aroma . really glad i got to try this one .  pours a clear light orange/amber , almost golden , thin white head forms , drops to a thin ring , no real lacing on the glass , looks average .  exquisite mouthfeel front , middle , and finish .

smells of plum and cherry . also very sweet and malty . hope it tastes as good as it smells .  pours a muddy amber brown with a fizzy but thick white head that recedes to lace on the outside of the glass .  amazing . this is just the second beer i 've had from alesmith and they both lived up to their reputation .

amazing citrus hop aromas as well as piney hops . just a great ipa m - perfect carbonation , medium bodied , good all around o - smell is magical , taste is damn good and drinkablity is great too , this ones a winner  pours no head , no lace but excellent legs . opaque black color .  mouthfeel is light/medium bodied with the perfect amount of carbonation , love how this one feels .

the smell is really great on this one . dark chocolate , roasted coffee , deep-dark red cherries and roasty malts . the bourbon smell is really spot on , it overwhelms once you catch hold of it , but it 's pleasant and welcome . the taste follows the smell , but it 's a bit more muted . the alcohol is a bit overbearing , it 's a sipper but it 's good .  pour from a 750ml waxed and capped bottle into a cantillon oversize wine glass . a : pours a .5 finger thick , creamy white head with poor retention . pretty standard for the style .  it has a richness to it that is accentuated by the velvety mouthfeel .

smells of citrusy hop/pine/diacitle tastes of hop/grapefruit.lemo zest/ and pine nuts , it 's delicious !  this was served at a good temperature and with a smallish , off white head that soon settled to a ring and some lace . color is a clear gold amber with lots of bubble trails .  the high carbonation makes for a wonderfull mouthfeel for a hefe-weisse .

the nose is one of the most gorgeous i 've ever smelled- apricots and flowers .  pours with a two-finger bubbly head that goes quickly and leaves no lace .  mouthfeel - perfect about of carbonation and body .

it smelled sour and something unpleasant to me .  mild head for the style -- no lace . lemon yellow color and appropriately cloudy .  silky creamy as it gives a nice full mouthfeel . i prefer this to the regular .
