'' it 's a fitting name for this turbo-charged ipa with its explosive floral-spice aroma , scintillating hop flavor , and roundhouse kick of bittering . this is a fine ale to sacrifice on the alter to the hop gods and another contender for the crown .  hazy amber color with nice foam , but it dies off rather quickly .  perfect balance on the hop weight throughout the beer .

hops all day , floral , grapefruit , and fresh grass are so strong . the smell transferred over , but more as an ipa . i thought this was a really good beer and would buy again if i saw it .  a ) pours with a finger thick head then settles to a thin lacing on top and at the sides of the glass . hazy body . visible sediment - hence the style , maybe but i do n't like visible sediment .  nice weight , carbonation , and roundness in the mouth .

smell was amazing . it honestly struck me as pineapple .  a : orange-gold , and only a small white head that faded very fast . a little cloudy , but good active carbonation from the looks of it . s : not much , but i get a little caramel/cooked fruit . a craft drinkers lawnmower beer , or a bmc drinkers gateway beer , good either way .  very full bodied , bordering on syrup but with a silky smooth finish .

a little bit of mocha latte as well.. overall really an inspiring smell wafting from this beer .  medium amber but staright up copper color with very quick head and a few bubbles .  i have no idea how this absolutely stunning mouthfeel got attached to a mediocre beer like this .

aroma is delicious : deep earthy , barnyard , with lambic fruitiness like lemon and sour apple . flavor is dry , some lambic funk without the tartness , and a tad thin ; a bit of a letdown after the huge aroma . definitely not a typical blonde but i was very impressed with the interpretation by this great brewery .  extremely hazy and dense . head is a light beige color , but dissipates quickly .  t-alot going on here starts out with the sweetness that the nose hints and finishes with a wonderful bitterness on the back of your tongue that lingers so you know you just drank an ipa , but it is incredibly smooth almost silky good medium to light body with an incredible carbonation level makes it a nice ipa even for someone not used to the style .
for the price , this is a damn good trippel .  beer pours as a amber color . not much head ?  beautiful pour and very thick on the tongue ; its a pretty heavy brew , but still quite drinkable .

aroma ? nope .  had this on tap over at pike 's pub in seattle where it was served cold ( too cold for my taste ) with a minimal tan head that dissapeared quickly . the color is a very dark brown that almost looks black in the pub lighting .  mouthfeel is absolutely perfect .

smells wonderful ; lots of tropical fruits ( mango , papaya , pineapple , etc . ) whoa ... remarkably thin and exceptionally drier than i anticipated .  nice viscosity to this , average head retention , a touch of lacing s : booze & plums , plus other dark fruits , faint oakyness t : follows the nose , some rich caramelized sugar , cherries & raisins up front .  m-this beer has a medium-full mouthfeel with a very creamy texture with a soft faint alcohol warmth in the finish . d- this beer has a smooth flavor that has a very subtle complexity and a nice flavor but the creamy texture and head is just amazing .

this is amazing . t : oh so much malt .  not much head formation . its a nice amber color with a little reddishness to it and a bit of cloudiness .  m- big heavy resiny sticky mouthfeel . nice minimal carbonation with a nice creamy mouthfeel .

the smell might possibly be the best attribute of this beer ... it is off the charts with pumkin , cinn . etc . not pumpkin like you bit into one , but of a pumpkin pie your dunk aunt mary serves on thanksgiving .  poured into a pint glass , opaque brown/black with just a trace of dark tan head .  m : notable because of how damn smooth it is .

fantastic . taste is almost as good with a tartness that offsets the sugar . an affordable thing of beauty .  opened up a 750ml bottle and received a cascade of foam . following clean up , it poured a light brown/amber color with a slight haze due to some yeast i stirred up in my fumbling .  entry is silky smooth with just a touch of carbonation showing on the back of the tongue .

very nice carmel vanilla cream coffee aroma . so sweet in the nose with a hint of smokey-ness . pretty solid malt presence from start to just before the finish .  a : looks like prune juice with absolutely no head .  mouthfeel was full and creamy with a lot of vanilla up front , followed by a mounds-like coconut/dark chocolate taste on the finish .

i loved the smell wow you could open this brew 15ft from me and i would either believe i was at ihop or you just opened a sweetwater blue .  little to no lacing but a nice thin layer of constant head .  m- smooth as a baby 's ass . d- something this smooth goes down real easy . truly fantastic , be sure to try this if you have n't already .

the aroma is phenomenal . tons of citrus hops and grassy notes . a really solid aroma . tastes surprisingly wonderful compared to regular ruination . well carbonated and really enjoyable overall  a - very light amber color with a slight ( not as much as expected ) haze , thick head that settles but is well retained s - cherry aroma with some wheat malt notes t - dominate cherry taste , but strong wheat malt base behind it and a very slight hop finish m - medium body with a moderate carbonation d - as far as fruit beers go , this is probably one of the best commercial beer available ( that 's not a lambic or lambic variant - way different ballgame ) .  it is very creamy , great mouthfeel .

unbelieveably charming and complex nose . elements of both a great beer and a fine single malt all at once . opens up flowery and malty with a spicy hop backbone and transitions into aromas of caramel apples and all things autumnlike . leafy , earthy , laden with ripe orchard fruits and a touch of oak in the finish like a single malt . a scarce product for which i have to thank goldorak and his generosity for the opportunity .  the beer poured a clear medium amber , forming a thin white head which quickly faded .  for the style and flavor of this beer it has a perfect mouthfeel .

very enjoyable aroma . t. it tastes much as it smell .  not much carbonation after an aggressive pour into a tulip glass .  mouthfeel - very smooth , agreeable carbonation level , slightly heavy , right on for the style .

s : truly one of the worst smelling beers out there . d : truly one of the worst tasting and smelling beers i 've come across .  nice oily sheen , above average lacing & below averagehead retention s : bourbon , vanilla , oak & toffee , plus some hazel nut ?  a little light for a german style but still tastes distinctly german . creamy mouthfeel and very , very smooth . medium bodied well carbonated making it quite drinkable .

smells like a chocolate cake with chocolate icing while served with hot chocolate , lots of , say , chocolate . constructed in a subtle style which mandates a good deal of concentration to catch the nuances , nothing obvious here . very clean finish , resets the palate for the next sip .  pours an opaque brown color with next to no carbonation , just a few bubbles .  mouthfeel is great . crisp , clean , and dry finish .

just about the perfect aroma for a west coast ipa . palate is hop-forward , with lots of citrusy bitterness . body is part creamy , part sticky , and very pleasant and appropriate for the style . this is one of the more approachable hoppy beers that still has a lot of character , and is a pleasure to drink .  pours a dark amber with a thin head that quickly fades .  m- perfect . d- nice to hang out and have a couple .

aroma is sour and sweet at the same time . citrus and candy aromas with a huge hit of dusty yeast . sour yeast balances the sweet aromas , this is making my mouth water in anticipation . very interesting . mouthfeel is lively and bubbly , carbonation is more than adequate .  a : pours a dark reddish amber color that is transparent .  m - mouthfeel is perfect . silky smooth bubbles and full bodied texture .

smell is very much of caramel and malts.. nice smell . taste is little simple but solid.. again hints of caramel , but a little too macro tasting as a previous reviewer stated .  it pours a hazy light golden .  the mouthfeel is what surprised me as it felt very rich and smooth .

s : red fruit , raisins , bourban , and lots of lumberjack sized wood notes . so smooth in the nose . a : beautiful beer . big rocky medium cell head , amazing lacing , and great cover over a deep red brown body of crystal clarity . d : great with food , but not as good on its own . still , the light body , and seductive scent keep me coming back for more .  appearance : a very hazy , copper colored beer . i spaced off for a second while pouring and unleashed a ton of sediment into my glass , so that did n't help the clarity . the head was a cream color and disappeared quickly .  smooth body with a near perfect richness and carbonation .

smells mostly of lager yeast . not bad , just incredibly faint in odor .  500 ml bottle , a : pours a dark red brown . very light colour for a porter , looks like a dunkel .  mouthfeel is full and round .

pale malts in the aroma with some copper and bitterness . this offering was nice but nothing that made it really stand out .  a : almost no head on this one , poured about about a knuckle high and quickly died down to a thin film hovering over the beer . there is some substantial lacing , whatever is left of the head really sticks ! the beer poured a cloudy amber , looks like there is little activity going on as far as carbonation is concerned , but the color is very inviting .  excellent carbonation neither overwhelms nor underimpresses .

superb . taste : it had a nice tang to it , more raspberries than blackberries , some rust .  pours with a nice head , dispears a little to quickly to a foamy crown . pours a little hazy that seemed to clear up over time , chill haze ?  great mouthfeel . very drinkable .

s - smell is mainly of sweet and bitter fruity hops . very creamy and very peppery .  on-tap at flying saucer served in a standard pint-glass a crisp orange with a thin diminishing head .  m - full body and medium-light carbonation makes for a smooth texture that fizzes slightly on your tounge . it warms the mouth and feels creamy . very unique feel and one of my favorite things so far .

intense aroma , tremendous estry complexity . cloves and other spices join the banana topped off with phenols and a note of solvent alcohol . this taste matches the scent better than perhaps any any other quality brew i 've had . medium bodied creamy mouthfeel .  a : pours a nice dark coal black hue with a small tan colored head . very little retention and no lace .  very full bodied , viscous , almost chewy and smooth on the palate , with soft carbonation - one of the best mouthfeels i 've ever came across in imperial stout .

s : extremely aromatic . extremely fresh . t : certainly citrusy , with some grapefruit , pineapple , and a bit of orange .  appearance - hazy , golden with a small head that leaves very little lacing .  the body is nice , not thin and not slick , wonderfully smooth and crisp .

the aroma was pure bliss , loads of vanilla . a decadent dessert beer !  a golden-orange pour gives a tiny head and practically no retention , lace or carbonation .  mouthfeel- thick and rich like a good imperial stout should be . great carbonation and texture .

this beer smells juicy and thick . awesome . taste : immediate alcohol jolt is accompanied by lots and lots of bitterness .  pours an orangey color with dark suspended yeast . a direct pour results in a 1cm bubbly head which retreats quickly to leave bubbles only on the edges with a sparse lace over the rest of the beer .  silky smooth in the feel care of the nitro delivery .

enjoyable . taste is almost sour , with tons of the clove that was evident in the smell . overall , started promising , but did n't deliver .  jet black in color . there is no foamy head though and looks flat .  low carbonation , and an astringent finish , with a hint of warming alcohol . perfect . d- excellent .

smell : heavenly , apple juice type smell . never smelled that before . taste : hoppy , malts are thin for a bock .  certainly looks like your average hefeweizen . the small pour made it harder to be sure about the quality of the head .  mouthfeel- the texture is creamy and sublime , absolutely perfect in every way .

smell- very small amounts of hops and malt . i was so intent on finding more to the aroma that i stuck my nose in the beer ... oops . taste- pretty good balance of hops and malt , however , there is very little of both .  appearance - brown with a hint of red in it smell - smells of caramel malt and coffee taste - similar to the smell - slightly sweet without being overpowering mouthfeel - crisp and mild drinkability - a delightful flavorful beer , that could easily be a session beer .  one of the thickest beer i have ever tasted , equal to the thickest , this is milkshake thick . quite an interesting beer but way to thick to drink in quantity .

fantastic . not all that impressive looking though .  poured a solid black with a thin tan head . retention was poor , and lacing was average .  the mouthfeel on this beer is really what sets it apart .

dare i say this is maybe the best smelling beer i have come across . just beautiful . certainly citrus and pine on my tongue . the malty backbone is there and it 's quite pleasant . as it warms i 'm getting a taste of caramel . carbonation is perfect . sticky hop oil coats the tongue to my liking .  got this bottle from a bif , thank you . poured in tulip glass at 41 degrees . appearance : a one finger white head that was creamy and foamy and , lasted only a few seconds . the clarity of the beer is mostly clear with a touch of haziness .  mouthfeel is perfect . a rich , creamy treat .

there 's now an excellent sweet whiskey presence along with subtle earthy oak and a good bit of vanilla/marshmallow character . faint charcoal , bbq and campfire underneath but overall this beer is just too hot and one dimensional .  did not see any head forming ( was only poured into a small plastic cup though ) .  m/d : perfectly carbonated , smooth , and incredibly easy to drink . champagne-esque mouthfeel and drinkability .

aggressive hoppy aroma that can be smelled from over a foot away ! upon closer inspection , you can smell some malt and graininess as well .  poured a burnt orange/copper color , very cloudy with a inch tan head ; had a malty orange odor that had hints of spice and hops .  feel ( 5/5 ) very effervescent on the tip of the tongue in the initial taste ( almost reminiscent of the more carbonated belgian ales , like duvel in this respect ) . this transitions to a wonderful fullness as it washes to the back of the mouth .

rich malty and roasty with a lot of chocolate and a hints of coffee , banana , and fig . i really do not feel this beer has matured yet .  this is a very dark , almost completely black beer . it pours with a shallow , thin head that quickly dissapears .  first , the appearance and mouthfeel are perfect by my standards for the style . mouthfeel is perfect ; thick , smooth , creamy and a long lasting citrus rind and biting hop finish .

the taste was a little underwhelming considering how wonderful the nose was . the body has nothing more to offer than some malt and a little hops .  pours a pretty much solid black with a tiny light brown head .  mouthfeel : incredibly smooth and crisp . definitely the best part of this beer . drinkability : the clean flavors and really smooth mouthfeel make this incredibly easy to drink .

a bit of booze & head retention s : bourbon & dark fruit , a bit of booze as this warms , plus pralines t : rich bourbon & vanilla notes up front , plus oaky dryness , leafy hops & raisins . ivan is n't terrible at all , but needs to grow some more depth to achieve greatness  cloudy peach/amber color and a slim head that vanishes to scant surface lace .  mouthfeel is super thick and coating .

an amazing aroma . t- biscuit malt is more present as well as some citrus notes such as pink grapefruit and lemon zest . o- extremely drinkable with a great aroma . the only issue i had was that it was a little less complex in the taste and a little malty , but a fantastic dipa that can compete with the best .  dark straw colored with thin white head with poor retention .  great , great mouthfeel .

nose is an other-worldly fusion of rich cocoa , coffee , and a bit of fruitiness compliments of the raspberries .  appearance is a deep dark midnight mocha chocolate brown which lets no light through . very little to no head of tiny foamy brown bubbles .  great mouthfeel , nice and crispy , but not before you get to taste the beer .

the aroma is amazing ... . it immediately reminds me of johnnie 's diner in mcconnellsburg pa ... 1st day of deer season ... 4:00 am.. very strong coffee ... and now what i know as whiskey . the nose is pretty phenomenal ... tons of coffee beans.. lite cocoa ... and there is a decent whiskey note that really does n't jive as what i think of as `` bourbon '' ... almost an irish whiskey nose .  pours a cloudy bronze-mahogany with amber highlights . the creamy tan one-finger head shows good retention and spotty lacing .  wonderfully smooth body .

phenomenal nose -- not much different than sumpin ' sumpin ' with bountiful pineapple and mango fruitiness bursting forth .  bottle ( 2001 vintage ) : poured a deep red/amber colored beer with a small but nice head with minimal retention .  finishes crisp with slight honeysuckle sweetness & a slight peppery edge mf : light bodied & crisp , perfect balance super drinkability , a near perfect kolsch .

s : definitely sour with notes of apple and lemon which is influenced by the wild yeast . t & m : starts sour and finishes hoppy with a hint of barley in between . there is a lightness to this ale that would make it a decent session brew for the summer months . i think the look and smell of this brew is more rewarding than the actual flavor .  golden , pilsner-esque smoothly effervescent body ... white head settles into hazy 1/8-inch line -- dark for a hefe ? yet an ale ? smooth , ticklish and bubbly on the tongue ; soft aftertaste with a light-to-medium body ... fruity yeasts meet metallic , dry pilsner malts in a mix that softens and cools hot evenings ... complex and satisfying ... the brew leaves a gentle hop/malt combination , pleasant enough to present flowers to the nostrils but memorable in its ability to touch all bases in the brewing process -- dissecting this would be almost as rewarding as drinking !  extremely creamy mouthfeel !

this is a beautiful smelling brew . subtle yet balanced brew , follows the nose nearly perfect . thin mouthfeel ( 4/10 ) and just passes the threshold on carbonation .  looks like an old beer my grandpa would buy , but i like the bottle anyway . not much head at all , a little disappointing . does have a clear golden color .  and this was a grave mistake , as this beer is truly excellent . i noticed the mouthfeel before the flavor : the bottle conditioning mj pointed out on the label made this beer velvety smooth .

aroma is a really rich and exquisite odor ... very roasty with an extremely nice bourbon aroma and abundant alcohol esters . really quite good . very good - recommended .  a : dark orange amber , nearly opaque , hazy , clearly unfiltered , tan head s : spicy , slightly fruity with dominant malt aroma f : spicy , malty sweet , slightly fruity flavor with a bit of a rye bite , malt dominates m : creamy , medium body , lightly carbonated , clean sweet finish o : i think spicy , malty when i drink this beer .  very viscous .

very interesting and unusual smells for a beer .  decent head retention with minimal lacing . not exactly what i expect an imperial stout to look like .  fantastic palate , great mouthfeel , smooth silky yet carbonated very well .

smells wonderful . intense , fruity , banana and clove .  poured into chimay goblet . a : pours an opaque light amber . rather thin head that disappears immediately and becomes faint lacing .  black cherries take on a sweet and sour lemon , with balsamic edge , which is both mouth-puckering and refreshing . carbonation comes out as creamy in the forefront , with a medium blast in the throat , all at the same moment . then returns to being creamy and rolls down the throat . pleasing .

fresh and vibrant hops ! very inviting . t : the smell was phenomenal , the taste just could n't possibly live up to that . very delicious beer , do n't get me wrong , but the anticipation was immediately set way too high once i got a whiff of this beer . still a fantastic ipa nonetheless . that unique wet hopped taste is abundant here ... very fresh .  vintage 2004 . the colour is cloudy , deep ruby red with a tint of brown ; the beige finger thick foam dissolves quickly into a thin lid .  m : perfection here , this is a great beer for chewing .

appearance : very dark chocolate in color , looks almost like root beer with a minimal creamy tan head aroma : it smells amazing , like desert but in beer form . delicious . taste : malty and choclately , but not heavily or overpoweringly chocolately at all ... . just like a hint of chocolate mixed with the delicious malts and surprisingly - but refreshingly - bitter ( in my opinion ) hit of hops .  appearance : dark cola brown with reddish hues when looked through the light . barely a crown of lace .  the carbonation , while lacking in the glass , is perfect on the palate . the mouthful is fantastic .

aroma : bread yeast with a hint of hops appearance : painfully bright lemon yellow .  3.0 a : this is n't the best looking ipa i 've seen . deeply hazed orange amber color .  slightly dry taste toward the end m : perfect mouthfeel as far as i 'm concerned , very smooth and creamy goes down very well .

smell - hearty , fruity yeast aroma ( melon , kiwi ! ) with notes of sweet hops . last smell has earthy finish , with malty aromas and vaguely pumpkin-ish notes . fantastic ! taste - this is a seasonal ale with a lot of heart .  i 've had this wonderful beer twice ; both times i drank from the bottle , room temperature . if someone asks me to name the best `` beer '' i 've ever had , this is always my recommendation .  mouthfeel - 5.0 loved the mouthfeel .

the smell of this was forgettable . picking up just a whiff of pumpkin and spice .  raison brown amber color .  it 's extremely mouth filling and hefty , yet luxuriously smooth , like a silk-covered sandbag . the feel of it alone will keep me coming back . finish is long and roasty .

this smells fantastic . t- the taste starts out with some of the barnyard odor i picked up and some mildly acidic sourness . d- the beer was very good , but it costs too much . probably the best smelling beer ive ever come across .  a : pours a clear , wheat-orange brew with some decent carbonation , topped by a shallow foam head that dissipates quickly . does n't look like anything special .  this is an extremely active beer with an incredible mouthfeel .

this is from a 6 pk picked up at the local grocery this has to be the freshest batch of goose isl ipa i think ive ever had , first it didnt look amazing out of the glass which isnt anything new but boy when you get to the nose on this one its all citrus and floral and a light malt backbone , the taste is right on par with the nose and has a wonderful fresh hop taste with a good solid bitter , this is a stunning beer which hasnt happened ever before when ive drank one of these .  $ 14 for a 6-pack - damn hop shortage .  perfect texture .
smell is ridiculously potent . i like .  reviewed 12/24/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a clearish reddish brown color body . suspended particles .  mouthfeel is excellent , smooth as butter .

smelled a whiff of malt & more alcohol than even the 8.1 % would 've suggested . definitely not something you savor , albeit better than the smell of old english .  cool artwork , but he does seem to have some varicose vein issues going on with his legs ... a - opaque dark brown body with a tiny cap of beige head . i 'm a little disappointed by the lack of head on this beast ... especially since i expected at least two heads from what the label depicted .  m : perfect . big bodied , oily , and effervescent .

smell : cold and metallic . not too full of aroma here . a very pleasing barleywine .  pours a more ruby-brown with about a half inch of tan head on top . retention was zilch , and there was no lacing whatsoever . that is definitely an expendable weakness though , because this beer was stellar on all other counts .  thick and chewy with minimal carbonation ... exactly as this beer should be .

very , very aromatic wheaty/fruity mix that is just excellent . t : very crisp and earthy , organic kind of taste to it .  appearance : all appear similar , the organic being a fairly clear , dark gold color , minimal head , and little lacing .  this is a medium bodied brew with an exceptionally smooth feel .

the nose hints at light sweetness , with big white pepper and spicy hops on a bed of hay . great , appetizing , enticing nose . on the palate , this beer is quite sweet , due to both malts and , it would seem to me , present alcohol .  a- deep brown , a ruby red on the edges , little head and rim retention last long .  m : smooth , rich , creamy , this is how an ris should feel . not overbearing , but the perfect balance of robustness and smooth dessert like feel .

smell : aromas of grape cocktail mixed with that artificial table syrup . the grape is very faint . mouthfeel : very malty , bubbly and straightforward .  a : pours a mostly clear golden-amber body . 1-1/4 '' lightly creme colored head fades slowly . carbonation bubbles are almost non existent , only one or two tiny ones rise slowly now and then in the glass . d : another great offering from oskar blues in a can . very crisp , very drinkable .  mouthfeel on this beer is damn near perfection in glass .

smells deliciously complex . i get the brandy a little more in the flavor , with the bourbon , chocolate , and roasted malts all pulling through in fine form ... bit of a molasses presence ... very interesting brew ; unique and tasty ... not quite as delicious as the nose led me to believe , but close . big boozy kick to the finish , unsurpising given the 12.5 % abv on this bad boy .  the brewers call this a belgian blond which is a far more accurate description than the bpa designation found here at ba . '' but those liquid varieties iof monks ' daily bread tip the scale at 2.5 to a max of about 4 percent abv . i downgraded it a bit for appearance because my examples ( 2 ) have both been quite hazy , looking more like a saison or hefeweissbier . this new brewery ( hardywood park ) has just opened in my hometown , richmond , va. , and i am looking forward to seeing their singel proliferate and become the daily swill of our town 's growing beer-smart public . it 's very good beer .  just has a silky smoothness that feels great going down .

the aroma on this is amazing . i have always thought i smelled pine in a beer until i took a wiff of this . amazing smell . i think i have a really fresh bottle because it does n't seem any of the aroma imparted by the hopback used to produce this beer has died down at all . not many get a 5 , but i think this one deserves it as most amber ales are n't extremely strong in the aroma department and this one breaks the mold . flavor is a bit lighter than the aroma but is still very unique . a strong pine presence and a finish with a touch of diacytl .  the color is dark brown to mostly black , the brown around the edges . the head is tan in color and about 11/2 fingers high , and falls to a thin crown , but , leaves little to no lacing .  the mouth feel was perfect and represented an oatmeal stout very well .

never pleasant , but expected . beer seemed to lose that skunky smell ever so slightly as it warmed up to room temp .  hazy , ( not cloudy ) , straw colored thin head , no lace .  the mouthfeel on this beer is practically perfect , slightly sticky with a slight creamy texture added by the everlasting head .

the aroma is incredible ! ! i get strong notes of port and brandy and all sorts of other dank dank liquors from this bad boy .  poured into a pint glass 7/16/10 burnt golden color ; faded yellow when held to light . 1/4th inch of white foam dissipates quickly ; only a skim remains . not much for lacing .  mouthfeel : thick , rich , and velvety . harmony : i am very impressed by how balanced this is . : yes .

it has a great scent , with a wonderful apple kick thats very nice . it has a good ale flavor , with a nice maltiness and an interesting , if slightly sour , apple taste , as if a granny smith apple had been squeezed into the bottle . it goes down nice , if a bit fizzy .  dissapointing appearance for a stout . poured about a half inch head that reduced to almost nothing . the color is a solid black .  the mouthfeel is phenomenal , with high carbonation and light to medium body relative to its strength .
the aroma of this beer is so powerful ... spicy , phenolic . quite unique for my experience .  a : dark brown . no head , just white foam along the edge of the glass .  great creamy carbonation .

golden amber color and a good head forms and stays the aroma is perfect sweet citrus aroma and hint of alcohol to let you know to slow down but never to much the taste starts malt with an earthy bitter .  it is a normal looking brew . a small , creamy-headed straw-coloured beer with lots of continuous bubble action . very nice stuff . singha is a bit creamy and sweet for me to want to drink more than a half dozen at one sitting , but it is a damned nice beer and one i heartily recommend .  a creamy , medium body . perfect . in general , i love the look , aroma , and taste of this beer ... but it sits rather heavy , and the bittering is particularly forward .
fresh coffee bean smell intensifies as the beer gets warmer .  pours a quite dark amber color with zero head as expected .  m - medium bodied , creamy goodness . highly satisfying .

nose has rich chocolate , milk chocolate , fresh coffee beans , toffee and brown sugar . very rich and completely upfront . sort of a natural organic smell to it , medium bodied with a big present flavor . one of the most flavorful and simple stouts i 've had in while .  appearance , smell , taste , mouthfeel , drinkability a - deep reddish amber , little head .  m = luscious , thick , excellent mouthcoat .

the aroma is perfect . it has a very malty and complex scent that is sweet smelling . it has awesome aroma and flavor .  appearance : augusta saison pours a very hazy dark caramel color with straw colored highlights . about a finger of eggshell white head reduces down to slight lacing . seems a little dark colored for a saison .  m - incredibly creamy and smooth , with good carbonation . terrific mouthfeel and very well balanced .

the aroma was exactly that pumpkin pie smell , nutmeg , cinnamon , amazing . the taste was also like pumpkin pie , but with a nasty , bitterish aftertaste .  a - cloudy and golden with a quick dying head . nothing spectacular but nothing terrible .  this is a meaty brew ; full bodied and luscious , one of the best in my opinion . carbonation that was not very visible reveal themselves while sipping ; nice .

s - definitely one of the unique barrel-aged aromas i 've encountered . based on the other reviews , i 'm guessing some of the solvent and incongruous citrus hop character has faded over the past eight months . plenty of oak , earthy , and char . d - this was very good , and reaffirms my belief that half pints has the most `` american '' portfolio of any brewery in canada .  pours a clear light copper orange with a 1 inch fizzy orange-white head that fades to an oily film on the top of the beer . no lacing on this one on the drink down . kind of a disappointing appearance .  mouthfeel is quite nice .

roasted dark chocolate and coffee in the nose , the raisin and dried fruit character comes through clearly , texture is smooth and malty without giving up a fresh and lively feel . not for everyone but very captivating .  it has a dark cherry color , lightly hazed , with low carbonation and an off-white head .  imho : a good representation of the style ; good balance , very sweet with a great mouthfeel .

smell : the first most striking smell is that of raspberries and tart fruit . there is more going on in here and there is a certain bit of almost mushroom like mustiness .  poured into a british pint ... decent head that fades fast and did n't really rise up to the occasion . little lacing .  the mouthfeel is heaven ! round and full , yet thin enough to be easily drinkable .

s : sweet , warming alcohol reveals a surprising and delightful layered floral fragrance . notes of violets , lily , and lilac . lush and romantic . i could n't stop sniffing this one . t : sweet and heady , corresponds to smell- fresh flowers , sherry with faint nuttiness , sweet warm alcohol . d : lush , heady , and strong , this is not a beer for pounding . a little bit goes a long way , plus you 'll want to savor it . best in easy doses .  review from july 2010 a - it pours an orangey golden hue , relatively pedestrian in appearance .  m : smooth carbonation , almost velvety mouthfeel and nice dry finish that keeps this from being an overly sweet cloying beer .

s - sweet zombie jesus . massive assertive pink grapefruit assaults the nose . m - nicely carbonated with a good clean finish . if one does n't like grapefruit then this ipa would be rather eh but ... if you like grapefruit this is a great beer full of delicious fresh flavors and especially aromas . i love this beer .  deep cherry body with a faint beige head the recedes to nothing . no cap , no wisp ring , no lacing .  mouthfeel is great , it 's moderaletly carbonated is surprisingly very dry and you get a blast of flavor before you even swallow .

very dark appearance with a beautiful tan head . smelled like hazelnut , vanilla , and butterscotch candy . it was very tasty and could see this beer paired well with a desert like tiramisu or cheesecake .  a : this beer poured a cloudy orange/golden color . not really much to look at .  smooth creamy flavor compliments light acidity which ends in an exceptionally clean finish .

the nose is just outrageous , showing a huge aroma of coffee , milk duds ( the sure sign of extended barrel aging ) , bourbon and light leather . the flavor profile replicates the nose , but is n't quite as intense or outrageous .  thanks to roadhouse appearance : poured with 1 cm bubbly off white head that dissipated to a very thin rim around the top after 2 minutes leaving almost no lacing .  m- about as thick of a beer as i have had and it is great . the smoothness of it is wonderful . you barely pick up any carbonation and that is fine by me .

pours a golden color , but not your crappy beer yellow but we call it golden because it sounds better . smell is of hops , beautiful hops . great citrusy hops . my goodness is this hoppy .  a- no head to speak of . pours a muddy reddish brown , a bit like the color of mashed cooked cherries . really does taste like cherry pie . m - medium body , great carb , coating and somewhat velvety .  4.5/5 mouthfeel - smooth almost has a chewiness . exceptional .

s - huge vanilla and bourbon flavor , mixed with caramel malts , raisins , dark fruits , brown sugar and a hint of tobacco . big aroma on this one , particularly when warm . t - the taste has a little more bread to it , but still quite a bit of caramel and dark fruits , and of course a ton of bourbon and vanilla . there 's a nice dry finish , a lot of sharp wood bitterness in the aftertaste .  a : brownish orange color ; moderate head dissipates quickly ; slightly cloudy s : very sweet , fragrant t : very hoppy , bitter , herby ; a classic ipa , this beer has an abundant flavor that lingers long m : rich mouthfeel d : very attractive for repeats overall this is one of the better ipas i 've had .  solid , smooth and somewhat silky mouthfeel ; full and great drinkability .

this beer has a wonderful nutmeg and pumpkin aroma and flavor . not sweet ; they kept this a nice ale and did not try too hard to make this into a liquid dessert .  a - pours a deep copper , forming a 1/2 inch off-white head . no lacing remains on the glass .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . the carbonation seems a bit higher than other imp stouts , but it goes well with the very thick , almost syrupy texture of the beer .

the aroma is very inticing - an inviting mixture of almonds , butter , coffee , burnt currant , toffee , plum , cherry , and the list goes on and on . after the swallow , a roasty coffee flavor combines with the almond and lingers pleasantly . the mouthfeel is luscious and creamy . overall , i came to this expecting to be underwhelmed or at best , mildly impressed .  pours a medium brown color with amber'ish highlights . there 's a thin layer of head , but it 's pretty subdued . reminds me a of a slightly tweaked uk brown , but with everything ( especially the hops ) boosted a little bit . this is a thick brew that has chracteristics that remind me a little of a cask or nitro brown even straight from the bottle .  m : great mouthfeel , perfectly carbonated and medium bodied .

a - pours deep dark red , hazy , small purple head with little retention and lacing , lots of large bubble initially s - big aroma of sweet raspberries , like wisconsin belgian red , about as far from a `` beer '' smell as you can imagine t - lots and lots of sweet raspberries up front with a huge tartness quickly evolving , finish is very tart , sweet , and pretty dry m - not much carbonation evident , medium-bodied , moderately dry finish , tart raspberry coats the entire mouth d - because of the style and the intense sweetness and tartness , this is not the most drinkable beer , much more of a dessert beer that you can split a bottle of with someone , not at all a knock against quality , just not a beer you want to drink a ton of after having the wisconsin belgian red , i had high hopes for the raspberry tart , and it did not disappoint . a wonderful change-of-pace or dessert beer .  thanks to csmiley for sending this one out to me bottle poured into a pint glass produced a finger worth of white head that faded to a good lace . the body of the brew was an interesting reddish brown color .  so complex , loving it ... a wonderfully viscous lip smacker .

the nose is not all that strong -- can pick up traces of hops , caramel malt , yeast , and plum . overall , a robust and very enjoyable beer .  real ale 's sisyphus ( 2007 ) pours up with a bit of a wallop , lacking much in the way of effervescence but with enough carbonation to create a small , thinnish ring of beige head around the glass above a hazy , deep copper-orangish amber colored body .  lower carbonation levels and rich body lend to the extra smooth feel .

poured into a new belgium snifter appearance : pours jet black with a small 1/2 '' brown bubbly head , gives it the look like its going to taste very carbonated aroma : i dont get much here , light smells of chocolate and caramel . overall : a unique beer from a very good brewery .  pour an almost copper color , slight off white head that is hanging on . slightly hazed .  the palate is silky smooth and warm with just great balance and character .
enjoyable aroma and taste .  murky dark brown body with no head or lacing to speak of .  mouthfeel is perfect for this style .

the aroma was a beautiful mix of tart cherry , plum , raisin , oak , clove , coriander , biscuit , and yeast . the flavor revealed all of the above in copious amounts , however the alcohol was n't very well masked , and the after-burn was a little too much . nicely smooth and surprisingly carbonated for a thick beer . good to sip , but difficult to finish an entire 750ml in one sitting , especially because of the alcohol burn .  little to no head in the pour , despite my attempts to get something out of it . what little head their is collects in a small ring at the outside of the glass . pours a very dark black the consistency of motor oil .  m : full bodied with a great carbonation feel . awesome here !

s- man this one fragrant beer . big fruit basket notes of white grape , peaches , pears , and apricots . d- overall a very pleasant beer with many desirable qualities . i 'm curious if this would age well and the flavors might become a little more fluid .  appearance : slightly rusty yellow , minimal head , naturally cloudy and unfiltered . low carbonation .  very smooth and creamy mouthfeel to this one . moderate carbonation , extremely refreshing .

s : huge malty nose : chocolate , dark bread ; sour cherry , molasses , wood , alcohol .  appearance : dark brown to black . not much else going on visually .  the taste and feel to me are perfect . not super thick , but still able to coat and linger . a well balanced flavor not too sweet or bitter , and carbonation that lasts to the bottom .

very nice . there is good clean bitter to start off , and hops do continue to dominate this ale .  12oz bottle into a pint glass a : pours a reddish mahogany with a khaki head that fades to a thick ring and leaves no lacing on the glass .  real big , nice an simple mf/o : super viscous , super smooth , creamy , and velvety . the best feel to a beer that i 've ever experienced .

very strong chocolatey smell to this one . strong chocolate and sweet sugary scents .  appearance - a decent amber colored iced-tea brew . a brief head fades to nothing after a minute .  coats the mouth - very clingy .
deep , powerful scent that was quite hypnotizing .  pours a pale gold with a fair amount of head , not much lacing .  the mouthfeel is right where it should be .

insanely hoppy , fantastic aroma . mainly grassy , but some intensely bitter grapefruit rinds and a touch of peachiness and aspirin .  the beer coming out of this small green corked bottle sloshed around in the glass and settled into a rusty orange color brew with very little foam .  smooth and full bodied , creamy as anything i 've ever had .

it smells slightly spicy . it also smells slightly honey like . i hate to say it since i like most alesmith beers , but i am not too fond of the aroma of this beer . this beer tastes quite syrupy .  the abv is higher than i expected , because this beer is exceptionally drinkable , and you can enjoy several without feeling bloated . 2 of the 4 beers definitely surprised me ( the other being the backdraft brown ) .  m : well , due to nitro , it 's incredibly smooth , especially considering the style of beer .

smell - for a pilsner , the hops freshness is wonderfully strong in the smell . definely smells more like an outstanding ipa than pilsner , but its great none the less .  thanks again to mtunnell for sharing this awesome boulevard brew at the 'goop tasting' a - rye-on-rye pours a hazy brown with a dense off-white head . a low level of lace forms .  mouthfeel is perfect for the style .

2007 vintage poured into a pint glass a : very dark brown/almost black with creamy tan head s : wo , it smells as if i walked into a bourbon barrel , very bourbony and oaky . next thing i smell is vanilla , sweetness , and smokiness t : bitterness attacks the pallet followed by a malty sweetness with vanilla and carmel overtones . d : this beer is a wonderfully complex brew but one or two glasses is going to be more than enough for me notes : working my way through their big beer series and now having tried this and their hopmouth i am excited to get to the rest of their big beer line-up  no head . dark , rust-orange in color ( i 'm beginning to sense a trend here with the rogue stuff ) .  very very thick and chewy . almost a meal by itself .

s : a very stong hop smell like i had just rubbed my hands with hops at a brew tour .  no dating , but stamped on the cap is l4082 clear and dark golden wit not much head , only a dusting with some swirling , itsy bitsy bubbles in a thin ring at the edge .  mouthfeel was velvety , body was about the same as chocolate milk . it was n't overly thick , giving it a clean smoothness perfect for sessioning .

the aroma was absolutely amazing and so unique . super herbal , spicy and floral with notes of ginger and orange zest . as the beer warmed , the ginger became progressively stronger .  pretty much no head , low carbonation .  its all creamy peanut butter with chocolate , actually its really awesome , but has me perplexed as on tap it was tons of vanilla and bourbon . a tad too rich for me , but its good ... the taste gets us back on track , more oak , chocolate and bourbon come through , still missing the vanilla though . finish is bitter , adds to keep the experience interesting . the alcohol is hidden well , creamy from start to finish . this was good , but not as good as tap where i was blown away .

excellent aroma . cherries are the star but they do not dominate to the point that the other aromas are masked . t - the taste is a touch of a let down after the incredible nose , though it still is a nice tasting beer . very effervescent and i might say it is a touch too carbonated . o - a very solid beer though i would say it is a touch of a let down , especially given how amazing the nose was . certainly a good beer and i would not mind having one to lay down for a while .  the head is nice but far too short lived .  it 's strong point was the mouthfeel . it was amazingly very smooth , probably the smoothest beer i 've had to date .
terrific , one-of-a-kind fruity taste with a smell to match .  a : pours a chill-hazed amber with a small head .  m/d - mouthfeel was rich and creamy and coats the mouth .

smell : very rich aromas , of grass and hay , wheat all over , like the fields vincent painted in saint-rmy-de-provence while rapidly and unstoppably descending into sheer madness . taste : very yeasty , like being at a bakery . pleasant , but not as exciting as the incredible nose . mouthfeel : carbonation is low , body is medium , flavor is full . a bit too much beer overall , i would not session or have several in one sitting , but super delicious nonetheless .  2006 vintage . murky brown color with no head .  mouthfeel is pure silk . very creamy .

a wonderful bouquet - grassy , floral hops , some coriander and a strong lemon coating . again that lemony taste sneaks up . good , complete , simply lovely .  head is 2 fingers and rocky . retention is average with good lacing .  really big , rich mouthfeel . thick and chewy with a smooth carbonation , which suits the decadence of the flavour well . in fact , this is one of the most perfectly matched mouthfeels i 've come across , so top marks for goose island !

d : this had an amazing scent , with very nice taste and body . very enjoyable brew .  a : brownish red , not much head , some lacing s : tart mixed berries up front , considerable amount of lactic acid character , hints of oak t : as the beer hits the tongue , the sourness is puckering , it quickly mellows out by mid palate and sweetness overtakes , the finish is a bit sharp and leaves a lingering tartness mf : light body , high carbonation d : alcohol is well hidden , over all this beer offers a nice tartness but the finish is a little disappointing .  the mouthfeel is full , lucious , slick and creamy , which makes for a most addictive imbibing experience . overall , a fantastic brew , i will certainly seek out other vintage offerings from this brewery .

i am getting an education in ipa 's and i love it ! aroma : mmm ... does this beer smell good ! pineapple is the first thing to hit your nose , along with a lot of citrusy , fruity hops . in a good way . taste/mouthfeel : lemon and coriander with just a tiny bit of bitterness in the back .  pours like a cloudy ice tea , very murky , and with very little to no head . not a pretty beer .  it tastes very nicely and ballanced of amber malts , hops , smoke and juniper , and it just feels great , full and creamy body with moderately low carbonation , just the way i like it .

wonderful blended aroma of floral hops , resinous grassy herb , pine , grapefruit , you name it . this has a great nose . taste is a little tame comparatively but still solid .  thin soapy head on an amber to light copper beer . rich caramel and toasted nuts , with a slight hop aroma in the smell . caramel and slight roasted character in the malt , slight hop grassiness , very clean yeast character , with a pleasant bitterness at the end . slightly undercarbonated , but very smooth , for the style , this was slightly heavy ... a very clean and malty apa , that dose n't revolve around hop aroma and bitterness .  extremely smooth from start to finish , one of the most pleasant beers in mouth and after .

its a beautiful thing . a slight touch of chocolate but over all its all coffee .  appearance is a hazy , dark brown ... not overly appealing really .  m - heavy . think store-bought chocolate milk made with whole milk .

what a good start s- strong piny citrus . smells like a hopheads dream t-woah tons of piny hops . i got this bottle very fresh .  aroma- earthy , deep carab , chocolate , a hint of acridity gives it an edge , deep and layered , but tight and not jumping out of the glass appearance- thin , dark espresso head leaves no lace . if you are the kind of person who spends 8 bucks on designer chocolate at the healthfood store , you 'll probably love this .  incredible carbonation for such a headsy brew .

aroma was excellent . hops .  a : very cloudy , deep straw color . a smooth pour produces minimal head that does retain well , and leaves some spotty lace .  a great mouthfeel that is easily recognizable .

no aroma from my pint glass even when it 's right under my nose .  rusty-brown colored pour with minimal head .  mouthfeel is like the appearance , a wondrous experience . it sets the standard for mouthfeel on a stout .

awesome . t - nice tart punch up front , wild fresh raspberries , alcohol prickle in the throat on the finish .  this beer pours a hazy medium golden hue , with one finger of fizzy white head , which disappears in an instant , leaving no remnants , lace or otherwise .  mouthfeel is just about perfect .

s - vanilla right away with milk chocolate and caramel .  i consider myself a beer guy because i like the strong bitter flavors of beer , as opposed to the sweet flavors of wine . it is a complex and rewarding beer to drink . if you think you might like to try a more 'cultured ' fruit beer , then i highly suggest this . the apple is the dominant theme , though the wheat beer base is strong enough to stand alone . this foundation is key and adds to the drinkability of the beer , while the apple note rides the head and the aftertaste leaving the mouth anxious for more .  f : body has medium viscosity . full and creamy , goes smooth over my tongue .

the aroma is quite extraordinary and captivating , but sadly the taste does not quite match .  poured into my 16 oz sam adams perfect pint glass a- brown with reddish hints..you could call it mahogany if you will . small 1/2 inch head that quickly dissipates . s- boozy malty sweetnes , cherrys in the forefront with other dark fruits t- wow , can you say dessert ? this is a drinkable cherry cream pie . very sweet malt profile with cherrys in the forefront and throughout the whole beer ... cherrys all over ... everywhere..ahhh . i am telling you this is dessert in a bottle . its like having 2 pieces of cherry cream pie for dessert ... no one does that .  love the mouthfeel on this , creamy , and a quick swish turns this into a frothy coffee milkshake .

lots to find here ! i felt funny buying this out of season , but it 's equally delicious around a campfire or firepit ( or on the couch in front of the tv ! ) during the summer . there 's some great complexity to both the aroma and flavor .  i found this beer very thirst quenching and satisfying , as it was well balanced and flavorful .  the body is fantastic . it is -- just as the name says -- like cream : slick , glassy and wonderful .

smell has the typical english hop aroma.very nice caramel scent and nice alcohol warmth .  reviewing this one for the first time , also the first time ive tried this one : ) served from brown 341ml bottle a- comes out of the gate with an explosive head that diasappears in mear seconds , the beer attempts to lace so hard but nothing doing here , lots of bubbles rising to the surface but no real head .  medium-light and very creamy in the mouth ; lots of bubbles .

its a perfect smell . it deserves its own goddess , a piazza fountain , and perhaps an epic poem or two .  on the pour : looks light for an ale..pale light gold with a white head , fads fast with little lacing , but the nose on pour was great , flowers and hops .  smooth , creamy mouthfeel with light carbonation .

really a very complex and interesting nose on this beer .  pours a light black with a single finger near-white head that suggests black barley . no lacing and head has a light body with mid-staying power .  truly exceptional creaminess . overall this was a refreshing take on the style with exceptional mouthfeel .

perfect imperial stout smell ! alcohol nose . burnt molasses , roasted barley , and a big malt sweetness converge in you nose so much you can taste the beer .  i 'm quite surprised by the scores here , this was the best beer of the day at mth ... pours a dark straw lightly clear ... the aroma is a really nice combo of wet grassy hops , immediately reminds me a stronger daisy cutter , nice but one-noted .  wonderfully thick and coating .

batch # 3 ( bottled feb. 2009 ) very pleasing aroma , smells creamy and rich . medium brown coloring with a ton of particles floating in it .  poured the typical pale ale color , a medium gold , with a solid 1 inch head that left minimal lacing . a solid , smooth and clean body makes this a very drinkable beer , one you could spend a sunny spring afternoon with , as i just did .  the body is delightful , silky smooth , a little warmth is all the warning you get from this strong brew .

the aroma is really amazing : spices are very predominant ( not sure if added , or ferm .  rich , dark brown in color . forms a thin , fragile , tan film on top which sticks around for about a second or two .  smooth and creamy mouthfeel with a hop free finish .

the smell was incredible , a rich chocolate malt that was almost like dessert . a fabulous porter !  the bytown brown has a nice but delicate aroma . the colour was of course brown , a wee bit on the darker side .  m - thought this beer was very smooth and carbonated to perfection , definetely got the mouthfeel down pat .

i spent some very enjoyable time smelling the beer before tasting it . the smell was sweet with a hint of bublegum and burnt sugar . appearance was that of a good , standard ipa .  the beer was a strangely yellowish color -- not like a miller or bud or anything , but deeper and richer .  m : extremely creamy and smooth , this goes down better than most any beer i 've tried .

aroma- clean smell with a light floral hop . nothing huge here and expected much more !  pours a ruddy brown , minimalistic impressions of head formation .  mf : this beer excels compared to other dipas with a velvety mouthfeel and the perfect amount of carbonation .

fantastic smelling brew , i ca n't keep my nose out of the glass !  thick as is to be expected of its brew , but not disgusting like mud .  mouthfeel/drinkability- one of the finest textures of any belgian beers i 've sampled , the mouthfeel is stunning ... smooth and rolling foam that only gets better the longer it 's there .

this was a light golden pour with a distinctly unique nose that i had never really found in an ipa . the finish was sweetness clearing but not as effervescent as the nose .  pours a very hazy reddish brown . a one finger head emerges and sticks around for a while .  the mouthfeel is ultra smooth and creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .

scent is what 's advertised : chocolate stout . perfectly balanced taste . chocolate is just right , not overly powerful .  poured a hazy and pale yellow color with a huge bubbly white head .  mouthfeel : stupendous . initially evervescent so as to allow a cascade of flavors and finally dry and comforting .

s : citrusy pine aroma . love dem hops .  pours a very dark amber color , but is somewhat translucent . not very carbonated and not very heady , little or no lacing .  crisp , well carbonated , has that indescribable quality that makes you want to drink more , and yet more .

this is billed as a spearmint infused ipa and that is exactly what you get ! like fresh mulled , whole leaf , spearmint iced tea . you better like spearmint or this one is not for you . d-well , my first mint bomb for sure !  appearance is an orangish cloudy color . not much head formed at all .  light spice gorgeous balance . flawless . the carbonation make this beer in my opinion .

very bold piney , citrus hop aroma . grapefruit , tangerine , and other citrus flavors dominate with floral and pine , but malt backdrop a bit on the sweet side . nice west coast style overhopped ipa much more complex and fruitier than hop stoopid .  punkin appears mild red in color , it is clear .  m : excellent : rich , tongue-coating medium body , supported throughout by abundant , smooth , rolling carbonation .

now i like vanilla so this was really cool , but it was *very* dominant .  pours deep brown red with many chunks of sediment .  m : thick , viscous and chewy ; one of the creamiest mouthfeels i 've ever encountered . yes .

smell is quite interesting . lemon , citrus , wet cardboard , touch of white grapes , floral notes of lillys and lavender .  batch 2x3 poured into a tulip 750 ml bottle thanks to forgetfu for this in a massive trade a -- poured a dark brown and settled dark black cherry color . good amount of haze . no head at all . on swirling the glass got some head but went bye quickly .  m : this is what makes this beer one of the smoothest i have ever experienced . almost like silk .

a very , very , very aromatic beer ! fruity , yeasty , sweet aroma . yet the simplicity is not a bad thing . in fact , it 's quite an enjoyable thing , because it 's so well-refined .  poured into an eku glass . a : nice amber color with great clarity and somewhat active carbonation . fizzy orange tinged head comes and goes quickly . leaves no lace .  though the bittering is brazen , the plush mouthfeel makes for a high quaff quotient .

when i first opened the bottle , the aroma of the hops absolutely smacked me in my nose like a mike tyson uppercut . lots of pine and a little bit of citrus too . nice orange color .  poured from the bottle into a bruery tulip and served with thanksgiving leftovers . the color is a somewhat-light chestnut brown that pours with a moderately-disappointing single-finger head with just a touch of lacing and not that much retention . there is a slight bubble ring around the glass throughout , however .  m & d -- mouthfeel 's the strongest of the beers i sampled from sly fox -- super creamy and mellow .

smell : i swear it smells like beef stew . not good taste : clean , mineraly , moderate hop flavor .  very good , very easy to drink ; great on a hot day ... but ordinary . it poured too light in color -- pale straw , with a nice two-finger head and moderate amounts of lace .  m : medium-full bodied and silky smooth . this is one of the creamiest , smoothest beers i 've ever had and is an absolute joy .

the aroma is very unique , i do n't really have a good word to describe it , so i will just say it is different and i like it .  a- reddish brown with a white cap that builds and falls just as fast . ends up with the juice look .  mouthfeel - more carbonation that what is visible . the mouth and tongue become numb after a while between the hops and the carbonation . quite memorable .

the smell is immediately impressive as you can smell this sucker from a mile away , with big piney , citrusy , fruity , and floral hop notes , along with some caramel , rye , biscuit , fruity esters , and a little alcohol ... truly amazing aroma here . the flavor is not quite as impressive as the aroma , with a huge hops blast upfront ( consisting of citrus and pineapple , and a little pine resin and grass character ) , along with some bread dough and caramel , fruity ale esters , and a wallop of alcohol . really enjoyed this one , though the aroma made a promise that the flavor could n't deliver upon . very nice beer from ob , easily my favorite of their lineup .  the colour is copper ( a bit paler than expected ) ; the two finger head is compact and beige . it sinks slowly with a fizzing sound without leaving much lacing .  mouthfeel is stellar with this beer . full and creamy with a touch more carbonation than the average stout .

the aroma was an interesting and impressive blend of citrusy hops and banyard funk . slightly oaky and vinous . vinegar notes were also detectable . once again , an intriguing mix of must/funk and punchy , citrusy hops . the brett character came through strong , particularly up front . some sweet malts were noticeable as well . overall , however , the beer the beer started a touch weak . crisp , bubbly and sprightly .  a : pale cloudy yellow , next to no head .  perfect for the style .

this smells incredible . smells just like thier red barn but with more sweet belgum yiests .  355ml bottle poured into pint glass 9/10/11 a clear dark copper with lots of little bubbles but not much for head or lace s a fruity nut bar with some hard toffee a little herbal hops and plenty of sweet malty goodness , fairly earthy and right on for the style t what i smell but a little leafy tea bag and some booze , not quite as nice as the smell but still pretty darn good m medium bodied with a sweet after taste that lingers o pretty solid marzen that 's working well with this chilly fall weather and the turkey dinner making me fatter i did n't even realize this was in the mixed pack i picked up but i 'm happy its in there .  great carbonation .

s : yeast esters ; light-colored fruits . mild clove and pepper spices . t : sweet malt character up front . o : solid representation of the style .  12oz bottle poured into an ale glass appearance-pours pure black with a very thin brown head forming . disappointed with the appearance which was lacking lacing and the brown frothy head some people here have stated .  really smoothe and thick on the mouth .

a bit chewy , and ultimately dry , but still quite excellent . overall , a delicious beer from terrapin , and a long-overdue mainstream style worthy of their name .  pours an opaque darkness with a wispy shallow off tan head that fades quickly , leaving negligible lacing in it 's wake .  t/m : the taste is a citrus , grapefruit hop dominance , but the mouthfeel is as creamy as a glass of milk . a very interesting brew that works out very well .

huge smell of strawberry and other fruit flavors . the taste is not as sweet as i expected and is very different from the smell . tastes of rye with a fruity sweetness and finishes dry .  when i first started drinking , i thought snpa was way too bitter . sierra nevada pale ale is an excellent choice for a `` real '' beer experience . i recommend sierra nevada pale ale with any rich dinner , as the crisp ale and bitter hops cut through the fattiness , especially with a good steak .  but what it lacks in scent , it makes up for in mouth-feel and taste : a moderate hoppy bite in the mouth with a superbly mellow honey-like finish and a nice residual alcohol taste . the mouth feel is as thick as melted ice cream .

first sniff evokes the most creamiest , coffeeist , deliciousist mocha flavors that i 've ever experienced.at this point , this beer is in the running , neck-n-neck with peche mortel , to establish a true champion . seriously , smell this beer , and name a coffee ( with this aroma ) that you 'd rather be drinking.smooth body and flows effortlessly over the palate , unlike other bitter presences .  looked up rue and i just hope ... nevermind . poured with a smallish off white head and a little lace .  silk smooth mouth .

smell is very nice and big with fruity , honey soaked hops , reminiscent of grapefruit and peaches especially as it warms . very low hop bitterness in fact , and could use a touch more bitterness to make it pop , but the hop flavor is very good .  bottle pours a very unclear light straw color . a big head which dissipates some but stays until the end .  carbonation is perfect . kudos on great mouthfeel .

smells amazing - malt , spices , and alcohol , wow .  pours dark brown with a small tan head which turned to film rather quickly .  the alcohol just lingers in the mouth a while , hence the 5 for mouthfeel . full bodied and thick in the mouth with a nice warming feeling .
very appealing . first sip reveals , average body with very mild carbonation .  completely opaque with no head .  thick and constantly evolving . they have fresh and full body . very dry .

2010 bottling . i saw all the reviews and had big expectations . a bitter hops flavor gives way to spice but to me just does n't come together properly .  hazy golden , w/ lots of carbonation , ebelweiss has lots of banana & clove on the nose & palate .  crisp and smooth in mouth , despite being served at sub-zero temperatures .

smells like raisins , rum , molasses , and chocolate syrup . very sweet .  a : pours a light straw color ; no head , no lacing s : tart apples with a delicious thick butterscotch/popcorn smell t : tart sour apple notes up front ; quickly transitions into a soft , warm caramel/butterscotch flavor as it travels down the tongue .  m - light to medium body and moderate carbonation .

s : spicy raisins and sherry . t : spicy , prunes , strong/warming alcohol in the aftertaste .  freshest by : nov. 20 , 2010 appearance : it has a light honey/brandy color with a 0.5 '' head that quickly dissipates . there 's a thin white film of lacing .  i 've had triples with higher content and less alcohol taste -nice feel in the mouth . smooth , malty and sweet . -not a bad beer by any means , just not what i was expecting . this beer did n't have that nice belgian greeting you get with the first mouthful .

bouquet is a big fat giant apple butter smell . really nice i like that a lot . taste comes out as average because of a high c02 component on finish and a weak bodied mouthfeel . the beer has fantastic components on it that are flat out fantastic , but make me wonder if it was ruined .  pours a still , clear amber with no head and no lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is quite lively , but does not make up for the almost empty taste .

aroma is n't as strong as other dipa 's i 've had but good . very citrucy . kinda pineapple and citric .  appearance : dark brown brew with a frothy tan head that dissipates quickly .  m - good . nice and thick , which is what you would expect for a decent imperial stout .

smell : not much to speak of . slight hints of burnt malts ... smells iron , almost blood-like .  kalamazoo stout pours black with just a little bit of tan head that quickly recedes . there is no evidence of lacing .  m : good , full body , adds quite a bit to the beer .

aroma is banana , peat , malt , spice .  sampled on 6-4-07 pours a surprisingly light and clear yellow , with a minimal head and decent lacing .  m - this stuff is very thick , definitely full bodied , chewy , and a decent amount of carbonation .

it actually smells rather pleasant . sweet , pilsner , it has a slight odd aroma to it but it definitely does n't smell bad .  a powerful pour begets few bubbles ; a millimeter-thick film is all that rises from the depths before disappearing forever . the lack of carbonation that dinged the appearance actually works beautifully here .  this beer is full of funk and bubble gum , yeasty , doughy , a little too sour for a saison . but it may be better with food not an easy brew to drink alone unless you want half 3 philosophers and half duvel in the same glass : ( sorry hut dissapointed . tastes better with food

not very complex but strong and pleasant . citrusy and tart at first sip , this beer starts out tasting like alcoholic 7up .  decided not to pour into a glass . i got ta say its a little low on the hops to be called an ipa , they are there it 's just not the punch i 'm used to . it makes me thirsty for another one , but that would n't help a bit .  33cl bottle a : nice head light golden , pale straw colour , nice carbonation , overall looks like it shoulkd look s : hops , malts , sweet bread t : basically the same thing as the smell only with a slight metallic taste m/d : good mouthfeel , very drinkable .

s : aromas of coffee , roasted grain , and dark fruits fill the nose .  a_pours a dark straw hue with a medium size off white head . this settles a bit too quickly into a smallish cap .  body is smooth and slightly creamy , which is pleasant and very much in character for the style . still , while refreshing , this is n't a particularly tasty beer .

aroma : sugary malts , with a strong spiciness , possibly cinnamon . there is also a dusty smell , like an old room ... yeah , weird , huh ? taste : the flavours are fruity , supported by the strong raisin and grape tastes . the aromas are not great , and had me expecting something terrible from the taste but i was pleasantly surprised by the rich fruity malts and gentle sweetness .  it does seem to be a time of great double ipa 's in america . it is hoppy to the point of being almost like a nice morning cup of grapefruit juice . all in all this is a quite drinkable double ipa , refreshing and full flavored , but still easy to get down , and with out the total pallet ruination ( wink , wink ) of some other double ipas .  nice light body and sparkly carbonation .

nice bitterness , good color and lacing and lots of malt flavor and aroma . but the burning alcohol dominated everything else .  a- pours a nice cloudy golden orange color with 1 with finger head . the head is fluffy but recedes rather quickly .  i bought this one at new beer distributors in nyc , a non-conditioned warehouse with a great a great selection ... im worried that its gone bad : a. pours a cloudy dark amber , with almost no head s. smells like sweet and sour yeast , malts , and a hint of bitter fruit t. sweet up front with some light malts , hints of sour , and finishes with a slight oakey , bourbony alcohol warmth m. medium and chewy d. not very , too sweet , this one is a sipper this beer does not taste very fresh -- it was aging in hot warehouse , probably for over a year , reminds me of a sweet bruin aged in oak barrels .

the aroma is sweet with a definite floral note to it , ca n't detect any of the cocoa . this beer just looks weird , smells weird and taste even weird .  peachy honey-gold , thick with bubbles , but not up top where it counts . brown sugar , caramel , apples , lemon , and a very nice , mellow but robust bay leafy herbal hop character round out the aroma . i suspected that in making a `` beer to dine for '' greene king was basically attempting an ale that tastes like a bland , inoffensive continental lager . bland it is n't ; it 's flavorful , grainy , husky , and sweet , well spiced with a sort of citric-herbal hop profile , nicely accentuated by a fizzy , airy mouthfeel . nice fruity undertones of grapes and orange as well . very good , i think , and indeed it was good with the chicken soup and rye crisps i paired it with .  somewhat creamy mouthfeel , finishes bitter .

malted wheat smell , a roasted , toasted malted wheat that is . as the beer warmed the bananas and caramel from the smell came into play , as did a vanilla sweetness .  pours a pale gold color with a small white head , the only underwhelming aspect of this beer .  light bodied and very smooth going down .

the harpoon winter multi-pack is a pretty good deal ; the beers are all pretty good , though they are mostly similar brown styles . s - as with nearly all of harpoon 's winter offerings , this beer has obvious notes of cocoa , along with a rich toffee malt presence . t - it tastes a bit wimpy ; the flavors are there , chocolate , roast , and bitter hop , but they are muted or 'mild ' , and it does n't serve this beer well .  i too am taken aback by this beer ; a good offering from ab ! pours a reddish-brown with a big rocky , off white head .  she 'll drink lindemans , but complains it 's too sweet . this is definitely less sweet and more funky . flavor is of tart raspberry juice with a funky edge , perhaps the oak . i 'm pretty sure this lambic is hopped , because there 's a really interesting play between the sour flavors of the lambic and bitter undertones in the beer .

glugs out a murky dull orange with zip for a head or carbonation ... nada ... uh oh ... well it certainly smells the part ... lots of actual pumpkin aroma with the usual cinnamon and nutmeg and allspice ... sweet malty background ... pretty good aromas ... dull maltiness brings an overwhelming spice and bitterness with it . almost like shaking ground cinnamon onto your tongue ... you get the cinnamon flavor along with a sharp biting bitterness that 's not at all pleasant ... lots of booziness as well ... reminds me of the bottle of pumking that i had that was way too boozy and spicy ... majorly disappointing ... schlafly 's offering wipes the floor with this ...  a : this was a bright golden color , a little on the dark side .  its probably the mouthfeel and the smooth sweet after taste that has changed my mind about this one .

no carbanation at all ... the aroma is ok , light wood , vinous , sweet , just not much funk , hard to think of this as a wild ... the taste is terrible , no funk , woody , harsh , stale .  it features dark garnet color , a placid mouthfeel , and a breezy haybale fragrance with moderate spice thats right where it should be .  body light and lagerlike , tho quite cohesive . rather lightly malted , like most of leine 's beers . god bless this family for outlasting the merger mania of the 1970s , but i wish they 'd brew some more substantial beers , like yueungling 's does .

great nose but after that not much great about it .  a nice medium colored golden beer . small white head only one quater of an inch stayed a while .  zero carbonation evident . palate : medium body and medium carbonation . this is the best aspect of the beer . average .

ah hurricane irene , you bitch ! s - cocoa nibs and a milky roasted malt . touch of char or smokiness , not much .  the beer pours a cloudy gold color with a short lived white head .  there 's a lot of hype for this brew , perhaps that 's because it 's trappist , but i ca n't for the life of me see what a lot of others see in it . not with brews like st. bernardus , rochefort , westmalle and chimay coming out of the same country . the flavour is equally misplaced , with notes of cherry amidst a weak , bark-like overtone . i notice the previous reviewer mentioned champagne , and this definitely has a somewhat champagne finish . it 's a brew that does n't quite know what it wants to be ... ale , kriek , champagne ? pass , thanks .
wonderfull complex smell , which keep me sniffing for 10 minutes .  cloudy yellow witbier color , nice fruity and clovy aroma . minimal head , avg lacing .  medium mouthfeel .

zero lacing & head retention s : roasty malt & choclate , plus coffee once warm t : coffee dryness up front , more of the same as this warms , plus roasty malt .  drank this one straight from the bottle . this is a very good brew and could drink these all night with a nice plate of spicy wings .  light mouthfeel with the right amount of carbonation .

poured into my pint glass from a bottle a : pitch black , small amount of tan head , tiny soapy lace ring s : loads of blacck coffee , hints of roast malt and chocolate . t : black coffee grounds , huge bitterness , earthy dirt flavor touch of smokiness m : medium to light body , a bit thin , low carbonation d : overall nothing real impressive , pretty average/  pours a slightly cloudy dark brown . head dissipates after a minute and leaves no lacing .  rich , buttery mouthfeel holds a palate of light hops , fruit ( apricots ? ) , and some breadiness . finishes with a very nice buttery texture and a taste of dry roasted malt .

) the aroma was pleasantly sweet and boozy . ginger and allspice were quite apparent , along with ripe fruits and sweet caramel malts .  a - alot of carbonation to this very pale brown brew . the bubbley head is white and fades very fast .  small head that dissipates quickly , solid carbonation throughout , seems like a dirty iced tea . mouthfeel : solid and crisp . very clean .

it has a nice head and a fruity nose ( chewing gum ) , that 's slightly yeasty .  this beer is nothing more than a very nice , full bodied brew with no unpleasantries . a good beer for any occasion and it would also be a good choice for any mainstream lager drinkers who wish to experiment with a mellow craft ale option . hopefully , calling it a spice beer is n't a deterent for those who are curious about giving this very tasty beverage a try .  mouthfeel/overall : mouthfeel is pretty good .

not overly complex or powerful , but good . flavours on the palate are light and unimpressive .  this pours with little to no head and was gone in 2 seconds .  m- medium body with pervasive delicate carbonation .

aroma of earthy and citrus / leaning strongly toward grapefruit hops .  a clear , deep red colored body , tiny white head does n't stick around for long .  m : fairly creamy , thick , and smooth .

was the color of varnished pine . s - wheat , tons of it . some yeast . basically the quintessential weissbier . smells dry , like roasted tea leaves , some flowery esters .  pours a golden color with a white , thin head that fades fast , lively carbonation .  the flavor also starts out with mostly malted flavors , slightly biscuity and once again a husky , grainy astringency . the hops are hidden in the background adding some minor floral and dry herb flavors and a mild bitterness , that is well balanced overall . the beer is well balanced , maybe a touch too malt forward , but their is a slight drying astringency and the flavors are n't well pronounced , and i would prefer a bit more hoppiness . not a bad beer per say , but i can say with confidence , i will never buy it again .

the bouquet is charming too ... a spicy and aggresive mix of coriander and pepper .  not much to look at . a little bit of butterscotch and chocolate . the brew is still good but perhaps it 's surpassed it 's aging peek .  there is a hint of citrus t : thin and watery with nearly no hop until the very end . m : the mouthfeel is nice and hearty . it is n't over or under carbed and it carries well throughout the tongue .
