way too bitter and hopped up , foul aftertaste ! it was not `` skunked '' , the aroma was what i expect from porter .  a : cloudy golden color could be caused by the decent amount of yeast in the bottle . has a thin white head that does n't last very long . the mouthfeel is , to me , the most outstanding quality in a fantastic beer .  the mouthfeel is medium and there is a pleasant level of carbonation .

nice dry malt nose with prominent but not overpowering spice ( sorry , but i 'm bad at identifying spices ) but it'ssomething in pumpkin pie ( nutmeg ?  poured with and without sediment to compare . appearance : very light golden color with some thin white foam ; with the yeast the beer became golden and cloudy .  taste : spices ( clove and banana ) and malt with the presence of alcohol flavor ( but not overpowering ) mouthfeel : high carbonation , crisp with a smooth finish .

s : milk chocolate , burnt caramel , vanilla , a hefty dose of smoked malts adds a rather campfire-like smell , faint notes of herbal , minty hops . the nose was very promising , but the complexity was just not there in the taste .  appearance- pours a very dark , almost black opaque body with a thick loose but creamy tan head . no head retention at all .  mouthfeel is nice had good body and goes down smooth .

aroma is sweet and mildly citrus hoppy .  16 oz twist off bottle poured into a nonic . clear deep red-brown color with a light tan creamy head that quickly dissipates to a ring and leaves no lacing .  the mouthfeel is pretty solid . medium bodied , decent carbonation , moderately sticky .
candied-sugar and honey sweetened malt with light toffee and caramel notes .  cloudy orange-with a brownish hue . decent lacing .  m fairly light bodied with medium carbonation .

smell - sweet malt , caramel , and hops present .  a- clear mahogany/red with a small and short lived beige head . a couple small patches of lace remain stuck to the glass .  light to medium body with some nice light carbonation .

the smell is very sweet and fruity .  poured a deep orangish with a flat head that kind of took the wind out my sails .  the mouthfeel is fine , drinkability is ok , the aftertaste is n't excessively long or unpleasant , but it 's just not that tasty .
three years later shared a bottle that was great chocolate and incredible aroma .  a : red , and very hazy . like , much , much too hazy .  the body is smooth and creamy . moderate carbonation .

s : twang of astringent grain . not much caramel comes through . t : caramel malt , no hop presence noticed . it does n't compare to my favs like hacker-pschorr and paulaner , but i do n't dislike it .  street , now chuo park avenue , outside gate two kadena ab , okinawa . it was perfect for the hot climate . i really like this beer .  mouthfeel : medium to fully body , dry , tingly hops on the tongue , medium carbonation .

smell was better . thats more like it !  appearance has a nice golden color with little head , but good lace .  full carbonation to the mouth feel helps distract from taste , and it has some smoothness to it .

the aroma is almost sweet and very fruity , with notes of berries , orange peel and wheat .  appearance : pours a dark brown , near black body with no real substantial head formation , but i was running my damn mouth , so i could 've just missed it .  m - full-bodied and refreshingly crisp in carbonation d - i 'll drink the 6-pack over a few nights , but i 'm rather disappointed in the brew .

( s ) - spices of nutmeg , cinnamon , allspice , clove , and apples , very cider-like . not as pleasant as the smell was offering . the pale ale aspect and the spices added really conflict with each other in a way that i am not a fan of .  pours a very dark amber ... almost black with a half finger head that melts quickly to ... nothing .  medium body and oily with low carbonation .

s : sweet malts , dark fruit , earthy hops , caramel , vanilla and some strong alcohol presence . hmmm ... t : alcohol is surprisingly dominant . not sure what it was , but i 'm pretty sure it 's not an oatmeal stout should probably be classified as a strong ale .  bomber poured into an oversized tulip . a : pours a clear pumpkin orange with a thin white head . no lacing .  it fades a little as it warms , letting chocolate eek through . it 's very hot , very boozy , with some chocolate bitterness coming through in the aftertaste . again , the alcohol overwhelms the other flavors . i 'm used to drinking big , strong beers , and this one does n't hide the alcohol at all .

honey colored . s-smells good and funky with some belgian spices and sugars . decent strength . d-overall , this is a weak gueuze , but not a terrible one .  beer is dark brown in color . no retention , minimal lacing .  it feels pretty dry , overall . mouthfeel : medium body with a good level of carbonation and creaminess . the texture is quite nice .

d - looked good , smelled good but it did n't deliver on taste .  appearance - average fizzy looks with a golden color .  nice fragrant hops in the nose and then ... butterscotch and band-aids full mouthfeel , hop bite on the tongue and then ... medicinal then ... finally an acrid farewell .

the smell here is amazing , smells like a latte almost , roasted coffee and sweets mixed with roasted malts and oatmeal , the good sweets are definitely from the oatmeal . taste is almost the same , roasted malts and coffee , a bit of hops bitterness , a bit of sweets but then there is some weird watery taste that throws it all off but does not ruin the taste .  pours a dark brown with ruby highlights but almost no head whatsoever .  mouthfeel is slightly thick and slick with a little hint of carbonation tingle .

sweet , almost apple like in aroma , light hints of wheat , fresh , crisp and clean to the senses , with the start sweet , top is light in feel .  dark brown almost opaque body . creamy tan head with low retention and little lace .  medium body with crisp carbonation .

very fresh , great smelling beer ( i suppose it helps that the brewery is less than an hour away ! ) t - the sweetness of hops and malt greet the palate .  appearance : very dark chocolate in color , looks almost like root beer with a minimal creamy tan head aroma : it smells amazing , like desert but in beer form .  m : medium body , smooth carbonation , dry finish but off a bit .

nice . t - quite sweet .  it has a simple amber colour and a quickly dissipating head .  the mouthfeel is good . it 's creamy and smooth and glides over my palate . overall this is just an average beer .

aromas are floral hops , biscuit , vanilla , sweet berries , apple , alcohol , banana , pineapple , sweet grass , malt and caramel . semi-dry finish with a lasting hop impression . excellent mouthfeel , clean and refreshing , slightly oily .  pours a fairly standard looking light honey color with a very small white head which leaves almost no lacing .  cherry soda almost for flavor profile , minus the cola mouthfeel - light , acidic with good carbonation drinkability - very easy to consume , lawnmower or beach bum beer , i.e .

the aroma is a nice smooth cocoa aroma and the sweet lactose that maybe part of the beer .  bronze brew with a very small , brief head and some very transparent lacing . crap .  taste : again overwhelmed by oak and sugar , now i 'm willing to commit to calling it rum . mouthfeel : definitely full-bodied and creamy like a nitro stout should be . tha'ts nice at least .
s - fruity , spicy , esters .  this beer also has no lacing . even without head this beer still looks alright .  this is a full bodied beer , but totally not my taste .

pours a nice clear copper amber with an obvious effervescence . the nose is full of fruit esters ; plums , raisin and cherry are all evident with a just a touch of hop bitterness to boot . the flavor is malty and earthy with a hint of smoke . all in all a smooth drinking but otherwise not notable pale ale .  it 's a deep golden color , not hazy like the style says it should be , with a really small head . nothing too impressive here , but it 's not like it looks bad .  mouthfeel : good . it feels like beer .

weak malty aroma . nice malty taste , some sweetness with a mild yet aggressive hopping .  appears a fairly clear copper with about a half-inch of cream colored lace . head dies down quickly leave minimal scatterings of lace .  i get some of the caramel , but the roast does n't pair well with this . the lingering funk of this beer is n't very good . i really like the brewery , but this bottle really did n't hit the spot .

the nose was pure unadulterated raspberry with a very pleasant fruity aroma .  poured a roasted chestnut light brown body with a small , dirty tan head . light lacing left by the quickly diminished head . the sweet caramel malts are really coming through in spades , but it 's not overdone .  mouthfeel is medium body and low carbonation .

smell is ok. smells like a wheat ale with some citrus and hop aroma .  a - pours a deep slightly hazy amber , forming a 1/4 inch tan head . very minimal lacing is visible .  m ) nice carbonation , not too heavy not too light .
aroma is rich and carmelly .  it 's only an average looking ipa . almost looks blonde . it 's a dark straw color , pale-ish like you 'd expect .  feels a little viscous with a lively carbonation .

after swirling the beer , i get a good spicy nose with a lot of fresh baked cinnamon roll notes and caramel malt sweetness . these 2 are pretty strong and overwhelm anything else i could get out of the smell . taking a few sips and ... the nice spicy smell does n't show up much in the taste at all .  cloudy light straw with a small white cap and slightly troubling brown yeast specks in suspension .  very sugary malt . mouthfeel is solid . creamy and smooth at first with a bitterness that soon meets it and rides out to a moderately dry finish .

this is not a good beer and is barely a good sherry , which is what it looks and tastes like . but utopias misrepresents itself as a beer and is certainly not worth the $ 120 you pay to drink it . buy a keg of winter lager instead for the same price and let it last a couple of months .  2007 pp saf : a - golden hue with nice frothy head and spotty lace .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

smell is very fruity , but i 'm having a hard time identifying the fruit .  a very muddy orange poured into my small la trappe glass.. i was befuddled for a long time with this one.. molly mentioned to eric that she smelled honey , and things sorta came full circle for this one .  this brew poured a small head of fine to large sized white bubbles and amber orange transparent body . it has a strong hoppy aroma and a strong hoppy flavor to boot . it has an initial hop flavor and a strong hop finish . you can summarize the brew in 1 word ! hoppy . a true hopheads delight .

smell : more subtle than a lot of fruit beers . still , fruit is the only aroma one gets from the nose .  this beer was had on a business trip to san antonio at the local flying saucer . looks nice . i assume the color is good since i only see black and white .  m- full body with low carbonation .

solid inviting scent of cereal , light chocolate , & just a twinge of dark fruit .  i had this beer about 2 weeks ago and wrote notes for this review ... poured into a pint glass , amber color , small white head , little to no lacing .  m- light body , nice carbonation .

poured into a the molen sniffer . smell : dark chocolate , roasted malts , leather , coffee and some hints of red fruit . overall : disappointing beer . highly overrated in my opinion .  on-tap at the alehouse in amesbury , ma review adapted from notes taken 12/29/2009 appearance : very dark brown / borderline black - oily looking without much of a head at all - might actually be oil , not beer ... smell : lots of booze - not just alcohol , but bourbon - wood , vanilla , molasses , burnt malts , burnt chocolate taste : remarkably intense and potent - loads of burnt malts , charred wood , bourbon , burnt malts - lots of chocolate , but i detected even more vanilla - the mouthfeel is so incredibly thick that i thought this almost tasted like burnt vanilla ice cream with a shot of bourbon added ( made sense at the time ) mouthfeel : one of the thickest , sludgiest , most viscous beers i have encountered - and honestly , it not only works but it also somewhat explains and compensates for the lack of carbonation overall : pretty much the definition of a sipper - only gets better as it warms - the abv is high , but chances are this beer will be consumed so slowly that it wo n't matter i actually had this on-tap twice .  feels good especially for a pale . resinous and nicely carbonated . if the carbonation level is my favorite thing about a beer then i 'm not gon na get it again .

bold nose of leathery prunes , toffee , black cherries , and cocoa .  pours quite calm , golden with a white head that settles to a thin ring around the snifter .  this just smells `` german '' too , with notes of melanoidans and flowery noble hops . this was sooo sweet and overpoweringly cloying that i could not finish this beer . it 's got some really wonderful aromas and complex malty flavors but the sweetness is just to overwhelming . maybe this is intended by the brewer for the style and i just do n't get it , or maybe something went horribly wrong between the brewery and my glass . either way , i really wanted to like this beer because of it 's potential . darn .

aroma is mostly raspberries , with a bit of strawberries and chocolate noticable too . the fruit aroma smells artificial , like candy or syrup ( even though the bottle says natural flavor was added ) . with that being said , it does smell nice to me .  pours a very clear golden color with a thin white head .  m : medium bodied with a full juicy mouthfeel . the high carbonation dances around in your mouth .

i am picking up the smell from about a foot away from the glass , very fruity ; apples , oranges , some grapefruit and a little pepper . the biting alcohol dominates the taste , there is some cherry and strong bitterness .  pours a light golden straw , with little carbonation and no head .  mouthfeel is good , very smooth and full .

the beer has a nice small to it - biscuity malt with plenty of citrus fruits .  poured into pint glass with a small head that split after a little bit.looks okay.alot of citrus hop aroma in the nose , a little bit of biscuity sweetness.nice balance between the citrus/piney hops and malt sweetness.very clean finish mouthfeel is medium bodied , very easy drinking.really nice fall release that strays from the pumpkin ale/oktoberfest norm .  had nice mouthfeel , esp .

very lemony with some dry hop tang . aggressive lemon is my major problem with wheat beers but this was at least ok to me ...  pours a dark brown color , cloudy , and with a weak head .  mf- nice and smooth , good for summer time relaxation slight carbonation and citrus invades the toungue .

aroma is strong . but the taste is bland .  the beer looks almost still . very small crown of a head that is khaki colored .  light bodied with decent carbonation it is a very easy drinking brew ideal for a hot summer day .

i was expecting more hops because of the imperial in the title but i am not disappointed though , smells really nice .  a - plate amber/yellow with little to no head .  feel is pretty good for the style .

smells malty and a lot like caramel and yeasty . nice head and good left over ring .  dark , dark brown pour with lots of red pouring through when held up to the light . 2-finger tan head , no retention , and no lace .  m : creamy , with low carbonation .

s - chocolate and coffee malts .  not much head , maybe a 1/4 inch , that quickley receced to a minimal lace . color is a rich coppery brown color .  its drinkability is smooth and somewhat water like with a bubbly , creamy , sweetness . this is the best coors product i 've had as of yet .

definitely enjoyed the wake n bake and big hoppy monster , plust the rye pale ale is n't bad . corn taste and nothing too special .  pours a clear ... amber color ... who would 've guessed ? barely any head . gave it an average for appearance but makes up for it in other respects .  medium bodied with good carbonation .

nose was subtle but very malty in it 's subtleness . malt , some very mild hints of smoke , sugar , brown sugar and some smells of malt sweetness .  filled to the rim with no head what so ever ... appearance is a gorgeous dark walnut with red hues , and some visible carbonation .  the beer felt good in the mouth : thick and velvety , but alas , no es bueno .

a-color of a well brewed tea - rich brown nut orange color . nice initial head about an inch deep and brown tinged . decent lacing s-sweet bread with spice notes t-toast that is slightly overdone with underlying sweetness of caramel . d-decent drinkability though getting a bit of a metallic sense in the aftertaste which i find commonly in lager styles .  light color hued for an ipa - almost a straw/gold color .  m : pretty creamy overall with even carbonation .

smells of bourbon , lots of bourbon , even in the restaurant . this i like . tastes like a run of the mill bourbon barrel ale . i 'm not sure what i expected , but the hoppiness of the big hoppy monster has completely left us .  a_pours black , jet black with a smallish coffee hued head . this diminishes quickly and settles into a small brown cap . lacing is non existant . despite the lack of head there is a good carbonation which cuts through the liquid which could be construed as cloying otherwise .  pretty good feel .

this is one great smelling beer . it almost reminded me of fff zombie dust . first taste was great , not what i was expecting from the smell but exceptional . a bit warming , but very sweet : pineapple , melon , hint of pine , small hint of phenol . awesome . taste was not as good as the smell .  2001 vintage , just like the picture . appearance : brownish and quite murky , like most cantillons the head was lively at first but died off rapidly .  m : smooth , almost caramel .

nice true belgian aromas on the nose : plum , wine cork , a little aniseed , and a light phenolic alcohol note - perhaps a little like shoe polish . promised a lot on the nose . it 's not bad , and it 's an interesting find , but it really does n't deliver in the end .  pours a dark copper color with little carbonation and very thin lace of head .  well i guess i just do n't have the make up to like belgian style beer . russian river is belgian heaven , out of belgium . so you belgian lovers , the worse i make it sound , the more you will love em . a hodgepodge of flavors assaulted you on this one . spice , cinnamon , pear , and a hint of banana . it also had a lightly toasted hint to it . probably a great beer to somebody other than me .

s - banana esters , citrus . hint of spice ; would n't be able to pick it out as clove if not for past experiences with the style .  pours hazy cola color with nice beige head .  m - medium to full body beer . pretty thick .

not really my cup of tea , but an interesting brew nonetheless . smell was very sweet , with lots of apricot and some citrus aromas as well .  on-tap at rock bottom long beach a : the pour is not a very pretty one . intensely turbid and cloudy yellow/orange color with a soapy white head .  m : crisp full carbonation , medium-bodied , nice finish .

smell is a hoppy piney scent . it has a very pungent acerbic aroma .  2008 vintage 750ml bottle poured into a cigar city snifter . a : red-orange-brown blend with a little ring of foamy head . d : i would say most of the booze has died off in this one making it easy to down .  mouthfeel : a medium to full bodied beer , with a good amount of carbonation .

herbal and soft white pepper aroma first , mild strawberries , sweet pineapple , green grapes , rhubarb pie . classic fruity hoppy nose from stone . a mild earthy bite , dry wheat , watery , thin in the middle with mellow fruity hoppy overall with very little else happening .  this brew pours with an orangish-gold body topped by a thin to medium thick head with good lacing .  nitro tap at the brew pub in new hope . i put this down to being a mix of flavors from my previous beer , the bengal gold ipa . it 's much like the smell of a dank basement where there is no fresh air and spiders are everywhere . perhaps the lines needed cleaning but i would likely not try this one again .

aroma is quite nice : coffee and roasted malts .  i had this on tap at the brewery and liked it so much i brought home some growlers . i 'm a huge skeptic of magic hat , but this was suggested to me because of my lucky kay affinity . some iipa 's i drink are way too overpowering and very hard to drink . a wonderful concoction that i hope magic hat keeps around .  the frist sip is a good medium/heavy mouthfeel .

smells of clove and ripe banana with a faint hoppiness .  appearance : cherry adam pours out a very dark brown and seemingly completely flat .  medium body with some sticky sweet coating -but in a nice way .

aroma is almost spicy enough to make your eyes water . ginger absolutely dominates , with a little pumpkin and malt crying for attention .  there 's a small island of foam floating at the top as well as a ring clinging to the glass .  m - it was crisp , sharp and smooth . a light bodied ale with a dry finish .

s- grapes , fresh cut oak , yeast , a touch of alcohol in the background . man the warmer it gets there 's a funky sweetness that hits your nose before you even get a sip that is quite unpleasant .  the dunkel is their strongest beer ! a bit lighter than normal for the style , more dark amber than brown . very small head . craft drinkers demanding all big beers all the time should probably head elsewhere .  this is a sour brew , but not that sour that it 's offensive , and there were just enough spices and carbonation complexities to keep it from being like a cider . mouthfeel is creamy and smooth , with light carbonation , a light body and a sour finish that leaves a fruity pucker .

s -- strong raspberry smell . not fake raspberry smell . a bit yeasty too .  appearance : : it pours a deep and hazy amber with lots of visible carbonation . the head was small for the style ( may have been a bad pour ) and did n't retain particularly well but had a nice even lacing .  medium carbonation .

s- smelled like pumpkin pie which is well , pretty much what it should smell like to give it a true pumpkin fall smell .  pours a amber color in the glass , sadly the head was n't much at all .  m : medium bodied . full , thick , and creamy . good .

the aroma is really excellent . fruity -- i detect cherries and fig -- with a malt undertone and a liquor like alcohol boquet .  pours a dark brown , the slightest trace of a tan head rises and fades into a thin ring around the edge of the glass , little to no lacing .  mouthfeel : smooth , sweet and full bodied which leaves a delicious aftertaste .

light lacing ... interesting aroma that really captures the essence of pumpkin , has some spice and chocolate notes as well . too much pumpkin for me , but its good ... taste is pumpkin pie on steroids , just terrible .  almost opaque in color with some clarity when held up to the light . no head to speak of .  mouthfeel is pretty full for the size of the beer .

aromas of dark dark roasted malt , dark fruit , a boat ton of alcohol and some molasses .  color was a very dark , rich brown , with a minimal , cream-colored head and no lacing .  mouthfeel- medium bodied with light carbonation . slightly chewy texture .

smells of raisins and dark malts .  bbd of 19 june 10 pours an effervescent honey color with 1 finger of ivory colored head . average head retention & lacing s : breadyness grassyness & metallic hops , plus floral hops once warm t : nice bready honey taste hop front , along with a touch of grainyness , plus a touch of pear .  mouthfeel : thick , medium-high viscosity . medium carbonation .
s : very yeasty aroma .  russet colored with nay a head . some floaties and not much else .  4 body on the full side of medium , carbonation ample .

s : quite a crisp scent . light citrus , pale malts , some touches of grassiness and cloves .  i 'm generally not a fan of light yellow beers , and thats exactly what this looked like . ( which i normally do n't notice , so it must have been a bit more than a hint ) finally after taking a sip i realised i was wrong to judge this beer by its color . overall i was impressed with this beer , dont let its smoothness fool you though , its a strong bugger .  mouthfeel - smooth with mild carbonation conclusion not bad , but nothing special .

nose is overrun by the vanilla and oak from the barrell , but a deep second sniff does reveal some candy sweetness from the mad monk lurking below . it basically smells dangerous though .  dark bronze color , slightly hazy . smallish bubbly white head , some nice lacing .  though it 's called a nut brown ale , the only nuttiness in this is in the aftertaste , which is by far the most pleasant part of my experience with this beer . it reminds me of the tommyknocker imperial nut brown , but that at least had a 10 % abv to explain its unpleasantness . i really do n't understand why this is rated so highly ; apparently i just do n't `` get '' this particular kind of brown ales .

the smell reminds me of leather , flowers , nutmeg , and various spices . very appetizing .  the murk appears to be from a bunch of little floaters , not a chill haze . about a finger of head that disappeared without leaving a trace .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with a viscous , chewy carbonation .

aroma is perfumy and of bubble gum , very sweet and pleasant . initial taste is of bitter cranberry and maybe a tinge of apple peel .  cloudy yellow with a supersmell and dito taste and mouthfeel .  the body was light and pleasantly carbonated , but there was zero drinkability to this in my mind .

smell : very sweet aroma of cherries and dark fruits . it 's the faintest bit spicy and a bit of brown sugar is detectable .  pours a deep dark brown with a small whitish tan head that falls fast with no real lace .  the aftertaste is sweet with quite a lot of alcohol , but very little bitterness . `` bivaly '' means `` bullock '' in hungarian but could also mean `` powerful '' . the carbonation is good for a lager ; fresh but not sharp .

the aroma is slightly funky and fruity , yeasty with strong turned pears , hints of grain , metal , and cheddar cheese .  at first glance the beer looks like it might be a let down . it is light in color and there was n't much head on it and its a bit hazy . i still gave the appearance a 3 because it had a nice color to it , even though its not what i would expect from a dipa at all .  m - medium bodied ale that goes down smooth and finishes nice and wet .

poured from chilled bottle into samuel smith pint glass . nice head after the pour , three inches of frothy goodness . minimal smell but that might be due to the fact it 's still cold from the mini fridge . i 'm trying to let this beer warm up a bit but it 's too good to let sit unattended . very nice robust taste to this dipa .  dense two-finger head with decent retention and light spotty lacing .  it is a quality brew from the perspective that it carries a nice light bodied quality with lovely crisp carbonation .

very inviting . t - watered down lemonade .  pours a hazy yellow color with a small , quickly dissapering head .  pokey , medium-light carbonation in a body just a shade above light . crisp and snappy .

the smell is great . biscuit and citrus ( bitter orange ) and a buttload of herbs with sage being in the forefront although parsley and thyme are pretty evident as well . the malts are entirely overpowered and almost impossible to pick out .  this was a mainstay in hawaii & still a nice beer regardles of where you find it pours amber to copper with a 2 fingers white head . no head retention , some lacing s : fruitty & piney , with floral hops sneaking in as well big fruittyness & bready notes up front , piney & citrus hops follow up .  mouthfeel is smooth . nice carb .

s : lemons , wheat , harsh phenols , typical saison yeasts . significant floral smells later , dandelion , lavender , and a hint of rose . a bit of dusty oxidation as well . saisons are a fickle mistress , and putting one in balance is not an easy task .  nice amber color , one finger head that dissolves a little too fast , no lacing .  aroma was very complex , spicy , pungent . flavor was just a mass of confusion . sasion ? triple ? wtf ? the reason this `` triple is so hard to nail down is absolutely flabbergasting . the brewer was very proud to tell us that 9 different strains of yeast were use to ferment this concoction . why 9 ? what was there about each that he hoped to add to his beer ? the real answer is that for a triple , you triple the malt bill .

a : good appearance good head retention s : smelled as it should but very nice deep coffee smell t : not what i hoped for it tasted like someone took a woke up took a lighter stout and poured coffee into it .  deep nut brown with thin brown head with little retention and no lacing .  alcoholy , grape sweet taste with an aftertaste of smoke . strong and syrupy sweet , but tasty . creamy . will probably age well . pretty good .

an unusual smell for a pilsener-type lager - sourdough with a noticeable hint of alcohol . start soft , malty , sweetish . worth a try .  pours a nice dark brown burgundy with an off white head leaving little bumps of lace .  the mouthfeel is good . it is a low bodied beer with adequate carbonation .

this is not a true lambic , because it is not like other lambic or fruit beers . smells - lots of cranberries here .  poured out of the bottle a slightly cloudy deep orange/copper color . the head was thick and white before it dissapeared quickly .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and perfectly carbonated .

quite nice . t : some bitter grapefruit up front followed by lots of resiny pine and bitterness .  pours a pale , straw yellow . i 'll take a red stripe over the usual macro lagers any day , but definitely nothing i 'll buy on a regular basis .  m - the spritzy carbonation is what i expected , giving this beer a crisp and light body .
decently balanced .  abita purple haze : its a medium bodied beer that poured a golden color with a purple tint .  mouthfeel is good . decent body and nice carbonation level .

aroma of light sour apple notes and grainy wheat malt is somewhat refreshing .  pours an effervescent , semi-hazed straw/gold with 3 fingers of pearl colored head . zero head retention & lacing s : grassyness & phenols t : green melon , grassy hops , slight dryness & hints of strawberries up front .  smells like a scotch ale . a clear miss . this may be the oddest beer i 've had in a very long time . it is mostly malt until the swallow where the hop shows up .

interesting . taste is really weird , but with a big toasted bread sense on the finish .  a : pours a bud light esque yellow with a small white head that disappears in about 3 seconds .  full bodied and carbonated well .
candy sugars . green apple , caramel , and winter spices . good strength !  sickly clear yellow color , weak soapy head is bubbly but vapid .  medium-full in body with smooth moderate carbonation .
poured 750 ml to chalice a : pours ruby brown , impressive head s : booze , lots of fruit .  a : clear hold colour . thin head without cream .  right on mouthfeel .
$ 16.99 for a 750ml . s-oak , anise , dark fruit , rock candy sugar , alcohol .  pours a golden beer with no head and lacing .  the mouthfeel is pretty good , long lasting ( forced ? ) carbonation .

the aroma is of toffee , caramel , and a hint of flowers . it is a rather strong aroma .  on-tap at ram 's head tavern at bwi airport : the beer appeared a light yellow-ish , with virtually no head .  m. very smooth with a little stickiness .

a great aroma of roasted coffee beans , with hints of vanilla in the nose . i was disappointed when there was no appearance of brewer 's lace on the side of my clean 16oz pint glass .  fizzy yellowy brown in color .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

a : nice golden , semi-clear appearance s : fresh , floral m : medium mouth feel .  corona is a beer that is now a victim of it 's own marketing success , as it is shunned by any serious beer drinker while still enjoying popularity among the youngest drinkers , the hip , and people who do n't really appreciate beer . i loved it in my college years and still consider it serviceable , especially in the summer , although i now can see it for what it is..fairly bland and well advertised . thin , pale yellow with little head .  mouthfeel : medium body with a very good carbonation level .

the nose is sweet and lemony , like tonic water . the mouth is fairly light and quite prickly .  a refreshing lager , enjoyed best on the beach with a slice of lime . it is because of its smooth , sweet taste , or maybe the lime just goes with the green bottle .  m : very light and frothy , has plenty of drinkability if you can deal with the skunkiness .

s : wonderful ! heavy hops laced with citrus are complemented by sweet , almost fruity , malts . m : pleasant , slightly dry and biscuity . d : it 's good , but not something i 'd drink on a daily basis .  other than the chunks of protein floating in my glass , i guess it looked alright -- clear orange/amber with a thin cap of fine beige bubbles .  it had a good thick body to it and was drinkable but not overly enjoyable .

the smell was a nice combination of nuts , caramel , and toastiness .  while light lager 's are n't exactly my favorite beer , stampede light is n't bad . it 's the ideal definition of a watered down beer . it 'll get you drunk , but i would n't drink it for the taste .  the classically unfiltered flagship beer from michigan - bell 's amber ale . one that seems to be divisive amongst die-hard larry bell fanatics and casual k-zoo stout and two-hearted quaffers . there 's a bit of that worn-out cheese-like hop character on the nose of this beer . there is something about the look and smell of the beer that evokes chewiness . there is a dulled hop bite in this beer floating atop of a cheeseburger-y blend of heavy yeasts and clunky sweet malts . the beer is thick and bold , one both a macro drinker and a blind taste-tester could harmonize negatively about .
nice complex aroma . boy is the taste a disappointment .  it also appears to be unfiltered as it looks like pond water .  lingers on the tongue a bit . this is the best part of the brew .
s- smells really nice .  appearance : cola color , with very tiny foam and low carbonation .  feels really smooth on the palate .
it smells fine .  krombacher pils pours a pale yellow with a fluffy white head from a brown 500 ml bottle .  m. nicely carbonated and crisp , refreshing , light bodied .

s : hopsy , with some citurs and pine . about the standard for an ipa , though i found that pine scent to be a nice addition . hmmm ... a swirl and another smell later and i 'm really getting the auroma .  this was a reddish/pink beer with a small pink head . when the head quickly disappeared , it looked like fruit juice .  the mouthfeel is this beer 's only saving grace ( if i had to come up with one ) . very creamy and smooth with mild carbonation .

very nice . i 've had a few tyranena beers and a few more tucked away for rainy days or a time where i need a palate cleanser ... this is the one ... very nice ipa , and from my experience , a pretty good brewing company that i wish i could get locally .  a- dark cloudy gold . looks very similar to unfiltered apple juice .  moderate body , w/ the dextrinous and full mouthfeel saving the beer .

s - very sweet raisin smell , hint of chocolate , and the bite of the alcohol , you can tell from the smell that it is going to be a strong beer .  from a 12 oz bottle poured an orange color with not much head , and what there was was pink .  t- tastes pretty damn bitter , with grapefruit and pine leading the way , after taste is just straight bitter , i would call this a hop bomb . m- just the way and ipa should be , very true to the style . overall this is not a bad ipa , it was just way too bitter for me , its seems that if the flavors arent blended together the best and the bitterness just takes over the whole beer . do n't think i would every buy this again but there 's plenty other shorts brews i will be getting instead .

the aroma was crisp and hoppy with some caramel malt sweetness behind that .  very red with gold edges , no head or lacing ( perhaps because it is from a growler ) .  m- medium bodied and well carbonated .

no problems here ... s - pretty straight forward here , sweet chocolate , roasted malts and sweet smoke , with some slight sweet fruit ( apricot ? ) mixed in . nice balence , again , no complaints .  appearance : crystal clear , light gold in colour with very little head -- just a very thin white foam lace . given this , i ca n't hate this beer .  3/5 m : medium/full body , warm and smooth going down . 4/5 d : too sweet for me to have more than 12 oz .

appearance- a very inviting amber color with a off white creamy looking head smell- has a very flora smell to it it hits you big time at first sip .  extremely pale and lacking real color , this adjunct is lively and bubbly .  m - medium bodied and smooth as you drink it down .

smell- intoxicating , caramelized/burnt sugar , vanilla . slight booziness . taste- wow very interesting .  i do n't know if this is old , but the bbd on the bottle is 6/09 , but it looks really flat .  m ) lively carbonation , smooth but strong . refreshing .

not a good start s- smells pretty spicy actually , lots of toffee and roasted malts in there .  pours a typical clear straw-yellow with a little white head - nothing special .  mouthfeel is good , rich and creamy .
d - the aromas were great , unfortunately , the taste did n't follow suit .  looks like dishwater .  mouthfeel is crisp , yet smooth . very beefy . this is weird .

s - nice grassy smells , some lemon and spice . while the nose was a nice saison , the taste was different , and not in a good way .  it poured slightly flat with very little tan head that quickly dissipated into nothing but a slight ring around the glass .  the infection has n't totally killed the other flavors quite yet and there are still some bourbon notes that save the beer mouthfeel : medium body with medium to low carbonation overall : i really want to try this one when it is not infected .

assuming this is more of a `` bitter '' style of carbonation/session beer , here are my comments : aroma - malty and i picked up something that was like plum or grape or ? no hop aroma that i could pick up .  looks more like a god pale than a a dipa ( or an ipa for that matter ! ) .  the mouth feel is decent , smooth and rich .

it pours a dark carmel color and has a smell of hops and barley .  bottle poured into pint glass appearance : the non-existant head makes this beer look like soda ; sort of looks like sprite .  light , crisp , full bodied .

nutty smell , with some dry spice ( cumin ? ) also present in the nose .  so it looks like everyone hates this beer but i am a fan of chilis in my brew .  body is right , but finish is somewhat boozy .

can only barely pick up sweet stewed fruit ( pear ) and yeast . bubblegum . not unpleasant though .  this is a cloudy yellow colored beer .  m- clean on the palate . light bite from medium carbonation .

first sip confirms jagermeister smell , but with a burnt aftertaste . most of the reviews here have hit the flavor right on the nose . jager / ale / menthol cigarette is an accurate description .  pours a very clear and extremely light yellow colour , with a fizzy and dissipating head of white crackling bubbles . not impressed .  mouthfeel- very fine carbonation .

pretty nice . t - the first flavor in a waxy flavor .  not much lacing to brag about . light brown in color .  mouthfeel is light and smooth . it 's a pretty good beer , a little bit too citrusy/floral for me .

nose is solid , big roast covers most everything but a fleeting glimpse of cocoa . there 's a displeasing tartness in the middle that fruits up as it warms ; not bad when cold , it goes south , fast . well , based on the smell , i was hoping that the poor reviews of this beer had bypassed my bottle .  a - pours a murky swamp water brown colour , no head , no lacing , little body carbonation .  good creamy mouthfeel adds to the `` what could have been '' feeling .

lawnmower beer ! the smell is powered by lemmon with barley , malt , and slight hop .  looks more like a light brown ale if anything . it looks like shit , and it does n't feel much better , but smell and taste wise , this is a stellar brew and worth drinking often .  m : medium bodied with just a medium carbonation .

s- smells of cooked pumpkin and mild spices ( cinnamon , nutmeg and allspice ) ... slightly sweet with nothing that overtly reminds me of hops nor malt . i actually like the aroma . it gives me the impression of pumpkin pie without any cloying sweetness or overpowering spice ... t- a mild flavor overall comprised of some weak pale malt notes , mild cooked pumpkin flavors , and some barely perceptible non-descript spiciness .  modest head that dies to a single ring of bubbles on the glass . no lace .  it has a nice mouthfeel and i definately would n't drink another one .

nice smell of chocolate and roasted coffee malt throughout .  not much going on here , very watery . i guess you could sit and drink this all day because there is no offensive taste , really no taste at all for that matter . i 'll stick with the shandy . skoal !  m : good mouthfeel on a reasonably full body .

s- hops dominating , i would compare it to a really well aged mature cheddar . i can appreciate the strong hop aroma but the lack of balance has me wincing with each mouthful , crying out for a little malt sweetness .  a- dirty yellow , white head .  so the mouthfeel is the biggest asset , followed by a fairly cool bottle .

the nose is nice , but the flavor is dominated by too much chemistry from the hops and alcohol for my preferences .  ... is quite spritzy , seems aged- not really in a good way ... musty , dust , honey aroma 's ... `` the firetrucks will have to wait their turn '' .. light hazy yellow-orange .. the mouthfeel makes it quite drinkable , but most will find it thin ... not worth the jackson ...  very little carbonation .

bbd : 08.07.2010 $ 1.79 from gene 's sausage shop . sour mash sweetness , wet wood , and earthy . later it was sweet and appley . sweet with some odd spices , maybe nutmeg . dry aftertaste from the alcohol .  pours gold , not amber/orange like most fests .  overall : medium bodied with a smooth mouthfeel , this porter is better paired with food rather than drank as a session beer . minimal carbonation holds back its potential .

aroma is harsh malty , with some dust and very light lime hops . pretty decent lacing too .  presentation : 16.9 oz ( .5 liter ) tall brown bottle , lots of foreign characters with little information about the beer . appearance : haze pale golden , almost murky . little head forms from the pour and disappears to nothing , few large bubbles rise to the top . ohh , my head .  m : a very nice , light and crisp mouthfeel that was very pleasant and easy to enjoy .

grapefruit obviously hits me on the nose first along with a maltiness . some grain comes through as well in the form of straw .  very boring looking golden color with a very small white head that disspates quickly with very little lacing and light carbontaion i can see .  nice mouthfeel , but thats about it .

2009 bottleworks x bottle . s - old fruit , and burnt sugar .  a : pours a clear apple juice color with a thin fizzy white head that quickly vanished first into a faint collar , and then into nothing .  mouthfeel is good , big , full and creamy . mayflower is one of those breweries that seems to do a good job with the mouthfeel of their beers .

fat yak looks good , smells good , but delivers nothing .  this beer is not for beer reviews , or critical analysis , however , its very popular in bolivia , so . this is the beer people often buy for parties becauce its really easy to drink and its cheap . good party beer , a dancing break beer almost no after taste kinda watery  this must be the least enjoyable rouge `` ale '' i have had so far ... it looks ok , deep golden orange hue with thin , soapy head . the aroma is very pleasant with a nice balance of sweet toasted malt and domestic ( that 's usa ) hops . the flavor is just plain weird to me . finishes with a sweetish , smoky flavor that continues with the oddness . what is most odd about this `` ale '' is that it is not an ale at all . it is a maibock , which is a german lager beer . it is as much an ale as bill cosby is a young white dude .

smells clean grapefruit pith .  light golden color , similar to hard cider , but with a slighly nicer head . overall a pretty drinkable beer , although i would n't pay for it , i 'll drink it when its left in my fridge .  d- goes down very smooth , definitely a good summertime beer .

intense aroma - floral , nutty , spicy .  pale yellow and clear with an adjunct white head that sticks bubbles to the side of the pint glass . no head duration or lace .  m : pretty nice mouthfeel , good levels of carbonation .

smells pretty good too some malt light hops .  maybe their 'beer beer ' anti-marketing is taking away market share ... this beer appears a clear , pale apple juice yellow colour , with one finger of fizzy white head , which displays a remarkable lack of retention , bleeding away before my eyes , and rendering nothing in the way of lace .  m - carbonation level is actually quite nice , unlike a lot of pils/lagers . slightly slick mouthfeel .

smell is strawberries and peaches . there is a little citrus here but this is all strawberry and peach in aroma .  pours with no head , bottle conditioned so there are chunky bits on the bottom .  this bastard was the best looking thing in the bar , so i 'm sippin it in . that said , i 'm tired of drinking bourbon beers . but maybe i 'm not suited for a `` wee heavy '' style scotch strong ale like this one . maybe i 'm a lightweight low abv smooth drinking bastards . not from the backwoods . still well made though .

this was offset however , with the smell of the brew , it did smell like pumpkin .  pours a sickly yellow with a fizzy head that fizzles away to nothing .  m : actually quite pleasant ... weighty but not heavy , well carbonated and textured ... a saving grace d : less than pleasant adjuncty aftertase brings down the score

a - very light translucent straw colored with a tiny white head that stays up for about 30 seconds before it dissapears . s - heavily spiced ; coriander , clove , nutmeg with a tiny bit of banana and grassy funk . t - i 'm getting a ton of pineapple juice and yeast with an assload of coriander , clove and orange peel .  appearance : pours a maroon brown with abundant off white/vanilla head in a weizen glass . the head retention was very poor and the carbonation was weak .  mf : light body , carbonated well , nice bitter finish .

appearance : rich amber with a foamy off-white head and some very nice lacing . smell : very mild citrus over some toasted malts . very mild - too mild . still , could use more aroma . wet hop american esb would be a more accurate description .  pours a clear pale yellow with a large foamy white head , lively carbonation , not much lacing .  somewhat thick and sweet on the mouth , with lingering cherry flavors . i 've had a lot of lambics but not a lot of krieks , but i can tell you doubtlessly that this is a very sweet beer that lacks many lambic characteristics .

and smells nice for the the style : big green hops , solid bready malt backbone , no off nodes of syrup or anything like that .  this came to the table filled to the brim so there was no head to review . it was a sort of amber color , yellow yes ; amber , not quite .  m/d - medium bodied and rather smooth and creamy . after two of the bbc big ipa 's i can safely say i dont have the need to go back .

sweet musty nose , dark malts , rich chocolate and a hint of caramel and dark fruit .  wacko poured an almost orange color , with a very small head that went away quickly .  consumed 12/03/07 at crown city brewing , pasadena . creamy nitro texture . then , unexpected black coffee bitterness appears on tongue long after beer is gone .

dark , strong coffee brown . while i like the look and smell of this beer ( heavy dark fruit , coffee , herbs , alcohol ) it 's just too off-base for me tastewise .  straw colored with a slight haze possibly due to very small particulates . short lived head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , and rather smooth with a gentle carbonation .

smell - alcohol , cocoa , coffee , vanilla , dates , and brown sugar .  poured pale brown-gold with very insignificant crown that did n't last very long . unlike most of the beer from this brewery , this one smells a bit too much like a swedish macro , with the additional touch of the smell of freezer burn .  mouthfeel : it is very thick and pretty smooth . this beer caught me completely off guard .

earthy yet sweet aroma with lots of citrus and floral notes . resinous hop oils with a good bit of citrus peel , grapefruit and slight pine presence .  pours almost completely clear , with virtually no head . not really `` good '' by craft beer standards but decent enough for a macro .  perhaps it was this sweetness that gave it a nice body and a good mouthfeel .

roasted malts , some coffee , carmel , molasses , and cholcolate in the aroma . weak taste by comparison to the aroma .  the taste was a bit heavier than other local ipa 's , but what i did n't like was the residue floating in the glass . the last glass i poured was so full of ( for lack of a better word ) crap it look like a package if instant cream of wheat had been poured into it leaving it undrinkable , it was poured out .  mouthfeel is light bodied , dry , some creaminess .

s - there 's a serious burst of fresh citrus and a little bit of nutty caramel malt action going on , then a ton of alcohol aroma comes out of nowhere and overshadows everything , . t - that smell is a triflin ' son of a bitch ! other than the semi offputting smell , this beer is wonderful and terribly drinkable ( watch out ) .  very pale yellow in color ( duh ) .  mouthfeel is big , thick and creamy .

n- chocolate and coffee , mixed with with bright bitterness along with citrus and floral hops .  pours a very effervescent bronze with 2+ fingers of white puffed up head . zero head retention & lacing s : honey , apricot & dates t : tartness , apricots & honey up front .  this was a bit dissapointing after the string of excellent beers i had from taps .

aroma of chocolate coffee and something burnt .  sure , it contains fillers and adjuncts and is probably carbonated unnaturally . of all the cheap beers , this one tastes the best -- - ( i do n't necessarily mind the corn aroma/taste ) . miller stomps bud easily in my opinion .  a strange medicine taste too mouthfeel - the one good part of the beer . nicely full body and a pleasently smooth carbonation feel to it .

the beer did have a nice big caramel malt smell but the taste was just not there .  finally got around to trying pbr - i bought a twelve pack in order to have a beer to drink with my co-workers after work - they only like american macros . this beer pours a pale yellow with abundant carbonation and a fizzy head that did n't stick around long .  4.0 m : medium body . good moderate carbonation . not particularly smooth from the acridity , but feels good when it 's in my mouth . i really liked the mouthfeel though and it almost made the experience a good one .

aroma is sweet with pear and honey mixing with caramel and some general fruitiness .  pours straw yellow .  and this is with some decent aging on it so the hops have had some time to calm down.. medium light bodied with lightish carbonation , this has a good mouthfeel .

nice aroma : toffee , butterscotch , dark fruit . however , something happened between the aroma and the taste .  fast dissapating head mid clear gold , looks like a pale lager smells likea pale lager starts with lots of carb and goes flat wheat pretty smooth says it 's a pilsner but its not really bitter at all my friend said while we were drinking it together sang `` cant find a bitter beer '' like the pearl jam song better man .  mouthfeel - the feel is fluid and smooth .

smells like raisin and boozey dark fruit , carmelized brown sugar ( perhaps thats the maple/birch syrup ? ) , and kola nut .  labat 's kokanee is one of the worst beers they make ... and that 's saying a lot ! kokanee has really damaged their good name by liscencing labatt to brew their beer for ontario and east .  m : light bodied , crisp and clean .

aromas of roasted chocolate , burnt grains and sugars , a nice kick of wafting dark roasted coffee , that freshly brewed coffee scent that wakes you up in the morning . pleasant roasted malty taste , but also bit of a letdown compared to the aroma , not as rich and full as i was hoping , nor as smooth as i would have liked , medium bodied mouthfeel with a rough dryness , bittersweet chocolate , burnt sugar , bitter cold dark coffee , the hops are pretty light , just a soft spiciness in the finish , overall , a decent , but far from great , dunkel , i would buy it if it was on sale , i also would like to try this from the tap , but there are several german dunkels i would choose over this .  this is a very underwhelming beer . the color is pale , straw yellow .  the palate is soft and tart with some nice and not so nice subtle flavors .

very well balanced . cloves are rather subdued , flavour-wise .  pours with plenty of carbonation yet hardly any head . like soda . dirty water .  mouthfeel is good . hearty liquid , with just a less than moderate carbonation .

aroma was of honey and belgian candi sugar .  with its straw yellow color , lace-less white head , and skunky aroma it behooves me why heineken is so popular .  m : light to moderate body is well-carbonated & refreshing .

no aroma that i could detect .  appearance : cloudy golden with a river water appearance about it . no head retention to speak of .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with spritely carbonation , and a velvety texture .

paired with the recommended warm goat cheese salad ( which was very nice ) . roasty aroma .  i had high hopes for this one but when it came to the table it looked like crap ; dark cola colour with no head and cloudy .  feels good in the mouth with a decent carbination for a dark beer .

the aroma was strong on malts and fruit , bringing pears to mind .  pours a golden straw color , with little to no head . no lace on the glass either .  m : this is where it 's most reminiscent of its style : sticky hop resin , lingering alcohol heat , bitterness hanging on the tongue .

s : smells just like root beer with a bit of added spice -- annis/liquorice with a very sweet aroma overall .  appearance : pours into a shaker pint glass a clear ruddy gold . disappointing .  surprisingly , this has a great mouthfeel . lighter carbonation than your cheap macro swill means it is easy on the old tastebuds .

s : lower than average hop aroma . get some citrus and a little fruity esters . no grassy notes . t : moderate hop flavor with exactly balanced malt character that is bready . excellent . d : awesome session beer .  pours a very clear , very light yellow with two fingers of light , airy foam and almost no carbonation . head quickly disappears and leaves no lacing .  alcohol present in the smell , along with butter , raisin and a hop finish . lots of flavors on this , but a little out of control for me . an initial grassy flavor of butter that does n't blend well with the raisin , pineapple , alcohol , brown sugar and hops . some seemed to like it , so chalk it up to personal taste i guess , but i did n't feel like the flavors in this one were in order . too much alcohol and too much buttery sweetness .

it smells like a good strong lager or decent german maibock , so the aroma is good and pretty much in character .  the raspberry flavor was no where to be found . it did have a nice smell but the taste did n't match it . a friend recommended it to me and needless to say i was not impressed and will not be trying it again ,  m - it was fairly crisp and smooth . a very light-bodied brew .

slightly sweet aroma with some spiciness . seems to have a pretty strong yeasty scent as well .  served in a pint glass at the pub : beer came to me with no head - just a few airy transparent bubbles on top , which was not very pleasing .  medium-light bodied with quite a bit of carbonation .

really . this is pretty crazy stuff . there 's a ton of syrup that hits the mid , and it 's extremely cloying . it 's one strange brew .  crystal clear pale gold with a fizzy white cap that disappeared quickly -- not even a collar .  medium in body ; surprisingly the malt character stands up well to the array of spices .

orange and coriander greet the nose at first , along with a mild malt backbone and some candy sweetness , along with rum soaked cherries and raisins . the flavour is incredibly mild , i was expecting so much more from the strong aroma , the malt tip-toeing through the tulips in the middle , most of the taste appears towards the finish , a rum raisin character with light fruit esters , and a wave of alcohol on the aftertaste .  a : there 's barely a head to speak of , and it goes away instantly . it 's a dark brown color , but appears mostly black . zero lacing .  m : full-bodied , thick , and syrupy with moderate carbonation .

s : strong spices up front including nutmeg and cinnamon . there is some pumpkin to be found along with some sweet malts and a bit of cloves . t : similar to the taste , there is a lot of spice which mask other flavors that are trying to come through . o : this seems like a decent pumpkin offering , but there are many better choices available .  this can poured a big head but died down to almost nothing and leaves 0 lacing on the glass . it 's a kind of odd , light gold color that is very , very clear . mostly smells like cheap lager cereal malts that you 'll get in pbr , coors , etc .  m : overall pretty good . medium at best compared to other ris , but very smooth . carbonation was appropriate or at least not distracting d : for the high abv and the taste profile losing its way this is a beer i could tolerate , but would not look forward to in the future .

smells light with apple and pear . smells almost like a white wine or champagne .  somehow most of this beer made it through the party unscathed , so it was up to me to make sure that not all of this fine microbrewed lager ( micro means brewed on earth right ? ) went to waste . clear straw color , vaguely unappetizing but mostly just uninspiring . probably better to drink it out of the bottle and not look at it . the sweetness of the honey and the bitter orange could me a nice combo , and it starts out pleasant enough . hey , blue moon , let 's just be friends .  light bodied , smooth and crisp . wow , a wheat that i actually enjoyed .

smell is heavily scented with spices and of course , pumpkin . taste is medium bodied typical ale .  lightly murky orange-gold with a modest number of flakes and specks ( nothing scarily large though ) . the small , cheap looking , off-white head falls rapidly to a thin film of soapy scum .  it is medium bodied and has a good level of carbonation .

the aroma is very strong with fermented fruits prominent , especially fig and date . undertones of molasses and brown sugar .  i was lucky enough to sample this beer at the gabf , but not my favorite sierra nevada beer . a : very light golden straw , little to no head s : spices and floral nose t : coriander , nutmeg and cinnamon tastes .  medium-light body ; crisp and more than semi-dry on the finish .

bright aromas of cranberry and cherry leap from the glass , along with a grape-like sweetness . i was n't nearly as impressed with the flavor as i was the aroma . it tasted like cranberry/cherry butter or margarine with a somewhat artificial , stinging , sweetness .  got this one from klevelandrocks , cheers ken pours a semi-hazed caramel with a pinky of pearl colored head . zero lacing & head retention s : apple peels & bubble gum t : apple peels , juicyfruit , a touch of cinnamon & white grapes up front .  it 's quite crisp and clean that really jolts the sense . the mouth feel really holds this beer together .

the smell is fantastic , i wish i had an air freshener that smelled like this !  appearance : light black and good clarity despite the dark colour . head : light brown and low head with very poor retention ( no lacing whatsoever ) .  m - full bodied that really fills your mouth and feels heavy .

pours a slightly hazy yellow-gold with pungent yeastiness immediately pouring out of it . orange/citrus aroma and a slight spiciness are at the forefront . purely in flavour though , it seems a bit lacking and does n't live up to the nose . quite fizzy , and easy to drink .  amber , full , very clean appearance . almost zero foam .  caramel malt , with some spicy rye thrown in , as well as the caraway seed . somehow this all molds together well . well balanced , minimal bitterness . interesting combonation of flavors .

aroma is n't what i expected , citrusy and some spices . tastes citrusy , the coriander is too strong and it has almost a chemical taste , it reminds me of suntan lotion ( well , how it smells ) .  pours a pale yellow color with a 1 inch head .  i almost feel like i got a little spice bite on my tongue from the peppers . m= smooth and delicious . feels like a good doppelbock .

overall this beer looks and smells really good , but the taste just doesnt work so well for me .  i was not impressed by the color or texture of the beer but it is not all about appearance . i still prefer bud light ! !  m : medium-full and well carbonated d : this beer nicely fits the characteristics appropriate for abbey beers , but is lacking in intensity ( as compared with other classic examples ) .

a- light yellow , clear , no head or lacing , small amount of carbonation bubbles floating from the bottom to the top of the glass s- smells good , very yeasty , malty , grassy ... almost smells like a lager t- nothing like the smell .  a - hazy dark brown pour . no visible carbonation and a ring of bubbles on the top . no retention obviously since there was no head .  lacqueredmouse caned this beer and i 'm not sure if i like it but i do n't think it 's that bad . flavourwise , its a light malt with a dash of honey that makes it sweet and like a hefe with no bitterness except the usual balance hops . i guess its an ale that 's nearly true to style except for the honey . there 's some clove and malt and a hint of banana but compared to pure blood hefeweizens it 's not in the race . i 'm glad it exists though because there 's room in the world for craft beers having a go .

s : great tangerine smell . there is a malt smell that is not strong .  this beer poured a bright strawey yellow color , with almost no head .  the feel is a little redeeming . it 's nice and crisp , with pleasant carbonation .

this beer was pretty decent , but i really do n't think it fit the dunkelweizen category . poured a cloudy amber with a nice bit of head , smelled typical of a weizen with clovey , banana overtones . but for the price , a nice beer , just think of it as a hefe .  pours ( finally ) a hazy orange color .  feel was full-bodied , smooth , with a nice creaminess . lacking a good balance of maltiness to offset the powerful punch of hoppiness .

middle of the road ipa . hops were somewhat present in the aroma .  pours golden straw with some head and very little lacing . for the price this is not too bad , will buy again.this cheap euro beer is better than most of our domestic macros .  good mouthfeel and drinkability despite taste .

the smell is all sour ! its all horse blanket with a hint of sweetness but no blueberries at all .  the pour was weak with almost no head retention .  not too overpowering , but not very pleasant mouthfeel is pretty good .

actually quite nice , not too pronounced but quite pleasant . unfortunately , it smells better than it tastes .  ) , but so gingerly as to forestall any chance of forming a head ( bad ) . this produced a slender glass of perfectly clear light gold beer , like filtered apple juice .  creamy smooth , this delivers a subtle blend of caramel malts and moderately bitter hops . every nitro beer that i 've tried has the same pluses of eye candy and mouthfeel , but i get disappointed in that they all remind me a little of the others .

s- smell sweet with citrusey grapefruit hops and a bready full character . not very strong smelling .  clear corn color , served with no head or lacing .  mouthfeel : medium drinakbility : medium , though i do n't crave another conclusion : gets a bit more unsorted as this warms up a bit ... i 'm not enamored with it by any means ; it 's not bad , strictly speaking , but it 's not that good either .

smell is alcohol , figs , and other dark fruits . brandy is heavy on the nose , this smells like an old liquor more than any type of beer .  a - pours a dark brown . hardly any head at all , what little came , did n't stick around .  it is smooth and foamy , with a crisp finish . it has a simple , balanced , amply bitter flavor . this is much better than their `` ipa '' .

a sweet and nutty , perhaps maple syrup detected on the nose .  a : pours a medium golden color with very little fizzy white head and no lace down the glass .  good mouthfeel . silky on the palate with a good level of carbonation .

but good - intriguing . taste is big and sweet - vinous , sour even .  now you know the beer has been poured into a glass , so let 's get on to the beer : appearance in dark amber with orange hues mixed in , but it looks dull and the head is poor .  well carbonated .

smell is very nice - medicinal qualities stand by a cotton candy and bubble gum like sweetness .  pours a bright orange colour with almost no head and zero lacing .  with its light body and fine carbonation , it is very drinkable .

smell - hops , caramel and slight earthy tones , very good smelling beer . taste - found this to be very disappointing , actually think i 'm drinking it from a plastic bottle .  silver can embossed with 1.59 i dont know what my obsession has been lately with trying cheap , likely-to-be crappy beers ... maybe its because i 'm in england , and in addition to all the great ales , there are droves of cheap cheap strange lagers around !  m - it 's fine in the mouth . it 's medium to tight bodied with minimal carbonation .

a : looks like carbonated morning urine . fizzed like a soda . s : very light malt and not much else except typical adjunct grains like corn and rice .  pours out to a somewhat hazy very dark brown , not forming a head , but just a slight ring of bubbles . absent carbonation .  mouthfeel -- full in body with mild creamy carbonation . drinkability -- a bit of a letdown , quite frankly . the mouthfeel , however , is pretty phenomenal , even if it 's more akin to a nice double/imperial stout .

s - the scent is potent enough that i can smell it a couple feet away . it has a nice malty woodiness with a hint of hops .  not a very good beer overall , but one of the top light beers available , probably only bested by sam adams light . pours a light , light amber colour and pretty much lacks any and all characteristics .  m : medium bodied with ample , fizzy carbonation .

on the nose initially , my first remark was `` delicious ; '' sporting lively citrus with some tangerine . the aroma however is n't as pleasant after a tasting , which consumed my impression of the beer and tainted the aroma slightly . this rude up-front taste becomes more approachable when sweet sugars come through as i continue through the glass while it warms , but the alcohol remains too evident without balance .  got this bottle off the top shelf in a cooler right behind the florescent light of the usa supermercado on gral flores st . color is very hazy amber brown or v versa .  the texture is thick or syrupy , and reminiscent of the cognac finish . too much sugar .

as it warms alcohol appears as floral and is very ethereal . t : unexpectedly fresh fruit character with orange/apple and caramel and light straw grains up front .  costco had mixed cases at $ 17 , but do n't mind me if i switch out the `` light '' , for more of this stuff . glug , glug , glug ... not very pretty comming out . it keels over & splashes some suds around , but nothing big . : ) everything smells really dusty ; floury . more watery then i would like . cheap enough filler , but it 's just so mundane .  mouthfeel -- medium to light in body , with ample prickly carbonation . it suits the style well .

banana and clove are very fleeting . i was pretty excited about the initial big banana pudding smell , but things just kind of died after that .  abosolutly no head . this beer is flat . it really just looks like wort in the glass .  the mouthfeel is fuller bodied , with a creamy and bubbly feel to the carbonation . this sits with some heft in the mouth ( this actually feels a little heavier than 7 % ) but other than that the overall flavor is alcohol free .

smell is what you would expect from a well balanced ipa .  a medium-bodied go-between of pbr and harp -- neither of which are `` lite '' beers . draught gives it a good amount of character for an otherwise empty style of beer and kegs are supposed to be the best way to tell the true colors of a beer .  aroma was pale malt and a weird kind of `` synthetic funk '' . it literally tasted like sugar water . there is a great carbonation in this beer which made it drinkable , but none of the great flavors of a true saison are present .

i think all of the previous reviews must 've been from a bad batch , because i get no alcohol on the nose , the appearance is n't cloudy at all , but a clear amber . and to those who say no hops , y'all must 've had a really old bottle or they changed their recipe because the hops blast you first in the nose , and then on the tongue . the hops linger in your mouth even 10 minutes after drinking . overall this is a decent hop forward ipa , but lacks balance .  a deep brown color , starting with a nice even head that quickly disappears to absolutely nothing .  this strong bite while being a little sweet m : texture is full , the foam stays with you while its in the mouth . the flavors really spark the tongue while it is in your mouth .
not really , but still very enjoyable . t : way to hop forward .  appearance is a dark straw yellow to orange color .  thick body , moderate carbonation .

s : bready , yeasty , very much in line with the smell of new belguim 's `` fat tire '' . a toasty smell with some subtle hints of alcohol at the end of the smell .  it 's too pale in color and has no head . kind of weird that there 's no head at all .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and initially crisp on the tongue , before getting more creamy feeling on the edges . this was pretty smooth overall , especially for 6 % .
neat floral thing is also looming about .  appearance - pours very light , in fact , lite light . very sudsy foam quickly disappates . a solid average macrobrew .  mouthfeel is full and round .

s - big nutmeg attack with hints of sweet cream and coffee . t -the tartness of this took my tongue by surprise at first with a follow up flavor of sour nutmeg with a chalky finish . second mouthful yielded a very odd 7-up flavor .  this beer poured a mid gold in colour it had good carbonation but the head was something to behold . it was foamy like the kitchen sink full of suds and the bubbles disappeared before your eyes. , all of which makes for a disconcerting appearance .  md-thick body and moderately carbonated .

smell had no complexity and no distinc odors but pleasant . very good taste with bitter finish ; also not complex but very nice .  a-poured a lightish amber beer , very clear . poured no head , only minimal bubbles , which quicly reduced to nothing .  mouthfeel is semi creamy , and not too bad .

there is a strong honey aroma , the lavender can be picked up , and there is almost a wheat aroma as well .  a : dark amber ; no head , no threads , no lacing -- you might think it dead !  the taste unfortunately got skewed right away as the butteriness of this brew superceded any and all other flavors . the feel was medium/full and creamy .

very subtle aroma consisting mainly of roasted malts . the taste brings out a real complexity not noticable in the aroma .  appearance/smell - appears pale gold/yellow , with no head and no lacing . has medium-high carbonation , almost looks dead and uninviting .  mouthfeel was creamy and smooth .

nice stuff .  the beer is a hazy copper color . the head dissipates quickly leaving nothing , and no lacing at all .  average at best ; certainly a letdown . mouthfeel : smooth and malty with light , rolling carbonation . sturdy body , that 's pretty chewy as well .

lot of chocolate in nose . unfortunately , the beer is better on the table than in the mouth .  very watery beer one of the more light tasting light beers i have tasted . it 's cheap drinkable beer that has less calories than your average macro lager .  the mouthfeel was good - slightly unctuous from the alcohol - definitely knew you were drinking beer .

smelled really promising to be a super refreshing beer off the bat . had some nice green apple esters and biscuity malts . unfortunately , my first sip i when it turned south . it was sweet and buscuity , but ended up feeling quite metallic in taste .  this beer looks rather pale with a washed-out gold color that is stained brown .  there just is n't enough going on if you can get past all the sugar . it drinks medium to full in body and is a smooth drink with no alcohol left behind in the aftertaste . it does n't come anywhere near anything by st. bernardus and it 's in the same price range .

smell - oh yum sours . tart apple , cherries , grapes ... degree of funkiness and woodiness . honestly a bit muted and kind of a disappointment . not really sour - definitely reminds me of new belgium 's vrienden . pretty mediocre .  12 oz bottle 4.8 % abv pours a clear , pale yellow .  this beer aint for the weak . it is bold on flavor and will challenge your conceptions of acceptability , bordering on ..not sure the right word , was gon na say cloying but it aint sweet , just chipotle-ish ... which is interesting and nice and present but a bit hard to take in . best appreciated when drinking slowly with food . but one damn interesting beer .

the aroma is lite caramel with some floral hops and white grapes .  this pours a pale golden colour with very little head which disappears quick smart . not a good looking beer .  smooth , almost creamy medium body .

smells good but taste turns my stomach .  a - extremely light yellow with plenty of solid white head .  definately the best part about this beer . drinkability . thin and light , i was expecting more body in this beer .

the nose is a burnt chocolate , a nice fragrance . the mouthfeel is creamy and soft with a mellow coffee flavor .  i mean its not the greatest beer in the world , but for the price you are gettin a decent beer , its very light and really easy to drink . the smell is a little odd but no different then bud light or coors .  at first it 's all pine resin , which was a bit of a let down for me . do n't get me wrong , pine is great , but the taste just did not live up to the tantalizing smell at all . initially , it came as just a hint ... a whisper of apple cider/hard apple cider .

aromas of big , citrusy , piney hops , grapefruit , grapefruit zest , orange . if there 's any malt , i do n't detect it . from the aroma , i expect a bigger , more puckering bitterness , this is rather restrained .  cheap and ultra-light , you can get over the watered down taste and general bad beer smell as long as you 're willing to buy and drink a lot of it .  mouthfeel : medium body and carbonation .

4.0 s : dark chocolate foremost , surprisingly . roasted malts , some coffee , and a hint of vanilla .  pours an oh-so pale straw . plenty of fizz and a thick white bubbly head that quickly disapears .  first sip reveals an average body with soft texture and very fine yet tingly carbonation .

malty and spicy , some yeast , banana , smells almost weisse like .  a frothy , honeycomb-like head forms and quickly dissolves . very weak color , carbonation continues throughout . not a solitary trace of head as the level of liquid goes down .  taste- incredibly biting bitterness , lays thickly across palate for being only five percent beer .

a sweet raspberry ( easily detected ) aroma dominates , with a slight cough syrup smell that reminds me of belle vue kriek . i was really impressed by the aroma , only to be let down by the taste .  though a bit more grainy and citrusy than i would care for , but not bad overall and at least it 's similar to the style it is trying to achieve . pours yellow with orange highlights . looks murky .  m- lighter side of medium in body and carbonation seems about right on .

a : pours a very dark brown with absolutely no head s : there was a good dark fruit aroma along with some sourness t : vinegar sour throughout the bottle .  50 % stiegl and 50 % lemon soda pours a very pale gold color .  a little too spicy for my liking m- thick , with a malty character . goes down smooth d- a little tough to handle all the spice .
