while the nose is quite pleasant , the coffee flavor has faded to the point of staleness .  this is definitely one of the lightest beers i have had . like the regular version , it does n't have much color at all and the head is n't to exciting .  mouthfeel is solid . a little resiny .

poured into a pilsner glass . the first thing that grabs my attention is the blueberry muffin-like aromawith , which becomes milder as my nose gets adjusted to the scent . the next thing i notice is that there is less head and no head as compared to sea dog 's regular wheat beer .  deep copper in colour , like an old penny . off-white head disappears in under two minutes . no lacing .  nicely carbonated , medium bodied . enjoyable in the mouth .

s - cherry malt , dark fruits , currant , alcohol vapors t - vineous grape malt , stingy alcohol burns the tongue a bit .  poured a small , soap bubble , off-white head that almost totally faded quick and no lace .  medium body with light carbonation .

from a foot away i can smell candy sugar and a little bit of alcohol .  this beer was kind of shitty in my opinion . this beer 's head was weak and faded incredibly fast .  mouthfeel : moderate and pleasant carbonation with a slightly creamy mouthfeel .

aromas of piney hops , light caramel and chocolate with some spice toward the back end . a good beer but not my favorite mikkeller .  appearance is a very clear yellow , compares to the most mediocre of macro-lagers .  mouthfeel is medium with good body and carbonation .

the smell is of sweet roasted malt . i thought i had a great beer from the aroma but was sadly dissapointed at the flavor .  almost zero head , despite a vigouros pour .  m : perfectly carbonated with a medium body and a texture that rolls right off the tongue , which works out favorably for me since i 'm not a huge fan of the flavor .

nose is a wonderful medley of citrus , grassy , and piney hops . this is a very enjoyable beer .  has a very pale yellow color with a small head .  with some bready and slight fruity flavors up front m : medium bodied beer , carbonation seems pretty good o : this is a different beer , not horrible but not really my favorite beer .

smells of caramel , chocolate , oak , licorice , molasses . this is a full nose for sure . yet there was a slight crispness to it .  appearance : pours a cloudy amber color with very little off white head that disappears completely . not very attractive .  m : good mouthfeel , carbonated just about right .
smell is good , honey hops spice with good malt balance .  pours a pale yellow with a fair head that dissipates quickly .  m : crisp sharp , and carbonated like a belgian should be .

a- poured a deep bourbon-looking amber with a two inch head that broke to one and stayed s- cherries , grapes , raspberries , and flowers- all very strong t- very strong and tart with lots of cherry and sugary flavors m- light , thin , and oily , almost like drinking cognac d- difficult to get down , especially with the high abv .  a : a light watery yellow color with slight low carbonation .  m = medium-heavy bodied , good smooth foamy carbonation on swish , good mouthcoating .

s- stale water with minimal malts , cereal grains , and yeast ... .no hops at all . no hop smell , very deluted .  this one tastes like it could be a macro . light , pale yellow and thin with a short lived wispy head .  the mouthfeel is the only area that garnered points other than appearance in my opinion . this beer was exceptionally smooth with good carbonation and a medium body .

the nose is the strong point , nice roasted aroma , with a chocolate malt scent thats rather alluring and has a very firm buttery presence . nothing too complex there but enuff taste to keep one happy . alot like a less potent version of coopers best extra .  poured out of a can a slightly cloudy light straw with a thin , quickly fleeting head .  mouthfeel is light , carbonation is medium .

it had a rich copper color and a strong floral hoppy nose .  a : pale straw color with little head , little carbonation and no lacing s : definitely a grassy smell .  despite the finish , the mouthfeel is excellent . d : avoid .

reviewed 5/25/2006 ( tap @ brouwer 's caf , seattle , wa ) : belgian ale aroma , dusty dark fruit , musty , flowery .  pours a one finger white head that fades quickly , leaving no lace . very pale , hazy amber color , yeast left in bottle .  mouthfeel : medium mouthfeel and very smooth .

smell - sweet malts and some fruity hops up front .  the beer is a bright golden color with a little carbonation and no head retention .  maybe a few faint whisps of caramel and soapiness t : heavy caramel flavor with a touch of soapy floral hops m : not bad at all , there is some creaminess , and it is full bodied enough for the style d : i think i will pass after this one .

smell is really nice : lots of floral hops , fresh cereal grains , nutty/bread aromas , and some alcohol .  the rathskeller wine & beer fest : a small sized head with fine sized bubbles.the body was clear with very little carbonation observed.the hue was pale yellow and the nose was somewhat earthy along with a hint of malt.the flavor was hoppy along with an aftertaste and the mouthfeel was tingly on my tongue and medium bodied.there was virtually no lacing with this beer.for a bock beer , the hue was wrong .  has a medium body with medium carbonation that makes the beer crisp .

at first this one poured nice , looked appealing , smelled great .  this poured without any head whatsoever , even with a vigorous pour . i got a light wispiness but that evaporated and nothing remained - no head , no co2 bubbles , nada . it was a deep amber in color .  at first taste , i was hit with a licorice and pine flavor -- and then some real sweetness from the honey . it 's earthy and sweet . tiny bubbles make for a pleasant feel . color of the brew is a brown orange -- very similar , again , to iced tea . this beer is a novelty . the root beer brew is close in taste to yard 's ben franklin spruce ale -- but not as good .

s- a very fruity smell to the beer . you could smell that the beer was going to almost be sweet . additionally , the agave played games with your mind and almost has you believing you need a lime and salt to drink it .  single bottle consumed ice cold at san salvador 's airport , on to the beer : this beer pours a light goldde color with almost no head . only a little bit of white foam hugs the glass , but it leaves no lace .  mouthfeel is fine . good carbonation .

if not for the hops i might think i was drinking a carbonated after dinner liqueur , 22 ounces of it .  drank this beer a lot through college and usually was satisfied just because i knew i paid very little and got a pretty good punch of alcohol .  moutfeel is nice and crisp due to a decent amount of carbonation .
it starts with a nice aroma of pumpkin pie spices .  a little bit of carbonation- to style . no lacing whatsoever .  mouthfeel is the only thing this beer is good at . medium body while still crisp .

s : wow . gin . weed . seriously , the only other beer i 've smelled with this much weed was devil dancer .  it pours out a hazy golden orange , with barely a hint of a head .  the taste is well , again kinda stale hops , but still some lingering hop bitters , mouthfeel is rich , and this beer is pretty strong .

a strong citrus aroma of grapefruit and lemon start out followed by a floralscent to finish it off .  a- clear yellow macro coloring with a little bit of head . again this is a very macro like beer .  m - bold and consuming .
nice but unexpected . a bit of sulfur .  a- hazy amber with very thin head that quick dissipates to nothing .  feel is pretty good with a good carbonation and some oiliness .

s : smells like a pilsner on steroids . it 's pilsner meets smooth lager and while it 's good it 's too smooth and muted to breakdown . it 's still pretty good but certainly nothing special m : in mouthfeel especially , the beer is half pilsner and half lager .  actually if you can get by all the adjunct unpleasantness , there is a bit of hop bite on the tongue that compliments the alcohol kick . my foray into malt liquor territory has left me feeling comfortably numb , but not totally stupid .  mouthfeel is medium with a nice thick body and a tiny bit of carbonation .

s - it smells citrusy ( orange and maybe some lemon ) with spices . the smell is very strong though . i say that because it has a sweet musk about it .  everyone really hates on this beer but prior to getting into craft beer this used to be my summer beer . i reviewed this beer without a lime which it desperately needs for drinkability sake . a-appearance is n't anything special s-the smell is better than several other macro brews out there . i believe this is still a drinkable summer beer as long as you wedge a good piece of lime in there . it wo n't win a blue ribbon after all but it 's drinkable  mouthfeel is good for what ever style it is .

the smell is sweet with a clean bitter note .  a - poured with sediment left it just a slightly hazy yellow wheat color with a tiny bit of head that went away within seconds and did n't leave anything .  body is the high point probably , some malt thickness is evident , but it makes its way around the mouth nicely with good medium carbonation to match .
the smells were of semi-sour grapefruits , with some sugar cane esters for good measure .  very pale amber with a distinct haze .  m - thick , viscous , smooth , moderate carbonation .

nose is subtle , but relatively complex : hints of sour apple and lemon rind , plus some floral elements and grain support . wow , this is n't even `` alright '' , it 's just plain bad .  appearance : the color of the pour looks very pale , but the dispersing sediment helps to bring out a lighter orange color .  the mouthfeel is on the lighter side of medium bodied with lively carbonation . it is nice to see leinie 's not going overboard with the carbonation like they usually do .

smell contains a touch of sourness to the beer lent from light cranberry and hazelnut flavors . way too watered down and misleading nuttiness turns into light alcohol tint and more water . yorkshire yeast too harsh and does not leave a memorable taste in the mouth .  saffron colour with no head . despite that , no lace at all .  m : this is probably one of the heaviest ipa/dipas that i have had so far . mouthfeel is quite thick , if you swish it around in your mouth its almost like a syrup .

it 's a pretty , fragrant , cleanly brewed hop water if you ask me .  12oz bottle poured into a tulip glass . i really had to pour roughly to get any sort of head to form and it faded quickly .  m - light and crisp . high carbonation .

i liked the smell , though .  dirty caramel body , big head with big sparkling bubbles . looked like some crazy foam packing material on top of pond water .  mouthfeel : thick , syruppy and sweet ... just what i like .

s- intense smoke . some bacon fat notes as well . finishes pretty clean .  poured from bottle into pint glass appearance - a light straw color with a white head that faded faster then the pour .  m- good lingering bitterness , nice body .

smells like more of a raspberry ale than a porter . it does smell good , but not like a porter in much of any way .  well it seems pretty much the same . average inoffensive american/mexican macro beer . lots of carbonation .  m : slick , fine carbonation in a medium to heavy body . leaves my tongue a bit coated and creamy , which is a nice surprise and levels out the bitterness quite a bit .

s -smell is incredibly , but not surprisingly an intense strawberry . no hint of malt in there .  2 a short fizzy head , big bubbles , clear golden , slight ruddiness from deep view 3.5 s maltyness reaches a foot away 3.5 t moderate hop bitterness , burping is essential to enhance aftertaste and afteraroma .  being some what of a foodie , i was excited to try this beer . i had their commander barleywine and was amazed , and was hoping for some of the same quality in this brew . can smell small hints of the vanilla , with a small hint of sweetness . t - as with the smell , it had to warm up quite a bit to even get any of the tastes depicted on the bottle . not impressed , solid made brew , just what was listed on the bottlle was not much in the taste . m- very easy to drink , goes down easy with very little alcohol taste . o - a solid made beer , just was not getting the tastes out of the beer described on the bottle . really wished there was more vanilla and anise flavor .

good cascade aroma ... it was served at a not-so-cold temperature and i think the beer suffered slightly from that .  a : pours a half finger head of fair cream and thickness , but terrible retention .  appearence was pale and fizzy . mouthfeel was standard for american pale lagers , and actually , had a bit of fullness in the cheek , which was nice .

aromatics : the cascades weigh in nicely here upfront floral and piney not bad not a lot of malt sweetness but definitely not bad the hops are nice .  pours to a slightly hazy dark amber with little to no head formation and obviously no lacing or retention .  a soft beer in terms of mouthfeel . i like the texture -- a bit richer than most pilsners .

smells wonderful . citrusy , grassy hops - very much like an ipa - grapefruits . great smelling , very well balanced . taste is a little disappointing , however .  when i pored this beer i was not surprised it was a light gold like bud light smell was floral but not too strong sugesting no taste whatsoever head was not there but taste was really good i was really surpised i would try other types of this beer . light but refreshing not to heavy or bitter  m : light , crisp , highly carbonated . spot on for the macro style .

the aroma comes out to greet you with the smell of sweet , fresh strawberries ( not syrup , but the actual garden-grown berry ) .  a- no head ! ! !  nemesis is full-bodied , and very viscous . slick and chewy , with a dry , boozy finish . not a drainpour ... thorn telling rabbit to `` well , finish it up '' after a syrup chug victory in super troopers comes to mind , somewhat appropriately .

the aroma is of ambiguous roast , charred wood and some fruity , fusel alcohol - spot on for an imperial stout .  but after a day of construction work in the sweltering summer heat , nothing beats an ice cold budweiser .  m- mouthfeel is good enough , adequate carbonation .

aromas were sweet , i could smell the toffee .  poop when opened . almost no head .  very odd approach to the normally lush pumpkin pie nose in good pumpkin ales ... '' let 's go for the crust '' . mouth is also crust-forward , throughout the palate with little bitterness to speak of . a crust bomb .

s - the nicely malty base beer provided a good backbone while allowing the yeast nuances to flourish . funky wild yeast tones of barnyard lay behind a layer of clay and earth . the nose is nuanced by complex ! t - muted , muddled flavor is a big disappointment after the nuanced but pronounced aroma . the nose offers much more .  until i noticed it was just very hazy and not suspended yeast/bacteria floating in the beer .  m : light-medium body , moderate-lively carbonation and a very creamy , smooth texture .

a : dark black , opaque , dark brown head , good legs s : coffee , roasty malt , hops , dark fruit t : burnt bitter malt , bitter hops m : medium heavy , thick , flat , smooth d : i didnt care for the strong burnt malt flavor way beyond roast .  this beer pours into the glass with a pale golden body topped by a thin head with some lacing .  mouthfeel : the thing that 's done correctly with this brew , as it 's full , creamy , and has enough carbonation to make me crave the other wheat flavors and aromas that are too obfuscated by the boysenberry flavors and aromas .

smells nice . t : whoa .  a - clear yellow body with a head of white standing less than an eighth of an inch tall and fading very fast .  mouthfeel is medium to full in body with a creamy , inactive carbonation .

s- the smell is actually kinda nice . it is fruity with an effervescence to it .  it poured a very watery off yellow with very little head and light activity .  medium body and carbonation with slight clingy feel .

aroma is of fudgy chocolate brownies , crme brulee , creamed coffee , and a little sherry . the taste is shorter and thinner than expected , but still good . overall , this was enjoyable . i think this is more of an imperial stout with some slight barleywine characteristics .  ok chaps this beer is interesting rather than good and maybe therefore worth a try - had one yesterday : a - light very light almost like lemonade or maybe `` radler '' s - hops and slightly sweet then ... i dont know how to describe it ... men s loos ? t - it tastes the way it smells at first ok but unspecatcular with an interesting aftertaste that soon turns into something nasty and therefore worth atry m - like a light lager type beer - average d - once drinkable - i think you should try it  the mouthfeel was also very nice , it was silky smooth and almost kinda chewy . the alcohol gave a warming feeling to my mouth and throat .

smells piney soapyhops . okay , by the end of the glass , the hops were wearing on me .  lightly browned , thin , fizzy carbonation ... it looks like watered down cola . even for an american light beer , this is bad .  small crispness .

smell - hops , floral , yeast , sugars , has a lemonish orange aroma .  a cheerfully labeled 12oz bottle pours a lifeless pint of thick black liquid . absolutely no head .  mouthfeel is actually pretty good .

nice fruity aroma ... .the best part of the beer .  this beer pours a clear pale straw color with a hint of gold . the head is small , and recedes within seconds into nothing .  healthy carbonation lends a slightly acidity to the mouthfeel .

aroma has a nice pleasant fruitiness with christmas spices like nutmeg , cinnamon , and tart tropical fruit nose really makes this beer nice in the nose . overall , the nose was nice i liked the tropical tart fruit nose , but the barrage of harsh spice really ruins this beer .  pours very light , just slightly yellowed , minor white head and lacing . would hit the spot in an extreme heat wave or while pushing a lawn mower .  in the end there 's a soap hoppy bitterness ( more soap than hop ) that sticks on your tongue . in fact , i want to wipe my tongue and mouth off . maybe it 's something in the colorado water . i 'll have to ask coors ! for that reason , drinkability is low for me , although if this is your thing , it 's a truly smooth brew for the abv and the category .

s - strong sweet molasses . alot of olive oil smell at first . as it warmed faint anise aroma .  the color is such a pale yellow it almost looks green .  mouthfeel is full bodied and thick ; really syrupy , hot with alcohol , chewy , with decent carbonation .

the smell is a nice lager smell with a faint hint of citrus .  i picked up a 40 on a road trip and saved it to wash down some chicken biscuit sandwiches . basically all the g. heileman schwag beers are pretty much the same .  mf- light bodied and cool with very soft delicate carbonation . bubbles still have enough vigor to keep the beer from feeling flat .

leaves a nearly solid tan curtain of foam on the glass , some of the most impressive lacing i 've ever seen . s : thick , sweet , fruity . caramel , brown sugar , honey , orange , cherry , raspberry , balsam fir , grapefruit . d : very disappointed in the taste , it is completely dominated by spicy black pepper and alcohol . i 'm quite disappointed that harpoon would put out something like this , so overpowering with alcohol burn .  the inconvienient placement of a label band around the neck of the bottle made it almost impossible to avoid pouring in a few bits of yeast . there is nothing on the label about bottle conditioning either which makes it equally difficult to avoid flakes of yeast sediment . it poured an amber beer with a thin white head that subsided to a thin film .  the sourness is there but not terrible m- good carbonation and surprisingly not as thin as i expected .

this is a strange beer . the aroma is pretty good , stone fruit , apples , spice and a bit of roasted malt . they used a very funny yeast for this beer , and i do n't think that it holds up to the malt flavor well .  very lime-y not very beer-y , but got ta admit on a hot sunny day , very refreshing . possibly a good way to introduce `` non-beer-drinkers '' to beer ?  good moderate carbonation and med-light body .

the aroma is a wonderful mix of spicey banana and clove .  poured into a darkness tulip on 6/1/11 thanks to mbpbugeye for sharing with the group dense , dirty rust brown . they were gone in mere moments . weak ? dry finish ; a bit wine-like due to the lack of carbonation .  full bodied , lowly carbonation .

it smelled like pumpkin , not just a hint of pumpkin but kind of like someone just split open a pumpkin .  straw yellow appearance with surprisingly foamy head .  mouthfeel- medium body , with a nice level of carbonation that pushes the hops to the fore-front .

almost 'not impressed ' with the smell . the aromas are a f* mess ; yeasty milky chauky semi-sweet bready malt thing going on .  boring color , no head , the hops caused an imbalance of taste .  the chewy mouthfeel will keep you around to finish the pint you ordered , but i doubt you 'll want another .

smell is very potent , butterscotch and sweet . very refreshing dark lager overall .  shortest lived head i 've ever seen . ) a macro light beer . d/o- i think the fact that i went to hawaii and brought a couple back from hawaii only to find out it was n't hawaiian has something to do with the fact why it does n't taste as good here in il .  body is medium with good belgian carbonation .

s : pine and citrus hop smell .  not quite a `` red '' beer . soda pop foam when poured with no head or lace . wonder how it 'd be using a weiss beer as a base instead of macro lagar .  carbonation and feel were quite nice , but the taste just seemed to be lacking .

the aroma is pretty nice , strong , mainly hops , amarillo and some piney types , but also maple syrup and a detectable presence of alcohol .  poured into a pint glass with 2 pours . a 1 finger off white head that disappears to nothing quickly . transparent light yellow color .  feel is right on point for a five percenter . carbonation is there , seen and felt without biting the tounge .

s : coffee and hints of vanilla and nutmeg . graham crackers , too .  appearance : deep yellow . the head virtually imploded ( i blinked and it was gone ) ; nothing remained after two minutes ( i am using the proper glassware , of course ) and there was no evidence at all of lacing . very unimpressive .  quite well carbonated .

aromas are extreme . coffee , chocolate , roasted barley , and dark fruit for sure . i got no indication that this was going to be a booze bomb in any way .  poured into a samuel smith pint glass on 10/19/11 light , faded straw-yellow ; pretty clear save for a bit of chill haze . one and a half finger head of white foam dissipates to a much thinner , soapy layer . hardly any lace . my first impressions are , in this order : watery , carbonation , metallic .  the mouthfeel was nice , but i did n't take many notes about it .

citrus and some hops jump out but not as hoppy as ya think it would be .  no head whatsoever , which ruined the appearance for me .  this is the fifth hefeweizen i 've tried . of the five this ranks fifth best . something about these dundee beers that initially offers a metallic taste when cold . perhaps i 'd call this a beer that is better than dull but in need of some more flavor . at this moment , my hefe-universe is franzikaner and weihenstapher taking the lead , with sierra nevada a distant third , followed by paulaner . dundee sits behind paulaner .

aroma was light and zesty , and perhaps the best part of this ale - lemon , white pepper , and sourdough bread .  this one pours a very transparent slightly golden yellow . blah . this would be a good lawnmower beer on a very hot day , very cold .  mouthfeel is another positive factor of this beer .

there is n't much by way of smell you can detect a little burnt smell when you get close but nothing too prominent . not the best stout but i like it .  one of the worst looking beers i 've ever had ... even for a wheat . pale yellow and cloudy throughout . no foam at all and really no lacing either .  full bodied , smooth and creamy , low carbonation .

smell is quite good actually .  light yellow color , small , yellowish short lasting head .  m : starts off lightly sweet but finishes lightly dry . a nicely balanced beer that rations its flavors out well .

minimal head and some lacing huge whiffs of fresh ground coffee beans , heresey bar , caramel and vanilla beans .  a - pours a pale golden straw colour , thin layer of head with no retention or lacing . o - a poor excuse for an apa , though a touch better than coors light or the like .  a - one inch off-white creamy and fluffy head ; light copper/bronze colored ; clear appearance with visible carbonation ; small patches of lacing s - floral , herbal , and perfume-like aroma of hops ; butterscotch lingers in the background t - very floral , perfume-like taste up front that reminds me of bubble gum ; diacetyl buttery flavor is also noticeable beyond the floral/perfume characteristics ; taste becomes more leafy and vegetable-like at the end of the taste with diacetyl still present - this taste lingers on the palate ; somewhat bitter towards the end of the taste m - light to medium bodied ; moderate carbonation ; fairly smooth mouthfeel that 's a little dry in the finish o - i 'm not sure of the last time i had an english ipa , but maybe i 'm just not a fan of this style .

has a light smokey smell . tastes a bit smoked , starts hoppy , but not too much , finishes a bit malty , very unquie .  served in a standard unmarked pint glass , has the typical watery clear golden macro color . for a miller brewing co. macro , it 's not the worst beer they have made . crisp and clean , with very little taste . as far as macros go , this is near the top .  the mouthfeel is on point for the style : creamy and smooth without too much carbonation .

smells is completely dominated by the odor of fresh ground ginger and an every so slight maltiness . taste is very mild maltiness with a subtle layer of ginger followed by a touch of hops , very underwhelming .  a-pours a very clear straw color with a sad one finger head that dissipates very quickly .  mouthfeel is light having good body with crisp carbonation .

s - yeasty and funky with a strong fruity aroma there is a sour bite even in the aroma .  this is a very cheap light beer that delivers on a watered down flavor . the color is a very light yellow that is not that appealing . the finish is not very good but it is quite drinkable and if you are looking to drink alot of beer for very cheap , this just might be your beer .  very mild tingle on sides of front of tongue .

very flagrant , floral/sweet hops dominate the nose , citrus and grapefruit . t- well when i could taste the beer without the huge amount of head on the beer it was good . pretty bitter taste , grapefruit and grassy notes up front . d- bad with my problem but maybe pretty good in a good bottle of it .  singha pours a yellow color with a thin white head from a brown twelve ounce bottle .  the body is solidly full for being an under 5 % brew . the carbonation is right near where it needs to be , but to me comes across as just a touch low at times .

the smell is very dark coffee , nuts , a bit of sweetness .  straw yellow with extremely active carbonation and white head that pulls a disappearing act if you look away .  full body but light in the sense that it seemed to evaporate from the tip of my tongue before i could swallow .

s- smell is promising . nice nutty smell with caramel overtones .  i 'm going against the grain here . it is very refreshing and goes down very smooth . while it 's obviously not on the same level as most micro offerings , it accomplishes what it set out to do . i would much rather drink this than bud light or miller lite any day .  quite refreshing and smooth .

thankfully does n't smell like a lager , it has nice citrus , coriander and a light banana aroma .  this one is one of the palest yellow macros out there , with a fizzy white head that 's more like a sprite than a beer .  slightly thicker feeling that i would have expected , i 'd put this on down as being on the light side of medium bodied and with a smooth texture . it is quite clean and crisp with strong carbonation and a mild bitter finish .

strong husky hop aroma..almost some bouban smelll ... orange wit ha bubbly head ... great semell ... fruity taste ... grapefruit and tangerine ... hops do n't overwhelm on the buds as the smell may indicate ... spicy finish ... a quality beer ... if west coastamerican pale ale was listed in the dictionary i would expect a picture of this beside it..an excellent beer .  the apperance was below average , with particles at the bottom of the glass , at the finish .  m - light to medium body with medium carbonation .

s- very sweet aromas of maple taffy and/or syrup some moderate grainy malt and yeasty bread like creaminess dominate the smells here . on the finish , it becomes much drier and leaf like , but not bitter by any means . if this tasted as well as the aromas let on , i 'd be in heaven , but rather i ended up in hell .  appearance - hazy , cloudy blond with an inch of off-white foam that retained very poorly .  finishes dry and bitter m : light/medium bodied , goes down easy d : would probably not buy this again , lacked any good hop flavor , ended up just being too bitter , ended up pitching this down the drain

the smell is slightly hoppy with a light citrus smell , but overall the smell is weak .  i had the same problem as shiloh ; absurdly huge head and way too much carbonation . in fact , it tastes and smells good ; there 's just way too much air in the beer , even after a huge amount of the gas was dispensed by a head that resembled a hot air balloon with a tiny passenger basket of beer dangling underneath .  mouthfeel : lower than average carbonation , good for a stout . body is very good .

smell is very nice with chocolate and roasted coffee dominating . fairly bitter for my liking , but still an enjoyable , pretty complex brew .  pours a cloudy orange with almost no head what so ever and minimal lacing .  it tatsed like pine sap to me .
s - boozy , for sure , malty goodness underneath .  below average retention , no lace .  f : nice carbonation .

interesting scent . upon first whiff , this one screamed `` pilsener '' to me , but after a few minutes , i found myself finding much more complex notes of apple and tart , along with a nice generous dose of bitter hops . had a nose more like an amber than a pale ale -- color me impressed .  poured a light yellow .  this is the shining moment for this beer . the carbonation just tickles the tongue .

smell : a strong blackberry scent , but with a hint of raspberry . the smell is good kind of of like when you pull a cobbler out of the fridge .  a- pale golden , straw colored even . weak head . s- corn , with just a shade of toasted malt .  m- light in body and good amount of carbonation .

on tap at the pdx deschutes brewpub in a 12oz tulip a : dark as night with 1 finger head of tan foam and nice lacing s : dark roasty notes , chocolate , hints of licorice t : taste mostly of chocolate , dry in the finish , as it warms up you get spicy notes of the orange and maybe a hint of the peppers , it 's earthy and , according to my notes , `` woody '' in the finish .  appearance is of the usual macro , light gold . top-notch cheap beer if you know what i mean . poured the first glass , after returning to drink out of the 40- i feel it is too carbonated  mouthfeel was smooth , with a medium body .

s- spicy fresh ginger with a brown sugar sweetness , much like a ginger-snap cookie and pale maybe somewhat caramelish malt , aromatic wood and toasted marshmallow . hops are very subtle , i can feel them in my nose more than i can smell them . t- i expected a much sweeter beer with all the ginger snap aroma goin on , but i got loosely malted toasty beer water with some wet dog and a touch of citrusy menthol ginger in the background . d- i was locked on with the aroma , but was pretty disappointed with the rest .  a beer designed to be drinkable , and nothing more . poured a yellow so pale i almost thought it was mountain dew . head dissapeared quickly , leaving me with my light , indistinguashable beer .  medium bodied , decent carbonation .

s - vinous as hell . chocolate and roast malt with lot 's of coffee , licorice , and some vanilla . t - more vinous .  a - very light yellow . no head ... no lacing .  mouthfeel medium in the body with a nice smoothness in between the cheeks .

they are quite subdued compared to my recent exposure , but they are well applied in their tropical tastiness . o : the look and smell are nice , but the flavor is a substantial disappointment for me .  this beer poured a pale yellow with a fluffy two-finger head that did n't last long .  good mouthfeel ... lightly carbonated , somewhat creamy .
quite unique .  pours a cloudy burgundy-brown with no head and no lacing .  fairly full with nice carbonation i was a bit let down with this .

based on the taste , one could imagine a fruity smell , but for me , it would be mostly imagined , as there 's not much of a smell at all .  served a surprisingly light amber color with a light wisp of white foam . does not look very dubbel-esque .  m - medium-light body , low english-style carbonation , and a fairly clean finish .

its high point is a fresh , sweet nose with an acidic twang which reminds me of rhubarb .  there was nothing all that special that stood out with this beer.it was just an easy drinking beer with no outstanding characteristics to rave about.it was just another beer.it poured a small sized white head with fine-medium sized bubbles that quickly dissipated.the body was clear with slowly rising carbonation with a straw yellow hue.the nose was malty and hoppy and some fruit notes ?  the mouthfeel is thick and creamy and the taste is very sweet with tons of malt , though nothing particularity interesting . the hops in this taste very medicinal . the taste is a bit blunt and lacks refinement .

smell was also very nice , light , crisp , frity , floral .  lb is a pilsner , so it shares some flavor characteristics with the more widely enjoyed miller lite . head is somewhere between yellow and white , and does n't last long on top of the drink . - backdated tasting : i first reviewed this beer on 21sep03 , this post is based on notes from that review .  m : medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . keeps good with the style o : stays within style guidelines for some of the aspects like appearance and mouthfeel , but really lacks the flavor and bitterness that is usually present .

2/3 glass beer , and 1/3 glass of foam ... .drinking straight from the bottle it felt like a fizzy alcaseltzer in the mouth ... the nose is probably the highlight ... nice fresh piney aroma with some pink grapefruit rind ... .the aroma is fine . overall i would not purchase this one again .  this beer poured a clear lightish amber , with white uneven low density head that left absolutely no lacing at all .  m- rather creamy and smooth . at least something is going right with this beer .

forst 25cl bottle only 3.5 abv and two months over date ( which i dare risk with lambic style beers ) a : hazy , dark red colour , almost no head ( not that strange for a lambic ) s : cherries a bit sweet but still real cherries , some tartiness t : way sweeter than i expected , tastes more artificial then it smells , not doing it for me m : it could do with a bit more gas , a bit too sticky o : it 's a no for me , i like my cherrie beers sour , i knew this was more on the sweet side , but it is really at the end of the spectre .  pours a one finger bright white head . head fizzles down quickly . color is a clear straw yellow .  body is more impressive with a gentle carbonation through a medium-thin body that makes you want to chew it . crisp with the pils , but still comes out tasting like a macro .

very nice . m - wtf man ? very dissapointing . lacking in some aspects , but still very enjoyable .  birra moretti is a crystal clear , straw colored beer with a white head that vanishes instantly .  the joy of this beer is in its exact representation of the stated ingredients on the bottle . in this case , the beer was light on the tongue in terms of crispness . there is a mild bitterness imparted by the hops but the gist is spice . definitely compelling . as for drinkability , this falls into the one and done category that is best shared amongst guests who are already drinking spiced eggnog .

below average head retention & good lacing after studying my glass further ) s : caramel , a little toasted malt & choclate t : caramel sweetness up front , then some earthy hops & grainyness as this warms .  appearance : hazy , no head .  m : light body and good carbonation .

jolly pumkin ales have a signature aroma that comes from their yeast strain . slightly funky and you really can build up an anticipation of tart just from the aroma . first drink and like usual i was taken back by how unique this brew is . its tart for sure and has an almost over the top citrus frontside and a mysterious chocolaty backside . what an odd combination .  the only really disapointing part was the lack of head .  feels pretty good going down , kinda thick with a long lingering bittersweet aftertaste and just a touch of warming slightly reminiscent of a tripel .

the smell is sweet , with a balanced blend of hops and burned malt .  looks thin and is thin . as i filled the glass it looked like pouring water that had been tinted with mercury .  mouthfeel and drinkability are this beers best attributes ... the beer is crisp and has a little bit of a bite on the tongue and lips .
s - crisp , floral , grassy grainy aroma typical of a high quality pils . t - kinda of a boring pils .  deep murky dark brown color . no lacing at all .  big full bodied beer .
smells of american c hops and some sweet alcohol .  pours a very pale yellow with a very thin head that dissipates very quickly .  m : high carbonation keeps it fairly light . quite drying .

n : eh , some dark chocolate , espresso , yada yada . smells like a stout .  a- i knew it advertised added beet juice but i was not expecting it to come out looking like cranberry sparkling soda . did not make me think `` summer beer '' m- like a less carbonated soda , but has the consistency just more carbonated than water .  m : good amount of carbonation runs off the middle of my tongue . medium thickness feel .

the aroma was of sweet malt and dark fruits . the look and aroma said sweet dark fruits , but the taste only delivered a washed out tanin flavor .  '' a murky brown pour yields no head whatsoever .  m - medium body and low carbonation .

ya , its the minimum in beer ; slight blond color , weak aroma and a disappearing head .  the color is surprisingly light , just a tinge darker than dirty water .  the feeling in the mouth is much warmer than the feeling of the glass in the hand .

sweet lemony and orange citrus zest , champagne-like yeastiness .  almost no carbonation or lacing .  mouthfeel is nice and smooth , coats well , but this is a 20 % + beer , and it should feel good going down .

i tried this beer at gabf . loved the vw and loved the taster books . s-well there was some burnt aroma rolling off early with a carmel finish .  a - pours out a gold color . no head and not very much carbonation .  with this final rogue , top 100 brew , i am now done with the brewery for the indefinite future . i could do without the funky ceramic bottle , but maybe i 'll find a use for it in home brewing . the aroma is a jumbled mix of bitter hops , bitter chocolate , and stale coffee . it 's acceptable , but not overly enjoyable . raw , acrid pine hops mixed with bitter chocolate does not a pleasing combination make . too sour and bitter , with almost a hint of saltiness about it . this is a melding of styles that did n't work at all . this is only the second below average grade i 've ever given to an ris .
s- citrusy hops are almost overwhelming on the nose .  it was an unusually pale yellow for an ipa .  well carbonated , with pretty good mouthfeel .

s : this smells absolutely awesome ! rich chocolaty smell . i love it ! t : this did n't taste at all like what i had expected .  pours a crystal clear fizzy yellow as expected .  good body , bit of carbonation but not harsh .

the nose is full of grain malts and a little citrus .  a - clear golden color with a thin layer of head on top . noticed that small bubbles kept floating up while drinking this lager .  m : well carbonated , crisp .

not a really bad beer , but in no way exceptional . everything is pretty much on par for a run of the mill mocrobrew , but this beer suffers from a strange juniper/pine flavor that definitely does not belong . there is an unwanted sharpness that deteriorates into a warm , bitter aftertaste .  better than expected for a cheap beer . my personal favorite from the cheap easy to drink category .  a nice mouthfeel , creamy medium body that is buoyed by the airy , not fizzy , carbonation .

s : bready malts with notes of ripen fruit , yeast , and a hint of caramel sweetness . t : toasted bready malts , like in the nose , is the main flavor here .  poured a medium reddish color ( cherry kool-aid ) with a smaller sized pinkish head . one wacko looking beer .  it 's not bad , necessarily , it 's just totally wrong for the style . that said , the mouthfeel is smooth , thick and rich , and the 6.3 % abv is nicely concealed .

s- pleasant aroma . had a nice brett smell accompanied by a vinous , sour characteristic .  this is a strange bird - poured into a tall glass , it gathered no head at all - so i stepped up my testosterone pouring the second half of it aggressivley - still nothing , and nothing came . deep golden colour - got myself ready for a sweet maibock like taste .  decent body ... it 's a carbonation supported medium body which makes it clean and crisp like crunchy fall leaves . i like the mouthfeel , just not too much else .

okay this was way too sweet and way too orangey for the beer . slow down on the spices and fruit , stick with what you know .  pours a pale yellow color , with no lacing , very little foam head , that quickly dissapear , smells like rice and corn , low alcohol volume , very crisp , does well chilled with asian spicy food , had it for the first time at a thai restaurant and loved it with the food .  md thick mouthfeel and strong carbonation .

aroma is interesting . my first thought was that it was almost like a high quality golden tequila , but no , it 's sweeter and fruitier , but there is something in there- wood smoke like i remember from the bad old days when i liked that other stuff . quite a disappointment after the decent interesting aroma . no spices , no complexity , no pepper , weak fruit .  not a bad beer at all if your looking for an inexpensive , refreshing , macro . the color and head retension leave something to be desired .  m - kind of a lingering bitter finish . fairly full bodied with moderate carbonation .
very intimidating for me .  appearance- received with no head again ! medium brown color body , good clarity within the body , and leaves no lace .  full-bodied with moderate carbonation .

aroma is cherry . somewhat artifical . after the aroma , i really wanted to like this , but just ca n't .  pours with a pale golden body topped by a thin head with little lacing .  m - light-bodied but definately present . nice carbonation .

lots of cloves . my brother , who loves belgium beers , bought this . i went with another wheat beer for my next . might be heading to the store for so e seasonal american ales !  i mean i guess im someone who appreciates beer at a good price , not that i wont spend my money on some quality stuff as well . as for corona it goes down smooth with little to no after taste , watery and good for people who dont like the bitterness of beer .  m - creamy and full d - not what i was expecting .

i love the blast of hops on the nose of this one . underneath that , there 's some sludgey , malty , molasseslike tones on the nose . great nose . it reminds me a lot of the alpha klaus aroma-wise . alcohol is hidden nicely . and the mouthfeel is quite pleasant . good all around .  downright shitty head retention and no beer lace . maybe this is due to the utter lack of head on the beer .  mouthfeel is medium-full , and is actually quite nice , but still this is not a stout in any way , shape , or form . sorry potosi , had to review to style , but i know you can do better !

pleasant nose full of grain and malts , quite appetizing to smell .  the color is a dark purple with small whitish floaties . the reason i thought that it was bad was because it had floating stuff in it .  mouthfeel is full bodied and not overly thick or viscous .

very nice . wow - where to begin with the taste , again tremendous complexity .  looks like my piss .  lindemans faro drinks pretty much like an apple juice infused gueuze . the problem is an unwelcome bombardment of sweetness . where i wish i would find increased tartness , its more layers of sugar . the way the sweetness lingers and mixes up with some unexpected must is interesting . it contains more funk , sour apple , and only a hint of the sweetness to follow on the tongue . this may ( or may not ) be a good example of the style , but i cant get into this beer . still , not entirely undrinkable .
smell is good .  the beer poured with literally no head and no explosion of carbonation within the beer . it looked totally flat . none whatsoever ! no lacing at all .  medium mouthfeel , smooth .

mainly peppercorn on the nose . some toasted malts can be noticed , but they 're pretty subdued by the onslaught of pepper . if you want to try something different , go for it , but unless you love pepper this beer probably wo n't impress you .  i tried eel river 's amber or something and was n't a fan of that one either . mouthfeel : decent taste : so-so color : pretty , but not an ipa color , maybe a 15 on the srm scale .  perfect for the style , extra stout all the way .

the bouquet is a well-balanced matching of pungent florals at first and a nutty , caramel-like sweetness in the finish . the nose also has a slight doughy or buttery presence that rounds out the bouquet .  if you like cheap and drinkable beer that still has some sort of taste and substance , this is definitely for you . while it has the characteristics of macro lager written all over it , it just has that little extra quality that makes you say `` hey this is n't half bad .  not a lot of carbonation . has a smooth feel and quite a heavy body .

this beer also has a wonderful aroma , bright grains are present , and some cut grass . unfortunately , this beer is all looks and no brains .  this is missing something . clear amber pour . no matter how hard i tried , i could not coax a head out of this beer .  its palate was very smooth and it gad a plesant malt fore and after taste .

s - not much going on with the smell ... malts and floral smells . t - great matly flavor with some hop presense .  pours an extremely clear pale yellow .  m-has a good medium creamy carbonation with a slightly dry finish .

the nose was upfront with a big coffee aroma , not overpowering , but definately solid . chocolate and caramel notes are present , as well as a roasty aroma .  a : pours a murky straw color with a huge rocky head that faded to absolutely nothing and left no lace .  m : nice and crisp , full-bodied , but like a soda , making it pretty easy to drink for an 8 % beer .
