aroma is sweet flowers and esters .  while this is not a complex beer , it is one of the easiest beers to drink , and it has just as much flavor as any of the run of the mill beers by anheuser busch , miller , or coors . while pabst is certainly nothing to look at , it is indeed bland , it is made up for by a better than average taste , and by being incredibly easy to drink . i recommend this beer highly for someone looking for a great value , and a solid , run of the mill beer .  not even a hint to it being a beer . i would think this is just black cherry soda . in fact , i thought it was way too sweet and a strong black cherry flavor overpowered the beer . there was a slight ketchup taste that i find in flemish sours .

was n't a big fan so i 'll stick to the facts ; a - looks like you would expect a blond to be . it also had medium carbonation s - slightly sweet and citrussy t - bitter then expected after the initial smell .  poured a bright orange with lots and lots and lots and lots and lots and lots and lots and lots of sediment .  s : this is the best part of this beer . m : it 's fairly smooth and none abrasive .

that being said , this beer does not look or smell impressive at all . sometimes it does not really matter .  it looks unassuming enough at first , like apple juice with a little over half an inch of white head . the resulting floating sludge appearance is not exactly appetizing .  the beer pours a fantastic long lasting head and was very murky although there is a full half inch of yeast slurry in the bottom of the bottle that i tried to leave behind . the yeast character of the beer overall is superb . the ester/higher alcohol balance is perfect . overly bitter , lingering , harsh and leaving an unpleasant finish . a shame the recipe let down the other quality work here . not quite as good as american flatbread or otter creek 's recent tripels .

the nose was a nice mix of soft caramel , chocolate and malt . sort of a large malt smell but very toned down .  freshness marked as `` enjoy by aug. '' pours a very pale , straw-ish yellow colored beer , touch of haze , with scattered slow moving carbonation bubbles . quick white foam heads dies to a translucent wispy lacing of almost nothingness . hmm ... i guess if you wanted a beer that you did n't really have to think about and wanted to suck down your neck in the hot summer ... this could be your beer .  a- bright crisp golden-orange , with a thin , though relatively resilient , head . t- a faint , watery lead-in leads to a sudden crescendo of unbalanced , un-alloyed bitterness . my wife finds a much more citric flavor , if i find this to be the case in future bottles , i will revise this review to reflect that . m- decent , sturdy , not to thin , slightly creamy . d- this bottle , to me , is unballanced and hard to enjoy .

very nice auburn/caramel sort of a color . no aroma except to say `` beer '' .  a : the beer is a pale gold color with a very thin white head that fades at almost instantly and leaves very little lace on the glass .  medium mouthfeel .

the aroma is much better . there is also a burnt malt taste here . overall , the nose was solid and i thought this beer was going to be good .  heavy carbonation with absolutly terrible brew head .  md-sstrong carbonation is about right .

the aroma is wicked sweet of raspberry , but as it warms up it smells more like roses .  this is a day at the the beach beer for me . great for pitching shoes , volleyball and kicking back in the sun .  it 's not quite what i expected in way of body and flavor , but as it 's warm outside i found that i drank it very fast . this beer has a smooth and very mild flavor , with little hops . the aroma is also very mild , with light citrus . while i do n't feel that this beer is very representative of the wheat ale , i do think it 's an excellent beer for beginner beer drinkers . it 's an easy beer to help transition from the common american beers .

aroma is good , head is good .  a medium sized white head with fine sized bubbles.the body was carbonated and slightly hazy.the hue of this beer was a pale yellow and it left only a fair amount of lacing on the sides of my glass.the nose was malty and somewhat fruity.the flavor was bitter , sweet and it left an aftertaste that lingered.the mouthfeel was smooth and thin.this beer lacks character as nothing really stood out with this beer .  good body for the style .
s : rich caramel and toffee aromas with an underlying nutty character .  a - poured out a clear yellow color with no head or lace .  medium/light mouthfeel .

aroma : smell is nice and complex . notes of molasses , smoked barley , and dark chocolate/coffee . inviting . taste : hmmm .  pours an almost clear yellow gold colour , with just a fizzle of head that spends itself quickly , dissipating to a ring of tiny bubbles around the edges . for something that calls itself a hefeweizen , it 's incredibly clear , despite the fact i swirled the bottom third of the bottle trying to stir up some sediment . nothing . a real shame - this is a very lacklustre looking beer . there 's nothing really off about it , it 's just incredibly dull and only barely scraping acceptability stylistically .  taste is smoky , doughy and of some dark fruitiness as well . smoky lingering flavor in the finish . light bitterness but i just was n't a fan of the smokiness in this beer .
smells really nice with strong cocoa scents .  faint yellow , no head . very cheap , hence , drinkable .  mouthfeel is creamy and bold .

s - funky , earthy and tart barnyard aromas at the initial smell .  pours very light amber below a wimpy white head .  the mouthfeel is the creamy nitro , and definitely the most pleasurable aspect of this brew .

smell -- sweet toasted malts , caramel , hints of chocolate . smells like a hearty , if not overly complex brew .  12 oz bottle poured into a mug a : pours an unappealing clear yellow , with a small white head s : has kind of a sour skunky smell , the smell i associate with most macro lagers t : taste is actually not bad , generally what i look for in a macro is the absence of any off flavors , and i find this particular bottle of heineken tastes pretty clean .  m - medium body with a good amount of carbonation .

stirred up a bit ( i know ) it gives off a very pleasing citrus/floral bouquet that really gets my hopes up t : not at all like the nose.. maltier up front with a creeping bitterness without any real hop notes , almost tastes like they used noble german hops like hallertau ... not what i was hoping for , it 's missing the botanicals that really keep me an ipa fan , a little spice/citrus finish perhaps ? sorry brew dog , i was pulling for you being half scottish , i like your stout but you might have to call this an english ipa rather than the american ( west coast/san diego ) style that we 've been spoiled on .  otherwise , it 's unremarkable . no head , no lacing .  the pumpkin and yam really gives it a nice full flavor and sweetness to counter the bitterness of the hops . m/o : very crisp and drinkable but also has a lot of complicated flavors . it 's nice but a little overwhelming with the flavors .

the aroma was smoky with hints of bittersweet chocolate .  beer is amber wiht no head , no lacing and strong carbonation .  some alc in the taste 4 m light to medium bodied , goes down easy but for abv 1.5 d 6.5 abv a bit excessive for single ipa .

s : smell is light , yeast , some breadiness , a bit of sweetness . t : lots of malt in this one .  a pale yellow pour with not much head , not much retention , and not much worth commenting on .  m : heavy bodied giving it a syrupy texture and has relatively low carbonation . it leaves a very sweet sticky feeling in the mouth begging for another drink .
this beer smells great , but failed for me in the taste department .  pours a four finger white head that fades quickly leaving no lace .  medim bodied with good effervescence .

smells good too .  had this late july in nc , review based on notes poured black with 1 finger of tan head . zero lacing & head retention s : some coffee grounds t : coffee through & through , nothing to balance it out all .  nice sweet malty straw taste with a medium mouthfeel .

the aroma is full of chocolate with some fruity undertones that remind one of cherries .  straw yellow appearance with foamy head that disappears quickly .  m - good carbonation , fairly large amount of bubbles .

a pretty good aroma overall .  milk stout 's appearance is its worst feature . the hint of red , however , is not a good development as it causes the stout to look watered down when in rests on the table .  feel : nicely velvety and soft , with a prickly medium carbonation and a body a shade over medium light .

the smell is dominant . it was very bready with faint hops smell .  1st smell - not much here , a little bit of that `` typical beer '' smell you get from a bunch of empty bottles laying in the trash ; but overall pretty bland 1st taste - watery , not much taste here ; the only taste i can really put my finger on is the typical macro lager taste ( they pretty much all taste the same - bud , coors , miller , etc . as far as sitting down and actually enjoying a good tasting beer , i would not recommend this one .  m : mouthfeel is on the mark . thick , moderate carbonation .

maybe it was the pour ( 40f into a chimay glass ) but i saw only a very small head , very small amount of lacing , and not much retention . that 's not to say i did n't enjoy it . the flavor was strongly malt forward with toasty , nutty with a hit after of piney hops , like cascades .  a- pours a clear golden color with a thin white head that quickly settles to a small ring . no lacing left . t- seltzer water with toasted grain and burnt corn flakes .  thin mouthfeel with a miniscule note of grains and hops .

smells like peat , malt , trainstation bathroom . after i got over the aroma the mildness and longevity of the flavor is amazing .  the beer is dark brown , almost black , nearly no head , no lacing . looks stale .  mouthfeel was fairly flat .

smell : nothing here to really speak of . a deep whiff reveals a biscuity malt aroma . other than that there 's really nothing going on .  pours a typical clear straw yellow with a thin white head .  mouthfeel : thin with no carbonation .

okay , well let 's get this started a- very nice golden colour with some light lacing , barely any head at all s- very malt vinegary , it was very off-setting for me as i 'm not a fan of the smell , but ... t- ah , the taste was so different from the smell !  retention is pretty poor .  weak , watery mouthfeel with a mineral water like flavor .

it 's potent and makes me think of something like cheap scotch mixed with an innocent pale ale .  original rating date : october 19 , 2008 pours light yellow , some hops on the nose . adequate carbonation .  mouthfeel : very light and flat .
pours really dark , with almost no aroma whatsoever .  appearance : cloudy orange with lots of weird particulate floating around .  m- thin . somewhat creamy , but overall a bit watery and thin .

i bought a bomber of big ballard in a grocery store . smell is faint , with a hint of sweet citrus , not the turpentine scent i might have expected from a nw dipa .  a : pours a hazy dark amber with zero head .  m -- watery , definitely could use a bit more body .

appearance- pale , clear yellow gold ... a three finger heads stands atop the surface . smell- a noseful of corn or rice is all i 'm getting here , with a hint of metal or ice cold chrome ... sweet and creamy , and vegetal .  now , on to the review ... pours a very clear slightly amber tint , fizzy white head settles very quickly . heavy carbonation .  mouthfeel was pretty thin after drinking through such a promising head .

a strong coffee scent overpowers all other aromas .  a : bright yellow color , with a poor foamy head , some bubbles too ; s : smooth , fresh malt and grain with plenty of carbonation ; t : sweet malt , grain and peanuts ; m : fizzy , refreshing , light body ; d : better than coors light , i enjoyed a lot with lunchables .  this medium bodied beer is too fizzy and overcarbonated .

the smell is a little disappointment ; it is like average ale of this style but more delicate . it was hardly any scent at all , but there was a little touch of hops .  appearance- there is a reason its served in a brown glass bottle . explosive head that rapidly fads and a pale clear yellow body .  mouthfeel was surprisingly thin for the style .

s- it 's your average american lager smell , really nothing inviting that grabs you like all right this is going to be awesome , unless you drop your lime in it before you take your first whiff , cause who do n't like the smell of limes ? t- it 's good as long as you have your lime floating around releasing it 's fruity awesomeness , like i said i would only drink one if limes are available , if not i 'll pass instead give me a ipa !  this is a plain looking pale beer with little head or lacing .  mouthfeel dissipated quickly .

no aroma . malty with a slight sweetness .  this beer is to get you drunk for as little money as possible . it smells pretty bad , tastes pretty bad , and looks like warm piss .  mouthfeel is thin and watery with low carbonation .

s : grainy , husky nose . t : taste like banana , comes from the yeast strain .  under hopped caramel bomb , weird burnt orange unappealing color , subtle notes of pine but otherwise reminds me of a milder version of dogfish head 90 minute , probably one of the less pleasant ipa smells on record .  mouthfeel , like i said was cold , also way too fizzy . i 'm not used to a white beer feeling like soda . drinkability is 'average ' because it 's not terrible , it basically is a normal run-of-the-mill white beer , but the carbonation and temp .

i love that smell . taste is like smoke sausage .  i tried this beer a few weeks ago and when i poured it there was absolutely no head . last night i gave it another chance and again there was no head . a - no head . zero .  mouthfeel was a bit watery and flat .

not a bad pale wheat but not my favorite and it 's strange that whole foods would be introducing this as one of their growler features so late in the season . very pale color , which is nice .  poured into pilsner glass pale yellow with minimal head that disappears almost instantly .  mouthfeel : the weakest aspect of this beer , very thin .

there is nothing really special about this beer . it is good beer to have while relaxing on a hot day . much better `` hot day '' alternative to coors light , miller light , bud light ... yes , i respect beer , i 'm not a pretentious beer drinker ... i will on occasion drink the above mentioned light beers . next time you are about to grab some coors light , try the landshark instead .  750ml swinging pop top poured into tulip may16,2011 a cloudy golden orange that 's cloudy enough that i ca n't see the bubbles , they do however spawn a fast falling two finger bone white head that leaves zero lace s banana , dry cereal , lemon and some yeasty spice and some very faint soap t some bubblegum comes out and there 's just a little more earthy spice then i could smell , somehow everything mingles just right and this is what i think the stereotypical hefe should taste like , the bananas just a little bruised compared to the smell but i always liked my banana just a little overripe anyways m light and fluffy due to a decent amount of carbonation , lingering flavors stick to my lips well after the liquids in my tummy o when i visualize a hefe i think of a big ass , hard to fit into my over sized glass , top hat of foam that just lasts forever , this was not that beer .  m - moderately carbonated , and starts off with a light to medium body . by the end of the sip though , this turns completely watery and flat . the mouthfeel is what messes this beer up for me .

s = a light smokey flavor but not overly impressive .  pitch black , can not see a hue or carb action , and the brown fizzy head dissipated to nothing within seconds . this drink swirls around like they made an imperial stout soft drink ( cola ) , appears cheap , and as one can predict `` ... this is going down the drain ... '' .  too thin , and too carbonated . the mouthfeel is killing all the fun of drinking this for me .

smell- a great mix of fresh baked bread , kfc biscuits and very aromatic hops . the balance of this beer was excellent . the bread dough malts and floral/citric hop bitterness was a great combo .  a- super macro , very fizzy at the start of the pour but really no head-at all . nice golden color .  very carbonated . watery mouthfeel .

it smells like the ambient air in the room i am in -- traces of my cat mixed with cooked onion wafting in from the kitchen to remind me i need to clean up after the chili i made earlier . if i sniff really hard i get laundry detergent from the shirt i am wearing ( it 's not even clean ) . the flavors of a really good beer are there , they just seem really watered down .  pours a pale gold , not yellow , gold , with a small , two millimetre head .  way , way too thin for an oatmeal stout . the body is light and watery , while the moderate massaging carbonation makes the beer break out in soft fizziness .
smell has that distinct lager smell , slightly skunky .  appearance- an average yellow lager with virtually no head .  very dry finish ... watery , no body , but some bitterness .

fresh hop aroma gives away to burnt brown sugar molasses type scent . just wish it was stronger . kind of leaves me dry mouthed and unhappy especially with all the esteem surrounding this beer and there arrogant bastard attitude .  pours an effervescent copper with 2 fingers of fast falling cream colored head . no lacing or head retention s : vegtal & metallic odors up front .  mouthfeel : no carbonation really hurts this beer when it comes to mouthfeel and overall enjoyment .

pours a typical clear straw yellow . s- bready , grainy is the first thing that catches the nose . slight rice smell .  pours a pale color , slightly cloudy with a small almost non existent head .  very thin in the mouth , like carbonated water .

not a whole lot of aroma . whatever 's detectable is standard english ale esters , a bit of plum and grassy malts .  poured from a 12oz bottle into a pint glass ... a-pours a very faint pale straw yellow color with a white fingers worth of head that dissipates right away to just a ring ... s-very light and sweet aroma like peaches and sweet fruits , very light malts and some corn ... t-very fruity and sweet up front like peaches or passion fruit and very malty with a corn like finish , very light and smooth .  mouthfeel was poor due to the lack of carbonation . it felt quite heavy , flat and oily with no real finish to each sip other than the burnt bitterness .

above average lacing & zero head retention s : not much , some metallic hops t : metallic hops , grainyness & cranberry juice or is it pomegranate ? ?  the lack of head makes the appearance factor drop a bit for me ... smells of pumpkin , anise , thanksgiving-style spices and a lingering fruity/spicy esters .  not bad , but this is one of those rare beers for me that struggles on mouthfeel ; this one is thin to the point of watery .

nose is flat . medium roasted malt flavors . fairly long finish ( more than i expected for a beer like this ) .  it looks like a flat apple cider .  overcarbonated with more cola likeness in the mouthfeel . more lace , less cola character , less carbonation .

s- a little hoppy , but sweet smell to it .  when poured properly , minimal head and lacing appear , and remain . not so bad .  the flavor has a slight bit of chocolate and a hint of roastedness , but it 's very plain and thin . almost watered down .

then it smells kind of nasty .  poured a very light transparent gold with a head that contained enormous bubbles . it 's got ta be like the busch of mexico . it 'd probably be easy to drink enormous quantities of this , so it 's got that going for it . it 's incredibly watery , but not really refreshing , in the way that club soda 's not very refreshing since that 's basically what this tastes like .  m : very watery looks thick , but is not .

really a breathtaking nose combining and punctuating all the great aspects of belgian dark ales . it smells amazing , but the taste and balance are completely out of whack .  looks pale yellow with a bubbly white head that does n't last long .  m : medium-bodied , almost completely flat , and 100 % boring .

the smell was that of a skunked pilsner . the skunk overpowered the hop and alcohol notes .  bottle poured into a tulip a : pours a very light straw yellow . it has a fizzy head with large bubbles , nothing spectacular .  the body was weak in depth , even for a lager/pilsner based beer : almost watery in fact , even though it was highly carbonated .

just a clasic looking stout if there ever was one . not much aroma-some malt and a sweetish sort of tinge . deep , hearty flavor . just enough sweetness in it to balance the roasted malt . full bodied . amazing how much flavor a beer of 4.9 % can be . i have enjoyed this for at least 25 years , long before craft beers were out there like they are now .  pours a pale red amber with a bubbly head that reduces to a bare lacing very quickly .  the taste is pretty sugary on the tongue and a little sticky . very watery with not much in the way of depth .

the nose is weak & thin & reminds me of a macro .  a : pale yellow body . s : similar to the other light macros - there 's not much of anything to point out . t : again , close to the other macro lights , but i do pick up a very slight sweetness to the 1/2 beer-1/2 h2o flavor .  very thin body , low carbonation .

s : sweet smell of grain and brandy ... the 14 % alcohol is evident . the finish is very long due to this consistency .  this very pale yellow brew is topped by a medium thick head with some lacing left behind .  it 's medium-light bodied and pretty scratchy in the mouth . it 's a bummer about the mouthfeel .
aroma : barely detectable notes of light bread and caramel . no hop aroma . overall very light on the nose .  an ol fizzy yellow brew , no head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied but very watery .

the aroma is a sour corn grist that is on the more offensive side of average .  it is smooth and easy to drink , making it a good party beer . though not terrific , it is worth a try , good for those accustomed to macrobrews .  mouthfeel was very thin for a porter .

the rye is there in the nose , along with that kind of dingy stale smell that a lot of pas throw off . a noble hop profile contributes to the aroma but adds almost no bitterness to this brew .  a-pale gold , thick white head s-smells like sweet barley , light , not impressive t-this is n't completely terrible .  12 oz bottle poured into a tulip glass a : orange and hazy with no head s : spices a bit of sweetness and faint alcohol t : sweetness both malty and from the sugar , spicy , apple-cider like flavor , faint alcohol m : almost no carbonation , medium body d : due to the lack of carbonation and mediocre taste this one was hard to swallow .
the smell and taste are enhanced with grain .  the beer poured a pale yellow , had no head whatsoever .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and thin with low carbonation , underwhelming .

clear straw yellow in color . smells just a little skunked but not enough to turn off , and theres a little grassy smell too .  although i ca n't say that i enjoy iron city -- basically just a super fizzy bland lager -- i would encourage anyone that visits the 'burgh to have one .  m ) all up front , empty at the back , light & bland d ) a good value lawnmower beer , that starts off well , but disappears quickly .
smells hoppy and skunked , but then , to me , all lagers smell the same .  it 's super clear yellow complete with fizzy white head .  m - watery , thin , and weak .

s : yeah , not much of anything here . the big star of this show is diacetyl , with a medium malt hint and almost no hops at all . weak . it is n't a terrible beer , by any stretch of the imagination , but it just reeks of unrefined brewing techniques and poor quality control .  it looks like bud light .  m & gt ; very watery .

s- not what i was expecting at all . the aroma is chemically-sweet and sugary with very little presence of citrusy or piney hops . there are faint notes of pineapple , but i 'm mainly getting a strong malt presence backed by a good dose of alcohol . there is a somewhat artificial quality to the smell of this beer . plus , the smell and the flavor of this beer are chemical-like and medicinal , making this a chore to drink .  you know , i know i should really be the good beer snob and say `` oh this shit sucks , tastes like hoss pee ... '' but i 'm going to commit total heresy tonight , and tell you what i honestly remember from the notes ... the pour and appearance looks like any other golden-orange malt liquor . there 's a little bit of lace though , amazingly enough ... the aroma is musty , metallic , and alcohol-y ... smells quite terrible , really . look , i really would n't consider this beer , because it 's not , but dammit , when it 's a good party goin ' on and i wan na let my `` gangsta '' side hang loose , i will hit the 40 long and hard .  mouthfeel was very very weak .
aroma is pretty piny , very hoppy , smells pretty good , there is some sweetness in there too .  absolutely no head formation or retention .  pretty thin mouthfeel also .

smell is very faint , not really much going on here . taste is far better than the smell , that being said it 's similar to grolsch but with less carbonation .  clear yellow , slightly ambered . highly carbonated . head dissipates quickly .  this brew starts out weak flavored , weak bodied , and , for me , continued to seem weaker and weaker as my palate adjusted to it . the bottom line : if you want to give mr. sam smith your money , exchange it for some oatmeal stout or imperial stout .

appearance : pale gold , good clarity , big pillow of frothy white foam with a rocky top , ok head retention aroma : grain , wet cardboard , cooked peas , hint of indescript fruitiness flavor : crisp lagery maltiness with an underpinning of passion-fruity hop flavor ; soap and corn ; very light bitterness ; finishes dry with a mild acidity and grainy aftertaste mouthfeel : light body , pert carbonation , crisp texture other comments : `` american macro lager '' ?  12oz bottle poured into a standard pint glass this beer has a surprisingly light color and was almost apple juice looking .  it tasted wheaty , slightly spiced and flat . it leaves a flat taste in the mouth as the taste sticks in the mouth . aftertaste does n't stick around that long and the beer goes down fairly easily .

not a bad beer , but certainly nothing amazing either . it had a bit of a citrus taste but it was n't overwhelming at all . seems like this is more of a summer beer so i imagine it has been sitting on the shelf for a little while . i gave it a shot as part of a mix and match sample pack . it was worth a shot .  poured into a tulip snifter . pours a somewhat cloudy gold . the head was initially about one finger of white foam , but it fizzed away into nothingness in almost record time . no lacing on the glass .  carbonation could be better ( little more then a tickle ) , but then it would feel even thinner . not a strong bite , no body , barely hopped , dark with good flavor .

nose is wonderful- flowery hops , honey sweetness , and delicate jasmine . where the nose succeeds , the taste falls short . it 's way too flowery , like perfume . some hops in the middle , but the flower finish kinda ruins it . not sure i would buy this again ; i wish the taste could echo the wonderfully balanced nose .  apperance : straw yellow with a minimal head .  mouthfeel : this beer was too bland for me and on the thin side .
the nose is a chalky sweetbread with a alchohol metallic note .  looks like apple juice .  the mouthfeel is very very fizzy , it 's almost like drinking foam .
in the nose is stale yeast and sweet grain .  ligh golden with quite weak head and similarly bad lacing .  m : worst part by far . way too light of a body and poor carbonation . it feels watery .

not much of the way of smell at all , completely lacking . not good but not bad just kind of boring .  pours clear and quite pale from a 12 oz . a hard to obtain cap of foam settles quickly as large bubbles pop away . a light carbonation from the bottom of the glass weakens in short order . nose is light overall , offering uncooked grain sense to it yet without metallic or vegetal notes to speak of .  yeah , i know , it 's an irish dry stout , and yeah , it 's supposed to be light for drinkability 's sake ... but it 's awful thin stuff , as if beer and water were mixed 50-50 . i love guinness extra stout , but guinness draught is just too anemic in taste , too watery in the mouth , just overall too ... lite .
minimal aroma , some sour and oatmeal scents .  it looked very light and bubbly .  mouthfeel : thin .

a - very black appearance with a little amber head and no lacing s - no smell to really pick up on t - smokey wheat and malt taste that is fairly crisp m - has a little bite to it and medium carbonation d - interesting brew would n't drink it all the time but worth trying .  deep yellow , golden . white foam , a bit scarce , and not to compact .  m : this is by far the thinnest doppelbock i 've ever had . it 's too thin even for a plain bock . the low carbonation gives this the mouthfeel of a coke that 's been sitting out too long .

smell : very nice . round , sweet cherry on top of a chocolate malt base .  can , needed to get one after my first yuengling came in a green bottle and was quite skunked . fair retention and poor lace .  m : way too watery , thin bodied .

nice lacey on the glass . just some hints of euro yeast , along with some grains mostly corn .  the beer has zero , and i mean zero , head with no lacing . it looks tawny brown , sticky , and slightly watery .  it goes down okay , but the body is quite thin .

wet cardboard is the first and most dominant aroma .  a - pours a hazy light copper color with absolutely no head . honestly this looks like apple juice . final thoughts : a good beer but absolutely no head and feeling like you 're drinking straight water still leaves me a little confused ... if those areas are addressed i would given this beer a b+ .  m : very poor mouthfeel .

it 's got a lightly roasted malt aroma , with nuts and an earthy background , but with a bit of an odd , funky smell too .  pours bronze with 3+ fingers of offwhite head . no head retention or lacing s : smells orange nehi t : orange notes & a little lemony hops up front .  unsatisfying feel .

s- nothing phenominal in the nose unfortunately ; if i were blindfolded i may have confused this with an american macro-lager . very grainy- the presence of hops was not detected . d- the primary saving grace of this beer is the fact that it is very easy to drink and is a decent thirst quencher , especially when enjoying hot mexican food .  ( fun fact , happy hour pricing on alcohol is illegal in ontario ... urgh ) pours a pale amber colour with almost head .  carbonation is a bit overkill . fizzy and annoying .

very dry roasted soy sauce smells . a bit modest ( or cold ? ) very sweet , licorice , burnt bread , and the soy sauce .  can design bespeaks honor , drunkenness , and virility . pours slightly paler than 45 , smells slightly stranger . i could drink this until 3 in the morning , but its 3:42 and i 'm not going to sleep until i drink the rest of this disregarded dirty low-down swill .  the beer is fizzy with no head , light and tastes of strong lime with a soured aftertaste which is supposed to give the `` salt '' taste . overall , i commend miller for going outside the box on this one , and it does live up to the hype - however fizzy and without the polarizing hot sauce . i would choose this over any corona or other such .

the aroma is next to nothing , very grainy , like a lager , but that is all .  poured out to a golden yellow color with a head that took off like a fart in the wind . seriously , i go and throw the bottle cap away , and the 1 inch head that was there a moment ago is gone . totally . a trace of foam is left on the top of the beer . it 's cheap beer . this could be a stepping stone for those who like cheap beer to enter the realm of craft beer , but it 's a damn small stepping stone .  i like ported to be fuller in the body and this has relatively no mouth feel , the mouth is like an american larger minus the over carbonation .
