subdued aroma and actually quite disappointing . what the aroma lacked , the flavor has certainly made up for .  deep brown in color with hints of red around the edges where the light shows through .  faint regardless t not far from the smell but with some faint grassy hops and the lemons not skunky , oh wait a minute the skunk comes out on the finish m i think the tap water here has more body , not as much carbonation as i could see and the aftertaste leaves something to be desired o looks great but tastes a little light struck , considering its a 3 $ 6pack i 'll cope just another basic bottle form peru , not the best one i 've had though but i 'd see this being a little better if the bottle was n't green and the brew was n't light struck

s : i definitely get a lot of fruit in the nose . orange and pineapple stand out . i also , however , am getting some veggie aromas like tomato ( really tomato juice ) and carrots . there is also a sweet smell which i ca n't tell if it is from malts of the fruit flavorings . notes : i ca n't get over that smell . i really turned me off to this beer . the taste was alright but it did n't make up for the ridiculous smell ...  a - good amber color s - ok mostly sweet alcohol t - sweet and boozy m - thin light carbonation d - low at 10 % and too sweet and cloying  the mouthfeel is light-medium bodied ( i 'm guessing the abv is 4-5 % ) with a welcome crispness to the carbonation but this is unfortunately overall coming off as too watery and lacking in the mouth at times . and the aforementioned weak body did n't do this any favors either .

roast malt nose with a slight smell of shoe leather . not a very good smell for an ipa . not much hops in the nose just malt .  it 's a bubbly deep copper color , no haze , with a creamy head . not a big head , but good retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is watery - like any other light beer .

this beer had a smell that reminded me of some of the cheaper , lower quality beers from my past , which was a shame , since i really enjoy this beer .  pours a rich hazy amber with little head .  s - um ... leaves something to be desired , a bit skunky and reminescent of a pharmacy t - much better than the smell let on , pleasing malts , a little corn m - not impressed with the mouthfeel , really light , carbonation comes through too weakly for a adjunct d - totally average , no place for taste in this bottle

s - there 's very little aroma here . some metallic character strikes me first , followed by a vague sweetness that i suppose could be the honey .  look : the beer pours a clear red colour with a small fluffy pink head smell : bit sour , but mostly dominated by sweet berries .  rather flat carbonation leads to poor mouthfeel .

but the aroma is peculiar , stale maltiness with almost no hops present .  a : moderate pour yields a 2.5 finger light , fine , milk chocolate head with good retention . beer is near opaque but as i hold it up to the light , i get a nice amber quality .  but the glaring problem here is that the carbonation here is quite low , which i do not like in an ipa . it makes this beer taste almost like flat soda . even though i enjoy the flavor quite a bit , the mouthfeel ruins it . o- great flavor here but the mouthfeel really brings down the quality here .

the appearance is a little light for an imperial stout and the lack of head retention worries me . s. roasted malt along with wet cardboard , and a slight sour tone .  pours a light amber with a one finger light brown head that starts lacing right away .  body is the main drawback of the beer ; very watery for the style .

aroma - not impressed . a very light malt aroma , rather faint , and not much else .  a good , persistent head .  m : even worse , overly thin body , low carbonation , and slick on the palate make the alcohol stand out .

aroma - very brief note of peat and smoke . it 's gone quickly , too quickly to get a good read on it . nothing really left to enhance the flavor until it warms up , where a trace of buttery diacetyl emerges .  this poured to a bright gold color with a great-looking head .  light and watery mouthfeel and low carbonation .

s : sweet malt and corn . no real big surprise there .  beer is amber and hazy with an offwhite head of small bubbles that leaves some lacing on the glass , some carbonation .  m - have to give it a low score considering that all the carbonation was lost when i cracked it resulting in an almost completely flat drink .

aroma is grainy and sweet . this beer is the ale and its more of a lager than an ale . fairly hoppy and malty for a lager .  bottle into a pint glass the beer was a dark penny copper color with one-finger of white fluffy head and lots of carbonation streaming up the glass .  thin bodied , sharp cola carbonation .

the head is a wonderful ( not ) light pink , however . some lacing the scent is ... gross . rodenbach , say it is n't so .  poured a mildly-hazed yellow-golden color with a thin white head and some spotty lacing .  mouthfeel : very thin and watery .

there is very little smell , but what you can smell is unoffensive at least . the smell is mostly corny . the taste is typical macro , boring , bland , but not unpleasant . very corny and a little hoppy .  it smelled exactly like caramel . the taste though , was just like the butter used on movie theatre popcorn . i do n't think i have ever tried a beer that just did n't taste like beer .  m- incredibly thin body with higher than expected carbonation .

kozel premium a - this beer pours a golden colour with a hint of amber , with a nice tight white head that retains well - 4 s - mothing of note except some mild malts - 2.0 t - small yeast and some malt and a dryish sweet finish . 3.0 d - nothing to write home about but does make a sessionable beer .  a stiff two-finger , off-white head has good retention with some decent lace left behind .  this beer is very light bodied and finishes very thin .

the initial smell of the beer was that of alcohol and a slight amount of malts . what disappointed me about this beer was the weak smell , and the rather light body .  sadly i had the same impression again but managed to drink 2/3rds of the bottle this time . i 'm a big fan of kriek 's , especially lindemans but for some reason this one and i just do n't get along . serving type : 75cl champagne style bottle with crown cap and cork .  m - almost none . no hops , no carbonation , no metal , no cardboard dryness on the tongue .

s : bready to almost meaty aroma . especially on the second pour . no diacytl note . t : malty with some sugar & carmel flavour .  pours a hazy amber to copper color with an off white head .  carbonation is almost nonexistant after the pour .

the smell is grassy hopness that reminds me of the hoping in bmc beers , only much stronger and with a larger malt character under it . maybe it 's the smell of the malt that 's reminding me of bmc , there 's a cereal smell going on .  it poured a dark cola brown/black with a decent white/mocha head .  too high of carbonation level created an almost uncomfortable mouthfeel . beyong this fault , a light mouthfeel with a semi-dry finish , dominated by a heavy-feeling hop bitterness .

settles down immediately with no head , no aroma . looks like typical `` beer '' but does have some refining taste to it .  poured from a bottle produced an orange amber beer with a one finger orange white head .  a very watery taste and mouthfeel . noticeable malt , but it tastes like they watered down my beer . too watery to be very drinkable . but light , so it helps its drinkability a little .

s - i 'd say the overall very light aroma is a yeast note . in general a disappointing nose .  no balance here , just tons of bitterness . well , i guess taste is very subjective and relative to a baseline ... some see a glass half full and some see ... i wo n't be buying it again .  m - low carbonation and very thin .

not much odor on the nose except some grainy corn .  appearance : a very clear , alsmost watery looking golden with no carbonation bubbles floating at all . the head is beautifully thick with very tiny bubbles .  mouthfeel was thin and flat ( as expected ) .

5.0 s : truly a great smelling brew . the bourbon is the first thing you notice , but it allows for the stout to shine through as well .  looks fine - orange/gold color with white head .  pitch black , ca n't see thru it at all . bit thin , watery . lactose then black patent are the first things i taste , but then falls flat . touch of bitterness at the end which is probably from the roasted grains and not from the hops .

aroma is weak , malts and feint coffee . taste follows the nose , very light , like drinking a guinness with a dash of coffee .  this beer was seen very well once i served in my mug , with a brown dark color and some coppery notes , good head of foam ; the smell is spicy , some malts are distinguished ; the taste is frutal , light bitterness and essences of caramel and toast malts ; the drinkability simply is well , adequate quantity of alcohol , for enjoy better with food , i took it with meat .  again , coffee and tobacco , plus a hint of cedar , m : very thin for a beer of this lineage , d : overall , not worth retaining for a long haul .

aroma - some plain grain and rice aromas . pretty much like budweiser but a tad more aromatic .  poured a big 3 '' head which quickly dissipates to nothing . lovely deep golden color .  fair warning : it smells like the brewers trapped a skunk fart within the bottle , and , to swill it between your cheeks reminds me why i need to get my cavities filled . it 's an unpleasant , sour taste that warms all too quickly . however , i think it pours pretty well and has a great taste when drank from a glass . the aromas are much more pleasant when let out of the dank green bottle . as far the appearance , it seems a little too much on the light side for a beer that tastes as heavy as it does .

moderately intense pine aroma with floral undertones predominate . some caramel malt is also present , but very subdued ( -0.5 ) dry middle and finish with lots of aromatic and bittering hops , particularly after the finish .  plenty of big bubble white head . well darker than american pilseners , a shade lighter than sam adams : a light maple syrup hue .  very thin .

smells of cardboard and apples with a hint of toffee .  poured from can into dupont glass.. no dating a- hazy , but a very deep orange color . hints of yellow on the edges . nice inch of white , fluffy head .  no foam in the mouth , it got a rich taste with just alittle to much sweetnes , got spice , vanilla and licorice .

doughy , with a soapy , lemon scent that 's just a bit too much . play-doh & rubbing alcohol on the backend .  pours dark brown , good carbonation . looks like i thought it would .  low carbonation , lack of vanilla , coffee and hints at cocoa m : flat and thin , has some carbonation issues .

smell : barely any aroma with this as the description touted it was brewed with black barley , roasted barley , and chocolate malt .  pours a nice golden orange which is the best part of it .  no mouthfeel but easy to finish and perhaps order another .

this beer is really well done . another fine beer by great divide brewing company . it was strong at first but after a while it drank really nice . i was impressed by the feeling that you get after you drink it . another good beer for me to drink on a cold winter 's night .  a- dark brown , reddish appearance with about a finger width 's of head .  way too watery for a stout .

tastes like any number of mexican lagers . rather malty so i guess they could call it a vienna lager . faintly tangy . from notes at a mexican restaurant in old town where it was on tap .  in a pint glass this pilsner is a lovely pure gold transparency . nice looking beer , love the bright golden hue .  big sweet amber malt scent , touch of bitter hops mixed in there . the thinness immediately strikes me . the malt and hop tastes are kind of underwhelming , there are some fruit and yeast tones that are fairly pleasing though . im not really a major amber guy to begin with , but this one seems like they forgot to put in half of the ingredients .

faintest of aromas , but seems like both malt and hops are there .  poured into my old guardian snifter pours a black , with some light underneath it 's a really dark red , 2 finger head with very little retention .  and it could have been better ; this beer is vastly undercarbonated , which gives the beer a nearly flat , somewhat thin feeling .

i just have to say 1 thing ... if you have to put a lime in your beer ... then you should be wearing women 's underwear ! this beer should only be served if you are eating at a mexican restaurant and you just ate a bean burrito filled with jalapeno 's and hot sauce . and i ca n't believe how high they price this garbage .  the beer pours with a thickish dirty pink colored head . the beer is a red color with a pinkish tinge to it .  s : malty/burnt smell t & m : the taste and mouth feel were both disappointing from what i was expecting . the watery flow of this beer was the greatest disappointment after pouring it and seeing the thick head .

aroma of hops , corn , and subtle berry fruits . slightly metallic.taste accents of malt and corn .  nice appearance and pours nicely .  theres a fruity sweetness up front , and a very light hopiness . overall , id describe this beer as watery and uninspiring.another gimmick beer .

aroma is somewhat muted , requiring a vigorous swirling of the glass to get anything significant -- even then it 's like pulling teeth . nothing to brag about here , but nothing awful either . biggest positive is that it 's better than killian 's .  off white head , when it settled it left some nice lacing on the glass . light copper in the middle , hazy with some sediment floating around .  it is cheap . so when i want three or ten of these after work they are ok. not a bad flavor for a cheap macro . cheap .

s - the scent is very subtle . there are some sweet hints here but it 's made up mostly of long roasted malt .  this beer pours a cloudy golden orange color . the head is two inches in height , and recedes quickly into fluffy lacing .  unfortunately , the look and smell of this beer were the best part . it 's bland to the tongue , blah to the mouth . calling it kenya 's version of budweiser is too mean , but i could probably reproduce the flavor of this beer by mixing singha , budweiser , and water .

nose is slightly malty/grainy and that 's it but better than some light beers i have had . sessionable with a good price , one of the better light beers i have had .  chilled bottle into a glass . a : pours a brown-black blend , impenetrable in my tulip but definitely shows some light through the edges if i hold it close to a lamp . has a strong mocha ( ha ! ) colored head that retains well and leaves splotches of lacing down the sides . the coffee does a good job of providing a balancing bitterness against the chocolate and caramel flavors , and the nutty components give it some depth .  but the thin mouthfeel really detracts from the experience .
s - grain , malt sweetness , some apple , not a ton else .  very little aroma from the glass , but looks darn purdy !  carbonation is too high .
has a good date on it ... no scent at all in this beer .  copper to mahogany clear color with a decent cream colored head .  m : thin , watery , and yet sticky . pretty gross .

smells very grainy with hint of hops in the back . tastes like corn with a touch of honey .  well , this beer came highly recommended and also suggested by my server at a nice restaurant to go with my main course . when my wife started reading the back of the bottle before i tasted it i already knew it was a poor choice , why would i want something that was going to `` ruin '' my palate with a nice dinner ? the pine and citrus scents that are referred to by other reviewers just hit me as a insect repellent / citronella and the taste was no better .  m : awful dry , tannic bitterness , d : not so average

slightly skunky , slightly fruity busch nose ... only kicked up a couple notches . a bit of cooked vegetables in there , mostly corn and a mild herbal note that might possibly resemble a couple hop cones .  sampled at mn autumn brew review . poured a clear amber golden color with a slight white head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied low carbonation , and an annoying cloying texture .

citrus aroma is so mild that i 'm inhaling foam .  a - this pours a dark amber color which is probably the best part about this beer . it looks like a nice beer .  appearance : bright golden-yellow in color , one inch head , cloudy , high carbonation smell : banana , wheat , and clove taste : wheat dominates ... there are touches of bananas , clove , and a bit of honey mouthfeel : very light bodied , high carbonation , very very sweet drinkability : light and weak for the style .

the smell of malt is very evident , not much of hop aroma .  appearance - white one finger head with good retention . super pale straw body .  the hop bitterness is clearly present , but it seems to fight the sweetness also present . a very uncomfortable aftertaste develops that leaves my mouth overly dry and soap-like . i did n't want to finish my pint , nor would i want another one of these .

i 'm a huge fan of this brewery . so much so that it almost overpowers that belgian funk . first beer i didn ; t like from this brewery .  12oz bottle poured into a pint glass appearance : pours a red-orange color with a one inch head that quickly dissipates . moderate lace clings to the glass and stays put .  mouthfeel is very thin .

s : i do n't care for the smell of this beer , which has always seemed skunky when it should be floral ( and i 've had it on several occasions , so it 's not one bad batch ) . the bitter taste , which may also occasion the smell i do n't like , is very good and hits several parts of the taste buds .  the color is a good ale color , the head is just right , but it 's just so bitter .  mouthfeel - weak and watery , not very enjoyable . very little carbonation .

limited release from this kasteel donker , brewed in 1998 , as stated on the bottle . 6 euro for 75 cl bottle . smell is very fresh : clear fresh red and black fruits , like berries , strawberries , cherries . lightly sour scent , with a hint of caramel . the alcohol is very well masked . it 's got roasty malt notes , some coffee and nuts .  i gave it good scores for appearance .  very watered down . nothing special to see here .

aroma : getting a lot of sulpher in the nose , which is weird considering this is an ale .  a good looking beer .  m : even though there are some pleasant tastes the mouthfeel is pretty bland and watery , almost no bubbles or carbonation .

the smell is very mild with some transient notes of aroma hops .  a : pours , uh , black . looks like a stout , as it is classified on the site . one finger of mocha head with good retention , some lacing down the glass .  plate is quite watery , really watery in fact even for a sub-5 % beer .

before this i would have to say what is the point of pumpkin ale , but no more weyerbacher changed my mind . i ca n't get my nose out of this , very inviting . they have done well to blend the spices and keep them balanced , unlike some spiced beers that just seem to lay on top .  burning witches ... ha ha ! looks like your basic pale ale on this one .  the mouthfeel was very thin , light and highly carbonated .

nose is loaded with grapefruity hops . band-aid aroma sneaks in as it warms .  pours pitch black with not alot of head .  the body is fairly watery which is probably the biggest downfall of this beer .
s : very faint smell of citrus fruit . t : grapefruit hops , lightly sweet breadiness .  clean dark brown in colour .  mouthfeel is thin and tinny .

for the life of me , i ca n't smell a damn thing from this beer . had to smell some food to make sure my nose was actually working . not sure what to make of that .  a : a crazy pink colour .  palate is weak .
rather bland smell . light , dry west coast hops and some very strong malt .  a nice looking , if only decent tasting beer .  m - thin soda pop feel .

aroma is of mild sweet caramel malts along with some grains . nothing real flashy to report here .  nice , large off-white foamy head . thre fingers , but seems to be decreasing to two , leaving no lace behind . very nice copper colour below .  m : this is where i have to knock off major points . despite being medium to full bodied for the style , this beer is flabby , slick , and gritty in the mouth .

as far as mexican lagers go , this is probably my favorite . there is a distinct flavor of corn present .  appearance nice , dark ( almost black ) body with a decent head that laced the glass well .  m : seltzer water , but this is slightly less carbonated .

s- the usual aroma of an adjunct lager , no definitive malt in the nose just husk and cooked cereal .  poured into a mug with a moderate amber body and a fluffy off white head .  mouthfeel : thin and a little flat . needs more carbonation to make the mouthfeel more lively to compensate for the rather weak flavor .

i did n't notice any smell at first but as it warmed i very deffinately smelled honey .  pours a pale orange-golden colour , with a bright and frothy white-yellow head that foams quite a bit , but stays solid enough , and forms some spectacular lacing .  mild carbonation , watery .

great aromas , star anise and fir/piney .  pours a crystal clear burnt orange color with a lighter red hue throughout . a good soft white head that does hide to the edge of the glass for some time before fading completely . not much lacing though .  mouthfeel is very limp flat and lifeless .

corona light , abv=4.5 % , cals~~109 , light lager reviewed 10/20/08 @ home , bottle & gt ; pilsner glass a 2.0 - very pale straw in color , little to no head at all s 2.0 - minor hop & malt notes , semi skunky smell in background t 3.5 - pretty good taste for a light beer , crisp on palate , minor hop finish mf 2.5 very thin body as expected , super carbonated d 4.0 - pretty enjoyable for light beer in taste & drinkability .  shining lighter golden color with a nice frothy head .  same story with the flavours ; chocolate , golden syrup , not all that complex very high carbonation , pretty ridiculous .

pretty clear smell : like golden sweet granny smith apples w/ some light malt , light raspberry that is barely noticeable taste : i was a little disappointed here , i was hoping that the apple taste would be a little stronger . the smell just wraps you in , inviting you to enjoy it ... but than the taste is strangely mellow .  a : pours a dark brown , nearly black color . a two finger tan head forms with good retention .  body is too thin and watery , however , and i would definitely call it the primary issue that needs improvement .

tall head that 's very fluffy and dissipates quickly but stays throughout the drink . small amount of lacing only toward the end of the beer s= not much of anything , very subtle hints of corn , malt and a very light note of hops t= what i would imagine miller high life tastes like if it had a little honey in it ... it 's ok but it 's not really my thing . light taste with a little honey when it goes down at the end .  typical fantome appearence , possibly slightly darker . vibrant , spice-led aromatics , with hints of spinach and herbs .  entry seems flat and introduces a mouthfeel which seems thin and uninspired .

smells of acidic oranges and coriander . hits you right in the nose as soon as you start pouring .  i had sampled a small amount of great divide 's yeti in the middle of several other great divide offerings , but that 's my only other imperial stout experience . the look of storm king on pouring was nice and fit my expectations for the style , but it was basically downhill from there .  the body was very weak and insubstantial .
first aroma : alcohol . second aroma : alcohol .  this beer was horrid . it looke good , a glistening khaki colored beer with a thin white head .  finish and mouthfeel are virtually nonexistent .

smells like a budweiser with light dry hop .  this baby pours out sexy like the relaxing woman on the label . a deep red body leaves lace all over the glass and reminds me immediately of strawberry . overall this light body beer is n't very drinkable , and wound up a drain pour or me .  mouthfeel is very thin , alomst non-existent .

smells mouth-watering good . all in all , this porter has a great smell , but not much else imo .  50 cl tall can a-pours a clear dark-brownish red with nice little beige head and decent retention .  the texture is rather flat and uninviting .

s - sharp malt and lemon zest . t - nice medium malt flavor , citrus twang and bitterness .  served in a pilsner glass , the beer pours a cloudy yellow/orange color with about an inch white head .  taste is similar , although it tastes like watered down coffee . very thin , not very interesting , and leaves a lot to be desired .

also it is closer to a helles ; the hops are not prominent enough to be a pils . standard yellow lager , green bottle syndrome overpowers the nose , a decent maltiness provides a tasty base ( a sign of helles ) , little in the way of hops although the finish is nicely and subliminally dry . recommended for just about anybody , even macro-swillers , but try to get enclosed 12-packs - this green bottle thing really sucks .  this was over hopped to my palate and had a strange aftertaste of bitterness that was not enjoyable . the normal bitter refreshing characteristics are gone and the overly bitter exotic tastes come through in a way you do not want to drink them .  just way to thin , watery and even under carbonated . give this a little more body and some more carbonation , and this will be a decent beer .

light sweet floral aroma . strong alpha hop lightly sweet citrus/floral quickly gives way to resinous hop then melding to a light barley and yeasty finish .  yellow and bright with a bright white foam ; good laces . classic pine , citrus hop aroma .  something is missing in the carbonation and mouthfeel as it lingers and never really cleans up .

s : tons of citrus , tropical fruits , pineapple , honey , and slight burnt honey malt . i could smell it for days.. t : tropical fruits , citrus ( pink grapefruit , ripe tangerine and tons of lemon ) , pale malts , and a slight alcohol flourish in the finish . i was really disappointed by the rating.. either the best or second best rated beer on here . i was very disappointed by its lack of mf.. overall : the most overrated ipa of all time .  my pint of the kronic poured a deep copper with a suitable head .  s : basic dark beer , some roasted malt and generic hops t : thin , distant malt and hops . m : not much , water comes to mind .

s- smells like old macro lager .  my pour resulted in two fingers ' worth of rocky , bone-white head with decent retention . color was a deep golden-yellow with ne-plus quality clarity . when a beer is this bright , i begin to wonder what they stripped away from it in terms of flavor .  some funky , dusty aroma , reminiscent of all abita 's beers . maybe the spring water . some fruitiness too . watery palate . tasty .

i 'd comment on the aroma but it is practically non-existant . maybe a faint malt aroma .  i love the brewery and the prez on the thing but good lord there 's nothing that can save this beer . t- a mess of sour apple and sour pear with too much sweetness and bitter wood ... i would n't spray this at my dog in fear it would hurt too much . m-pungent and sour ... bitter/sharp , and the the good cheese sharp , but the sunny delight sharp .  thin-bodied and watery with adequate carbonation that lends itself to good drinkability , true to style .

the aroma is pretty limp ... nothing in the way of bananas , maybe some mild phenols , some burnt rubber , aldehydes , and yeast . quite unimpressive .  pours a dark blush , it 's red , very red . decent two finger head recedes to a cap and laces adequatlely .  mouthfeel : very light body that leaves me hanging .
aroma was basically missing .  a - really nice clear rust color , no lacing .  mouthfeel : thin , watery . foams a bit upon swishing over the palate .

very unappealing nose .  appearance : 8 oz serving in a medium sized snifter , ned 's red pours a purplish , shoe polish color with deep red hues and an off white cake head that rapidly dissipates to leave rather attractive lacing .  mouthfeel and carbonation are pretty weak overall .

s - not much . hint of burnt toast and hint of coffee . t - light flavour of slightly burnt cold coffee .  pours clear orange dense white head good retention and lace .  the mouthfeel is disappointingly thin .

the aroma is full of adjuncts , some malts ; overall , the overall effect is a very generic , yet restrained , sweetness . overall , i was pleasantly surprised with falstaff ; it was a step above the run-of-the-mill bmc lager .  crystal clear , a little darker yellow than i expected , basically gold in color . it had a two finger cap of bright white , soapy bubbles that fell quickly , but left behind a surprising amount of clumpy lacing .  mouthfeel is quite thin .

smell : ligh corny smell , maybe a note of hops . there 's a sharp smell too , like funky yeast , but it 's all light despite not being very attractive . taste : very corn based in sweetness , like it was brewed entirely with corn .  a- pours slightly cloudy amber with a fluffy almost three inch thick head leaving thick lacing scattered throughout .  m : too much carbonation for me d : could be drinkable but not really worth it for the lack of flavor would n't buy this again ...

pours a decent pale straw , with a medium white head that quickly recedes and does n't leave much lacing . smells skunky at first but it fades away and there is some light doughy malt and some grassy hops . overall , another euro pale lager that got skunked at some point on its way to my glass .  appearance a nice dark color , with a weak brownish glimmer when held up to light . not a very impressive head , with a fluffy white consistancy .  the mouthfeel is incredibly watery .

little to no hops in aroma or taste makes this a very easy drinking beer . if you ever get a beer craving in a mexican restaurant , this and dos equis are your only two real choices .  i was excited at first , but like most others , i find this appalling bew undrinkable . there 's a horrible fake chocolate taste mixed with who knows what else .  palate was thin and rather crisp for the style . mouthfeel is wide then crashes to thin making me think this beer was n't fully fermented . no carbonation to speak of on the mouthfeel .

the aroma is malts and corn ... and that rather nasty stink that is commonplace among adjuncts . served cold enough , the odor isnt too much of a problem .  this is an ok , very standard , boring west coast pale ale , but better than some . it 's light copper with a red-brown hint , smallish off-white head slowly shrinking to a thin top and some decent lace .  mouthfeel : thin and watery with too much carbonation .

this does n't smell too nice . a big whiff of that corny , adjunct sweetness comes through . the tatste is a big improvement on the smell . a little bit of corny sweetness comes through , but some legitimate light malts too .  i can not believe that this actually passes under the name of guinness . huge creamy head , jet black body .  way too much carbonation .

not much to the smell , a bit of hop spice , slight floral with barely a wiff of malt .  a - pours pretty dark , deep red color when held up to the light .  m/d : a light body that is thin and watery .

smell is extremely faint muted nuts , yeast , and aged english hops .  pours pitch black with a one finger light beige head that quickly settles into a thin lasting ring .  m : surprisingly light in body live a clean , watery finsih .

it smells of berry-like fruitiness , toast , caramel malt ; not a lot going on . mild and clean , this does n't exhibit much malted rye or rye whiskey . i love the concept of this beer and had high expectations , and while it is good , the flavors and especially the aromas are somewhat muted for such a high gravity barrel-aged beer .  plenty of foamy head .  the palate is thin .

nose is not pleasant to me ... wheat malts , and slightly smoky .  a- nice clear gold with a little rosy hues , handsome finger of persistent head , not bad looking at all .  m= flat as a board . wish it was carbonated but there is nothing here . flat as a board .

s. normal beer smell , nothing very special to it . t. i can taste a little sweetness in it , no much bitterness . but it is surely very drinkable .  after taking the bottle from the fridge i left it for awhile to get it to its recommended serving temperature , between 8 and 12 c. it poured a lovely dark amber , about 2cm head that quickly receded into a thin layer of small bubbles .  extremely light feeling on the tongue , watery , but with a fair amount of carbonation .

very drinkable , very fresh ( its chief strength ) but surely nothing to get excited about for those who have been around the beer block a few times . this beer is perhaps one of the best introductions to the american craft beer category for the uninitiated . my obsession with fat tire is more of a socio-psychological one as to the narrow demographic that proclaims this beer to be perfection in a bottle , and my attempts to get inside their heads to look for answers and clues for how to help them get into the rest of the thousands of awesome american craft beers .  pours a clean orange-ish to brown color with an off white head .  m : lacking , really felt like a light lager in my mouth , it 's that fizzy .

- $ 11.99 for the 6 pack in meadville , pa - `` fresh-by '' date on bottle ( best by 06/2011 ) , small blurb about beer on neck - medium head from pour , thin white lace stays around edge and clings to side walls as beer was being consumed - very faint aroma , hoppy but not floral , not strong - okay overall taste , not too bitter and very little carbonation .  anyway , pours a dark , clear red with a solid , quite stick head .  mouthfeel is thin and watery and low on carbonation .

oddly , i did n't pick up an aroma from this one . flavor is tart and sour cherries and a hint of cheese . nothing else i can detect .  650ml bomber poured into tulip 8/1/12 a hazy golden orange with little for carbonation , head , or lace looks like a still glass of beer . perhaps a dirty glass because the second pour gives me a long lasting thumbs width of off white foam that leaves a few partial rings of lace s cotton candy and orange-sicle with a little booze and sour tea bag dipped in solvent t quite sweet and a sour citrus thing does n't help its cause , some grassy caramel , not a very good dipa , tastes a little off and has a thrills gum thing going on too m a little flat and syrupy , sticks too the lips but only a little heat from the booze , sugary aftertaste o too sweet with off flavors , not a dipa i 'd drink again not sure what i was expecting for my 3 $ bomber but i still feel ripped off .  the palate is thin .

s : some faint hints of corn and malt , no hops to speak of . t : some light corn notes are the main flavour , overall , not bad for a macro , very sweet .  pours a light peach color with a short white head and a good bit of lacing on the way down .  average . better than extremely cheap beers , worse than expensive ones . if you do n't want anything interesting to drink , grab a michelob .

s - pungent sour aroma with something that reminded me of a dry champagne .  brilliantly clear , dark golden with brass accents , forming a poofy white head with surprisingly decent retention and very nice lacing . carbonation is moderately strong , forming some streamers .  medium-bodied with a hard water mouthfeel . palate is left dry with notes of dusty herbal and grain .

sniffs of corn dont help a whole hell of a lot . quaff is crisp , clean and very dry surprise , surprise .  poured a clear bronze color with a creamy and thick head ; some lacing down the glass .  this tastes empty , watery and thin on the palate , the carbonation sorely lacking what is otherwise a quite pleasant taste .

has sticky lacing s- hops , hops , hops is what i smell . also smell some caramel and alcohol . i love dipa 's but man this is too super duper hoppy for me .  a- pretty enough . cloudy thick copper , grainy , creamy white head and nice lace .  the mouthfeel was totally ruined by the insane level of carbonation .
smells like burnt coffee , that is really old .  nice light copper hue with modest head .  mouth feel is thin but warms to an alcoholic finish .

aroma is rich , molasses , ripe pears and plums , raisins , black coffee , and a hint of brown sugar . very intense mix of scents i also get a brief hit of smoke on the nose . very malty flavor with coffee up front followed by a nice ripe fruit twang , and finishes roasty and some smoke again .  i had great anticipation for this beer yet it turned out quite boring . very dark raw umber in color .  mouthfeel was poor , super thin with way too much carbonation .

the smell included grain with not much else weak and not good . the mouthfeel was light body and very clean .  a - nice and dark , held it up to a light and could not see through it . maybe a 1/4 inch of tan head . s - i smell coffee , some alcohol and chocolate , and something else , not sure what . i would n't sneak this into a hobo 's stick and bindle , that 's how bad it is .  mouthfeel is marginal , thin and fizzy , very mexican macro .

bight hazy yellow ... nice white head ... .the nose is very inviting ... seems to suggest a nice balanced spicing profile ... corriander , some orange peel , perhaps a little nutmeg ... outstanding aroma . taste is a slight let down ... more bitter than i like my whits ... a lot citrus on the taste ... also some peppery like spices.. body is on the ligth side of medium .  a nice golden color . white foam , stays a bit then disappears .  really thin body , goes down faster than you can taste it .
t : a lot like the smell , grainy , corny , sweet with a little tartness .  + nice appearance , fair sized head , nice retention and lacing ... scotch like color .  thin and somewhat watery body .

s - resiny bitter hops appear weak in the nose and are backed be equally weak bready amber and caramel malt . faint for an ipa , i 'm digging to pull anything from this . t - bready amber malt and caramel sweetness provide a good base for the low hop presence .  hard pour gave a 1 1/2 finger white head that died down almost as soon as it came .  coming from a bottle , this beer does not have a creamy enough mouthfeel for what i want from a stout . i have had some bottled stouts that were excellent , but this is too light and carbonated .

the first impression is of a very skunky beer as is the case of all their beers i have drank . if you can get by the smell this is a pretty good beer .  poured a dark brown with reddish highlights .  m : only thing i can really knock , for having such strong flavors , this is quite thin on the palate for what it is . only thing i can seriously knock is the body , it 's so thin and watery .

this smelled of creamy malts , and it tastes like creamy malts as well .  pours a very clear , sparkling brass . lots of fizzy carbonation . leaves a decent smattering of lace .  t- watery flavor , i thought it was lacking . pumpkin is nicely present and i sort of lost the other great flavors that i had smelled . m- worst part of the beer , way too watery for the flavor and smell .
s- not very aromatic , faintly sweet .  beer poured a pretty dark , dark brown .  carbonation seems weak too ... and it is pretty light on the mouthfeel .

smell - little smell , taste - nice refreshing when cold , quite crisp with little aftertaste mouthfeel - slightly more carbonated than average , drinkability - this is a pretty easy drinking beer , and is quite refreshing on a hot day , not much after taste , and a good crisp taste while drinking  pours a one finger tan head over a crystal clear bright light orange liquid . marchiano cherry meets jelly belly in a carbonated beverage .  the body is the lightest i 've had for such a high abv stout , and this is probably the culprit for me not liking this beer or any of atwater 's as much as i might . everything i 've had by them so far has a diet coke body and a medium at best finish . vanilla java porter was okay for me , but definitely on the thin side .

s : wow ! ! ! you really get the usual hefenweizen smell with all the banana , nutmeg and slight sweetness . but there are also the hops ! there is lots of citrus-like smells : lime , lemon peel , light tangerine , peaches . also a light floral/herbal smell . t : well , the taste goes along with the smell . there are the banana , nutmeg and sweetness . there is also the lime , lemon peel , light tangerine and peaches . sadly , the flavors do n't blend as well as in the smell . the floral and herbal are stronger though than in the smell . lots of mint . o : it is a quite interesting beer for sure , there is n't much like it in the beer world to my knowledge .  it pours out of the bottle a nice coppery-amber with a fairly thick light tan head .  thin , watery with no carbonation . i didnt realize the age when i bought it and i would say this really went past its prime in carbonation .

a few whiffs in the nose took me down a few notches with it 's rotten adjunct aroma , even when cold . do n't smell the beer . do n't serve warmer than ice cold .  it pours an inviting red ; indeed , i was rather excited after the pour .  the result is a thin , watery , and disappointing mouthfeel .

unfortunately , what looks appetizing does n't smell quite so good ; as i detect a cooked corn aroma overpowering some traces of hops .  poured with the mosher method ... which doesnt work well with sedimented bottles . a. tight white lace , slight haze , orange/amber .  mf- the body here is pretty watery to me with lower carbonation that i would expect . db- pretty much the sort of flavor you would expect in the style but with a weak mouthfeel that does n't compliment the beer .

it was really hard to smell anything -- maybe a bit of wheat ?  a : slightly hazy , ruby colored in the glass . nice white head .  i 'm not sure if the previously mentioned stout flavors are influencing my perception here but the feel seems very watery .
s- not much on the nose ... a very weak nose .  dark bronze in the glass , head a very light brown colour - looks good .  for me , the beer really went downhill in the mouthfeel .

aroma was immediately skunky over grain , malt , hops , and a little spice . flavor left the skunk behind - and turned out pretty good !  appearance : copper orange , decent quarter inch head that leaves good lacing on the glass , held up to the light you can see quite a bit of yeast in suspension .  t. i love the taste , for a cheap beer it is quite good m. very watery d. i can and do drink this beer all night long .

smell is odd , mostly of condensed cooked vegetables and grains and with a metallic shallowness .  color was a dark amber with a think off white head .  mouthfeel is pretty watery , some fizz as it goes down .

i love guinness . there are few beers this strong in flavor that are this drinkable . it does n't have any distinct notes or floral stylings , but its got a great balanced flavor . it did take a minute to get used to the flavor initially .  i knew when i picked this up that i 'd regret it but i did it anyway ... pours a quite nice deep brown ... quite clear.. smallish head.. pretty nice actually ... skunked ... only way to say it ... pungent deep funky skunk aromas dominate and do away with anything else.. maybe a touch of vanilla or something but that 's about it.. sweet and a bit oaky with some vanilla highlights but basically skunked in the taste dept as well ... when will these brewers learn ?  m : watery d : just okay , and i know its wrong but the limn and la sal go into this one .

the smell is kinda stinky , it smells like any skunked old euro pils that just spent a year on a boat , in a green bottle , on the sun deck .  a : pours a bright , crystal-clear pale gold color . the tall , foamy white head has decent retention . some soapy lacing forms an irregular but persistent pattern on the glass .  m very very thin , maybe the thinnest i have rated .

i spent the whole time drinking this beer wondering how it could taste so rich and delicious without have much of an aroma at all .  having sampled this brewery 's tasty pale ale , this red was quite a letdown . poured a vibrant amber-red . true to its namesake , this beer was lifeless .  over the top carbonation . other than the carbonation it 's an ok lager but there are better ones out there .

smell : big time cherry , almost smells like kasteel rouge however there is still a rugged sourness funk that comes along with this style that i do love so much . this beer is really timid all around what a dissapointment .  a - clear amber with ~1 finger of head . no lacing .  t : more of the same from the nose , and as watery as expected . m : not much going on here . i imagine leaving a club soda open for an hour and then drinking it would feel about the same .

appearance = 20 % red , nice color , cloudy , low carbonation , litle to no head smell = 20 % citrus smell , slightly sour taste = 40 % cirus flavor , slightly hoppy and bitter mouthfeel : very light , not impressed .  appearance was totally unexpected - huge four finger fluffy white head on top of a clear yellow lager with noticable carbonation .  slightly flat . ends up feeling a bit watery .

the tartness of the wheat and the bock just did n't do it for me . the tartness almost had a soy taste to it .  really not much to say here ... the appearance is the best thing about this beer , it 's a typical light golden color with a frothy 2 finger head that shrunk to a thin white head , left little lacing on my mug .  flavor and mouthfeel were a bit confusing . however , the flavor seemed to be sort of hiding behind a rather watery mouthfeel which made me lukewarm on this beer .

there was not much smell , maybe some hints of bread and malt .  figured id give it a try after all the press . pours a moderate copper with an off white head .  it quickly became apparent that there was very little mouthfeel , and whatever taste -either from the malt or hop bill - was absent .

scent does n't have too much going on ... somewhat reminds me of a dark mexican lager . i do detect some caramel malt , but that 's about it . i also get some bread characteristics with a bit of skunk ( which can be expected from such an old bottle ) .  caramel/orange color with a 1mm cap that does leave a very nice lace -- both lacy and the rings of foam effect that you like to see . nothing special on the smell .  m : the worst part it my experience . it was so carbonated that the first sip felt like it was cutting my mouth .

the nose is a little sweet . there is n't a lot of smell at all .  poured a huge off-white head that sat above a hazy golden beer .  m- high carbonation and medium body . the carbonation reminded me of seltzer water , way too much and which had a sharp mouthfeel . pretty sweet and the carbonation was just way too high to make it very drinkable .

appearance : very solid , textbook ; very big fluffy white head retention ; yellow straw color ; very cloudy , like thick fog ; aroma : somewhat bland and unexciting ; slight honey vanilla ; not much of a spice presence ; a little bit of fruity and floral , but not much flavor : has a honey , vanilla backbone with mild lactic acid ; not much spice and not much fruit mouthfeel : similar impression as above ; unexciting ; mediocre ; nothing special at all ; far from it i 'm wondering if this is either too old or a bad batch .  out of a bottle this beer was a gold/amber color with lots of visible rising carbonation . the head was one finger thick , bright white and retained ok as a skim but laced very well .  m - to much carbonation in consideration with the taste . the high carbonation presence kills this beer .

12oz bottle poured into a snifter fridge temp 2008 appearance : pours a somewhat cloudy golden orange with a 1/2 '' white head . smell : lavender , orange , grapefruit , lemon peel and an overall hoppy aroma . kind of under-attenuated and quite sweet . mouthfeel : smooth , medium bodied and bitter .  a : pours a slightly hazy orange color with a 1.5 finger white foamy head . by the time i got from the kitchen to my desk the head had reduced to a decent layer of foam on top . left some impressive lacing actually .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .

s - cherries , bourbon , wood , some type of complex smell that makes them all together more than their parts . best part of this beer , imo . t - intense but not so much as smell .  my gf who does n't like beer normally , but likes duvel ordered a duvel . anyway , later he brought a sample of duvel green to taste and i know i had an ipa on my mouth and she a duvel on hers , but my only impression of green was , well , unremarkable . want a light beer that does n't taste like crap , this is for you .  thin harsh mouthfeel .

smell - the smell leaves a lot to be desired . there is caramel malt , grainy with a hint of toffee - not much else at all .  bomber into my midnight sun cervoise , envy is a burnt gold with a 1 finger , creamy white head that pretty quickly subsides , leaving moderate lace . oddly , the head was pleasantly rocky on the second pour , and left thicker , foamy lace , so i bumped it up a 1/2 point .  citrusy and maybe some pineapple as well m : full bodied , harsh bitter mouthfeel that is not very enjoyable really d : not a horrible beer but nothing i would willingly buy again .

started off with a decent pour , a clear lite yellow with a nice white head that laced my pilsner glass quite well . aroma is again weak , just some very lite malts , on the grainy and grassy side .  drank from a 1 pint , 9.6 fl oz bottle at the ginger man , new york , ny batch 4 served in a snifter dark chestnut in appearance with a bubbly , frothy , cocoa colored head that quickly faded to a thick ring .  both of these co-mingle into the aftertaste m : light bodied with too much carbonation o : this is a great dessert beer that manages to mimmic apple pie with the spices and apples and is easy to drink , but as a stand-alone `` pale wheat ale , '' this one is way off the mark .

the nose was weak and i was n't able to detect any hops aroma .  off tap at wrigley field this beer was a crystal clear brew of bright golden color . the white head retained well on my cup 's brim and left scattered lacing as it descended . forgettable .  very light . in the mouth it is awfully fizzy ( hmm , maybe that was a pow after all ) .

very weak nose ... ca n't make out much malt , but can get a little grassy/floral hint . just like nose , i do n't get any malt ... the taste is n't strong or overpowering at all .  huge , solid white head . orange-gold color with a haze .  the body was light , the mouthfeel watery and the carbonation light .

smells like almost nothing . light fruit esters and water . inoffensive , if nothing else .  strong bourbon flavor , does not mask the alcohol very well . might do well with aging for a couple of years .  nose was faint and grainy , mouthfeel flat , and the flavor followed the nose . pass on this one .

very bread like aroma with cracked grain being the main scent , then it blends to floral and citric fragrance . this is an okay ipa , the color is standard and the aroma is very tame .  looks like an ipa ; there was a nice rocky head in my sampler glass , though it did n't last .  watery body , carbonation is vital to keep it from boring [ me ] .

been a while since i had one of these ; i remembered `` xx '' being pretty good for mexican beer ( which has never impressed me ) but i think i `` remembered '' incorrectly . the aroma is rather funky : an almost doughy yeast that 's hard to get past .  a -- clear , pale straw gold color with a dense white head that holds well .  mouthfeel is very thin and watery , very little body to speak of .

s : not getting much if anything from the nose . a sweet malty aroma is barely there but that 's about it . t : the taste is mostly sweet malt with a very slight bitterness on the finish .  poured into a pint glass a : aggressive pour yields 3/4 finger white head with good retention .  this is definitely a flavorful beer , but the feel in my mouth and stomach is pretty similar to that of your bmc lager . thin , watery , and generally just empty feeling . overall i 'd call this one very average .

aroma was a bit off putting , smelled slightly sour with a hint of pickles and grain .  although a suitable color for a stout , it 's got very little aroma beyond some light chocolate and a peas . also making a cameo appearance is ... lettuce .  mouthfeel is weak , fizzy beer .

mild malty aroma is hard to detect , and perhaps this beer 's weakest point , as it performs well elsewhere .  in a word , ugh . pours very dark , with only slight ruby highlights showing under direct light .  the end falls flat due it 's lack of carbonation m : flat and poor . it loses me on the lack of carbonation , loses taste , body and overall feel .

aroma is very chocolaty ... a semi-sweet and roasted chocolate smell is very noticeable with some floral hoppiness in the background .  tastes like blue moon mixed with thrilla vanilla schnapps .  m - medium-bodied and drastically under-carbonated . d - easy enough to drink , but the lack of carbonation combined with a lack of flavor complexity make it difficult to enjoy .

s : typical lager smell , not much , a touch of alcohol and light malts t : very smooth and refreshing .  pours a highly carbonated clear copper color with a huge off white head .  mouthfeel is as thin as it gets . the best thing about a bud light is its drinkability .

it smelled like a beer . not much else going for it .  12oz bottle poured into my narke tulip ... a dark but clear copper , lots of light tope head , good retention and lacing ... at first the aroma is really nice and sweet but then the alcohol comes through , too strong so it starts to turn me off ... the taste takes the aroma to a new level , all piney alcohol and incredibly strong , i almost gagged my first sip .  only downside is the lack of body here .

no offputting smell .  a : hazy gold color , tan head about half an inch or so thick , with excellent lacing , pretty fair head retention . quite cloudy .  mouthfeel is quite thin and watery , and leads to a soapy feeling .

24 oz poured into a pint glass a - golden color with a white head that dissipated quickly , a lot of carbonation s - sweet , malts , corn . not really appealing t - something like malts , sweet , grassy maybe , taste is n't all that bad but each time i put my nose in the glass i get that smell .  dark mahogany color , creamy head . have some dfh 60 minute and a brown ipa waiting in the fridge , hoping for a better product from this brewery with those .  the body 's mouthfeel and accompanying appearance issues are too much for me to recommend this as being drinkable .

aromatics lead off with a whiff of peach skins and tart pits . an obtrusive , moldy , musty cardboard aroma takes hold and detracts throughout the glass .  here is the verdict : a : a nice deep ruby red / dark mahogany . a tan head that disappears quickly .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and pretty watery .

`` night in the woods '' tasting 3.29.08 thanks to dmeadows for sharing his 2006 bottle a- pours a perfect deep brown with some carbonation and a minimal white head a- there 's a very organic `` stable '' smell ( probably the peat ) along with whiskey . the combination of smells were very similar to my cat 's litter box & it was difficult to separate the smell from the tasting .  poured cold from the bomber into the pint glass this shows an anemic clear gold color with a giant foamy white head and real chunky lacing .  the taste ... .well , it 's one of the most watery and flavor devoid beers i 've ever had . the body is of a somewhat watery cereal grain taste ... .which leads into a finish with more cereal sweetness mixed with a bit of grassiness and hay . but , with all the decent beers out there , i 'm not sure why i should seek this one out .

aroma : moderate malt , light bread , toasted , molasses , hops , ( what hops ) , nothing there . my be moving towards `` skunk '' state .  poured from a deuce-deuce into a wine glass for maximum enjoyment . appearance : opaque and black , with soft hints of red and/or mahongany . thin tan head which does not stick around very long . does n't look overly thick or too thin , i like the look of this brew . taste/mouthfeel : simply put , much like red wine poured into a stout .  mouthfeel is extremely watery with almost no carbonation .

no detectable smell .  on to the beer : well , the color of the beer has a raspberry infused orange color to it , hazy . the head color has a pink tint to it , and it has surprisingly good head retntion and forms good patchy lace .  it was fairly thin and very carbonated , with a mild coffee aftertaste . there was no distinguishing character to it , and it was too thin . and like all of the cooperstown beers , it had way too much head and carbonation .

seved cold in a cold mug , with lime , and i added salt for extra effect and flavor .  big thanks to heyohh for sharing this a - stout . and while i 'm at it , why do n't i just go and brew a stout with some damned oysters . other than the dairy aspect , mostly i am getting a lot of alcohol and espresso . d - this beer tasted worse than an infected sexual chocolate that it unfortunately was sampled with . tremendously epic fail in my book .  mouthfeel : very thin and in my opinion over carbonated .

s - strong aroma of alcoholic lemonade . nothing else is detectible .  it looks pretty good , a deep amber , decent head , but slides down the hill after that .  feel still sucks though , very slick and watery .

lots of malt here , really not that much else at all .  this one was cloudy straw colored with a large white head that formed a plateau - so far , so good . not much lacing .  for a cheap 3.79 beer ... this is good stuff ! very light body and almost zero head even when poured vigorously like a rice beer .

smell : very artificial sweetness ; almost like the smell of nestea artificially flavored raspberry iced tea , but as a beer .  pours a crystal clear , very pale straw color with a bright white head into my pilsner glass . excellent retention as well .  aromas come through but are trumped by a tangy , thin , watery mouthfeel .

the real quick and dirty : the pour is light yellow with a decent head , and the nose is vaguely malty .  a nice amber/copper color with a minimal off-white head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with light watery carbonation . the only downside is the watery mouthfeel .

that damn cheese smell that i cant get over is still there . the cheesiness didnt persist in the taste , thankfully .  pours a muddy , dark brown with a huge , dense tan head that lasts a while and leaves chunks on the glass .  very thin , but not too much carbonation .

aroma is pretty tame/lame .  big thanks to emerge077 for the share a - it pours a deep chestnut-brown , between hazy and opaque , with a persistent wisp of ecru froth .  m : the body of old guardian is almost thin .

metallic . light grain and husk smells are there , too . metal also is prominent in the taste- but that 's the only unpleasant taste . very different from most euro . lagers .  growler into a pint glass . poured straight down the middle of the glass , beer gives about 3 '' of solid head . pretty much downhill from there .  m - bad . champagne-esque carbonation ; prickly and somewhat thin .

distinct 'urine ' quality , metallic , cooked veggies/corn , lots of grainiess . an unpleasant macro , had to pound this .  i just got back from a trip to panama and this is my thrid favorite of the local swill . it looks good , smells fine , taste like a adjunct lager in the green bottled import mold , lacks real body , i could and did drink this all night .  the mouthfeel is light bodied with aggressive carbonation , and a watery texture .

the nose is big , sweet and has hints of orange , but beyond that , it is non-existant . the cloying sweetness , poor depth and lack of body ruined this beer for me .  pours a dark brown color with a small , bubbly off white head that fell quickly leaving some decent lacing .  mouthfeel is painful due to the high acidity .

brown 75cl corked and caged bottle , the cork carries the best before date of 03/09 . poured in a duvel glass and a hoegaarden grand cru one . i could detect no aroma what so ever , which in its self is very strange , because the taste was full bodied and strong . the no show of any aroma does n't help either .  this one poured a very dark black cherry soda color that came close to being brown .  m : very watery and thin body with medium carbonation .

about 1/2 finger head in my sam adams glassware smell - hardly any smell but slightly euro and slightly skunky despite the bottle date was still 30 days out in time .  looks very nice upon the pour with a clear amber body with a nice white head that descends at a slow pace , and laces well . reviewed 01-16-2010 poured a hazy orange with a strong head that left moderate to light lacing .  mouthfeel is too light for the style and carbonation is too high .

very bitter smell , to be expected with a pilsner , but almost had a skunked smell to it .  this beer is not my stlye but had to try because i love s.t . the beer had the smell of grape ginger ale and i knew it was not going to be a beer i like from the get go .  m- not much to the mouthfeel , very bland and left a weird aftertaste .

i could n't detect too much of an aroma , but it had a nice deep roasted flavor that surprised me because of the lack of smell ... and great drinkability .  poured from the mini keg into a nice tall german glass . very golden in color like jewelry with a nice foamy head that has good retention and leaves light lace .  the body is watery thin .

smell is a little soapy ( i only rinsed ) , faintly grainy , & again metallic . it needed a little more bite , but otherwise decently inconspicuous for the style .  it was a deep brown-red-black color with a thin creamy head .  very watered down .

it 's a cheap beer that tasted not bad before but seems to be slightly better now . in fact , unlike other macros where it would be near impossible to taste any malt ( usually they are tasteless or full of corn flavors ) , this beer does seem to present some malt sweetness that normally i 'd associate with traditional lagers whether foreign or domestic . still not much in the department of hops bitterness or floral citrus-like flavors .  a- pours a deep brown with a one finger , very light tan head s- smells of alcohol , vanilla , and chocolate t- sickeningly sweet taste , weird blend of vanilla , milk chocolate and medicine .  mouthfeel is definitely thin .

inoffensive summer refresher . a far better alternative to mass-market beers if you 're looking for a beer to accompany casual tv watching or cooking . not worth a whole lot of analysis , but not bad either .  a : 'maple syrup ' amber , clear with very little carbonation , a few stragglers rising slowly . dense creamy head , khaki tan and slow to fall . suds cling staunchly , a few larger bubbles amidst a blanketing cap .  i can not find any hop first impression is how thin the liquor is . the low carbonation matches this and also explains why there is little lasting head . even as a lesser dry stout , it is watery and flat .

the smell is not very distinct in my opinion . it tastes pretty nutty . there are no foul aftertastes and it leaves you wanting more . if there were only a way to get that nuttiness in the smell .  appearance : deep , clear amber colored pour . a sticky white head that retains reasonably well .  everything suggested about complexity and structure within the nose and the appearance is met with a waters , formless and thin feeling beer . some wheat prevails , and some smoothness of texture , but there is not half as much of the pillowy champagne carbonation that i would have wanted .

smells indistinct , a bit of oatmeal - sure - but for the name being captain bastard , i feel a little cheated .  a great brown with no head , i think that is more to do with how the jp cafe pours than the beer .  first sip is fairly thin body especially for a milk stout . i keep coming back to how thin the body is and find it a little disappointing .

never really a fan of heineken due to the cost versus other typical pale lagers . nicer appearance than most light beer , kept a head longer and pretty good lacing around the glass . i 'm trying to compare this to its style ( which is not my favorite ) .  deep ruby red with a thin pink foamy head .  very thin . high carbonation simple and uninspiring , breaks a few key rules for the macro lager style too .

smell has some dark fruits , a bit of alcohol .  this porter pours a nice looking espresso brown with a sizable tan head that has decent retention qualities and leaves some nice lacing behind .  m- way , way too carbonated . it makes the thinner body feel worse

smell : nothing , i mean nothing in the nose for this beer .  ( a ) - deep , rich amber . a dirty amber . the head was a nutty tan -- very nice . a minimal amount of lacing , but it stayed awhile .  okay i know alot of people hate on cobra for being cheap malt liquor , but ive had many many cheap beers that tasted much worse for example bud ice .

um , it does n't really smell like a hefe . it smells a bit sour , citrus tones .  poured into a flaired tulip glass fro a 12oz brown long neck bottle crimped cap . hazy , golden amber with a dense , creamy head leaving some nice lace curtians down the glass . very lively looking the bubbles remined me of looking into a snow globe lots of stringing off the sided of the glass .  taste is ok - same roasted chocolate malt that was in the nose again no coffee - weak flavors - i have had stronger porters mouthfeel - a very thin light body with low carbonation overall - maybe this was past its prime or i got a bad bottle - but after drinking this i would not buy this beer again

smell : the only scent i get is metallic . this is not a 'flavor explosion ' , but it 's really nice anyway . now , if only something could be done about this beer 's smell ... .  a - nice dark brown color . not a great head , but a good one finger that hangs around some . nice lacing .  m- this beer was basically flat . theres no reason an ipa shouldnt be carbonated .

basically , it 's an average looking apa with little aroma and the taste is good without any `` flaws '' but it just does n't have a lot of it .  bottle picked up at bevmo , la mesa .  earthy hop flavors , finishes and lingers into the after with hop flavors , though mild m- start out pretty thin but develops as brew warms , dry and crisp finish , hops abuse can felt in aftertaste ( still mild though ) d- the flavor is decent throughout with improvements as the beer warms , the body does n't recover like the flavor however , starts damn near watery and has little progress .

smells extremly sudued .  i still get an exasperated look/sigh ... c'mon bartender ... this beer is cheap with my mug club card , and there 's a lot of it ... but other than the beautiful black appearance , the rest of the beer is underwhelming at best until nearly at room temperature . though dark , it is quite thin in the glass and the mouth .  m-very thin and watery with light carbonation and a slightly sticky feel .

instead , it is straight freshly ground coffee beans . take some fresh ground coffee and rub it between your fingers right under your nose , and thats the smell of the coffee bender . t : the fresh ground aroma does n't translate as well to the flavor profile . by no means is it bad . the coffee is more of a roasted flavor here , and the malts shine through nicely . m : smooth , medium bodied . d : a very nice , if not unique , brew that anyone who enjoys a little coffee in their beer should take a chance on .  this ipa looks nice in the glass . clear amber , with a decent head . it crowns slowly to leave a nice lace .  less complex flavours , there is a little chocolate and coffee but then it quickly falls flat . carbonation is to high , body too watery .

golden hazy color , almost amber smelled of hay and yeast , typical wheat beer good mouthfeel , not my favorite wheat by any means , but drinkable a standard rendition of a wheat beer , overall i am fairly unimpressed from magic hat with this one , circus boy is a way better wheat than this , and their hipa was actually unique and memorable for an ipa for a seasonal . the worst offering i have had from magic hat , but still drinkable on a hot summer day..  it 's a warm brown , only slightly transparent , with an off-white head that foams up about two inches in a pint glass and settles to a quarter inch over about a minute .  m - very thin bodied and carbonation level seems a little off .

it simply shouldnt smell as it does with a saturation of phenols that lean closer to formaldehyde than beer . strict bjcp judges would likely pan this beer on the demerits of its smell alone . but strangely enough , i enjoyed the strong coffee flavor that managed to survive the aroma .  bottle : poured a clear golden ale with a nice big head with better then average retention .  mouthfeel was nothing to write home about . watery and boring .

it 's largely without aroma except for faint notes of berries .  poured into a snifter a true black , with no light peeking through even when held up to it . head came in a sandy brown , moderate in size ... .so far so good with this beer . upon tasting this stout really falls to pieces , the taste is n't offensive by any means ... it 's just sort of ... blah . very tingly metallic in the mouth for a stout and almost completely lacking in those great roasted barley flavors we all know and love in a stout .  m : the feel is where the flatness really kills this beer . it 's nice and slick but the lack of carbonation really puts a damper on the rest of the experience . d : this has all the right components for a great dipa if port brewing could just get their carbonation issues solved .

surprisingly it feels thin and watery , and has very little aroma , taste reminds me of old coffee . the guinness in europe may be different so it 's hard to judge , but i 'm not a big fan of the american version , and i agree it 's overpriced .  bottle : poured a deep bright yellow color beer with a medium pure white foamy head with surprisingly good retention .  in the mouth it is thin and watery lacking concentration of flavor and depth .

s- not much here . some sweet malt but nothing too strong . slightly metallic . d- good stuff here , i like this beer as a summer bbq-type brew .  the appearance in a tulip glass was at first rather pleasant , with some nice ruby color showing around the edges , a reasonable finger of head , and the aroma had noticeable if a bit understated notes of dried cherry .  mouthfeel : hugely carbonated , paired with such a strong showing of sour lemon it 's almost sickening . no real body on this one , just very light and carbonated .

no distinguishable smell - lager-esque , but nothing that stands out .  pours a ruby garnett tone with a large creamy light beige head which leaves scattered lacing down the sides of my glass as it dwindles rather slow .  m : very thin with very little carbonation .

smell : not very powerful but malty and some hints of caramel . taste : much better and fuller than the smell suggests .  this dark sepia brew gives a decent 1/2 '' of tan head that settles to a thin frothy and stable layer with some larger bubbles and a good meniscus around the glass .  thin , fizzy mouthfeel . i 'd rate this lower if i really thought they were trying to brew a `` dubbel , '' but as a generic misguided `` abbey ale '' this is more flavorful than much of new belgium 's regular offerings for example ...

it has a classic smell , yes they added honey but the smell is a good helles bock flavor with bready malts , a hint of caramel , some nuttiness and a touch of hops.there is a little bit of fruit in there too .  pours a nice coppery shade with the palest of yellow heads . good retention , carbonation still going after 10 minutes in glass .  mouthfeel - light to watery side .

l : dark golden look , with a nice foamy head ; s : very akward ( overripe/rotting strawberry ) , strong metallic element ; t : in line of the strange smell , but better because of the malt .  i 'm dissapointed because it looked really nice when pouring . mouthfeel is very , very thin and just doesnt seem right for the style this one is destined to be pored down the drain unfortunately .  a vigorous and sustained bead fed the head as i took my first sip to find that this beer had no real texture or body .
smell of malty bitter graininess with a faint caramel note .  the pour was black with a nice tan head .  the mouthfeel is extremely watery - it tends to wash out the flavor .

smell : malty , very malty . hints of spicy flavors and i can almost smell the alcohol , at 8.8 % abv , not too surprised by that .  pours a golden , copper color ... light white head with some carbonation working its way to the top ... smells ... well ... to be honest , the first , and second , an third whiffs make me think of a barroom floor the morning after .  a little too much roughness . feel is tacky , raw and sweet .

didnt know this was a molson product till got to this page . aroma is caramel malt but otherwise empty .  a : poured a deep orange with good carbonation and a nice white head s : not very good .  not much taste , just thin malts and an odd taste i ca n't really describe . thin , watery , not too carbonated . the bad taste is n't really apparent seeing how thin it is .

the aroma has a hair-treatment , chemy aspect like a `` perm '' type-smell , not pleasant .  poured with a big white head . disappeared quickly , but left moderate lacing .  mouthfeel this one is sour and very alcoholic .

aroma is actually a bit muted .  the creme brulee java stout looks and smells pretty typical for the style , thick and black , brown head , a day-old coffee grounds smell , but the taste is , literally , the worst i have ever encountered in a beer .  mouthfeel was thin and light with a lot of carbination , not my ideal , but what you 'll expect from an average lager i suppose .
